<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-TRUSTEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ALLEGATIONS MAY FORCE INDIANA TO ACT ON KNIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of new accusations about the volatile behavior of
Bob Knight, Indiana's basketball coach, a meeting of university
trustees scheduled for Sunday has taken on new urgency.
</P>
<P>
   John Walda and Frederick Eichhorn _ the trustees who were
assigned to investigate charges that Knight put his hand around the
neck of the former Hoosier player Neil Reid at a practice in 1997 _
are expected to report at the meeting about the progress of their
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But several other recently reported accusations about Knight's
behavior have created the sense that the nine trustees may decide
to expand the investigation of Knight or begin moves to force the
coach out. The most damaging new accusation is from Jeanette
Hartgraves, the athletic department secretary, who said Knight
threw a vase in her office 12 years ago, shattering it against a
wall, in an angry fit about not being able to see Ralph Floyd, who
was then the school's athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Simpson, Indiana's vice president, denied Friday
that trustees were already considering whether to ask Knight to
resign, and he disputed reports that the coach was scheduled to
meet with Myles Brand, the school's president, on Sunday. He said
Knight was on vacation and due to return late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, who has spoken for Brand throughout the investigation,
said that if a meeting had been set up between the coach and the
school president ``I would think I'd be aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The quickened pace of the investigation, which was originally
intended to conclude by June, has prompted more public
demonstrations of support for Knight, as well as newly stated
opposition to the embattled coach. Todd Starowitz, an athletic
department spokesman, said many of the team's current players said
they would leave the program if Knight was forced out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players became very upset today, and told me they were
tired of being quiet,'' Starowitz said. ``They don't want to see
things tried in the media. To a man, everyone supports Coach
Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray Sperber, an Indiana professor who frequently writes
about college sports and has been a critic of Knight, said his
e-mail messages showed the coach was beginning to lose significant
support among Hoosier fans and alumni, largely because of the
vase-smashing accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone from a steady 3-to-1 for Knight and me shutting up
to a 3-to-1 for me speaking out and `Knight must go!''' he said.
``I think that the revelations really shocked some people and
silenced others.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
