<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER COULD HAVE SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Anaheim Angels pitcher Kent Mercker is in stable
condition in the intensive care unit at UC Irvine Medical Center
after being diagnosed with a sub-arachnoid hematoma in his brain,
also known as a cerebral hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   An arteriogram and CT scan were performed late Thursday night
after Mercker left the game complaining of a severe headache and
dizziness. The tests showed bleeding within space of the brain,
according to Dr. John Kusske, chair of neurologic surgery at UCI.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, 32, will remain in intensive care at least through the
weekend for further evaluation and tests before moving to a regular
room. Doctors are trying to determine the cause of the bleeding,
which has stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't localized it,'' said Angels team physician Dr.
Lewis Yocum. ''The bleeding settles in the lower part of the skull.
An injury of some sort prompted the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen it in baseball. I've seen it with concussions,
it's fairly common in hockey. But I haven't heard of active
bleeding in a baseball player. It's something that could occur with
the stress of pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Yocum said surgery is a possibility, but the course of treatment
will be based on the cause of the problem. It could be the result
of an aneurism, malformation or any number of medical conditions.
It also could be a one-time occurrence, but it remains a serious
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time there's bleeding around the brain, it's a potentially
serious situation,'' Yocum said. ``He was very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker also was fortunate Yocum and team trainer Ned Bergert
decided to send Mercker to the hospital for tests Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw things not typical of a mild headache,'' Yocum said.
``The severity of the headache, other medical signs. Ned and I
didn't feel comfortable trying to take care of it at the
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman, Yocum and pitcher Kent
Bottenfield, a friend of Mercker's and teammate with the Cardinals,
visited Mercker at the hospital Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sleeping but woke up when we got in,'' Stoneman said.
``He recognized us immediately and had a smile on his face. He had
a lot of gadgets attached to him, but other than that he looked
really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia and several players learned the severity
of Mercker's situation while in the clubhouse after Thursday's
game, and it took them by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to see him in the trainers' room a couple of minutes
after he came out of the game and it seemed like he was feeling
better,'' Scioscia said. ``But he still had a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia addressed the team during a midafternoon meeting on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We addressed the team, not only to give them an update but
also to set up a support group for Kent and his family,'' he said.
``You're talking about a guy in his early 30s. Having a condition
like this transcends anything happening on the baseball field. It
makes it trivial. It's very frightening to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker's wife Julie is flying to Orange County today from the
couple's home in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the medical department is very concerned, and when
they're concerned, it's something serious,'' Scioscia said. ``This
is real life, the real world. It's sobering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously our concern right now is for Kent's well-being. Our
thoughts and prayers are with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was placed on the 15-day disabled list Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
