<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN RESOURCES PAID CEO $8 MILLION IN 1999, PROXY STATEMENT
SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   TOPEKA, Kan. _ David Wittig, chief
executive officer of Western Resources Inc., got an $8 million
paycheck in 1999, including a one-time $5.4 million payment as
compensation for lost benefits and income from a previous employer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The compensation, which was disclosed in the company's proxy
statement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission, came
in a year when the company struggled with its investment in
Protection One Inc., a monitored security company. The company also
tried to complete its merger with Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co., a
deal that ultimately fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig received no bonus for short-term performance of the
company in 1999. But the $5.4 million payment is raising eyebrows
because the company has struggled to conserve cash and has asked
shareholders to take stock instead of a cash dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded, '' said Walker Hendrix, counsel for the
Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board, a consumer group. ``I don't
understand why with everything else they picked this year'' to pay
the $5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Koupal Jr., a Western executive vice president, said the
$5.4 million was agreed to in 1995, when Wittig joined Western. He
left a higher-paying job at the Wall Street firm of Salomon
Brothers to come to Topeka. The payment, which was to be made in
1999, was meant to bridge the difference.
</P>
<P>
   In other compensation in 1999, Wittig took more of it in stock
than cash. He now has 450,000 shares of Western stock, not counting
stock options, and has an interest in seeing Western's stock price
recover, Koupal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His interests are clearly in line with shareholders,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While most utility stocks did poorly in 1999, Western performed
below average. If an investor had held $149 of Western stock on
Dec, 31, 1998, it would have been worth $83 a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Western closed Friday at 15.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy statement also disclosed Western has a life insurance
policy on Wittig and will recover the $5.4 million when he dies.
Wittig is 44.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Cafer, general counsel for the Kansas Corporation
Commission, said regulators would only consider the appropriateness
of the $5.4 million payment if the company asked to include it in
future rates. Current rates do not allow the payment to be
shouldered by consumers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
