u i BC-KOREA-MASSACRE-3RDLD-     05-13 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MASSACRE-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT TESTIMONY ON KOREAN MASSACRE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn.)  (CORRECTS ``foxhole'' to ``machine-gun emplacement'' in 21st graf
begin: ``And one soldier...'') 
By ELIZABETH BECKER and FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New evidence has been published that appears to undermine the
testimony of two witnesses who said that U.S. soldiers were ordered
to kill civilians during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Their charge was featured in a prominent and detailed news
report last September by the Associated Press, which concluded for
the first time that U.S. soldiers killed hundreds of Korean
civilians in June 1950. It also quoted veterans who said they were
at the scene, some of whom said they were given orders to shoot.
Other soldiers quoted by the wire service said they did not
remember such orders.
</P>
<P>
   Army documents retrieved by Stripes.com, an electronic edition
of The Stars and Stripes, which covers the military, and an
investigation by U.S. News &AMP; World Report, question the credibility
of Edward Daily, a witness in the original Associated Press
investigation of the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The new reports state that he was not at the site, the No Gun Ri
bridge, when the refugees were killed, but instead was serving with
a maintenance unit miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Daily was among those who told the Associated Press that the
shootings of civilians at No Gun Ri were carried out under orders.
``The command looked at it as getting rid of the problem in the
easiest way,'' he said. ``That was to shoot them in a group.''
</P>
<P>
   A second of the dozen witnesses quoted in the original
Associated Press report, Delos Flint, also was not at the bridge on
July 26, 1950, when the shooting reportedly began, according to the
new reports; they found he had been wounded and was already ferried
off the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone Friday, Flint stuck by what he told the AP.
``They told us to shoot,'' he said from his home in Clio, Mich. ``I
told the other guys you can shoot all you want but I didn't believe
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Flint said he could not remember much of what happened after
he was seriously wounded in the fighting. ``I don't hardly remember
being sent to the hospital and I didn't remember anything for a
long time after the war,'' he said. ``I do remember spending 18
months in the hospital at Valley Forge.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these discrepancies, senior Defense Department officials
said Friday that an Army investigation has confirmed the central
element of the AP report, that U.S. troops fired on refugees,
resulting in what the Pentagon calls the ``tragic death of hundreds
of civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon would not comment on the scope of the killings, nor
the duration of the shootings, while the investigation is under
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has concluded that as many as several hundred civilians
were killed at No Gun Ri and is focusing on the orders given to the
U.S. soldiers at the bridge, according to a senior Army official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the taking of innocent life,'' said the senior
Army official, who noted that over 1 million people died in that
war. ``What was unique in this situation was this notion that it
was intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pentagon official said the Army has interviewed
hundreds of witnesses, American and South Korean, and is examining
thousands of pages of documents to discover whether GIs killed
civilians accidentally in the heat of battle, whether they were
ordered to do so, or whether they thought they were under orders to
do so, as some of the A P witnesses asserted.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy AP investigation in September won two of
journalism's most prestigious awards, a Pulitzer and the Polk.
Numerous newspapers, including The New York Times, carried the
report on their front pages. And it prompted an investigation by
the Pentagon, concerned about the impact on relations with an
important Asian ally, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts about some sources are coming out just over a month
after the board of the Pulitzer Prizes awarded the AP its prize for
investigative reporting, ``for revealing, with extensive
documentation, the decades-old secret of how America soldiers early
in the Korean War killed hundreds of Korean civilians in a massacre
at No Gun Ri Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement this week and later interviews, AP officials
defended their work, saying that Daily's account was not central to
the original dispatch nor to subsequent accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And they said they do not question the ambiguous and sometimes
contradictory evidence of how the killings at No Gun Ri occurred _
rather, they say, their reports reflected that ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Smith Tunney, the director of corporate communications for
the wire service, said Friday, ``The first question is what
happened at the bridge. We have done extensive research and double
and triple-checked facts. And we're not apologetic about what we've
done. It was all dependent on distant records and there were many
ambiguities, all of which was in our original reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Former soldiers initially interviewed by the AP gave accounts
that contradict the new reports, and placed Daily at No Gun Ri,
according to one of the reporters. A copy of the memo was made
available Fridayto The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   One former soldier, an officer, described Daily's receipt of a
battlefield commission.
</P>
<P>
   And another soldier present, Jim Kerns, drew for the AP
reporters a diagram of his machine-gun emplacement and those on
either side, according to Martha Mendoza, one of the three
reporters who wrote the article. ``I was on the right-hand side,
Daily was on the left, and Harold Blanc, he was in the middle,''
Kerns said, according to the memo.
</P>
<P>
   The Army refused to comment on the new evidence uncovered by the
news organizations this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to maintain the integrity of the No Gun Ri review, we
will not address the accuracy of any press reports,'' Charles L.
Cragin, acting undersecretary of defense for personnel, said in a
statement. ``It is premature to discuss our findings until the
review is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident at the railroad bridge near the village of No Gun
Ri took place in the early days of the Korean War. Army commanders
feared that North Korean infiltrators were part of the refugees
fleeing the fighting between the two Korean armies.
</P>
<P>
   The AP said their reporters had spoken to six veterans who said
they fired at the refugees and six others said they witnessed a
mass killing. Daily and Flint were two of the veterans who have
said they were at the bridge and were ordered to fire on civilians.
Following the first AP report, they were interviewed by other
newspapers, magazines and television networks, and expanded on
their original charges.
</P>
<P>
   However, the official Army records unearthed by Stripes.com
showing that neither man was at No Gun Ri when the refugees came
under fire. The evidence about Daily's presence at the scene is the
most sharply disputed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newly uncovered documents, Daily did not serve
in the unit, and did not receive the battlefield commission he
described to the AP. The documents also contradict other examples
that Daily has cited of his military record.
</P>
<P>
   In an autobiographical sketch for a history of his division's
Korean War experiences, Daily claimed to have been awarded the
Distinguished Service Cross, Silver Star, Bronze Star and three
Purple Heart medals, none of which appear in his official record,
according to the newly uncovered documents.
</P>
<P>
   Daily could not be reached for comment at his home in Tennessee,
but Mendoza, in an interview yesterday quoted from the text of
video tape interviews with Carroll. Mendoza quoted Carroll
describing Daily's battlefield commission, ``Daily was commissioned
as a 19-year old kid,'' he said. ``That's how short we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other documentary evidence contradicts the memories
of other principals, according to AP journalists.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Charles J. Hanley, another of the three AP reporters, said that
Eu- gene Hesselman, in an early inter- view, contradicted the daily
report for his unit.
</P>
<P>
   The unit's ``morning report'' indi- cates that he had been
wounded and evacuated on the day the killing be- gan. Hanley said
that Hessel-H man had explained to a reporter months before the
publication of the No Gun Ri report that he had re- ceived a
shrapnel wound to the hand, but had remained at the site after
being bandaged.
</P>
<P>
   According to several documents, Flint had been evacuated for
medical treatment the day before the incident , according to the
new reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that some guy isn't credible doesn't mean we don't
have a problem,'' said a senior Pentagon official. ``But it is a
warning that there is bad information floating around.''
</P>
<P>
   In those first months of the war, the Army was under-equipped
and poorly trained, according to Col. David R. Hughes, retired, who
as a lieutenant in the th Cavalry earned a distinguished cross and
two silver stars in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a seven-mile retreat just before No Gun Ri and the
first units got chewed up badly,'' said Hughes who arrived in Korea
a few months after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pentagon official said the investigation will be
completed in the fall, not in June as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   The wire service began piecing together accounts of the massacre
after one of its Korea-based reporters, Sang Hun Choe, covered the
latest unsuccessful attempt of some of the victims to gain
reparations. Last September, the AP published the long account,
which is still posted on its Web site (www.ap.org),, complete with
videotapes containing sections of interviews with Daily and
Hesselman.
</P>
<P>
   The AP released an article early Friday on the Army's continuing
investigation into No Gun Ri. The article cited the documents
uncovered by Stripes.com that contradicted the AP investigation,
and noted that U.S. News was preparing a report on the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
