<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, May 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
ELECTION-FLAKE _ The state Democratic Party announced Friday that
it will file a complaint with the Federal Election Commission
accusing GOP congressional candidate Jeff Flake of violating
campaign-finance aw. The announcement came an Arizona Republic
story detailing Flake's $72,000consulting fee from the tax-exempt
Arizona School Choice Trust, which was made possible by a
tax-deductible, $50,000 donation from Flake's campaign-finance
chairman. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOL-INSPECT _ The company in charge of a mammoth statewide
school inspection is financially troubled and dogged by lawsuits
from creditors, raising serious questions about its work. &UR; Arizona
is refusing to pay any &UR; more on the $2.6 million contract until
Ohio-based Flex-Tech Professional Services re-inspects 303 schools.
Reports from those schools were wrong, inadequate or could not be
produced. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIRE (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ When local radio stations announced where
Los Alamos residents could discover whether their homes were still
standing, evacuees spilled from hotels and friends' homes, creating
a traffic jam on New Mexico 502 at the turnoff to Pojoaque High
School. There, they found Red Cross volunteer Marion Johnson
standing on a chair, yelling out the addresses of the 260 homes
destroyed by this week's ``Cerro Grande'' fire. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL;
