r a BC-TORNADO-KAN &LR;      05-13 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHILD'S LIFE LOST IN TORNADO AFTERMATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE and JERRY BERRIOS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The danger to human
life appeared to be past. But nearly 12 hours after a tornado
touched down in southern Leavenworth County, Kan., a porch roof
collapsed about 10:30 a.m. Friday and killed a 4-year-old girl in
Tonganoxie.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The girl, whose name was not released Friday, was pronounced
dead at Children's Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She was the only fatality _ and no one else was reported injured
_ as a result of at least two tornadoes and straight-line winds
that raked Tonganoxie and Kansas City, North.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night storm skipped and plundered its way over and
through parts of Leavenworth County and Clay County in Missouri,
catching many people sleeping or unawares. Trees were uprooted;
power was knocked out at several thousand homes; and material from
structures and fixtures became flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   At a car dealership, a Toyota Tundra pickup truck ended up on
the general sales manager's desk. The dealership was closed when
the storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, North, J.D. Campbell marveled at the tornado's
randomness as he helped a neighbor clear tree limbs from her yard
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature moves in mysterious ways,'' said Campbell, who
lives in the Prather Hills neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive damage in the Northland was limited to a relatively
small area. Hardest hit were the Jay Wolfe Toyota dealership and
the John Chezik Honda dealership, both in the 3900 block of North
Oak Trafficway.
</P>
<P>
   In Leavenworth County, more than 200 structures were damaged,
including 125 homes and 25 businesses in Tonganoxie, a town of
about 3,000 people. An Assembly of God Church was destroyed, and
four of 17 buildings at the Leavenworth County Fairgrounds were
destroyed or badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said a tornado touched down in
Tonganoxie about 9:55 p.m. and stayed on or near the ground in
Leavenworth County until about 10:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado from the same system touched down about 11:25 p.m. on
North Oak Trafficway. That funnel cloud stayed on or near the
ground for about four miles, to Northeast Parvin Road and Chouteau
Trafficway.
</P>
<P>
   Some Northland residents reported hearing the sirens after the
tornado had passed. Others said they heard the sirens before the
storm. And others said they couldn't remember what came first _ the
tornado or the sirens.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor warning sirens in Kansas City were activated at
11:25 p.m., said Kansas City Emergency Preparedness Coordinator
Mike Karl.
</P>
<P>
   Karl acknowledged that some residents had complained about not
hearing the sirens, but he said the sirens are an outdoor warning
system only and can be difficult to hear indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has 54 outdoor warning sirens; most are placed on
poles near police and fire stations, schools and parks, Karl said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tonganoxie, officials said, the sirens went off about 10
minutes before the tornado touched down. Tragedy
</P>
<P>
   In Tonganoxie, Dennis Stevens, the owner of a Kansas City tree
service, was trimming a storm-damaged tree in the 500 block of
Sixth Street Friday morning. Next door, he said, he saw a man on
the porch's small, flat roof clearing debris and cutting tree limbs
with a chain saw. Then, he saw the roof collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard all this screaming,'' Stevens said. ``I thought
somebody had to be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonganoxie Police Chief Ken Carpenter said he expected the
girl's name and city of residence to be released this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, most of the damage appeared to be caused by fallen
tree branches, which leaned against roofs Friday and littered the
front yards of most of the homes around downtown Tonganoxie.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Franiuk said keeping the town safe was a priority.
The National Guard is scheduled to come in today to help keep
traffic away from a one-square-mile section around downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate this thing did not touch down hard and
heavy, because we'd be in real trouble,'' Franiuk said.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado stripped part of the roof from Tonganoxie Elementary
School and water soaked six classrooms. The damage: at least
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Classes were canceled at the school, as they were at the
Tonganoxie junior and senior high schools. The latter schools
escaped damaged but were closed in case temporary shelter was
needed, although it wasn't. The elementary school could reopen
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Kansas Gov. Bill Graves issued a
declaration of disaster emergency. Spokesman Don Brown said the
declaration set in motion an assessment of the damage by state
agencies. That could result in federal assistance, including
low-interest loans for damage repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Kansas Adjutant General Greg Gardner was in
Tonganoxie Friday. Insurance Commissioner Kathleen Sebelius is to
survey the damage Monday. Cars smashed
</P>
<P>
   Steve Okenfuss, managing partner of the Jay Wolfe Toyota
dealership at 3920 North Oak Trafficway, stood outside police tape
Friday and surveyed piles of twisted metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just demolished the building and everything inside of it,''
Okenfuss said, referring to the tornado. ``It looks like a big foot
just smashed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Okenfuss said two Toyota Land Cruisers were holding up the front
of the building. Of the 300 vehicles on the lot, Okenfuss said,
about 100 were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Although damage was extensive, he said, the situation could have
been worse. ``Fortunately, the building was empty,'' Okenfuss said.
``If this had hit at 5 p.m., there would have been 40 people
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the dealership's future at the North Oak Trafficway
location might be decided next week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Chezik said he hoped to be selling cars on
Monday and have his dealership and 63 employees fully operational
by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chezik said he was amazed at the damage. Of 217 cars on the lot,
he said, 48 were damaged. Chezik said more than 700 memorabilia
items that he stored at the dealership were safe. Items include
baseballs, bats, shoes and jerseys autographed by baseball stars
such as Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting North Oak Trafficway, the storm headed east and
did damage in several neighborhoods between North Oak Trafficway,
Vivion Road, Chouteau Trafficway and the North Kansas City
boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Hit especially hard were the Sunset Hills, Sunset-Dixon, Prather
Hills and Cooley-Highlands neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry King, who lives on North Cherry Street, couldn't walk down
his front steps Friday because of the twisted pieces of metal.
``I'm just glad we are alive,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-foot-long steel beam, thought to be from the Jay Wolfe
dealership, sliced through Bernice and Tom Smiroldo's living room a
few blocks away on Northeast 39th Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bernice Smiroldo felt lucky. ``I would sure have hated
for it to come through the bedroom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, neighbor Denise Lanning agreed. ``This could
have been a tragedy for a lot of people,'' she said. Storms erupt
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bunting, a meteorologist for the National Weather Service
in Pleasant Hill, said the storm produced tornadoes and also
powerful, straight-line winds.
</P>
<P>
   The storm system brewed up west of Topeka, Kan.,when warm moist
air was able to rise into a cool air mass. The storm likely spawned
two or three funnel clouds at Tonganoxie with winds up to 112 mph,
a class F1 tornado, said Lynn Maximuk, chief meteorologist for the
National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service classifies tornadoes from F0 to F5, with F5
being the strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Once past Tonganoxie, Maximuk said, the tornado lost strength
and moved east with wind speeds of 60 to 70 mph. Maximuk said it
ended about 10:15 near Basehor in Leavenworth County.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderstorm cell continued east at 25 mph, through
Wyandotte County, Kan., and then Platte County, Mo. Later, the
storm intensified rapidly over southern Clay County.
</P>
<P>
   There, a tornado developed and stayed on the ground for four
miles. Bunting said the funnel ended about 11:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A myth that has been repeated many times holds that
tornado-bearing storms approaching Kansas City from the west veer
south or north of the metro area as they approach outlying areas,
such as Tonganoxie, perhaps because of geography or temperature
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this kills the Tonganoxie split theory,'' Bunting
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, the last tornado recorded by the National
Weather Service in the metro area was in western Leavenworth County
in 1996. Other tornadoes were reported in Lee's Summit, Mo., in
1992 and in Pleasant Hill, Mo., in 1977, and some weaker tornadoes,
without large amounts of damage, have also been reported.
</P>
<P>
   The most infamous tornado to strike the area in recent decades
was in 1957. A tornado touched down near Williamsburg, Kan., and
roared northeast through the Missouri towns of Martin City,
Grandview, Hickman Mills and Ruskin Heights. On the ground for 71
miles, it killed 44 persons and injured 531. Hundreds of homes were
destroyed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
