r a BC-LAPD-MORALE-LADN     05-13 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-MORALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALE ERODING AMONG LAPD OFFICERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reacting to U.S. Justice Department claims that
Los Angeles police violate residents' civil rights, many patrol
officers say morale has hit a new low and it has damaged how they
do their jobs, in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any morale. Instead of helping out each other,
we're almost against each other. Everyone's paranoid,'' said a West
Valley Division officer and five-year veteran of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bill Lann Lee, acting chief of the Justice
Department's Civil Rights Division, charged that lax supervision
has led officers to engage in ``a pattern or practice of excessive
force, false arrests and unreasonable searches and seizures.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a former Los Angeles civil rights lawyer, also said the
city must accept a consent decree or defend itself in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, several officers said they welcome a lawsuit to
exonerate the rank-and-file, but federal oversight could seriously
damage the Los Angeles Police Department's law enforcement effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought it was bad now? Wait till the feds come in,'' said
an officer, who like others asked for his identity to be withheld.
</P>
<P>
   One sergeant said he'd like to see the issue go to court so that
the allegations are detailed and defended. ``I'd like to know
specifically what we've done,'' said Sgt. Bob Weisz of the West
Valley Divison.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear generalities, but no specifics. I see the finest
officers in the world here. I'd like to see the city attorney fight
it, rather than run and hide,'' said Weisz, a 27-year LAPD veteran.
``I really don't think they're going to find viable facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer John Smith of the North Hollywood Division said federal
scrutiny would prove the rank-and-file officers are doing their
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the federal government's takeover and threatened
consent decree is a vindication of rank and file's assertion that
it's management's fault. Management got us where we're at. It gives
credibility to that belief,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not totally opposed to having the federal government come
in and take over _ taking it out of the hands of the City Council,
taking it out of the hands of the politicians and putting it in the
hands of the people it needs to be in, and that's legal experts,
judges and lawyers _ people who implement the law, not the
professional administrators and professional politicians. I think
it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officers said the extra scrutiny on the rank and file may
make them more apt to ``drive by and wave'' to people, rather than
stop and confront them.
</P>
<P>
   Several said rather than federal oversight, the Los Angeles
Police Department needs better-trained supervisors who properly
manage officers in the field.
</P>
<P>
   However, some officers welcomed the federal monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me. I have no fear for the feds to come
in,'' said one Foothill Division officer.
</P>
<P>
   One West Valley officer of 10 years agreed that he had no
problem with the federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody's doing their job right, they don't have anything
to worry about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers throughout the San Fernando Valley argue there's
plenty to be concerned about, including federal officials being
unfamiliar with department policies and tactics.
</P>
<P>
   And they worry that the prospect of being second-guessed will
cause them to hesitate when they should be acting instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's where you see that lack of proactive police
work,'' one West Valley officer said after joking with his fellow
officers by picking up the phone and identifying himself as the
``FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   The West Valley officer with the department for five years cited
an example: A condominium complex was having problems with
prowlers, and police had no suspect descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The officer decided to do extra patrol there recently and ran
into three African-American men wearing gloves and coats on a warm
day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me being white and them black, I'm not going to deal with
the race problem here,'' the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'm checking out the area, where there have been
burglaries, and if they see anything suspicious, please call the
police station and that I appreciated their help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Makes you sick, huh?'' the officer said, knowing full well
that they were the potential suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like that before. Before, you'd tell them to turn
around and put their hands on their head and ask them, What the
hell are you doing wearing gloves in the summertime? You'd ask who
they are, where they live and pat them down for weapons and ID,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that, he said, could now potentially label him a ``problem
officer'' today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Foothill Division officer questioned the timeliness of
the federal authorities' four-year probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the feds have known the past couple years that something
was wrong, why didn't they step in long ago?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3962 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MOLEGIS-KAN &LR;      05-13 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLEGIS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Missouri General Assembly ends session  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR and OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ A muddled
legislative session beset by partisan bickering lurched to an end
Friday with individual senators killing major bills and House
members rehashing issues from earlier in the year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Missouri General Assembly approved 83 bills this year,
compared with an average of 203 over the past 15 years. While each
party blamed the other for the paucity of legislation, both tried
to put the best spin on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, we've had a lot of achievements,'' said Senate
President pro tem Ed Quick, a Democrat from Liberty. ``We've had
some disappointments, but we ended up with a pretty fair session.
We'd prefer to talk about what we were able to do for citizens
instead of why we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Steve Ehlmann, a St. Charles Republican, said the GOP had
tried to follow the Hippocratic oath: First, do no harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, we could have,'' he said. ``There's nothing we
didn't do today that we can't wait to do next January.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan said the session was a good one considering
the overtly political environment of this election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were fighting the election every day,'' he said.
``There are other things in life besides this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he was most proud of the passage of a plan to
issue $2.25 billion in bonds for road construction. to win approval
of a plan in his last year in office would have been a particular
disappointment, he said. ]
</P>
<P>
   He also cited legislation on fighting child abuse and
methamphetamine, expanding gun-free schools and funding education
as major accomplishments. Carnahan said failing to designate how
tobacco settlement funds would be used was bad public policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take any imagination to know what will happen,''
Carnahan said. ``There will be urgent good needs, and we'll just
take it from the tobacco money. You saw that happen this session.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was disappointed that tougher drunken driving
legislation had failed. suspected drunken drivers. ]
</P>
<P>
   Democratic legislative leaders complained that abortion managed
to worm its way into nearly every issue. House Speaker Steve Gaw, a
Democrat from Moberly, noted that abortion provisions were even
attached to bills regulating long-term nursing care and tanning
beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just doesn't make sense to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion also submarined a last-ditch effort to salvage a trust
fund to hold the proceeds of Missouri's tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan called for setting up a trust fund to hold the
payments from cigarette makers and ask voters to approve a plan to
spend them. That plan fell apart Wednesday when abortion opponents
insisted on sweeping language to prohibit the money from going to
any organization connected to any group that performs or refers
women for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, who supports abortion rights, said the language was
unacceptable because it could have prevented the state from using
money to pay for health care at most hospitals and clinics in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents put together a plan to save the trust fund by
attaching it to a bill designed to reduce teen smoking. The added
section would have set up the account to receive the roughly $180
million a year in payments. It would have given lawmakers until
next April to submit a spending plan to voters.
</P>
<P>
   The added section made no mention of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. John Schneider of St. Louis County said he
intended to tack on the anti-abortion language.
</P>
<P>
   With only five hours left in the session, Quick reluctantly
pulled the issue from consideration and agreed to remove the trust
fund amendment from the bill. The Senate then approved the rest of
the bill, which requires much tougher laws on youth smoking. The
bill would have prohibited possession of cigarettes by youths under
18.
</P>
<P>
   However, the House killed the bill over a provision allowing the
use of children under 17 to conduct stings on tobacco retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But both chambers approved a child-protection bill inspired in
part by the torture and starvation deaths of two 8-year-old Kansas
City brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Gary Bass were found dead in October. Authorities said
reports of abuse had been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires social workers to contact police when they
open an investigation. Each county also must designate a chief
investigator who specializes in child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Social-service agencies will be required to enlist the help of
other organizations, including a public-school liaison, when
investigating abuse reports. State agencies also will provide
voluntary services for families of children thought to be at high
risk of abuse or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Bonner, an Independence Democrat, added an amendment
to punish adults if a child left unattended in a vehicle caused an
injury or death. He said the legislation was unrelated to the death
of 6-year-old Jake Robel, who was dragged to death after being left
alone in a car that was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republican senators derailed a bill designed to
protect nursing home residents from abuse. Led by Sen. Sarah
Steelman of Rolla, the group held up a vote for two hours Friday by
insisting on including a provision that guaranteed a profit for
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The provision would have sent up to $133 million in additional
tax money to nursing home operators who care for Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor, Democratic Sen. Harold Caskey of Butler,
expressed frustration at the extended debate as the clock was
winding down. He accused Steelman and Republican Sen. Bill Kenney
of Lee's Summit of trying to kill the reforms by filibustering it
to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not killing the bill,'' Steelman retorted. ``I'm trying to
help it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the government was demanding better care from nursing
homes without paying enough to cover the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Craig Hosmer, a Springfield Democrat who handled the bill
in the House, said the bill grew out of a study committee that had
heard stories about abuse of nursing home patients from all parts
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Steelman offered an amendment that would have prohibited any of
the elderly abuse reforms from taking effect until the state
appropriated the extra money for nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Caskey was incensed. The bill's death, he said, would allow
nursing home workers to abuse and steal from residents in their
care with virtual immunity from prosecution. He said the reforms
would cost nursing homes nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're saying is to take care of your residents and check
to make sure your employees are not abusers,'' Caskey said. ``We're
not asking them to do anything more that what they already should
be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Steelman and Kenney said something needed to be done to help
nursing home owners, who say Medicaid pays them $13 a day less that
it costs to care for each patient.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne Goode, the St. Louis County Democrat who heads the
Budget Committee, said the proposal would precipitate a budget
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, which pays for health care for the poor, is an
entitlement program, Goode reminded his colleagues. Therefore, if a
provider performs the service, it is entitled to payment regardless
of budget constraints.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sent to the Budget Control Committee, which voted
6-2 to kill it. The extra provisions made it too expensive, members
said. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
