</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS GO 1 DOWN TO HEAT AS HOME-COURT ADVANTAGE VANISHES
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a wild moment, the official Dan Crawford waved
off the basket. For a panicked few seconds, Pat Riley was coming
out of his Armani jacket, going out of his mind and coming unglued
with 2.2 seconds left in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Then the referees conferred and the decision was made, much to
the dismay of a distraught Jeff Van Gundy. The brave floater that
Anthony Carter sent up over the tips of Patrick Ewing's fingers
Friday night in overtime was not touched on the way down by Alonzo
Mourning. The basket was good, and the game-winner was in the
Heat's hands.
</P>
<P>
   With 2.2 seconds remaining, the New York Knicks had a chance to
win the game, but Charlie Ward's pass to Latrell Sprewell was
swiped away by Jamal Mashburn. Riley quickly exited as Madison
Square Garden fell silent. The Heat had done it: Miami had come
into the Knicks' home and stole back the home-court advantage by
taking Game 3, 77-76, Friday night. The Heat took a 2-1 advantage
in this best-of-7 second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 will be played Sunday afternoon at Madison Square Garden.
This one was a thriller. It ended with Carter guiding the Heat much
more ably than Hardaway. It ended with Mourning scoring 23 points
despite foul trouble. The Knicks were led by Allan Houston's 24
points, and 23 from Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks forced overtime when Patrick Ewing came up with his
first basket in 15 minutes as he released a game-tying 15-foot
jumper with 2.6 seconds left in regulation. Backpedaling down the
court with his wrist hanging in the air for effect, he seemed to be
waving goodbye to the Heat for the night.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as if Ewing was prescient when Charlie Ward fired a
bullet pass to Marcus Camby for a dunk just a tick before the shot
clock went off to give the Knicks a 75-71 lead with 2 minutes 13
seconds left in overtime. But the Heat came back to tie the score
on two free throws from Carter, plus a jumper by Mourning with 1:17
left.
</P>
<P>
   After Ewing dribbled the ball off his own foot, the Heat had a
chance to take the lead, but Dan Majerle missed an open 3-pointer
with 30 seconds remaining. It was Ewing's turn again as he went to
the free-throw line with 13.7 seconds left. He hit one of two to
leave the Heat with a chance to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Carter drove to the basket, let go of a floater over Ewing and
watched it bounce into the basket with 2.2 seconds left. At first,
the referees ruled offensive interference. With Riley yelling, the
officials overruled the call. They did not have the benefit of
television, but the replay showed that Mourning did not touch the
ball on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   It was another episode in this rivalry that resembled a finger
painting stuck on the refrigerator _ a game only a mother could
find beauty in _ but it was not short of the kind of intense drama
that left everyone glad to witness the grinding glory of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat stayed in the game on the shooting of Clarence
Weatherspoon and P.J. Brown when Mourning was forced to sit down
for 12 minutes of the second half after picking up his fourth foul
midway in the third quarter. The Heat took a 60-57 lead with seven
minutes left in the game after Brown shook free for an open jumper
on a pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Knicks had scored just one point in the
fourth quarter. On the Knicks' next possession, Houston hit a
jumper for the team's first field goal of the fourth quarter with
6:47 left in the game. Mourning, who slipped back into the game
with eight minutes remaining, came up with a jump hook to give the
Heat a 62-59 lead. The Heat went back-and-forth with the Knicks
with plays like this: On a scramble for a loose ball, Brown dug it
out of Sprewell's hands, a play that led to a basket by Mashburn.
After Mourning lost the ball when he was trapped, he gathered it
and sent up a jumper that fell on the shot-clock buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks countered with Houston. He shook Majerle's hands-on
defense for five straight points. But Houston missed a free throw
with 2:48 left, and the Knicks trailed by 66-64. After a mindless
jumper by Mourning early on the shot clock that missed, Ward drove
the baseline and lofted up a floater right over Brown with 1:33 on
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The tension was palpable. On the Heat's next possession,
Mourning grabbed a rebound, was fouled by Ewing and went to the
free-throw line with 1:09 left. He hit both. The Knicks had a
chance to tie the score, but Houston's jumper missed, then Camby's
tap back fell off the rim. But with 24.6 seconds remaining, Carter
missed a flinging jumper as the shot-clock buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had time to line up either a game-winning 3-pointer
or a shot to tie the game. Unlike in Game 1, Camby was on the floor
instead of Larry Johnson. The Knicks ran a play to get Houston the
ball, but he missed his turnaround jumper. In a frantic scramble
for the ball, Camby tapped it to Sprewell, who sent the ball to
Ward, who missed an open 3-pointer. But the rebound went off the
Heat with 6.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The ball went to Houston. And knowing the Heat would double him,
Houston directed the pass to Ewing, who hit his 15-footer to send
the game into an overtime that ultimately proved extremely
frustrating for the Knicks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks wanted to approach Game 3 more clear-headed. For two
days, Van Gundy preached assertiveness to a team that seemed easily
flustered in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing, when you do get open against Miami, you have to be
ready to shoot and you have to play without hesitation,'' Van Gundy
said before Game 3. ``You can't hesitate when you get it because
they're going to close hard. You can't pass up open shots.
Indecision and hesitation is hurting us right now offensively. You
have to shoot it, catch and pass it, or catch and drive it
immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
