<HEADER>
A3966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-13 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RILEY FINDING HIS TIME IS PASSING BY
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley is back in town, the venerable crunch-time
coach who brought you Showtime in Los Angeles, Short Time in New
York and now Zo Time in Miami. Friday night Riley pulled another
rabbit out of his hat with Alonzo Mourning saddled with fouls and
Tim Hardaway barely able to walk. The Miami Heat forced the New
York Knicks to play one of those nasty, head-butting, arm-wrestling
games that used to be New York's signature but now is just
something they do whenever they play Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing's jumper with 2.6 seconds left sent this brutal
Game 3 into overtime. But then the rookie Anthony Carter _ Miami's
rabbit in the hat _ threw up a shot from almost behind the basket
with 2.7 seconds left in overtime to give the Heat a 77-76 victory.
Thus, in one game the Heat managed to beat up the Knicks, retake
home-court advantage and take a 2-1 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, just when you were about to write off Riley, call
him a thing of the past, he gives himself another day.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the coaches who patrol the NBA sidelines, Riley has left
the most intriguing footprints. More intriguing than Lenny Wilkens,
though he has not coached as long, more intriguing than Phil
Jackson, though he has not won a recent championship.
</P>
<P>
   Riley represents a thick slice of history and evolution in the
NBA, from substance to style. He's part of the transition of an era
when the NBA leaped from the shadows and devoured college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The footprints leave a trail from Schenectady, N.Y., to
Lexington Ky., and Adolph Rupp's segregated world of basketball. To
a journeyman player's career through the NBA: San Diego, Los
Angeles, Phoenix. From there, to the Lakers' radio network, to the
Lakers' bench as an assistant coach, then as head coach, inheriting
one of the great teams in NBA history, anchored by Magic, Kareem
and Worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Riley fashioned the Knicks into his own image of a grinding,
nasty, mean team. Now Riley, at age 55, seems stuck. After nearly
20 seasons of coaching, four NBA championships, motivational books
and lectures, he seems stuck between gears. He pulls a rabbit out
of the hat every now and then, but no one thinks of him much as a
magician anymore. The Heat has not gone beyond the second round of
the playoffs since 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the Knicks swooped in on Miami and took away its
home-court advantage for the fourth consecutive year. The Knicks
have eliminated Miami the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's loss, Riley made an interesting point that goes
to the source of his and Miami's dilemma. He said the team worked
hard for 82 games to earn the home-court edge. ``We gave it all
back in one two-hour stand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That has become the Heat: tearing through the regular season,
going all out on a Wednesday night in December to win a meaningless
game. When the playoffs arrive, Miami is beaten down by the
intensity of its own heat.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is the coach and president of an empire he created. Like
so many icons and legends, Riley has lost track of time and a sense
of timing. One local talk-show host in Miami calls Riley ``Stand
Pat Pat'' because he has kept Miami's nucleus together so long. Too
long.
</P>
<P>
   Riley kept Hardaway one season too long even when all signals
pointed to the fact that the once-mercurial guard no longer
possessed the skills to take Miami close to the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird understands that success is dependent on players.
That's why he is getting out of coaching. No player can do what he
did in the clutch. So why bother? When Riley was in Los Angeles, he
was in awe of Kareem and Magic. With each successive head-coaching
job, he seems to have embraced a narcissism that puts him at the
center of every universe.
</P>
<P>
   Miami could come out these next two games and scorch the Knicks
and then go back to Miami and avenge the last two early exits.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not. The Heat is limited to a brawling, brutal style of
basketball that used to define the Knicks. But the Knicks have
added Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby while Miami stood pat.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is the last of the supercoach era, but his luster is
wearing thin, though there is always something captivating about
him. The Knicks-Heat soap opera has moved to New York for
Heat-inspired slugging and sloshing around.
</P>
<P>
   That phase of this drama is coming to a close. The other day
someone asked Hardaway how his injuries were affecting his play.
Hardaway said, ``I can see places I want to go, but I can't get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   A fitting portrait of the man who used to be the king of crunch
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
