<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAM PETTY KILLED IN NEW HAMPSHIRE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
 - PETTY-NYT   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam Petty, the only fourth-generation athlete in U.S. sports
and part of the famous NASCAR auto racing family, died Friday after
after a crash while practicing at New Hampshire International
Speedway. He was 19.
</P>
<P>
   Petty's car appeared to brush the wall on Turn 3 of the
1.058-mile track in Loudon, N.H., spin out and then slam into the
wall. Petty was preparing for Friday's qualifying for Saturday's
Busch 200.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of his red and blue No. 45 Sprint PCS Chevrolet had to
be cut open to remove him as the crowd looking on fell silent. He
was rushed to Concord Hospital, where he died of head trauma, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first driver's death at a NASCAR event since 1994,
when the Winston Cup drivers Neil Bonnett and Rodney Orr each died
in separate crashes at Speedweek in Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Petty was the great-grandson of one of stock-car racing's early
stars, Lee Petty, who won three season titles; the grandson of the
sport's most successful driver, Richard Petty, with seven season
titles; and the son of Kyle Petty, at 39 a Winston Cup series
regular and the head of Petty Enterprises. Lee Petty, 86, died on
April 5 after complications from surgery for a stomach aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty was headed back from Europe Friday with his daughter
and was unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   One snapshot that will endure is of Adam at age 1, being hoisted
onto Richard Petty's shoulders in Victory Lane after his
grandfather won the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``As young as he was, I think that day he decided he had such a
good time that he was coming back,'' said Chip Williams, a veteran
NASCAR publicist. ``All he ever wanted to do was race cars. I've
never seen anyone happier to be racing. Really, I've never seen
anyone happier to be doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he could not remember crying around the racetrack,
but he admitted that he cried on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a girlfriend,'' Williams said of Petty. ``He
put everything into racing, and he was one of the happiest guys on
earth. He would hate to hear me say it, but he was truly a sweet
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty began racing Go Karts at age 6. He made his NASCAR debut
at 17 in the Nascar Weekly Racing Series, competing in 25 races.
The following year, 1998, he got his initial Busch Series start,
finishing 27th. Last year he started in 29 Busch races, with no
victories and a high finish of fourth.
</P>
<P>
   This year in the Busch Series, his best finish was 12th in 11
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Enterprises' tentative plan, after it signed a deal with
Dodge to drive two of its cars when the manufacturer returns to
Winston Cup Series racing next season, was to have Adam Petty drive
one of them and try to win the rookie of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Petty's death may raise questions about what age drivers
should be and how much experience they should have before being
allowed to compete in the sport's upper echelon, where speeds can
approach 200 mph. Some argue that a famous last name can sometimes
serve as a dangerous shortcut to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is whether the corners at the newer tracks _
New Hampshire International Speedway opened in 1993 _ are too wide,
creating more risk of cars spinning out of control, as Petty's
apparently did.
</P>
<P>
   But those are issues for another day. On Friday, there was too
much shock.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR president, Bill France, issued a statement of
condolence, in particular to Petty's parents, Kyle and Pattie, and
his grandparents Richard and Lynda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pettys are an integral part of the sport of NASCAR,''
France said. ``The entire NASCAR community will miss Adam Petty.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran driver Sterling Marlin said he thought of the trauma
gripping the Petty family, with Adam's death coming so close after
his great-grandfather's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have really suffered some losses in the last few weeks,''
Marlin said. ``I know they are having a hard time right now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
