<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY LIKES WHAT HE SEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ With catcher Todd Hundley coming off the brutal and
frustrating 1999 season, a few months ago it didn't seem to matter
he would be a free agent at the end of the season, a remnant of the
Los Angeles Dodgers buying out his option shortly after he was
acquired in a 1998 trade.
</P>
<P>
   But an offseason of incredible work has turned around Hundley's
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   If his output continues, Hundley's switch-hitting bat,
especially his power from the left side, could make him a coveted
player, because teams want that pop in the middle of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth time in six games, Hundley homered, a two-run shot
in the first inning of the Dodgers' 13-0 win against St. Louis on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel normal again,'' said Hundley, who has nine homers and
25 RBI. ``I feel like I did a couple of years ago, before I got
hurt. The work I put in this winter is starting to pay off. That's
what I attribute it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Only left fielder Gary Sheffield has more homers (11) and RBI
(28) than Hundley, who's hitting .297. In his last seven games,
Hundley's hitting .304 (7 for 23) with five homers and 12 RBI. He
also has 20 RBI in his last 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt this good in a while,'' said Hundley, whose 41
homers in 1996 set a major-league record for catchers. ``I go out
there and expect to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Knowing your Park: Chad Kreuter will catch right-hander Chan
Ho Park today. The two have quickly developed a strong rapport. The
results have been an ERA markedly less with Kreuter calling a game
instead of Todd Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Park's ERA is 4.63 with Kreuter starting, as opposed to 7.31
with Hundley starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just how you deal with him,'' Kreuter said. ``Sometimes I
went out there and got mad at him. His first start in Montreal, I
yelled at him. He was letting it all slip away. I said, `If you
don't suck it up and get focused and get focused on me, you're out
of here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Other times I've told him that he had great stuff. The
situation dictates it. You have to be a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Throwing problems: As talented as Dodgers third baseman
Adrian Beltre is offensively, what truly excites everyone about the
21-year-old is his ability to play defense just as well.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's been a rough six weeks for Beltre in the field.
The Dodgers attributed many of his 29 errors last season to
inexperience and figured this year would be better.
</P>
<P>
   But through 33 games, Beltre leads the National League with 10
errors and his .903 fielding percentage is third worst in the
league. And many of the errors have come either by errant throws or
bobbles after fielding the ball cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Beltre said. ``I was working at it
in spring training and it was getting better. It's one of those
things. I don't know. I'm trying to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Reliever Gregg Olson rejoined the team after
undergoing an MRI Thursday in Los Angeles and now has been
instructed not to pick up a ball or 10 to 14 days. The MRI was
negative, but it showed a muscle strain causing inflammation near
his right elbow. The right-hander, signed to a two-year, $3 million
free-agent deal in the offseason, hasn't pitched since April 8 in
New York. . . . Eric Karros extended his hitting streak to seven
games with a fifth-inning homer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
