<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCRHON </SLUG>
  
 A DAY WITH GORE IN L.A. _ BLUE-COLLAR DIGS TO GATED PALACES  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore woke up Thursday at dawn in the modest
home of an East Los Angeles-area principal. Within an hour, he was
greeting kids at the Elizabeth Learning Center in Cudahy, where the
mostly Latino students are so poor that their parents usually work
two jobs and make less than $6,000 a year. Every child qualifies
for a free lunch.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours later and a universe away, darkness was falling
as Gore's motorcade glided through the gated community of Bel Air,
past homes so expansive they could have housed entire classrooms of
kids.
</P>
<P>
   He was raising political money, lots of it. So much that the 50
well-heeled attendees, sitting by candlelight on the rose-covered
patio overlooking the jeweled city lights, could easily write a
check for $10,000 each to the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Do the math: Each check was more than enough to support an
average Latino family at that inner-city school for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential campaign provides plenty of contrasts, and the
vice president's agenda Thursday underscored that dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   At the Elizabeth Learning Center, Gore greeted the neatly
uniformed children when they arrived for school, and he was there
when they left. Besides putting big smiles on some cute faces, Gore
highlighted for the national press the successes of a school where,
despite enormous poverty and challenges, 95 percent of the kids go
on to college.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side is the evening fund-raisers at
multimillion-dollar homes grander than anything most Americans can
imagine. Lavish events such as the one Thursday night close out
many of the days in this campaign, on both the Republican and
Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bel Air estate, a gated palace, reporters were trooped in
poolside after dinner to record Gore's remarks to the guests, who
donated $500,000 to the DNC. (Until then, the usual drill calls for
parking the media in the garage, along with the Jags and the Secret
Service.)
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes are revealing about a candidate, but here there's a
contrast, too.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fund-raisers, Gore's campaign is far more open
than that of Texas Gov. George W. Bush. The Republican raised $4
million last week in two private homes, speaking to just 170
people. Do the math there.
</P>
<P>
   But, by Bush's own dictate, no reporter is allowed to see the
candidate in such exclusive settings, or to report on what he says
to those donors.
</P>
<P>
   They're off limits to the media.
</P>
<P>
   They say the press corps covering the political campaigns gets
jaded. How jaded? On the way out to California, Gore went to the
back of Air Force II to chat with reporters, who lately have been
complaining that he hasn't given press conferences. But the movie
``American Beauty'' was playing on the plane. And, hey, it won a
slew of Academy Awards, after all. Bottom line: Reporters, well,
just weren't interested. Gore returned to the front of the plane,
outpolled by Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest question Gore got on his trip came from a young,
hip reporter from Channel 1, a school cable operation, who didn't
pull any punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our audience, you're a pretty old guy,'' the kid started
out, diplomatically. ``You were a teen once yourself. ... Can you
tell any stories that show you are down with teens?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was expecting Gore to say he was the Mack Daddy of
politics, and that the economy is still Da Bomb. But it didn't go
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is 17, and my youngest daughter is a senior in college.
Having been a parent to four children, I have remained pretty well
in touch with what I'm able to see going on,'' said the 52-year-old
Gore. ``This generation is absolutely terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Short answer for our teenage readers: ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
