<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-GUNS-COMPUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI COMPUTER PROBLEM HALTS GUN SALES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Md)  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Legal gun sales around the nation came to a halt
after a computer software malfunction at the FBI prevented instant
background checks of prospective buyers, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Thursday afternoon, gun store owners and the police
were unable to access the the FBI's Interstate Identification
Index, a database containing the criminal records of 36 million
people, said Steve Fischer, a spokesman for the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The problem involved a software malfunction at the bureau's
facility in Clarksburg, W.Va., and was not a result of computer
hacking, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI said the current breakdown of the criminal records
database was the longest to date. Technicians believe that the
system cannot be repaired until Saturday evening at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The malfunction also knocked out the system by which law
enforcement officials around the country use fingerprints to access
criminal records, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun dealers in different parts of the country complained to the
FBI that it was costing them business, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're also calling their congressional offices across the
country, and we're hearing from them also,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal background check, which can take place within
seconds when the system is functioning properly, was mandated by
the 1993 Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   Named for President Ronald Reagan's former press secretary,
James Brady, the law bars felons, minors and those convicted of
domestic violence from buying guns.
</P>
<P>
   In November, President Clinton credited the Brady law with
blocking more than 470,000 gun sales to ``felons, fugitives,
stalkers and others prohibited from purchasing firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association vigorously opposed the law,
however, arguing that it would not stop criminals. The association
also denounced the law as onerous for law-abiding gun store
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of gun stores said they had failed to complete sales
Friday. Some said they continued to accept paperwork for gun
purchases, and would run the background checks when the database
was again accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly getting in the way of business,'' said Ronnie
Ball, the owner of Dawson's Small Arms of the World in Annandale,
Va. ``People are not happy about it, but if it's a legitimate
computer breakdown, what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   At the Gentleman Hunter in Bethesda, Md., the owner, Art Harris,
told The Associated Press, ``We haven't lost any deals yet, but
Saturday is our biggest day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
