r a BC-PRESCRIBED-BURNS-SFCH     05-13 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESCRIBED-BURNS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FOREST MANAGERS DEFEND `PRESCRIPTION' BURNS  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN and CHUCK SQUATRIGLIA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an accidental inferno raged in New Mexico and some
politicians demanded an end to controlled burns, forestry experts
maintained Friday that ``prescribed'' fires are the only way to
prevent more disastrous wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos blaze has destroyed 191 houses, including about
100 duplexes, and scorched 30,000 acres since May 4, ignited
controversy over the practice of setting small fires to prevent big
fires.
</P>
<P>
   Forestry experts argue that prescribed burns of the type that
spawned the New Mexico fire and another on the North Rim of the
Grand Canyon are vital to managing the nation's wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no real alternative to prescription burning in the
intermountain West and the Sierra,'' said Jerry Franklin, a
professor of ecosystems studies at the University of Washington in
Seattle. ``When you don't use it, you increase the chance of
catastrophic ... fires significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Alamos may have an unfortunate effect on fire policy,'' he
said. ``But everything we do as a society involves some risk. There
are always probabilities of outcomes, and sometimes bad things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue there are other ways to thin the brush and scrub
that provide fuel for forest fires, and they want Uncle Sam to use
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government's controlled burn policy is out of
control,'' said Rep. Joe Skeen, R-N.M., who, like many
congressional critics of controlled burning, promotes logging as a
safer alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy, U.S. Secretary of the Interior Bruce
Babbitt and U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman imposed a
30-day ban Friday on prescription burning in the western United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Though the moratorium can be construed as governmental
soul-searching, it is not expected to bring a significant policy
change.
</P>
<P>
   That's because prescription, or ``controlled,'' burning is
considered by forestry experts to be the only way to maintain the
health of America's woodlands. Decades of wildfire suppression,
they say, encouraged rampant growth and ultimately made the fires
that did occur far worse.
</P>
<P>
   It is a paradox that burning forests makes them stronger. Forest
managers view the practice as an environmentally sound way of
reducing fuels on forest floors and thinning thick stands of
second-growth trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, fire removes older vegetation, reducing surface
fuel accumulations and greatly reducing the chances of a crown
fire,'' a type of blaze that races through the tops of tress with
explosive force, said Michael Hilbruner, a U.S. Fire Service
ecologist.
</P>
<P>
   The fires also return nutrients to the soil, stimulate
biodiversity and help some tree species germinate, Hilbruner said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when prescription fires go wrong, they can go very wrong
indeed. Los Alamos isn't the only evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   A prescribed fire set April 25 to clear grass and brush from
1,500 acres from the North Rim of the Grand Canyon jumped its
borders Wednesday and has scorched 7,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, firefighters in Northern California lost control
of a prescription burn on U.S. Bureau of Land Management land near
the Trinity County hamlet of Lewiston; the fire blackened 2,000
acres and destroyed 23 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Forestry experts said such accidents are no reason to end a
practice that is, by and large, beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in the business who are very experienced never get
any credit,'' said John Fort, director of the National Interagency
Prescribed Fire Training Center in Tallahassee, Fla. ``They're
trying to do the right thing by the environment and the public, and
the weather gets them every now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Watson, the regional director for California and Nevada for
the Wilderness Society, said his organization remains bullish on
prescription burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Views on fire have changed radically over the years,'' he
said. ``We once saw it as destructive; now we see it as beneficial.
Fire has helped shape the landscapes of the West. Any problems we
now have with fire have grown out of our overly successful policies
of controlling it in the past, which allowed fuels to build up.''
</P>
<P>
   As valuable as prescription burning is, it is not always easy to
manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, you're playing with fire, and sometimes it gets out
of control,'' Watson said. ``A lot of the problems are
weather-related, and you can't control how or when the weather
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos blaze has induced some politicians to call for an
end to prescription burning. Instead, they say, logging should be
used to thin fire-prone stands of timber.
</P>
<P>
   But logging alone won't do it, said Wally Covington, director of
the Ecological Restoration Institute at Northern Arizona University
in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need both,'' burning and logging, he said. ``Under the
dense forest conditions we're now seeing in many areas, there's no
way you can burn without getting a crown fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to thin, rake the litter away from the old-growth
trees, burn the slash (dead trees and limbs on the ground), then
continue low-level prescription burning on a regular basis,'' he
said. ``And you have to do it in landscape-size units _ 200,000
acres or more instead of the the 1,000-acre units we're dealing
with now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For more information on wildfires and prescription burning, go &LR; 
 &UR; to www.nau.edu/ecorest on the Web. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
