<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANDY FOR DREIFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Darren Dreifort found a way to give the Los Angeles
Dodgers' beleaguered bullpen a break. He gave them the night off.
</P>
<P>
   In his most commanding start of his career, Dreifort was staked
to a five-run lead before taking the mound and then overwhelmed the
most potent lineup in baseball, shutting out the St. Louis
Cardinals 13-0 on two hits Friday at Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's third career shutout was the Dodgers' first complete
game of the season. It also ended a losing streak at four games,
and a losing streak on the road at seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's pounding that ball down and not overthrowing it, I
don't care what club is out there, they're going to have
problems,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson. ``He controlled the
game. We have some other guys on the staff that can do the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green had a three-run double and Todd Hundley hit his
ninth homer of the season to stake the Dodgers to a 5-0 lead. Green
finished with two doubles and four RBI and Todd Hollandsworth and
Alex Cora each had three hits. Eric Karros added his ninth homer of
the season in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, the early lead was more than enough for Dreifort,
who allowed a first-inning double to Eric Davis and a single to
Fernando Vina in the sixth. Dreifort (3-1) faced two batters over
the minimum, and faced the minimum of 24 batters over the final
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was outstanding and I had a great rhythm with
Hundley behind the plate,'' said Dreifort, who threw 110 pitches.
``We had (second baseman Mark Grudzielanek) in the right spot a
couple of times. Everybody was outstanding. You can't ask for
anything more than that of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Dreifort's first shutout since Aug. 18, 1999, when he
beat Florida 7-0. Kevin Brown threw the last two-hitter for the
Dodgers on Sept. 4, 1999, in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``By far, it was his best outing of the year, obviously,''
Hundley said. ``But it was typical Dreifort. The first couple of
innings he was strong as a horse. Once he gets tired, then he has
control on his slider and changeup. It would be nice for him to go
down (to the bullpen) and throw for an hour before the game and
settle down. Once he gets tired, he settles down.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of his career, control's been a problem for
Dreifort. He has it mostly corrected, but now and again the
wildness will crop up. After the early lead, Dreifort experienced
those problems by walking Vina on four pitches. But the
right-hander's confidence was given a huge boost when Hundley threw
out Vina trying to steal. Vina was the second runner in 20 attempts
Hundley's caught.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed a two-out double to Davis, threw a wild pitch
and walked Mark McGwire before getting Jim Edmonds, the recipient
of a six-year, $57 million contract extension earlier in the day,
on a called third strike to get out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was as smooth an effort as Dreifort's had. He was
aided by double plays in the third, fifth and sixth innings, but
the Cardinals never threatened. No St. Louis runner made it past
first after the first inning, and Dreifort retired the last 10
batters he faced. He struck out six and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort's been throwing the ball well all year,'' Green said.
``It's nice to see him get that complete-game shutout. You don't
see that very much anymore. It's big for us, especially coming
after we lost four in a row.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
