r a BC-SCHOOL-INSPECT-AZR &LR;      05-13 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-INSPECT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL INSPEC TIONS COMPANY ASSAILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The company in charge of a mammoth statewide school
inspection is financially troubled and dogged by lawsuits from
creditors, raising serious questions about its work.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is refusing to pay any more on the $2.6 million contract
until Ohio-based Flex-Tech Professional Services re-inspects 303
schools. Reports from those schools were wrong, inadequate or could
not be produced.
</P>
<P>
   Accurate inspections are vital. They will be used to determine
how much money it will cost to bring Arizona's dilapidated schools
up to minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance policy purchased by the state is helping Flex-Tech
pay its bills while it tries to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions were raised when Flex-Tech's bid was being
considered, but were overlooked in an effort to hurry the
already-behind-schedule project along, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Flex-Tech, it seemed, was telling the state what it wanted to
hear: that it could inspect every school in the Arizona in four
months, and for at least $3 million cheaper than any other bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a construction company, and when several bids
come in at one price and one comes in much, much lower, there's
something wrong with that bid,'' said Rep. Jean McGrath, who
questioned Flex-Tech's ability to pull off the job when the Joint
Legislative Budget Committee approved the contract in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that they are just incompetent,'' McGrath said. &QL; 
COMPANY TO STAY ON &QL; 
The School Facilities Board oversees Students First, the
court-mandated plan to pay for school construction. The Board has
no plans to fire Flex-Tech despite its repeated missed deadlines
and inability last week to produce the work listed in an $800,000
bill to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Flex-Tech CEO Cecil Weatherspoon met with Facilities Board
officials Thursday and agreed to re-inspect schools whose reports
were not properly done. Weatherspoon did not return calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flex-Tech assured us they will fully meet the requirements of
the contract,'' said Phil Geiger, executive director of the
Facilities Board. ``We've given them additional time to complete
that and established a plan to have (Weatherspoon) meet with us
weekly to update everything.''
</P>
<P>
   John Deere Insurance Co., which insured the $2.6 million
contract, is helping Flex-Tech pay its employees and will help keep
it afloat until the job is done, Geiger said. Weatherspoon had
initially resisted getting a bond, and nearly lost the contract in
January because he was a month late producing the insurance, public
records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the story here is we were pretty damn smart to get a
bond, or we'd be out $800,000,'' Geiger said. ``We took all the
appropriate precautions and then some.'' &QL; 
SHAKY FINANCES EARLY ON &QL; 
Before John Deere stepped in, Flex-Tech's fortunes appeared to be
shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Flex-Tech saleswoman Shiela Ingram said she was fired Tuesday
after asking about her paycheck, which was five days late.
</P>
<P>
   In her termination letter, Weatherspoon cited ``financial
difficulties the company is currently temporarily experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said everything was depending on the state of Arizona
because it didn't pay us on this $800,000 invoice,'' said Ingram,
28, who worked at Flex-Tech's Sandusky, Ohio, headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Flex-Tech is also being hounded by creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Comptrol Inc., an industrial-components distributor in Garfield
Heights, Ohio, sued Flex-Tech on March 10. An attorney for Comptrol
said Flex-Tech owes $91,988 for products it hasn't paid for.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Accutech Corp. of Fulton County, Ga., sued Flex-Tech
for $3,985 plus interest. W.W. Granger Inc. of Niles, Ill., won a
$5,423 judgment against Flex-Tech in February in its 2-year-old
suit, an award which Flex-Tech has yet to pay.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how Flex-Tech looked financially when it bid for
the schools contract in November. But at least one of the
creditors' lawsuits had been filed at the time. &QL; 
CREDIT REPORT STILL MYSTERY &QL; 
Flex-Tech came highly recommended by its six business references,
but the State Procurement Office won't release a credit report it
commissioned on Flex-Tech at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic requested the report under the federal
Freedom of Information Act. The state has refused to release it.
</P>
<P>
   The office did not even show the report to the JLBC staff _
simply reporting that the report was ``adequate'' _ according to an
internal memo in the Flex-Tech file.
</P>
<P>
   Facilities Board head Geiger did see the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any lawsuits, but they were showing debt,''
Geiger said. ``There were comments about late payments to some
vendors but nothing that would rise to the level that would
preclude them from being a successful bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Another employee fired last week has little faith in Flex-Tech's
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Greer, a construction estimator who worked for Flex-Tech
in Phoenix from March until Wednesday, said the estimates to fix
many of the schools are inaccurate and based on speculation. He
said he was fired because he would not deliver estimates for what
he said were subpar inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a professional estimator and I couldn't ethically do what
they wanted me to do,'' Greer said. ``The assessors did such a
rotten job . . . I refused to put down bad numbers.'' &QL; 
OTHER RE-INSPECTION WOES &QL; 
Greer said the re-inspections ordered by the School Facilities
Board will be a tall order since many of the assessors were
retirees who have left for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger said he was aware of Greer's complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does not appear to be anything at this time that rises
to the point of impropriety or illegality,'' Geiger said. ``We know
there was vague and inadequate information in the reports. That's
why we're having Flex-Tech redo the estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   A random look at some of Flex-Tech's inspections reveals
problems even in assessments the Facilities Board considers
reasonably well done. Assessors must look into any problem
identified by the school as well as any problems they find.
</P>
<P>
   In some reports, serious problems identified by school officials
were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Cactus High in Phoenix listed problems with pooling rainwater
that has flooded buildings and ruined electrical circuits, as well
as malfunctioning bathrooms. The school's assessment does not say
if the problems are worthy of repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was dropped on this one,'' said Bob Reiss, a
technical advisor for the Facilities Board, referring to the Cactus
inspection. ``The school's concerns were ignored, so we're going to
have to send Flex-Tech back.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, Flex-Tech appeared to be headed for trouble from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Inspecting every school in the state and estimating a cost for
repairs would require a large workforce, plus expertise in
engineering, construction and architecture. Flex-Tech had little of
any. &QL; 
QUESTIONS RAISED AT START &QL; 
JLBC staff members questioned the use of Flex-Tech when the
contract came before the Legislature in December. But they
ultimately recommended approval because the state was months behind
schedule and the Legislature had set aside only $2 million to get
the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned about the size of the company and that they
didn't have substantial experience in this type of work,'' said
Richard Stavneak, JLBC staff director. ``What people are forgetting
is that, at the time, there was substantial pressure to begin the
process. Our only other alternative would have been to go back to
the Legislature to approve more money. This result is not
surprising, but we were hoping for better.''
</P>
<P>
   A bidder on the contract, Terracon of Tempe, contends that
Flex-Tech was able to low-ball its bid because it used
subcontractors almost exclusively to do the work. Jim Craven, the
firm's local manager, said he planned to use his people but did not
know until after the bid was awarded that he could have
subcontracted the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outfoxed,'' he said. ``Flex-Tech is an employment
contractor and they hire as they go. They have no people . . .
working for them. It's not illegal, but we could have done that if
we thought those were the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven said his company, which bid $6 million to do the
inspections, is interested in finishing the job if Flex-Tech
defaults. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Robbie.Sherwood(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-8146. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
