<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CHRISTIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN W. CHRISTIAN JR., FORMER HEAD OF B. ALTMAN, DIES AT 74 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., N.Y., N.C., Ohio)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John W. Christian Jr., a former president of B. Altman &AMP; Co.,
died Sunday at his home in Richmond, Va. He was 74. The cause was a
heart aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Durham, N.C., Christian graduated from Duke University
in 1948 with a degree in business. He then began his retailing
career at Thalhimer's, a department store chain based in Richmond.
In 1960, he became senior vice president and general manager of
Thalhimer's.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Akron, Ohio, in 1969 to become president of the M.
O'Neil department store chain, where he remained until joining B.
Altman's in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very interested in upgrading our designer presence,''
said Lewis Kaufman, who worked with Christian as the general
merchandise manager, and succeeded him as president in 1982.
Kaufman added that the store was one of the first in America to
have a Versace boutique.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Christian became chairman and chief executive of La
Vogue Inc., a chain of women's specialty clothing stores.
</P>
<P>
   Christian is survived by his wife of 51 years, Pauline; a son,
John W. III &UR; , &LR;  of Richmond; a daughter, Anne C. Collins of St.
Louis; a sister, Mary Ann C. Rogers of Durham; and four
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
