A3985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-SENATE-GOP-NYT &LR;      05-13 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOVES COME OFF IN N.J. GOP SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The Republican candidates for the U.S. Senate
barely uttered an unneighborly word about one another in their
debate Monday. But with 24 days left until the June 6 primary, the
knives have come out.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William L. Gormley, who has raised more money than
his three rivals but had spent little until this week, has begun a
direct-mail campaign assailing the record and character of United
States Representative Robert D. Franks. The other candidates are
James W. Treffinger, the Essex County executive, and Murray Sabrin,
a former candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In two full-color advertisements, Gormley portrays himself as a
tax-cutting conservative and Franks as an untrustworthy,
big-spending tax raiser in fiscal conservative's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The two ads seem lifted out of the pages of a supermarket
tabloid. In one, Franks is rendered as some sort of two-headed
alien. ``Doubly Dishonest,'' screams a headline.
</P>
<P>
   In another, a trim Gormley, shown head to toe, grins broadly
next to a headline proclaiming his support for ``37 tax cuts.'' It
brings to mind the kind of ad that might proclaim ``I lost 37
pounds!'' Among Gormley's specific claims about Franks are that the
congressman ``flip-flopped on impeachment,'' by first voting in the
House to impeach President Clinton and then signing a letter urging
the Senate to approve a deal to censure the president instead.
</P>
<P>
   In faxes to supporters and reporters, the Franks campaign is
responding by accusing Gormley of ``deceitful distortions and
lies.'' For example, Gormley also claims Franks ``missed 2,600
votes'' as a state assemblyman from 1980 to 1992, ``but showed up
to vote himself two pay raises.'' But Gormley voted for the same
pay raises, said Charlie Smith, Franks' campaign manager. ``I find
it inherently deceitful that someone would use against an opponent
issues that they held the same position on,'' Smith said. He added
that calling Franks cowardly and untrustworthy was ``over the line,
beyond the pale of debate that should be happening in a Republican
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   David J. Murray, a consultant for Gormley who specializes in
direct mail, defended the two mailings, saying, in effect, that
Franks had started the attacks. He referred to mailings that the
Franks campaign had sent to Bergen County Republicans weeks ago. In
those mailings, Franks was described as a ``real Republican,'' and
Gormley as a ``Florio Republican,'' insinuating that Gormley had
been cozy with Jim Florio, a Democrat, while Florio was governor in
the early 1990s. Florio is seeking the Democratic senatorial
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Murray also said that it was fair to fault Franks for raising
the national debt as a congressman, though Franks notes that he
later voted to reduce the debt by $1 trillion over five years.
``That's such hypocrisy, to say it's what I did last that
matters,'' Murray said. ``You don't get to determine the statute of
limitation on things.''
</P>
<P>
   The next Republican debate will be May 22, and Smith hinted that
it might be less congenial than Monday's initial encounter. ``I
imagine there will be an effort by all the candidates to draw
starker contrasts and engage their opponents in direct
comparisons,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
