r a BC-ELECTION-FLAKE-AZR &LR;      05-13 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-FLAKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMS TO FILE FLAKE COMPLAINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - The state Democratic Party announced Friday, May 12,
that it will file a complaint with the Federal Election Commission
accusing GOP congressional candidate Jeff Flake of violating
campaign-finance law.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came in response to a story in The Arizona
Republic on Friday, May 12, detailing Flake's $72,000 consulting
fee from the tax-exempt Arizona School Choice Trust, which was made
possible by a tax-deductible, $50,000 donation from Flake's
campaign-finance chairman, Valley developer Ira Fulton.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon press conference that was interrupted by a
surprise appearance by Flake, Democratic Party officials described
the arrangement as money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what appears to be a well thought-out plan to take
money from an individual, run it through a tax-exempt organization
. . . and into the pockets of a candidate,'' said Marty Harper,
general counsel to the Arizona Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said they will also lodge a complaint with the
Internal Revenue Service and the U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Charities are prevented under tax law from directly or
indirectly benefiting federal candidates and from providing
``sweetheart'' consulting fees to contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats made it clear that they believe Flake's biggest
mistake was tapping Fulton for the consulting fee. Fulton has a
long friendship with Flake and a penchant for charitable giving.
But he also has already contributed the legal limit to Flake's
campaign war chest and sits on the candidate's campaign
fund-raising committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we would be having this press conference if he
hadn't raised the money from his finance people,'' said Mark
Fleisher, state Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Flake squarely addressed questions from reporters about his
consulting arrangement, but sought to dismiss the matter as a flame
ignited by the news media and fanned by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it was silly of me to think the press would not be
cynical,'' Flake said. ``But the idea that we are trying to skirt
the law is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Flake said he has been working about 30 hours a week for the
trust, trying to network with large corporations to help establish
a new payroll-deduction program that could bring new contributions
into the trust.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Democrats of using his consulting fee as a
battering ram against school choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, and the reasons the Democrats are here today . .
. is because they are very much opposed to poor children being able
to go to the school of their choice,'' Flake said.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Democrats of making political hay over his job
rather than putting up a strong candidate to face the eventual
Republican contender in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats don't need an investigation, they need a
candidate,'' Flake said. ``It's as plain as day.''
</P>
<P>
   One member of the board defended Flake's intentions, but said
the candidate erred in failing to be sensitive to appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Flake made a mistake in not anticipating that people
would perceive something wrong with the money for the payroll
deduction effort coming from an individual involved in the
campaign,'' said Jay Heiler, a board member of the School Choice
Trust. ``When you are running for office, you must pay attention to
appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Flake's opponents were less inclined than Flake to blame
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Liddy, a Republican contender for the 1st Congressional
District who took a leave of absence from his law firm to run for
the office, said that, ``at a minimum, there is a perception
problem (with Flake's consulting fee).''
</P>
<P>
   ``If my advisers had come to me with this idea, I would have
said, `No way,' '' Liddy said. ``It just doesn't pass the smell
test.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0117EDT &QL; 
