<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-CHILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY ANGERED MOM LEFT CHILD, 8, AT MUSEUM FOR 6 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An 8-year-old Queens girl was abandoned by her mother
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art on Thursday and was found
wandering disoriented among the antiquities in the Egyptian wing,
police said Friday. The girl's mother was arrested when she
returned to pick her up six hours later.
</P>
<P>
   The child, Latisha Isaac, caught the attention of a guard
Thursday afternoon because she was alone and appeared anxious, a
museum spokesman, Harold Holzer, said Friday. The guard, Gregory
Monaco, asked the girl if she was alone, Holzer said, adding, ``She
said she was looking for her mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Paula Isaac, 40, of South Jamaica, Queens, had left
her daughter about 12:30 p.m., after the girl had gone to the
bathroom, according to a police report. ``Mrs. Isaac states she
left her child at the museum because she was mad at her for wanting
to go to the bathroom,'' the report said. Isaac wandered Manhattan
on foot for hours before returning to the museum about 6 p.m.,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Tall for her age and slim, Latisha appeared anxious but grew
more comfortable as guards walked her through the museum, trying to
find her mother, Holzer said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl had been searching on her own for about an hour. ``She
spent the whole time looking for her mother,'' a police official
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the guards could not find the mother, they called the
police at the Central Park Precinct, Holzer said. Before the police
arrived, the girl spent her time with museum staff members, at one
point sitting with volunteers in the circular information booth in
the museum's cavernous lobby, where she drew pictures with crayons.
</P>
<P>
   Latisha seemed calm and relaxed once she was with museum staff
members, Holzer said. ``She was very articulate, very poised,'' he
said. After 45 minutes at the information desk, he said, she
announced that she was hungry and was taken to the museum staff's
cafeteria, where she had a bologna sandwich, a taco and some fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the museum staff could call her father, the girl said,
``He's not here,'' adding of her mother, ``She's a single mom,''
Holzer said. Isaac later told the police and prosecutors that her
husband died of cancer about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were drawing up a criminal complaint last night
charging Isaac with endangering the welfare of a child, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   When Isaac returned to the Metropolitan about 6 p.m., she asked
the guards at the front door whether a lost child was inside,
Holzer said. The guards referred her to the Central Park Precinct,
where she was questioned by detectives and arrested. Her daughter,
whom police had taken to Lenox Hill Hospital for a medical
evaluation, was pronounced in good health and placed in the care of
the city's Administration of Children's Services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-FLEMING-NYT &LR;      05-13 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FLEMING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUS FLEMING, A LINCOLN CENTER DIRECTOR, DIES AT 56 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill.)   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gus Fleming, the director of concert halls at Lincoln Center
since 1988, and before that the company manager of the Lincoln
Center Out-of-Doors Festival and a line producer of the JVC Jazz
Festival, died May 6 at his home in Mount Vernon, N.Y. He was 56.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McMahon, a spokeswoman for Lincoln Center, said the cause
was cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As director of concert halls, Fleming oversaw the day-to-day
operation of Avery Fisher Hall and Alice Tully Hall and was
involved in everything from the installation of new production
technology to marketing and box office systems.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, whose full name was John Payne Fleming, was born in
Chicago in July 1943. Both of his parents, John A. Fleming and
Helen Payne Fleming, were physicians, and his father was also an
alternate to Jesse Owens at the 1939 Olympics. He received a
bachelor's degree in history from the University of Rochester and a
master of fine arts from New York University.
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn to the arts first as an actor and performed in
several Broadway and Off &UR; - &LR; Broadway productions, including ``No
Place to Be Somebody,'' ``Jimmy Shine'' and ``Operation
Sidewinder.'' He also had roles in several films, including
``Serpico.'' From 1977 to 1983 Fleming was an adjunct professor of
speech and theater at John Jay College in Manhattan. During his
years at the college, he developed a program that took theater to
the inmates at Rikers Island. He also produced an off-Broadway
play, Dennis McIntyre's ``Split Second.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming was also involved in several musical projects. As a
performer, he played bass and sang in the Wickers Creek Bluegrass
Band. And he was a producer of the Grande Parade du Jazz in Nice,
France.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Lincoln Center as the company manager for its free &UR;  &LR; 
multidisciplinary Out-of-Doors Festival. Among the events he
produced were a Folk Heritage Day and a Blues and Gospel Day. In
1984, he and Coleman Barkin started the Roots of American Music
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Kimberlee Kimes; three sons, John
Nicholas, Joshua and Samuel; a daughter, Helene Elizabeth; a
stepmother, Clara Fleming of Chicago; and a sister, Dorothy
Ohlendorf of Gales Ferry, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
