<HEADLINE>
HEARD THE ONE ABOUT NEWARK TURNING HIP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ On a recent Thursday evening, at the grand opening of
Maize restaurant, a crowd of men in five-button suits and young
women wearing Prada and DKNY mingled over passed hors d'oeuvres of
tuna tartare, sipping glasses of Gray Goose vodka. As a jazz singer
in a spaghetti-strap dress sang ``La Vie en Rose,'' flashbulbs
captured the smiles of young artists and musicians, next to the
beaming mayor, two former governors and the ageless baseball icon
Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   It may have looked like the opening of the latest bistro on Park
Avenue South or Spring Street, but what made the gathering notable
was that it wasn't in Manhattan at all; it was in downtown Newark,
a city not much known for chichi restaurants and the clientele to
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this incredible energy of young artists and writers
and musicians coming here, drawn to the realness of the city,''
said Verushka Spirito, a young woman with a Sinead O'Connor
haircut, who stood at the bar with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of Maize, located at 50 Park Place, inside the
historic Robert Treat Hotel, was certainly a big event by Newark
standards; it is easily the most fashionable restaurant the city
has seen in years, with a sleek, airy dining room, cigar lounge and
tearoom, and an executive chef, Pat Kotsonis, whose resume includes
Le Bernardin and Bouley.
</P>
<P>
   It's another indication that a city long moribund, an easy
target of late-night monologuists (``First prize is one week in
Newark; second prize is two weeks in Newark'') is reawakening.
Besides an economic resurgence and ambitious real estate
developments, Newark is seeing a much less publicized flowering of
artists, writers and musicians _ honest-to-goodness bohemians. Hard
to believe, but it may be transforming itself into a cool city.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night, Queen Latifah _ the rapper, actress, talk
show host and Newark native _ gave a record-release party for her
Flavor Unit Entertainment stable of hip-hop artists at Groove, a
local nightclub. She is negotiating to develop the Griffith
Building on Broad Street into luxury apartments, a restaurant and a
nightclub. Shaquille O'Neal, the National Basketball Association's
most valuable player, sneaks back to his native Newark from Los
Angeles for soul food at Je's Restaurant on Halsey Street, and he
is also looking to invest in the city, said Mayor Sharpe James.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have swirled that Robert De Niro is taking over a
waterfront restaurant, though De Niro's partner in the TriBeCa
Grill in Manhattan, Drew Nieporent, said he was unaware of any such
plans. Well then, maybe James Gandolfini should think of buying
into a riverfront bistro; after all, his Tony Soprano _ inarguably
the coolest character on television today _ came by his childhood
neuroses in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the Jersey chic of ``The Sopranos,'' however, that is
luring artistically inclined young people to inner Newark. Nor is
it the recent building boom that includes a new baseball park where
the minor-league Newark Bears play and a downtown arena that will
be home to the New Jersey Nets and the Devils by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, young transplants cite the reasonable rents and
15-minute trip to Manhattan by New Jersey Transit train; the
vibrant mix of Portuguese, Spanish and Brazilian restaurants and
bars in the Ironbound section, and a grass-roots fine arts and
music scene, which even draws New Yorkers on a reverse night-time
commute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of friends that come out from Brooklyn and
Manhattan for Sounds of the City,'' said Elisabeth Ssenjovu, a
programmer of events at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center, of
the free outdoor series she oversees. It begins June 1 and features
spoken word, rap, reggae, Latin jazz, Dominican and Haitian music.
``It's Sounds of the City, not sounds of the suburbs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence P. Goldman, the president of the three-year-old
performing arts center, which normally books top national artists
like the Mark Morris Dance Group, pointed out that the home-grown
outdoor series has played an interesting role in the city's social
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge young middle-class now in Newark _ white,
African-American and Hispanic _ for which there had previously been
no civic gathering place,'' he said. ``Basically, what Newark
really needed was a good singles scene. That's what Sounds of the
City provides, and it doesn't require police or security guards,
all it requires is young people willing to meet each other and have
a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there are skeptics. Many Manhattanites, familiar with
the stigma of crime and urban decay that has long hung over this,
New Jersey's largest city and still one of the poorest in the
state, refuse to believe there's a new Newark. ``Get out of here,''
said Chris Hulbert, a publicist, who has represented trendy New
York clubs like Hush and Ohm. ``There's no way Newark is cool.''
</P>
<P>
   But to spend an afternoon and evening with Ssenjovu and some of
her friends is to get an unmistakable taste of the East Village on
the Passaic River. There is a thriving literary movement, ranging
from the online Newark Review to a spoken-word series whose host is
Ras Baraka _ a son of Amiri Baraka, the former LeRoi Jones _ at the
Lama Lounge on Linden Street.
</P>
<P>
   There's the smoky, couch-filled Euphoria Cafe _ located in the
shadow of the Prudential Insurance Co.'s global headquarters at
Broad and Academy Streets _ that draws a dreadlocked collegiate
crowd (and even some of the suits from Prudential) to poetry slams.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Ssenjovu, 24, tall, lean and wildly energetic,
seems to embody the hip side of Newark. ``I grew up in the Jersey
suburbs, in Union County,'' she said. ``My family's originally from
the Ironbound. They're Italians who moved out to the suburbs, and I
guess I've come full circle now.'' She lives with her husband,
Patrick, a Ugandan-born actor and performer, in a renovated
chocolate factory in the Ironbound, which got its name from the
rail lines that encircle it.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Voulgaris, the owner of Maize, who was born and raised
in Kalamata, Greece, said she has waited years for the city's
long-trumpeted renaissance to finally take hold. ``I got excited
about three years ago in all the activities upcoming in Newark, and
I decided that's where I wanted to invest in and to stay,'' she
said. When the arts center opened, ``there was no doubt in my mind
that it was no longer just a dream _ it was a reality,'' she
continued. ``I'd say that the difference I've seen in three years
is breathtaking. There are streets where nobody ever wanted to be
around 6 p.m., and now people freely walk around at 10 or 11
o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, Harper's magazine called Newark, which never
fully recovered from the rioting of the 1960's, the ``worst city in
America.'' Its vast tracts of housing projects inspired the
nickname Brick City. Nowadays, violent crime is down more than 50
percent from 1995, and real estate values in the immigrant-heavy
Ironbound have risen 30 to 40 percent since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As they toured the streets of the working-class Ironbound,
Ssenjovue and her posse of friends, including Fernando Baptista,
born in Portugal, and Khabirah Myers, a native of Newark, jokingly
acknowledged that they have the look of a walking Benetton ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's just my generation, or my group of
friends, but everybody seems to be in an interracial
relationship,'' Ssenjovu said. ``My husband and I feel very
comfortable here, he being African, me being white. I've traveled a
lot, but this is the first place I feel is home. I lived in Berlin,
I lived in London. I certainly don't feel at home in the suburbs,
but it's weird, I really feel at home in Newark.''
</P>
<P>
   Lori Barcliff, a young African-American who also works at the
performing arts center, said, ``My family came to Newark in the
'30s; my grandparents lived in the West Ward, near South Orange
Avenue.'' After attending college in California and living in
Florida, she returned to New Jersey to live in the Ironbound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the cafe culture that's on Ferry Street,'' she said.
``You go to the grocery store, the bakery, the Portuguese fish
market, and you can basically do all your shopping on Ferry Street
and not have to get in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about recent high-profile investment in the city,
including the 11-acre sports arena site that also calls for bars,
shops and restaurants, Ssenjovu said with mock horror: ``Just
please don't say we're the new Hoboken! That's my biggest fear in
the world.'' She sees Hoboken as a case of gentrification run amok.
``Newark's still got an urban flavor that I don't think will be
changed by that, it's still really edgy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spirito agreed. ``You don't want people moving in and all these
yuppie bars erupting and suddenly you're losing the Brazilian
flavor and the Portuguese flavor,'' she said. ``You'll lose the
Haitian community and the Cuban community. That's what makes
Newark, and we have to make sure it stays.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Newark has been known as a hip-hop and rhythm and
blues hotbed, spawning such artists as Redman, Canibus, Faith
Evans, Rah Digga and Lauryn Hill, whose remembrances of her
childhood there are captured in her song ``Every Ghetto, Every
City.'' (``Every ghetto, every city and suburban place I've
been/Make me recall my days in the New Jerusalem.'')
</P>
<P>
   At his desk in the Beaux-Arts City Hall, which has served as the
backdrop for Hollywood films like ``Presumed Innocent,'' James
said, ``Many of these up-and-coming rap artists have gained
strength through struggle, have stepped over a crack vial, stepped
over a hypodermic needle, and onto the stage of life.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0126EDT &QL; 
