<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NEWARK-2NDTAKE-$ADV14     05-13 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWARK-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEWARK: stage of life.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The city's greatest living cultural figure, however, is a Newark
expatriate. From his debut novel, ``Goodbye, Columbus,'' in 1959 to
his latest, ``The Human Stain,'' Philip Roth, a product of Newark's
Weequahic section, has ``turned his bleak part of Jersey and its
people into a kind of Jewish Yoknapatawpha County,'' Robert Stone
wrote in a review of an earlier novel.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's Newark is a spectral one; the lower- and middle-class
Jewish milieu has largely vanished, and his references to
contemporary Newark can be biting. ``My father was one of those
Prince Street guys who loved that city all his life,'' recounts
Swede Levov, the tragic hero of ``American Pastoral.'' ``What
happened to Newark broke his heart. It's the worst city in the
world ...'' He adds: ``Used to be the city where they manufactured
everything. Now it's the car-theft capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fictional reminiscences, circa 1995, are now out of date.
For one thing, Newark no longer leads the nation in car theft. Many
of the 19th-century factories that housed the city's leather,
garment and toy manufacturers are seeing a rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as the temperature topped 90 degrees, Ben Polsky
paced around his fourth-floor loft in a factory building on New
Jersey Railroad Avenue, wearing shorts and flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   Polsky, 34, is a painter, who shares a 3,500-square-foot loft
with his wife, Holli Schworno, 35, also an artist. ``The scene here
is very organic,'' he said. ``The artists who have come to Newark
are a lot less interested in meeting a bunch of other artists down
at a cafe; they're interested in having enough space to work and
still have some semblance of a family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally from Miami, Polsky moved to Newark eight years ago
from New York's Lower East Side. He and Schworno came before the
economic boom, when it was still possible to rent 3,000 square feet
for $600. While rents have risen substantially since then, huge
artistic spaces in the Ironbound still cost a fraction of those in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, ``what they call artists' lofts all look like
multimillion-dollar Ikea ads,'' he said. His loft, across the
street from the elevated railroad tracks separating the downtown
from the Ironbound, is undeniably authentic: stiflingly hot,
paint-splattered, strewn with art-making debris. He smiled and
sopped the sweat from his forehead as a New Jersey Transit train
whirred past his window at eye level. ``We call that our toy
train.''
</P>
<P>
   Polsky still hears the skepticism from his Brooklyn and
Manhattan friends about Newark's newfound hipness. ``We get that
all the time,'' he said, ``and quite frankly I hope it continues.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
