<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ALAMOS: CINDERS, DESPAIR
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARY JO PITZL AND JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(SANTA FE, N.M.) _ It will be at least a week before the 11,000
displaced residents of Los Alamos will be allowed to return to
their fire-scarred town.
</P>
<P>
   So, when local radio stations announced where people could
discover whether their homes were still standing, evacuees spilled
from hotels and friends' homes, creating a traffic jam on New
Mexico 502 at the turnoff to Pojoaque High School.
</P>
<P>
   There, they found Red Cross volunteer Marion Johnson standing on
a chair, yelling out the addresses of the 260 homes destroyed by
this week's ``Cerro Grande'' fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, Ridgeway! I'm still doing Ridgeway!'' Johnson shouted.
Then louder, ``I'm still on Ridgeway! I haven't gotten to another
street!''
</P>
<P>
   In the mountains above, the fire continued to grow across 32,000
acres, singeing the edges of the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   One woman waited for the bad news, then stood shaking in the
crowd, holding her lunch: a salad with dressing that rippled as she
shook. Her husband stood next to her, stroking her hair. She walked
downstairs, away from the crowd and sat on an Army cot, head in her
hands, crying.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Blossom found her home was not on the list, though houses
on either side of hers were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the power of prayer,'' she said, bouncing up and down
and glowing. ``That's what it was. I asked him to put up a hedge or
some kind of protection, and I knew he would.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur Bergquist couldn't believe his house wasn't on the list.
He kept scouring the pages taped to the wall, fingering each line,
saying his address over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be totally gone,'' he said. ``Up
until now, I was thinking that I was going to have to rebuild
everything.'' &QL; 
FLOOD OF SUPPLIES &QL; 
They wiped out the underwear selection at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   They toted toiletries, hauled hay and carted canned goods until
the governor, of all people, had to stand up and publicly say, ``No
mas!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Cross has asked me to make you aware that they can't
handle any more clothing or food,'' Gov. Gary Johnson said Friday
afternoon. ``Right now, we need some money.''
</P>
<P>
   New Mexicans opened their hearts, wallets and truck beds to
bring supplies to victims of the Cerro Grande fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing things, and it's really making a devastating
time better,'' said Julie Pugsley, a Los Alamos evacuee.
</P>
<P>
   Julie and her husband, Robert, were staying at an Albuquerque
hotel, courtesy of her employer, US West. The company also picked
up their cleaning tab.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers from throughout northern New Mexico pitched in to
round up animals stranded by the fire and house them in a makeshift
animal shelter at the Santa Fe Rodeo grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Pugsleys found their 3-year-old cat, Shasta, at the rodeo
shelter Friday, after searching two kennels for their lost pet. The
reunion was joyous, even though the couple were unsure of the fate
of their home.
</P>
<P>
   Robert was hopeful, saying he had seen the intact roof of their
home on a television news clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a spruce tree in front that's 30 feet tall, and the
grass is green,'' Pugsley said. ``You walk 50 feet to the right,
and the house is down to its foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Julie was pessimistic. She had just spied their neighbor's
address on a list of 191 Los Alamos homes destroyed by the
wind-whipped blaze. &QL; 
MARVEL AT GENEROSITY &QL; 
Throughout Santa Fe on Friday, fire victims marveled at the
generosity of their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might all be a little crazy around here, but when there's a
problem, people here really come together,'' said Talina
Melenchenko, as she shushed a crowing rooster at the animal
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   She had traveled from Madrid to pitch in, giving Gatorade to
refugee rabbits and slicing up apples for the chickens. The shelter
overflowed with donations from area residents.
</P>
<P>
   Sacks of dog chow were piled high, rivaling the height of nearby
bags of cat litter. Rugs, blankets and sheets abounded for bedding.
Outside, Diann Mills was drying off one of the scores of animal
carriers that volunteers had donated.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who evacuated her Los Alamos home Wednesday, said
pitching in was better than sitting in her hotel room. Besides, she
said, working was a way to delay learning about the fate of her
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed with everybody,'' Mills said. ``I heard
they estimated it would take 10 hours to get people out of town,
and it took four hours. I was just proud of everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Law, Met Haynes and Ryan Boudrie are the pride of their
Los Alamos families and friends. The three young men drove through
the spreading Los Alamos fire Wednesday, ferrying out livestock and
pets. Their three trips rescued 15 horses, 11 bulls and two goats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could touch the windows on both sides of my truck and they
were hot,'' Law, 17, recalled. The flames rose up on both sides of
the road like a tidal wave, and smoke obscured all but a few feet
of road, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned home after the animal rescue, Law said he had
no interest in watching television coverage of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been there, done that, driven through it, don't want to do
it again,'' Law said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporters at Judd.Slivka(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8097; and MaryJo.Pitzl(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8963. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
