<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, May 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE (Washington) _ New evidence has been published
that appears to undermine the testimony of two central witnesses
who said American soldiers were ordered to kill civilians near the
No Gun Ri bridge during the Korean War. Senior Defense Department
officials said that the new documents and testimony will not deter
the Army's own investigation of the July 26, 1950, incident that
led to what the Pentagon called the ``tragic death of hundreds of
civilians.'' The Army investigation was sparked by a series of
articles published by the Associated Press that won the Pulitzer
Prize this year. By Elizabeth Becker and Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-PAKISTANIS (Rangpur, Bangladesh) _ The world
ceaselessly churns out human tragedy. The newly conquered. Newly
dispossessed. Newly hungry. Newly diseased. Newly destitute. One
calamity overtakes another, and the 240,000 ``stranded Pakistanis
of Bangladesh'' know they are the leftover unfortunates of distant
yesterdays. For 29 years, they have been spread across this nation
in 66 squalid camps, each a tightly packed thatch firetrap. They
live as refugees, though theirs is a more peculiar predicament.
They did not leave their country; their country left them. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 and map are being sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEADOFFICIAL (Beijing) _ China's top foreign exchange
regulator, who was rumored to be involved in a corruption scandal,
died after he fell seven stories from a hospital window. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen has sent a letter to Senate leaders sharply criticizing a
proposal to withdraw funding for U.S troops in Kosovo by next July.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLO-DEFAMATION-SUIT (Denver) _ What began as a dispute over the
behavior of pet dogs has escalated into the biggest legal threat
ever to hit the Anti-Defamation League, a $10.5 million jury
verdict against the organization for comments that its Denver-area
director made defending a Jewish couple who claimed their Catholic
neighbors were anti-semitic conspirators, plotting to harm them and
their children. The case, now on appeal, raises issues of privacy,
defamation and the purpose of the ADL. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   PA-GUNS-POLITICS (Beaver County, Pa.) _ It has become
conventional wisdom among Democratic strategists that the Million
Moms March for gun control this Sunday will be good for Vice
President Al Gore in his quest for the presidency. But the
conventional wisdom does not apply in this Ohio River county.
Nestled in the shadows of shuttered steel mills 20 miles northwest
of Pittsburgh, Beaver County has been a Democratic bastion since
the New Deal. It is also a haven for hunters, Second Amendment
devotes and the National Rifle Association, Gore's sworn enemy. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   MOMS-MURDER (Pine Bluff, Ark.) _ This weekend hundreds of
thousands of mothers will gather in Washington D.C. for the Million
Mom March, a protest against gun violence in America. We visit the
mothers of murder victims in this down-and-out little city that in
1997 and 1998 was the per capita murder capital of the nation. This
is murder in America at its most typical and extreme. Typical
because it is down and out, and in the South, the region that leads
the nation in murders. The mothers we talked to don't really know
about the march. But they know a lot about murder. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NABISCO-ICAHN (Undated) _ Carl Icahn has said he is willing to
pay $22 a share for Nabisco Group, which owns 80.6 percent of
Nabisco Holdings, the maker of Ritz crackers and Mallomars. Icahn,
a financier who has made several runs at Nabisco, disclosed his
plan in a regulatory filing on Thursday but stopped short of a
formal offer. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-TELEFONICA (Madrid, Spain) _ In Spain's corporate world,
with its cozy relationships and closely knit elite, it might have
seemed that Juan Villalonga's greatest asset as head of the
national phone company was his boyhood friendship with the prime
minister, Jose Maria Aznar. But Villalonga, the 47-year-old
chairman of the company, Telefonica, has also made his way on his
own. In the process, Villalonga has made Telefonica a darling of
investors. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Anne M. Mulcahy, the new president and
chief operating officer at Xerox Corp., is often mistaken for Carly
Fiorina, the chief executive of Xerox archrival Hewlett-Packard.
And Mulcahy gets a huge kick out of playing off the parallels. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-SUVS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Across the Detroit area and in
Washington, people were trying Friday to interpret Ford Motor Co.'s
bold acknowledgement that it faced a dilemma in balancing sales of
highly profitable sport utility vehicles with the company's desire
to be a good corporate citizen. In an industry with a long history
of resisting safety and environmental advances like seat belts, air
bags and catalytic converters, Ford's forthright stance took many
by surprise. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WPP-Y&AMP;R (London) _ Sir Martin Sorrell finally achieves his goal
of the last decade: creating the world's largest advertising
company. His company, WPP Group, confirmed Friday that it is buying
Young &AMP; Rubicam, allowing WPP to leapfrop over Omnicom Group and
Interpublic to be king of the hill. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
