<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTING MUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's 550-foot news-and-views edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News: Major League Baseball officials have finally responded to
the barrage of home runs by launching an investigation into the
juiced baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Views: This is like sending officials of Shell to study what
caused the Exxon Valdez oil spill. It's baseball's version of the
Warren Commission and single bullet theory.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the 2000 ball is wound tighter than Dick Vitale.
I knew it the first time I saw a hitter at Dodgers Stadium hit a
pop foul over the upper deck. Confirmation came a day later when
another foul soared in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with home runs, but baseball is pushing
its luck by laying it on so thick. The current rate of 2.6 home
runs (and 10.7 runs) will set new records if they hold up. Records
have already been set for most home runs in a day (57), week (262)
and the month of April (931).
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 5,528 home runs were a major league record, a year
after Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa blew up the single-season
records, which came a year after the Rockies (239) and Mariners
(261) set new N.L. and A.L. records for home runs by one team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have hit 74 home runs in 34 games, and I can
remember when Busch Stadium was considered a pitcher's park.
</P>
<P>
   It just cheapens the game. Baseball's zealous mission to convert
looky-loos into fans with a barrage of fireworks threatens to anger
the choir. News: Some critics suggest raising the pitching mound
from its current height of 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It wouldn't bug me if that happened. Baseball lowered it
from 15 inches to 10 in 1969 and survived the change. But I can
offer a four-point plan that's easier to implement.
</P>
<P>
   1. Give the black of the plate back to the pitchers. Once upon a
time, umpires rewarded pitchers who could work the ball along the
edges. Now they squeeze it the other way.
</P>
<P>
   2. Enforce the strike zone as written in the rules. This would
return the high strike to the game, since the rules say the top of
the strike zone is the letters. As it's called now, any pitch an
inch higher than the belt is a ball.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove all body armor from hitters. Every time I see Barry
Bonds walk up to the plate with that kevlar on his arm, I wish a
pitcher would plunk him in the ribs. 4. Create a standard on the
height of the seams of the ball. Give pitchers something to dig
their fingers in to and it would compensate for the tightness of
the leather. The current balls are as smooth as a baby's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   News: Randy Johnson beats Kevin Brown 2-1 in an old-fashioned
pitcher's duel.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Anyone who watched the game and came away bored is
welcome to return to soccer. It was great baseball. I'll take the
sight of a masterful pitcher overwhelming big men with sticks over
450-foot lollipop fly balls any day.
</P>
<P>
   News: The NCAA announces plans for a Home Run Derby as part of
the opening festivities at the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Here's an example of the epidemic. Two years after
aluminum home runs became a mockery at the 1998 World Series,
leading to length-to-weight ratios for metal bats in 1999, college
baseball is again embracing Gorilla Ball. Stop the insanity!
</P>
<P>
   News: Padres pitcher Rodney Myers is out for the season after a
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Views: If you saw the video of Myers' foot sticking to the
astroturf in Cincinnati, then you will agree that artificial turf
must be banned immediately. With so many advances in synthetic
grass fields, there's no excuse for digging up every last stitch.
</P>
<P>
   News: NHL playoffs reach Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Views: And look who happens to be coaching in them -- Larry
Robinson. I'm certainly not going to criticize the Kings for moving
in another direction after Robinson's mild tenure . Andy Murray had
a good first season and Dave Taylor already has made some great
moves as G.M. But whatever ailed the Kings and Robinson isn't
affecting the New Jersey Devils with him as their coach. Maybe the
Kings didn't work hard enough for Robinson. Maybe his steady style
is more effective with teams on the east coast, where there are
fewer winter diversions. I'd like to see Robinson and the Devils
win the Stanley Cup, if only because he's a class act who readily
accepted all blame for the Kings' failures. There's all kinds of
redemption at work in the NHL playoffs. If the Philadelphia Flyers
make it to the finals without Eric Lindros, it will put Bobby
Clarke back atop the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers' Hall of Famer and G.M. went on the power play when
it came time to take Lindros' captaincy away from him. Patrick Roy
and Ray Bourque are the redemption stories for the Colorado
Avalanche, and the Dallas Stars would be looking to prove last
year's win was more than a skate in the crease. Of course, based on
TV ratings, 99 out of 100 Americans think the Stanley Cup is what
Stanley wears when he's asked to play catcher.
</P>
<P>
   News: Tommy Lasorda is named head coach of the U.S. Olympic
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Views: I just want to be there when some reporter from South
Korea asks Tommy his opinion of Kim's performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
