<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-NYT &LR;      05-13 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT ROUND GETS CLOSER FOR O'NEAL AND LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Los Angeles Lakers held off the Phoenix Suns with
free throws and spoiled a 31-point effort from Penny Hardaway to
take a 3-0 lead in their Western Conference semifinal series with a
105-99 victory Friday night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored 37 points and grabbed 17 rebounds, and
Kobe Bryant added 25 points. The Lakers hit 35 of 51 free throws
and can sweep the best-of-7 series if they win here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, Glen Rice and Brian Shaw combined for six straight free
throws that gave the Lakers a 102-97 lead with 37.5 seconds
remaining to finish off the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Baskets by Luc Longley and Shawn Marion gave the Suns a brief
95-94 lead, before O'Neal made a strong move inside to put the
Lakers back in front as the teams traded leads.
</P>
<P>
   Two clutch plays lifted the Lakers into position to beat the
Suns. With his team trailing by 91-90, Ron Harper of Los Angeles
missed two free throws, but O'Neal rose above the rim for a
left-handed tip-in to put the Lakers ahead by one. After Hardaway
missed a jump shot, Bryant hit a short jumper for a 93-90 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had pulled the Lakers into an 87-87 tie on a 3-point play
with 6 minutes 8 seconds left, putting his team into position to
close out the series with one more victory.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in Game 2, the Suns appeared in control late in the third
quarter, this time holding a 72-65 lead with three minutes
remaining. Then again, the Suns had not beaten the Lakers in two
playoff games and four regular-season meetings, so doubt still
lingered.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, the Lakers closed the gap to a single point at
76-75. Shaw finished the 11-3 rally with two free throws after
being fouled by Todd Day with two-tenths of a second to go.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two points at halftime, the Suns briefly rattled the
Lakers with an 11-2 run to start the third quarter, taking a 61-54
lead. From there, Longley scored three straight baskets, but the
Suns could not extend their lead past seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, the first half amounted to an O'Neal free-throw
exhibition. The Suns tried bearhugs from Oliver Miller, forearm
shivers from Longley and a flying tackle by Kevin Johnson, but
O'Neal made them pay every time. O'Neal, perhaps preparing himself
for some rough tactics from the Portland Trail Blazers in the
Western Conference finals, smoothly sank 8 of 10 free throws while
scoring 16 points and leading the Lakers to a 52-50 halftime lead.
He finished the game 9 for 15 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   With six minutes remaining in the second quarter, O'Neal's
driving bank shot sent Longley sprawling and capped a 17-6 run that
gave the Lakers their first lead at 35-33. The center had plenty of
help from the outside, too. After failing to hit a 3-pointer in the
first quarter, the Lakers drilled five of them in the second
quarter, getting two each from Robert Horry and Rick Fox and one
from Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Horry sparked the Lakers early in the second quarter, scoring
eight points in 90 seconds, including his two 3-pointers that cut
the Suns' lead to 30-26. Bryant also came alive, scoring 8 of his
12 first-half points in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway and Cliff Robinson led the Suns with 14 points each.
The Suns, believing they could beat the Lakers on the fast break,
ran as much as possible in the first quarter, grabbing a 28-18 lead
behind Hardaway's eight points and Robinson's seven. Better defense
and the quicker pace helped neutralize O'Neal, who led the Lakers
with seven points but scored only one basket. He was 5 of 6 from
the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   With the Suns in their face from the start, the Lakers shot 27
percent in the quarter, making 6 of their 22 attempts. The Suns,
who opened with a 15-3 run and led by as many as 12 points, were 10
of 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers quickly regained their shooting touch, putting the
Suns back between O'Neal and a hard place. With Bryant, Rice and
Horry tuning up their jump shots, the Suns' early lead evaporated
like water in the desert heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All bets are off right now,'' Suns coach Scott Skiles said
before the game. ``We'll do whatever we can to stop Shaq, but not
at the expense of leaving guys open all over the place. They've
proven they can hit the big shots from anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
