<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-13 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CONSPIRACY REALLY RIDICULOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHOENIX _ Pssst, did you hear? In defiance of the league's
trading moratorium, the Los Angeles Lakers reportedly have acquired
for their title run a sixth man more valuable than Rodney Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The proud, paranoid people of this city swear this late pickup
is the one killing the Suns, not Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry? A.C. Green? Neither has a thing on this Conspiracy
fellow. That's how he was identified in the local media Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Con-spir-a-cy.
</P>
<P>
   Guess he's so big, his surname is superfluous. You know, like
Michael or Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this major player, this series stealer, happens
to be invisible to everybody except Phoenix fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you wonder: Is that Oliver Miller or Oliver
Stone taking up all that space on the Phoenix bench?
</P>
<P>
   The description of this Conspiracy character that appeared in a
local newspaper profile Friday was of a monster spawned in David
Stern's laboratory expressly to destroy small-market teams like the
scrappy Suns in the name of higher ratings.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, then Conspiracy is the one who has hounded
Luc Longley into 10-for-26 shooting and re-routed all 12 of Rodney
Rogers' three-point shots away from the basket in this
best-of-seven Western Conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   Following Phoenix's logic, Conspiracy also is the one with his
teeth inJason Kidd's left ankle. And he must have been the one who
stepped on Cliff Robinson's foot in the third quarter, thereby
forcing him to the bench with a twisted ankle on the heels of an
inspired performance.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3 at America West Arena, Conspiracy evidently was the
one clearing the perimeter of Phoenix players so Robert Horry had
an unobstructed view of the basket for the jumper and two
three-pointers he knocked down in the first 90 seconds of the
second quarter to shake the Lakers out of a stupor that induced a
10-point deficit after 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest while, it looked like perhaps Conspiracy was a
scratch on this evening. You know: DNP _ Commissioner's Decision
(same as in NewYork, where the smaller-market, scrappy team from
Miami beat the Knicksin overtime on the strength of Anthony
Carter's questionable basket).
</P>
<P>
   But on the strength of clutch free-throw shooting down the
stretch, theLakers prevailed 105-99 to take a commanding 3-0 series
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who put together winning streaks of 16, 19, and 11
games during the regular season en route to compiling the league's
best mark (67-15), had lost their previous four road games, dating
back to April 5.
</P>
<P>
   We guess Conspiracy only suited up for games at the Staples
Center before Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The very idea that NBA officials tilt games in favor of
large-market teams to help the ratings is so ludicrous as to be
laughable. It certainlytickled the funny bone of Phil Jackson, who,
contrary to what the Phoenix fans would have you believe, did not
go to the NBA Finals all 11 yearshe played in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful idea,'' Jackson said, sarcastically claiming
Conspiracy as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson understands where underdogs get these wild ideas. It's
the officiating, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball umpires may influence the outcome of a game by how they
frame the strike zone, but they call only balls and strikes, not
personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   With a few quick whistles, a basketball referee can put a player
on hisheels better than can the best defender.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case for O'Neal, who got caught a couple of times
in the paint standing as still as the figure on his league MVP
statuette. He picked up his fourth foul with 6:56 remaining and had
to tread lightly the rest of the way. That's not easy when you're
7-foot-1 and 335 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the eighth-year center finished with 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, all the Lakers did a lot of standing around on
offense, turning the triangle at times into a quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   And yet they manufactured a victory anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Phoenix fans will start seeing clearly now. The plain
truth, even if they refuse to recognize it, is that consistency and
constancy have carried the Lakers this far, not any conspiracy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
