<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET CLOSER TO SWEEP OF SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The heroics, this time, looked different.
Lessspectacular, less prepackaged and made-for-SportsCenter. But
the results were no less impressive, no less damaging to the
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting 47 minutes of a back-and-forth affair, the Los
Angeles Lakers finally inserted the dagger in the final minute and
15 seconds Friday night, making nothing but free throws to slowly,
surely push the Phoenix Sunsto the edge of elimination, turning a
one-point game into a 105-99 victory at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That's three Laker victories and zero for the Suns in this
best-of- seven series, with the Lakers going for the sweep on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal once again led the way, with 37 points and 17
rebounds, and he came through at the foul line, hitting 9 of 15,
including 1 of2 with 26.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, the hero of Game 2, struggled from the field,
making 8 of20, but scored 25 points and contributed two free throws
of his own down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also got a boost off the bench, with Robert Horry
contributing 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway scored 31 points for the Suns, who also got 23
points from Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had a 12-point lead in the first quarter, but neither
team had firm control at any point after that. For most of the
fourth quarter, they simply exchanged 1- and 2-point leads.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two games of the series, the Suns were
essentially atwo-man team. But they finally found a few other
options to supplement Penny Hardaway and Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers, the NBA's Sixth Man of the Year, but an invisible
man in this series so far, reappeared when his team needed him
most. Though still without a 3-pointer in the series, Rogers found
other ways to help,scoring 9 points through the first three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Clipper paced the Suns in the fourth, scoring 6 of the
their first 13 points, but he fouled out with 26.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been one of our keys, is to slow him down,'' coach Phil
Jackson said. ``But as I've said before, benches come alive on the
homecourt.The bench, the road is not as easy for them. And
tonight's a measure ofwhether we can hold Rodney Rogers in check or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Lakers had not won on the road since
April 5, though that was a slightly misleading statistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are numbers, but we've only played four (road) games in
five weeks,'' said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   All four were losses _ two in the final week of the regular
season, when the Lakers were just cruising to the finish, the
second two at Arco Arena, in the Lakers' first-round series with
the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'd like to win on the road,'' said Jackson, whose team
went 31-10 away from Staples Center this season. ``We know we have
to reach that point where we have that ability to win on the road.
It's important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the ability to win on the road that gives you a
measureof `us against them,' it's the idea of winning against odds,
it's playing your best for your team and all those things I think
create a good atmosphere for a basketball club.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Lakers who entered halftime with a slight lead,
52-50, but it was Phoenix that controlled the game for most of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns blitzed the Lakers early, on the scoreboard and in the
paint.They aggressively double-teamed O'Neal, and he promptly
missed 5 of hisfirst 6 field-goal attempts under the duress.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed the Suns to take an early 12-point lead, and with
the Lakers making just 6 of 22 from the field, Phoenix held a 28-18
advantage by the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Robert Horry changed the game almost single-handedly. Horry
started off the second quarter by scoring 8 quick points, including
back-to-back 3-pointers, to cut the lead to 30-26.
</P>
<P>
   With the Suns continuing to crowd O'Neal, long-distance shooting
suddenly became the Lakers' savior. Rick Fox also hit a pair of
3-pointers, and Glen Rice added one of his own as the Lakers took
the lead back and maintained control through the end of the half.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, in turn, got more room to operate and scored 7 points in
the final 3:18 of the second quarter, finishing with 16 points and
eight rebounds in the half. Half of his points came at the foul
line, where O'Neal_ shooting 44 percent in the postseason _ made 8
of 11 attempts. He made 3 of his last 4, after a pair of quick
intentional fouls from OliverMiller.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored 12 points in the half, making 4 of 10 shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
