<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     05-13 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX BEAT ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ORIOLES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ With the man who spanked him, Frank Robinson,
watching from a seat behind the plate and injured teammates Nomar
Garciaparra and Carl Everett confined to the visitors' dugout
Friday night, Pedro Martinez switched back from punishee to his
accustomed role of punisher.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the poor Baltimore Orioles, who never had a chance. A night
after completing his five-game suspension for hitting Cleveland's
Roberto Alomar after being forewarned that was a no-no, Martinez
set down the first dozen Orioles and last 14 Orioles in order,
struck out 15, and allowed just one runner to second base in a
two-hit, 9-0 demolition of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Was he making a point to F. Robby, the Hall of Famer who is
baseball's avenging angel _ the official title is vice president,
on-field operations _ because he slapped him with the suspension?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Martinez, who barely pitched inside all
night. ``He understands the way I am. He understands about
baseball. I don't have anything to say to him. What I have to say,
I say in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez tied an American League record for strikeouts in
consecutive games with 32. Martinez, who already did it last year,
shares the honor with Luis Tiant (Cleveland, 1968), Nolan Ryan
(California, 1974), and Randy Johnson (Seattle, 1997). The major
league record for whiffs in three consecutive games is 47, set by
Ryan in '74. Martinez's next start is scheduled for Wednesday night
in Toronto against the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox ace, who recorded his first shutout of the season, has
allowed just one run in his last 26 innings. He has not allowed
more than two earned runs in any of his seven starts, and has had
just one inning out of 53 1/3 this season in which he has given up
as many as two runs. And one of those runs was unearned, the result
of a second-inning error by first baseman Mike Stanley April 25 at
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's only hits Friday night came in the fifth inning on a
ground single through the right side by Albert Belle to start the
inning and a soft single to center by Jeff Conine. Belle had never
gotten a hit in 13 regular-season at-bats against Martinez until he
topped a 1-1 pitch between first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who did not walk a batter, struck out every Orioles
batter, getting catcher Greg Myers and Maine's Mike Bordick three
times apiece. He whiffed five in a row in a span that began with
the last out of the seventh and ended with Bordick's strikeout to
start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan had advised another Hall of
Famer, former Orioles pitcher Jim Palmer, that he was in for
something special Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were pretty good,'' Kerrigan teased his former teammate,
``but watch this guy tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And what would he have told Palmer after the game? ``You were
pretty good,'' Kerrigan said, ``but this guy is on another
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 48,354 in Camden Yards was on its feet when
Martinez ended the night by striking out Delino DeShields, the man
for whom he was traded from the Dodgers to the Montreal Expos after
the 1993 season. DeShields made a feeble offering at the last of
Martinez's 113 pitches in a game that required just 137 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That gave him plenty of time, as he made his way back to the
dugout, to borrow a pen from a cop and sign a ball tossed to him by
a female fan.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, beaten, 1-0, by Tampa Bay in his last start despite
striking out 17 Devil Rays in a route-going performance, raised his
record to 6-1 while lowering his earned run average to a
microscopic 1.01. That's more than a run below the No. 2 man in the
league in ERA, James Baldwin of the White Sox (2.34), and four runs
below the league average of 5.12.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of support for Martinez despite the
absence of Garciaparra, who went on the 15-day disabled list with a
strained left hamstring, and Everett, who is day-to-day with a sore
right quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God Petey is pitching,'' closer Derek Lowe had said
before the game, ``but we've got good enough guys to pick up the
slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Good call. The Sox, winners of five of their last six and eight
of their last 11, banged out 16 hits in sending the Orioles to
their fifth straight loss. The Sox gave Martinez a 2-0 lead even
before he went to the mound and wrapped it up with a four-run ninth
that included a three-run home run by Brian Daubach, his seventh of
the season and second in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff man Jose Offerman had his first four-hit game of the
season, including a leadoff home run in the fifth. He also scored
three runs and knocked in two. Darren Lewis, playing center field
in place of Everett, had three hits, including a push-bunt single
in the first that served as catalyst to the Sox' two-run rally
against loser Sidney Ponson.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon had two hits and two RBIs, Mike Stanley had two
singles, and Daubach had a double and a run-scoring fielder's
choice, giving him four RBIs on the night.
</P>
<P>
   But the night, as it invariably does when he's pitching,
belonged to Martinez. ``That's as dominant as I've ever seen him,''
said Orioles manager Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, remember, was sitting in Cleveland's dugout last
October on the night of the Martinez Milagro (Miracle), when he did
not give up a hit over the last six innings in the deciding game of
the 1999 American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps pitching like this, he'll win 30,'' said Hargrove,
echoing the same refrain Martinez heard at the All-Star break last
season, when he was 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Martinez has not made more than 33 starts in any
season, Hargrove's projection is far-fetched. But he's allowed.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson wasn't sitting among the paying spectators, he was
hopping from one broadcast booth to another while Martinez worked
his magic on the Orioles. Martinez was asked if Robinson had made
any attempt to contact him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What for?'' the Sox pitcher said.
</P>
<P>
   In case Robinson wanted to explain himself, was the reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came over and said hello, like he usually does, and kept
walking,'' Martinez said. ``I just said hello and kept watching
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he was watching couldn't touch what came on later, live
and in prime time: The Pedro Martinez Show. Miss it at your own
peril.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4018 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-13 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAIRS' HOMER IN NINTH SINKS SASAKI AS WELL AS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Kazuhiro Sasaki, closer.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki was scorched for a three-run, game-winning homer by Matt
Stairs in the ninth inning Friday night as the A's stole first
place in the AL West from Seattle with a 9-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that performance with the game-losing two-run homer
Sasaki gave up to Texas' David Segui on Wednesday, and Seattle
manager Lou Piniella had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sasaki earned the closer's job in spring training,'' Piniella
said. ``He just lost it tonight. From now on, we're going to have a
bullpen by committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to close with whoever I feel like closing with.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, the Mariners have lost three games
in a row. And in all three games, the Mariners have blown the lead
late in the game. Sandwiched between the two Sasaki losses was a
game-losing homer that lefty Arthur Rhodes gave up to Jason Giambi
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took a 7-6 lead into the ninth with Jose Paniagua
having thrown two shutout innings in the wake of a go-ahead RBI
double by John Olerud in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Sasaki looked shaky from the start. He gave up a single to
rookie Terrence Long on a 1-1 pitch, then saw Randy Velarde bunt
Long into scoring position. Sasaki then missed with back-to-back
pitches to major league RBI leader Giambi, at which point Piniella
opted to walk Giambi intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   It goes against the book to put the go-ahead run on base, but
the thinking was sound. Stairs is limping around these days and
hasn't been hitting. Giambi is hitting everything. If Sasaki could
get Stairs to go after a forkball, a double play seemed likely.
</P>
<P>
   That was a big if.
</P>
<P>
   Stairs, hobbled by a left knee injury, hadn't driven in a run in
May. But the squat lefty is the master of the big homer in the late
going, and he did it again, launching a 1-0 pitch into a parking
orbit in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Of more significance to the Mariners was the fact that Sasaki
has done the same thing in his past two appearances. He's missed
with his forkball, then he's gotten hammered when he tries to come
back with his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   This development could mean a return to closing status for
almost any of the Mariners relievers. Jose Mesa had 33 saves last
year and Rhodes did occasional ninth-inning work for Baltimore the
past few seasons. And Paniagua Friday gave the M's two of the most
clutch innings the club has gotten in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good out there,'' Paniagua said after having missed a
couple of games because of back spasms. ``But we'd all feel a lot
better if we hadn't lost that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Piniella and fellow manager Art Howe of Oakland
were talking baseball near the cage during batting practice. One of
the subjects of the conversation was how, in the American League
West this year, no lead was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Mariners and A's went out and put those words into
practice. Seattle took a 5-0 lead, squandered it all and went back
ahead on Olerud's double in the seventh before Stairs put the issue
to rest.
</P>
<P>
   The victory pushed the A's into the lead in the AL West by a
half game over Seattle, the Mariners falling out of the division
lead for the first time since April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez, perhaps inspired by a sign carried throughout
the Coliseum by a couple of young ladies reading, ``Alex Rodriguez
is a hottie,'' continued his hot-hitting ways. He drove in a run
with a sacrifice fly, another with a double and a third with an
infield single.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Rodriguez's flying feet that gave the M's their final
lead.
</P>
<P>
   After his infield single in the seventh tied the game, Rodriguez
scored all the way from first base on Olerud's double to get the
lead back for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Also making a huge contribution was DH Edgar Martinez, who
stretched his hitting streak to 11 games with a single and a
three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The loss couldn't be laid entirely at Sasaki's door.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had a chance to break the game open in the top of the
ninth when the Mariners loaded the bases with no outs. But the
middle of the M's order _ Olerud, Martinez and Jay Buhner _
couldn't get the ball out of the infield, and Sasaki had no margin
for error.
</P>
<P>
   And, earlier in the game, starter John Halama had a 5-0 lead but
gave most of it away in a five-batter stretch by walking four men
and hitting another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sailing along, and then that,'' Piniella said. ``I
don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Halama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you what happened, but I don't know,''
Halama said. ``All of a sudden, I couldn't throw a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours and five innings later, neither could Sasaki. When he
finally did, Stairs launched it for the stars.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
