<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKESID-LADN-(SLA     05-13 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKESID-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SNOWBALL'S CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There was a pulse but not much. There was a lament,
but it was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns know what they have to do after their 105-99
Game 3 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday night _ just beat
the team with the league's record four consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   So the Suns tried to hold their heads up, tried to talk brave,
but it was hard not to sense the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can win,'' said Suns guard Penny Hardaway.
``Once we get one, we're going to try and make it a snowball
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to quit. It would be easy just to fold it in
and say, `Let's go home,' and let 'em have it. But we're going to
make 'em work.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Suns know they have all that bad history facing them.
No team in NBA history has ever come back from a 0-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel like we can beat them,'' said Suns center Luc
Longley. ``But tonight we had too many dumb plays, bad plays. I
really feel we can do a better job on Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the safest assumption of the night, since
Shaquille O'Neal scored 37 points and had 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the way O'Neal scored nine of them that was still
irking the Suns. O'Neal took 15 free throws, making nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the foul line kept them in the game in the fourth
quarter,'' Hardaway said. ``You shoot 20-some free throws in the
fourth quarter alone, that's going to keep you around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. It's a situation where you put yourself in
there, play tough defense and try to be physical, and this is the
playoffs _ and they get bailed out at the free-throw line. It's
already tough enough to stop these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot 51 free throws on the night _ 23 in the fourth
quarter. The Suns took 34 free throws overall, eight in the final
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been that way the whole series,'' said Suns forward
Rodney Rogers. ``There's nothing we can do about it. We go out
there and play our hearts out and leave everything on the floor,
and it's the same results all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley struggled terribly against O'Neal in the first two games
in L.A., started slowly Friday, but hit four field goals to give
the Suns the lead in the third quarter. Even if he did feel a bit
handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an official tell me tonight not to lean on Shaq,''
Longley said. ``I really don't know what you're supposed to do. I
kept leaning on him. If you can't lean on him, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Like you're not, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Suns aren't in a very big way after Friday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix actually played well. Hardaway scored 31 points, Cliff
Robinson 23, and even Rogers showed improved play after two
miserable games in L.A., scoring 15 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were down 100-97 with less than 30 seconds to play,
when Hardaway missed a three-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to take a dribble and then fade away with it, and
you can't shoot it that way,'' Hardaway said. ``But if I was in
that situation again, I'd take it again. It hit the front of the
rim and just came off.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over, they were left down 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you play anybody when you're down three
games,'' Rogers said. ``No matter what we do or try, it seems like
we're not supposed to win. We just have to find a way right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 0300EDT &QL; 
