<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NEWLAKE-LADN-(SLA     05-13 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NEWLAKE-LADN-(SLANG)...WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS NEARING SWEEP OF SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The heroics, this time, looked different. Less
sectacular, less spine-tingling, less tailored-for-SportsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive rebounds, offensive hounding and swished free throws
won't make too many highlight shows _they certainly lacked the
flair of Kobe Bryant's game-winning jumper in Game 2 _but those
ordinary plays carried the Lakers for the final two minutes of Game
3 Friday night as they slowly, methodically drained the life out of
the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   With a grind-it-out 105-99 victory at America West Arena, the
Lakers snatched a 3-0 lead in this best-of-seven conference
semifinal series and pushed the Suns to the brink of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers came here looking to win one of two, but getting that
victory immediately makes all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one means you've got a chance to end it. If they
would have had this game, they would have had hope that they could
tie this thing up,'' Ron Harper said. ``Now, since they're down
three games, they know they got a long hill now.''
</P>
<P>
   That uphill climb is a battle against the odds, and history. No
NBA team has ever come back from an 0-3 deficit to win a
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, the Suns will yet have to find a way to slow Shaquille
O'Neal, who hit his average in this series by scoring 37 points to
go with 17 rebounds. Bryant, in an encore to his Game 2 theatrics,
scored 10 of his 25 points in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they played extremely well, I think their confidence
was high,'' Bryant said of the Suns. ``I think we got a couple
lucky bounces here and there and they missed a couple big shots
late in the game, but other than that they were right there with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that's the toughest part for the Suns. For two
straight games, they had a victory in their hands, only to see it
disappear in the closing minutes, or seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a desperate situation right now,'' said Phoenix guard
Penny Hardaway, ``but it's not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway led the Suns with 31 points, and Clifford Robinson
added 23, but no one could come through down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made all the key plays in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Down a point with 4:17 to go, Robert Horry missed two free
throws, but O'Neal sneaked in to tap in the second miss for a 92-91
lead. That seemed to give the Lakers a boost, though Phoenix took
one more lead, 95-94, on a Shawn Marion jumper with 2:50 to go.
</P>
<P>
   But then a penetrating Bryant found O'Neal for an easy dunk.
Harper blocked a Luc Longley attempt, leading to a 24-second
violation with 2:07 left. The rest was a blur of Suns fouls and
Laker free throws. Bryant made a pair, Rice made a pair and Brian
Shaw made a pair to stretch the lead to 102-97 with 37.5 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers and Robinson missed consecutive 3-point tries,
O'Neal corraled the rebound and made 1 of 2 free throws to help
seal it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good sign for the Lakers, who watched O'Neal make 9 of
15 from the line after hitting just 44 percent to date in the
playoffs. He also survived a few intentional fouls designed to
force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about the hack-a-Shaq,'' he said. ``I haven't
worried aboit it all year, so I'm not going to start worrying about
it now. I don't think I've really been struggling, I just haven't
been hitting them. I hit them when I need to hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had his own struggles and finished 8 of 20 from the
field. But he came through at the end, including a 3-point play
that tied the game midway through the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A critical play, Kobe's play to tie the game,'' said coach
Phil Jackson. ``It put that game in a position where we could play
it to our level.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant, ``I was just waiting for the fourth quarter.
Whenever you struggle like this, there's something about the fourth
quarter, there's something about the crowd on a road game behind
their team that just clicks, and you know you're going to bust
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's down to a one-game affair, Sunday at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long weekend for them, waiting for that Sunday game,''
Jackson said. ``This is the exciting part about it for us, that we
have this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But are the Suns already done?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' Harper said. ``They're a team who goes out and goes
hard. I don't think they're going to lose hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
