<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4038 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-RE     05-13 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENJOY THE SHOW. TEST WILL FOLLOW. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(editors: 1st graf should be italicized)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``But Heisenberg, Heisenberg! You also have been deflected! If
people can see what's happened to you, to their piece of light,
then they can work out what must have happened to me! The trouble
is knowing what's happened to you! Because to understand how people
see you we have to treat you not just as a particle, but as a wave.
I have to use not only your particle mechanics, I have to use the
Schroedinger wave function.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Frayn's play ``Copenhagen'' arrived on
Broadway last month, a three-character drama about the
philosophical implications of quantum physics that Ben Brantley,
chief theater critic for The New York Times, called ``the most
invigorating and ingenious play of ideas in many a year.'' But does
anyone understand it?
</P>
<P>
   Frayn imagines the conversations that might have taken place
between the physicists Niels Bohr and Werner Heisenberg, on a night
in 1941 when the two scientists men met in German-occupied
Copenhagen. Bohr had developed the ``old quantum theory'' of atomic
matter; Heisenberg announced the famous uncertainty principle in
1927. These and 22 other dates and theorems are in a timeline
(written by Frayn) contained in a Playbill foldout. Sample entry:
``THE WAVE EQUATION. 1926 Schroedinger finds the mathematical
equation for the wave interpretation, and proves that wave and
matrix mechanics are mathematically equivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh huh. Not since Tom Stoppard threw together James Joyce, Lenin
and Tristan Tzara in ``Travesties'' in 1975 have audience brows
been lifted quite so high.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn uses the Bohr-Heisenberg meeting, and the uncertainty
principle, to show the unknowability of all things. But what  &UR; is &LR; 
the uncertainty principle?
</P>
<P>
   We put that question to some members of the audience at a
performance of ``Copenhagen'' and to several people involved with
the production, as well as one genuine scientist. No Cliff Notes
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Grisiatis, freelance press agent: ``Oh, jeez. You're
talking to the wrong person.'' Grisiatis looked in panic at his
companion outside the Royale Theater during intermission at
Wednesday's matinee. Nonetheless, he bravely advanced a definition.
``You can never predict. You can only take an educated guess on
certain things. Is that about right? Science was never my strong
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Hodges, creative director: ``I understand what he's telling
me to understand, but I don't understand how a particle can be a
wave and a particle.'' Hodges works at SPOTco, the design studio
that produced the Playbill timeline. He recalled Jeff Goldblum in
the movie ``The Lost World,'' saying that the uncertainty principle
meant something like, ``You can't study a thing without changing
it.'' He said: ``It's like on Broadway there'll be someone someone
hates and someone someone loves, depending on your experience of
that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Vanarendonk, retired United Nations official: ``You
cannot identify a particle at the same time,'' he said, drawing
thoughtfully on a pipe at Wednesday's matinee. ``In other words,
the movement, if you want to freeze it in time, then it is a
particle. But, if you want to understand. . . . Let me put it this
way. . . . It's quite difficult to conceptualize. You can identify
you by placing you in time and place. The particle you cannot put
at the same time in the same time and place. And that is the
uncertain_'' he cut himself off.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymous audience member: ``I'm very distracted by all the
noise here on the street,'' she said, struggling to explain
uncertainty. ``I don't understand it, no. Are you recording this?''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Bosco, who plays Bohr: ``There is nothing explainable in
the universe at the deepest level of science,'' he said. ``In the
quantum mechanics and the nuclear physics that we're talking about,
whatever you observe changes the nature of what you're observing.''
Bosco, let it be noted, confessed to some initial skepticism about
the play's appeal and difficulties memorizing his more technical
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cumpsty, who plays Heisenberg: ``I would say it means
you can't know the location and velocity of a particle at the same
time, or, to extrapolate, in its theoretical form, as Heisenberg
says in the play, of anything,'' he said. ``If you want to
understand the physics you're going to have to go off and read a
book,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Greene, author of ``The Elegant Universe'' and a professor
of physics and mathematics at Columbia University: ``As developed
in 1927 by Heisenberg, it tells us there's a fundamental limitation
about and on what we can possibly know about the microscopic realm
_ where something is and how fast something is moving,'' he said.
``We can't know both of these things with absolute precision.'' As
for Frayn's science, ``It looked good to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Frayn, playwright: While the play was in previews in New
York he received a letter from a confused audience member who wrote
that ``She couldn't understand a word of the science and if I
didn't remove it, the play wouldn't last long on Broadway,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-RE     05-13 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPENHAGEN-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENJOY THE SHOW. TEST WILL FOLLOW. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(editors: 1st graf should be italicized)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
