<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-13 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 14:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LABOR (Washington) _ The American labor movement is
mounting its biggest lobbying campaign ever on trade matters in
seeking to defeat the Clinton administration's effort to normalize
commerce with China. Unions are holding dozens of meetings on
Capitol Hill, putting intense pressure on individual legislators
back in their districts, staging rallies and writing huge numbers
of letters across the nation. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-INTERNET (Ina, Japan) _ The Internet is quietly
transforming Japan, making celebrities of small farmers, empowering
women, changing the way people apply for jobs and schools and
generally chipping away at traditional patterns of behavior. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-WARLORDISM (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ With the
apparent collapse of a nine-month-old peace accord, Sierra Leone is
on the verge of slipping back into warlordism. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-SANKOH (Undated) _ In the wake of fighting among
rebel groups and government troops in the capital of Sierra Leone,
officials loyal to President Ahman Tejan Kabbah are beginning to
amass documents they say shows the extent to which the rebel leader
Foday Sankoh was systematically exploiting the country's diamonds
to pay for his rebellion and enrich himself. ``Terrible people in
history keep very good records,'' a high-ranking government
official said in a telephone interview Saturday. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BORDER-EXECUTIONS (Mexico City) _ In 1995, after being
acquitted by a Texas jury of cocaine trafficking, Alberto Ochoa
Soto, a reputed member of a Colombian drug cartel, was released
into Mexico, where he was greeted by his lawyer, witnesses said. As
the two men met on a bridge, however, a Chevrolet Suburban drove up
and several men with Mexican Federal Judicial Police credentials
seized Ochoa and the lawyer. For five years, little news emerged to
clarify the men's fate _ until last week. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-WAR-CRIMES (Djakovica) _ With winter over, international
teams have resumed their digging in Kosovo, searching for bodies
and other clues that would back the indictment of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and four of his top allies in Serbia
on charges of genocide committed before and during NATO's bombing
of Yugoslavia last spring. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-FATIMA (Fatima, Portugal) _ Pope John Paul II goes to
Fatima Friday afternoon though Saturday, his third pilgrimage to
the shrine that contains the bullet that failed to kill him on May
13th, 1981, the feast day of Mary. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-ENTREPRENEURS (Dortmund, Germany) _ Time was, in this
region, Grandpa worked for Krupp, Dad worked for Krupp, and if
Junior did not work for Krupp too, everyone was aghast. Here in the
heartland of German heavy industry, the big companies took care of
you, and employment was for life. Think again. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTIONS (Austin) _ Special Report: Gov. George W. Bush
is certain that the 127 people who have been executed in Texas
during his tenure were all guilty. But interviews with officials
who help administer the death penalty in the state, all of whom
believe in the death penalty and support Bush, reveal that the men
and women whose jobs involve reviewing case records, considering
inmates' appeal and weighing their final pleas for clemency are
less sanguine than Bush about both the fairness of the state's
judicial system and the risk Texas runs of executing innocent
people. By Sara Rimer and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   With EXECUTIONS-CASES, sidebar on six cases.
</P>
<P>
   MOLECULAR-FARMING (Undated) _ The production of drugs in
genetically altered plants _ called molecular farming or
biopharming _ seems poised to represent the next wave in
agricultural biotechnology. Until now, efforts have mainly been
directed at protecting crops from pests and improving the taste and
nutrition of food. But just as the production of bioengineered
foods has been controversial, molecular farming is already raising
some safety and environmental concerns. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ORLEANS-TERMITES (New Orleans) _ Formosan subterranean
termites with an insatiable taste for irreplaceable historic
structures have been devastating the French Quarter, drawn to its
moist, porous bricks and centuries-old wood, ravaging ancient live
oak trees. The Quarter is ground zero in the federal government's
$15 million effort to thwart the Formosan, the most destructive
species of termite in the world, capable of building colonies of up
to 10 million writhing white bugs, which devour an average of 1,000
pounds of wood a year. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   HEMMINGS-STREET (Charlottesville, Va.) _ Editor of local
Afro-American newspaper objects as city considers naming a street
after the family of Sally Hemmings, Thomas Jefferson's slave and
putative mother of his children. ``There's so much more history of
achievement among freed slaves, why honor her status as a
concubine?'' editor asks. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-DOCTORS (Miami) _ A decade-long dispute over the licensing
of a special group of Cuban doctors here is testing the power of
the Cuban American lobby in Florida against that of the state's
medical establishment and is about to involve the American Medical
Association. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   MINN-WILDFIRES (Gunflint Trail, Minn.) _ As foresters and resort
owners still struggle to clear trails and restore cabins devastated
by last year's firestorm, they face the legacy of the July 4, 1999,
blowdown: the prospect of large and destructive wildfires, made
more likely by the thick blanket of drying logs, leaves and needles
left behind. The fire last year left 25 million trees destroyed
along nearly half a million acres through the heart of Minnesota's
remote and treasured Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness near the
Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   ASIANS-MEDALS (Washington) More than a half-century since they
braved enemy fire after first enduring the contempt of their own
countrymen, 21 servicemen of Asian descent have been awarded the
nation's highest military decoration, the Medal of Honor, for
heroism during World War II. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ENVIRO (Washington) _ As early as Monday, the Supreme
Court will announce whether it will hear an appeal from a ruling
last year that invalidated two new clean air standards issued in
1997 by the Environmental Protection Agency. While the case
concerned an important issue of environmental law, what set off
shockwaves last May was not so much the actual decision as its
rationale: The 2-1 ruling by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit held that the Clean Air Act, as
interpreted by the agency, ``effects an unconstitutional delegation
of legislative power.'' By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   UNIV-PHOENIX-AUDIT (Washington) _ The University of Phoenix, a
leader in providing college education to adults via the computer,
has improperly allowed students to obtain $50 million in federal
loans and grants, the inspector general for the Department of
Education has found. The agency's audit recommends the university,
which refutes the findings, pay back the money.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-ADS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ On a trend that is changing
the face of political advertising: the increasing insertion of
special-interest groups into the process as masters of the attack.
By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMERS-RESPONSIBILITY (Los Angeles) _ After decades of
caricature as the most self-indulgent and permissive generation in
American history, baby boomers _ including Al Gore and George Bush
_ are realizing it is time to get with the program. Despite their
differences in political orientation, the two parties' presidential
candidates, both of whom were born into the vanguard of the boomer
generation, are delivering the same message on the campaign trail:
``responsibility.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
