<P>
   BBO-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Baseball notes and news. Lead item:
It's beginning to smell a lot like 1994. That would be the aroma
coming from the American League West. When the 1994 season ended
prematurely, courtesy of a labor dispute between the players and
the owners, no AL West team had a winning record. None had even a
.500 record. The Texas Rangers were in first place, and their
record, 52-62, was far from .500. They are at it again. By Murray
Chass.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ NFL notes and news. Lead item: The
National Football League could soon face one of its most difficult
challenges, as an association made up of dozens of head coaches and
hundreds of assistants is preparing to file a lawsuit against the
league early next month seeking improved working conditions and
benefits. While there remains a solid chance the situation could
soon be settled without court action, several owners and members of
the association believe a legal battle may be imminent. By Mike
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ NBA notes and news. Lead item: About
the same time the Portland Trail Blazers were on their way to
postseason redemption, the Utah Jazz was writing its own obituary,
several years after most observers forecasted its demise. Their
second-round Western Conference semifinal has been rife with
symbolism the past week; the title-less, aging veterans who simply
don't have enough left versus the deeper, younger team who may
issue a sincere challenge to the Los Angeles Lakers. But the
Utah-Portland series goes beyond merely the players. By Mike Wise.
</P>
