<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CHILD-COSTS-REVIEW-AR     05-13 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-COSTS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COSTS OF RAISING A CHILD, THEN AND NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may take a village to raise a child, but a family still ought
to be able to afford one. It now costs about $160,140 to raise a
middle-class child through age 17, according to the Department of
Agriculture's annual report, ``Expenditures on Children by
Families.'' That's up from $25,229 in 1960 and $69,333 in 1980,
seemingly a huge increase. But that 1960 figure, adjusted for
inflation, would equal $141,998 today, so in fact, the cost of
bringing up baby has risen only about 13 percent since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Housing has always been the biggest single expense, these days
making up about a third of the cost of rearing a child, just as it
did 40 years ago. But many other expenditures have changed since
then.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, for example, child care was a tiny subcategory lumped
into overall housing costs. In the 1970s, however, as mothers of
young children poured into the work force, child care expenditures
shot up. By the 1980s, child care and education were given their
own category, which now comprises an average 10 percent of expenses
for preteens. Education costs _ school supplies, books and tuition
_ have risen, too. They now account for 8 percent of family
spending on teen-agers, up from only 2 percent in 1960. A large
proportion of that increase is likely due to spending on private
schools, according to Mark Lino, the Agriculture Department
economist responsible for the report.
</P>
<P>
   Health care costs, 4 percent of the total in 1960, are now at 7
percent, having risen sharply in the last 10 years. Food and
clothing, by contrast, haven't fallen as a percentage of the whole.
</P>
<P>
   Single-parent families spend about as much on each of their
children as much as two-parent families, by using a greater share
of their income for their children. And across all income strata,
families with a single child lavish about a third more on that
child than families with three or more children spend on each of
theirs. The rich spend about half again as much on food, clothes
and health care than the poor, and more than twice as much on
housing, child care and education.
</P>
<P>
   Costs are highest in in Western cities, lowest in rural areas
and Midwestern cities. And as every parent finds out, older
children cost more than younger ones: child care costs go down, but
not enough to make up for all the extra food, clothes, and video
games.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-income baby born last year, incidentally, will have
cost $236,680 by the year 2016, the Department of Agriculture
estimates. But don't worry, that's not adjusted for inflation. Keep
in mind, however, that even after college bills are paid, almost
half of all parents in their fifties are still supporting their
over-21 children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
