<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4054 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-RAIDER-FUND-NYT &LR;      05-13 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-RAIDER-FUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING) 
 A TWO-MONTH OLD FUND, CARRYING A BIG STICK 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATE BERRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most mutual funds keep their distance from companies on matters
of corporate governance, but the $3 million Allied Owners Action
fund, introduced on March 10, jumps in with both feet.
</P>
<P>
   Its goal is to buy shares of companies with underperforming
assets or subpar management, then to lobby for change _ helped by a
network of investors called to arms through a companion Web site,
eRaider.com.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, the fund posted its first target on the site:
Employee Solutions of Phoenix, a staff leasing firm in which the
fund had acquired a 5 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The raid may already have had an effect on the company,
according to Aaron Brown, president of Privateer Asset Management,
which oversees both the fund and the Web site: On May 5, Employee
Solutions announced that Quentin Smith, its president, chief
executive and chairman, would relinquish the chairman's position.
The move was one of several supported by Privateer, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is also clamoring for changes to a management
restructuring plan. And it wants a separate shareholder vote on a
new contract for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Employee Solutions, James Donnelly, declined to
comment last week about the restructuring or the fund's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had 1999 sales of $938.9 million, was once a
hot stock. In 1996, it was rated as one of America's best small
companies by Forbes magazine. Shares hit a weekly high of $28.375
in February 1997; they now are at 43 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Employee Solutions ran into problems because of skyrocketing
workers' compensation rates and a growth-by-acquisition strategy
that saddled it with debt. The current management took charge in
1998; by then, the shares had tumbled into penny-stock territory.
It posted a loss of $56.1 million last year, and on April 20, its
auditor, said the company might not be able to continue as a going
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who says he has been in discussions with Smith on the
proposed restructuring, describes his dealings with Employee
Solutions as amicable. ``They have treated us from the beginning as
a large investor and someone who communicates honestly with
shareholders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One area of disagreement: According to Brown, management would
prefer to gain concessions from holders of the company's $85
million in debt, including forbearance on interest payments, and
seek a capital injection from outside investors once its stock
price has risen.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, for his part, said he would prefer raising capital now to
extinguish the debt, even if it diluted the value of existing
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he wants an independent party to render a fairness
opinion on both the restructuring and Smith's contract _ and has
not ruled out a proxy fight. He says he is in contact with
shareholders who _ together with his fund's position _ control
about one-quarter of Employee Solutions' shares.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Employee Solutions hired a new auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is upbeat about the raid. ``This has already been a
success, because we've taken a process that was behind closed doors
and we've made it transparent,'' he said. And he will continue to
be busy: The fund, which is down 2.7 percent since its start, has
investments in five other companies, whose identities it has not
yet disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
