<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BASKETBALL-HERO-REVIE     05-13 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASKETBALL-HERO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO SAVED THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(duplication notice: also sent with `s' code)  
 (EDS: Boldface word in 2nd graf should be italicized.)  
 By CHARLES PAIKERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has been made of the National Basketball Association's
post-Michael Jordan blues, epitomized by financially troubled
franchises, declining television ratings, a rash of empty seats at
regular season games and overly drawn-out playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Cassandras bemoan the current state of a league
that does, after all, generate over a billion dollars in revenue,
the Basketball Hall of Fame is considering the inclusion of a
long-forgotten Italian immigrant bowling-alley proprietor from
Syracuse, N.Y., who saved the game when it was  &UR; really &LR;  in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 1953-54 season, the future of the five-year
old NBA was very much in doubt. The game's biggest star, George
Mikan, had retired, and attendance was falling sharply in a league
that had dwindled to nine teams from 17 just five years earlier.
Making matters worse was the increasing tendency of teams to slow
down the game to protect leads or prevent more talented opponents
from getting the ball. The final score of one game in 1950 was
19-18, and it wasn't uncommon for a team to pass the ball around
for five minutes before taking a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pro basketball, which after all was in the entertainment
business, had committed a mortal sin: It had become boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things went from bad to worse,'' said Maurice Podoloff, the
league commissioner at the time. ``The games were interminable.
Attendance was suffering. We were in a desperate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Danny Biasone, the feisty owner of the Syracuse Nationals.
Biasone had emigrated from Sicily in 1918, when he was 10 years
old, and by 1946 he owned a bowling alley and a liquor store in
Syracuse. Biasone, a self-described sports nut, got so upset when
the nearby Rochester Royals allegedly refused to play a game in
Syracuse that he vowed to get the city its own pro basketball team.
Which he promptly did, procuring a franchise from the National
Basketball League in 1946 for the grand sum of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The players became part of Biasone's family. His wife cooked
pasta and laundered uniforms for the young men, who had to hold
down other jobs in the off-season to make ends meet. In Syracuse,
they hung out at Biasone's blue-collar bowling alley. On the road
they took long bus and train rides to play in smoky arenas with
names like ``The Tub of Blood,'' where hostile fans would shake the
basket while the players were shooting and occasionally run out on
the floor to slug them with pocketbooks or bare fists.
</P>
<P>
   Biasone loved it all, and couldn't bear to see his beloved Nats,
now in the NBA, go under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew fans weren't paying to see the ball being dribbled
around all night,'' he said in an interview in the mid-1980s. ``So
I went to those fellas in the league and said I'm having a tough
time selling something here. There's one thing basketball needs, I
said. It needs a time. I don't care what the time is. Put in a
time!''
</P>
<P>
   The other owners were skeptical. But Biasone won them over in
August 1954 when he invited them to Syracuse to watch his idea in
action. On a hot and humid afternoon at Biasone's alma mater,
Vocational High School, the future Hall-of-Famer Dolph Schayes and
other local players played the first game in which each team had to
shoot the ball within 24 seconds or lose possession.
</P>
<P>
   Biasone started yelling at them if the clock got down to five
seconds, while NBA patriarchs like Ned Irish of the New York Knicks
and Walter Brown of the Boston Celtics saw the future of the game
unfold before them as the players streaked up and down the court.
</P>
<P>
   The league instituted the 24-second rule that fall, scoring
soared and the pro game was revived. (The Syracuse Nats also won
their first and only championship that season).
</P>
<P>
   ``The adoption of the clock was the most important event in the
NBA,'' Podoloff said, ``and Danny Biasone is the most important man
in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   But after he sold the Syracuse Nats to a group of Philadelphia
businessmen in 1963 for $500,000, Biasone languished in obscurity.
He continued to run the neighborhood bowling alley until his death
30 years later, and, despite several nominations, was never voted
into the Basketball Hall of Fame. His supporters hope that
historical neglect will be rectified next week, however, when the
Hall of Fame, which is once again reviewing Biasone's
contributions, announces the newest members of the league's
pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   And why 24 seconds?
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we were averaging about 60 shots a game per team,''
Biasone said. ``If each team used up 24 seconds for a shot, they
would average 60 shots. But the exact number wasn't important. My
idea was to keep the game going, to speed it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
