<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   (Eds: Boldface words in first
quote should be italicized.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Ringing Endorsement for Bush
</P>
<P>
   Looking a bit like a teen-ager forced to attend a classical
music concert, Sen. John McCain stood shoulder to shoulder with
Gov. George W. Bush at a news conference on Tuesday in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I  &UR; endorse &LR;  Governor Bush, I  &UR; endorse &LR;  Governor Bush, I
 &UR; endorse &LR;  Governor Bush,'' McCain intoned over and over, after a
reporter asked why he seemed so reluctant to use the word.
</P>
<P>
   The repetition probably had the effect McCain intended: It
reduced the term to ridiculousness. Still smarting over the
negative turn that the primary campaign _ and some of Bush's
commercials _ had taken, McCain had for weeks resisted falling into
line behind the presumptive Republican nominee. When he finally did
so last week, saying Bush had the ``vision, knowledge and
expertise'' to be president _ and that he himself had no interest
in being Bush's vice president _ there was a tight, grudging
quality to the event.
</P>
<P>
   As if to confirm that the political and journalistic worlds have
for months been hanging on McCain's every word, his utterance of
that single word was the major political news of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed pleased to have gotten over that hump, but Vice
President Al Gore reminded audiences that the two Republicans were
not all that in sync. Speaking that same day in Washington to the
Anti-Defamation League, Gore brought up an issue that divides Bush
and McCain, the Confederate flag that flies over the South Carolina
statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong to remain silent about it,'' Gore said, an
allusion to Bush's deferring to the people of South Carolina on the
issue. (McCain recently declared he had erred in not announcing
earlier that he favors the flag's removal.)
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to politics, Gore's boss is not remaining silent,
either. It was disclosed last week that President Clinton is
serving as a behind-the-scenes adviser to many Democratic
candidates across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can't live without a campaign in his life,'' said Sen.
John Breaux, D-La.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The German Army Hero, Updated &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The past is inexhaustible in Germany. Beyond each confrontation
with the Third Reich, a new accounting always lurks. This time it
was the turn of the army, which has tended to cling to the notion
that Hitler's crimes were the work of the SS and death squads, not
the Wehrmacht.
</P>
<P>
   Turning his back on such views, Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping stripped a base of the name of a Wehrmacht general long
regarded as a hero and renamed it after Anton Schmid, a sergeant
who was executed by the Nazis in 1942 after he disobeyed orders and
helped Jews in the Vilnius ghetto. Honoring him reflected Germany's
growing determination to place ``Zivilcourage'' _ the courage of
conscience _ above duty in its scale of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I merely behaved as a human being,'' Schmid wrote in his last
letter to his wife. But very few people in Hitler's Reich had the
courage to do that.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Reformers Win An Uncertain Victory
</P>
<P>
   When the votes in the runoff election were counted, Iran's
reformers appeared to have clinched their majority in the new
parliament that is set to open May 27. But they remained on
tenterhooks: The all-important Council of Guardians, dominated by
the hard-liners who have labeled the reformers as foreign agents,
has yet to certify the three-month-old results from first round of
voting in the capital, Tehran, as well as the runoff races.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUSAN SACHS
</P>
<P>
   A New Way to Diet  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Ross walked into a suburban Detroit convenience store last
week with a $100 bill and bought a hot dog for himself and 98
lottery tickets for his wife Nancy. Now they're multimillionaires,
after purchasing one of the two winning Big Game lottery tickets.
The 47-year-old swimming pool company owner and an unidentified
ticket holder in Illinois will split $363 million, a record for a
lottery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't eaten in three days,'' he said. Was it the
excitement or the hot dog?
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN
</P>
<P>
   Planned Fire Turns Wild  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal government effort to thin dense pine forests with a
controlled burn near Los Alamos, N.M., suddenly burst into a
disastrous wild fire. Heavy winds sent flames racing through
tinder-dry canyons and then residential areas, and even across
portions of the highly sensitive nuclear weapons laboratory at Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The local head of the National Park Service, which set the fire,
was suspended, more than 25,000 people had to be evacuated and at
least 260 homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear lab suffered no major damage and officials said
there was no release of radioactivity. Still, officials said, it
could take weeks to get the facility running fully again. Officials
also said it could take weeks before services could be restored so
that residents of the area can move back to their homes _ those
that still stand.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES STERNGOLD
</P>
<P>
   Let the Bidder Beware
</P>
<P>
   The perils of Internet auctions _ and the potential for fraud _
were highlighted when the price of a ``great, big, wild'' painting
soared on eBay from 25 cents to $135,805 on speculation that it was
by the artist Richard Diebenkorn. The seller, Kenneth A. Walton of
Sacramento, later acknowledged that he had fabricated part of the
story that described the work and had bid on the painting ``for a
friend.'' EBay suspended him and voided the auction.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
