<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scandal Fallout for Clinton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton leaves the presidency about eight months from
now, few assume that he will hang out a shingle and practice law.
Nonetheless, he is battling to keep his law license in Arkansas in
a proceeding that could result in his being disbarred or suspended
from the practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent filing, Clinton disputed the main charge against him
_ that he lied under oath when he denied having had a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky _ by continuing to insist that
his answers were technically accurate if misleading. A decision may
come later this month.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Coronation in Russia  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seemed more coronation than inauguration _ a palace, a choir,
a red carpet, a huge gold emblem. But after Vladimir Putin was
sworn in as Russia's second president, he pledged to build a
democratic and capitalist nation. Capitalist, yes: His new prime
minister, Mikhail Kasyanov, is an economic liberal who has deftly
renegotiated Russia's Western debt.
</P>
<P>
   But democratic? At week's end, a police raid and search of the
media conglomerate that is the Kremlin's major critic, Media-Most,
left some wondering about Putin's political ideals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL WINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Hacker Found (Perhaps)
</P>
<P>
   Onel de Guzman, a 23-year-old computer student, came forward
after several days of hiding and admitted in Manila that ``it is
possible'' he had unleashed the program that crippled e-mail
systems around the world. The Philippine National Bureau of
Investigation did not immediately call de Guzman a suspect, but
said agents would question him.
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman, a student at the AMA Computer College, was suspected
after it was learned that he had submitted a thesis proposal that
resembled the destructive virus that paralyzed the accounts of
e-mail recipients who opened an attachment with the subject line,
``I Love You.'' His lawyer said de Guzman was ``not really aware
that the act imputed to him was done by him.''
</P>
<P>
   A Politician Unfazed
</P>
<P>
   Ever the optimist, former Gov. Edwin W. Edwards of Louisiana
said that prison is ``nothing to be afraid of.'' The prison system
is well-managed, he said, and provides its residents with food,
medical attention and a place to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards may well have a chance to test his assessment first-hand
at some point. He, his son, and three other co-defendants were
convicted on Tuesday by a U.S. District Court jury in Baton Rouge
on racketeering charges related to the extortion of businessmen
seeking riverboat casino licenses. The 72-year-old Edwards, a
four-term governor who escaped conviction in two criminal trials in
the 1980s, has vowed to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
<P>
   Out of Jail  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amy S. Grossberg was sentenced to 30 months in prison in July
1998, having pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the death of her
newborn son, who was found dead in a motel trash bin in Newark,
Del. After serving 22 months, with time off for being well-behaved
and earning 21 college credits in correspondence courses, she left
prison Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT HANLEY
</P>
<P>
   Unwanted Advances  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy, the Army's top female officer, won
an early round in her sexual harassment case when the Army's
inspector general concluded that she had been the victim of sexual
harassment four years ago. At least two reviews are needed before a
final decision by the vice chief of the Army. Kennedy charged that
Brig. Gen. Larry G. Smith accosted her in her Pentagon office after
a routine briefing. It is the first time one general has accused
another of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELIZABETH BECKER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
