<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: H. DOBRZYNSKI 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scandal Fallout for Clinton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton leaves the presidency about eight months from
now, few assume that he will hang out a shingle and practice law.
Nonetheless, he is battling to keep his law license in Arkansas in
a proceeding that could result in his being disbarred or suspended
from the practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent filing, Clinton disputed the main charge against him
_ that he lied under oath when he denied having had a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky _ by continuing to insist that
his answers were technically accurate if misleading. A decision may
come later this month.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Coronation in Russia  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seemed more coronation than inauguration _ a palace, a choir,
a red carpet, a huge gold emblem. But after Vladimir Putin was
sworn in as Russia's second president, he pledged to build a
democratic and capitalist nation. Capitalist, yes: His new prime
minister, Mikhail Kasyanov, is an economic liberal who has deftly
renegotiated Russia's Western debt.
</P>
<P>
   But democratic? At week's end, a police raid and search of the
media conglomerate that is the Kremlin's major critic, Media-Most,
left some wondering about Putin's political ideals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL WINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Hacker Found (Perhaps)
</P>
<P>
   Onel de Guzman, a 23-year-old computer student, came forward
after several days of hiding and admitted in Manila that ``it is
possible'' he had unleashed the program that crippled e-mail
systems around the world. The Philippine National Bureau of
Investigation did not immediately call de Guzman a suspect, but
