<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4073 &Cx1f; var-z
u p BC-ADULTERY-POLITICS-REV     05-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULTERY-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S LEFT (OR RIGHT) TO CAST THE FIRST STONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presumptive Senate candidate tells reporters that his
marriage is kaput _ possibly even before informing the mother of
his children. He has already announced his high regard for the
``very good friend'' who accompanied him to a recent press dinner.
A few hours later, his wife counters with her own news conference,
choking on tears as she says that her husband has not only been
unfaithful but serially unfaithful, previously with a member of his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   And the public's reaction? Instant statewide polling suggested
that New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's personal problems would
have no effect on how most voters would view his candidacy. A Daily
News headline summed it up: ``Voters Don't Care.''
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't that Americans are no longer concerned with moral
issues; they may simply be drawing the line between public and
private behavior that the media no longer draws for them.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Americans have punished candidates who made them
aware of their messy intimate lives.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller divorced Mary Todhunter Clark to
marry Margaretta Fitler Murphy, the public was scandalized, and his
presidential chances crippled. When Ronald Reagan was elected
president in 1980, a mere 28 years into his second marriage, it was
considered a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Voters never got the chance to judge House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who surely deserves a place in the chutzpah hall of fame
for wagging his finger at President Clinton during the impeachment
debate. Gingrich was no longer in power when Americans learned that
he was involved with a congressional staff member at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., who was about to replace Gingrich as
speaker, decided to step down after his own past indiscretions were
revealed by Larry Flynt, the publisher of Hustler and
self-appointed hypocrisy cop.
</P>
<P>
   But the very fact that there is a continuing debate over whether
Giuliani still has a political future shows how far the public has
come since, as William Bennett, a conservative writer and former
secretary of education, says, ``the ancient standards were in place
in the days of yore _ 1987,'' when Gary Hart's presidential
campaign went pfft after the story broke about his affair with
Donna Rice. Even his wife's decision to stand by him did no good.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said adultery, by itself, is no longer fatal for
candidates for higher office, and even such ``complicating
factors'' as lying about an affair, or carrying on with an
underling, seem to matter less and less. While he believes that
those factors should end any campaign for higher office, Bennett
said, ``I'm not having a lot of agreement on that, even around my
own office.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprisingly, several Republicans said they do not
think that Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky is responsible for
the shift in public opinion. Instead they feel that Clinton's
popular success is just more evidence that the culture was moving
in that direction anyway: Voters elected him _ twice _ knowing they
were not getting Ozzie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is anesthetized to all of this in-your-face stuff
about private lives,'' said Rep. Michael Forbes of New York, who
switched parties and became a Democrat last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean they don't have concerns and opinions,''
Forbes said. ``But what the public really doesn't like is when you
beat your chest with righteous indignation about somebody else's
behavior and then do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Estrich, who closely followed the Hart drama while running
Michael Dukakis' 1988 presidential campaign, says the country seems
to have moved so far so fast since Hart's downfall that today a
messy affair can actually be a plus for a candidate, especially one
who seems to need a little humanizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, right now it helps in the weird political world
in which we live,'' she said, ``because watching them be human,
even if it's because they're having an affair, is better than
watching them be politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   New York voters certainly were responding sympathetically when
they recently learned that Giuliani also has prostate cancer, which
he has said will be the prime consideration in deciding whether he
stays in the Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With divorce so common, fewer voters and candidates are in a
position to judge others for the same problems they have.
</P>
<P>
   There would obviously be no arms buildup on this issue in a
Giuliani-Clinton matchup, and no commercials from Clinton's
campaign featuring footage of her opponent's distraught wife.
</P>
<P>
   Though most political analysts say the public still holds women
candidates to a higher moral standard, even that appears to be
changing: Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, with strong ties to the
religious right, recently survived revelations of a long-past
affair and was subsequently re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of other, perhaps more subtle factors now influence
whether the public will tolerate private indiscretion from any
given elected official.
</P>
<P>
   Other considerations for voters include how the (apparently)
wronged or exiting spouse reacts. And how well the public likes the
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep seeing Judith Nathan described as a nurse and a single
mom,'' Estrich said, referring to Giuliani's friend, who is 45.
``And I think the situation would be different if she were a
25-year-old aspiring model.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the candidate been hypocritical?
</P>
<P>
   Can he or she take the heat?
</P>
<P>
   How conservative are constituents? (Last year, supporters of
Gary Bauer, the ``family values'' presidential candidate,
criticized him simply for meeting alone with a female staff
member.)
</P>
<P>
   And most important of all: How well did voters like the guy in
the first place?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; var-z
u p BC-ADULTERY-POLITICS-REV     05-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULTERY-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S LEFT (OR RIGHT) TO CAST THE FIRST STONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presumptive Senate candidate tells reporters that his
marriage is kaput _ possibly even before informing the mother of
his children. He has already announced his high regard for the
``very good friend'' who accompanied him to a recent press dinner.
A few hours later, his wife counters with her own news conference,
choking on tears as she says that her husband has not only been
unfaithful but serially unfaithful, previously with a member of his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   And the public's reaction? Instant statewide polling suggested
that New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's personal problems would
have no effect on how most voters would view his candidacy. A Daily
News headline summed it up: ``Voters Don't Care.''
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't that Americans are no longer concerned with moral
issues; they may simply be drawing the line between public and
private behavior that the media no longer draws for them.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Americans have punished candidates who made them
aware of their messy intimate lives.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller divorced Mary Todhunter Clark to
marry Margaretta Fitler Murphy, the public was scandalized, and his
presidential chances crippled. When Ronald Reagan was elected
president in 1980, a mere 28 years into his second marriage, it was
considered a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Voters never got the chance to judge House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who surely deserves a place in the chutzpah hall of fame
for wagging his finger at President Clinton during the impeachment
debate. Gingrich was no longer in power when Americans learned that
he was involved with a congressional staff member at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., who was about to replace Gingrich as
speaker, decided to step down after his own past indiscretions were
revealed by Larry Flynt, the publisher of Hustler and
self-appointed hypocrisy cop.
</P>
<P>
   But the very fact that there is a continuing debate over whether
Giuliani still has a political future shows how far the public has
come since, as William Bennett, a conservative writer and former
secretary of education, says, ``the ancient standards were in place
in the days of yore _ 1987,'' when Gary Hart's presidential
campaign went pfft after the story broke about his affair with
Donna Rice. Even his wife's decision to stand by him did no good.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said adultery, by itself, is no longer fatal for
candidates for higher office, and even such ``complicating
factors'' as lying about an affair, or carrying on with an
underling, seem to matter less and less. While he believes that
those factors should end any campaign for higher office, Bennett
said, ``I'm not having a lot of agreement on that, even around my
own office.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprisingly, several Republicans said they do not
think that Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky is responsible for
the shift in public opinion. Instead they feel that Clinton's
popular success is just more evidence that the culture was moving
in that direction anyway: Voters elected him _ twice _ knowing they
were not getting Ozzie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is anesthetized to all of this in-your-face stuff
about private lives,'' said Rep. Michael Forbes of New York, who
switched parties and became a Democrat last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean they don't have concerns and opinions,''
Forbes said. ``But what the public really doesn't like is when you
beat your chest with righteous indignation about somebody else's
behavior and then do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Estrich, who closely followed the Hart drama while running
Michael Dukakis' 1988 presidential campaign, says the country seems
to have moved so far so fast since Hart's downfall that today a
messy affair can actually be a plus for a candidate, especially one
who seems to need a little humanizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, right now it helps in the weird political world
in which we live,'' she said, ``because watching them be human,
even if it's because they're having an affair, is better than
watching them be politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   New York voters certainly were responding sympathetically when
they recently learned that Giuliani also has prostate cancer, which
he has said will be the prime consideration in deciding whether he
stays in the Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With divorce so common, fewer voters and candidates are in a
position to judge others for the same problems they have.
</P>
<P>
   There would obviously be no arms buildup on this issue in a
Giuliani-Clinton matchup, and no commercials from Clinton's
campaign featuring footage of her opponent's distraught wife.
</P>
<P>
   Though most political analysts say the public still holds women
candidates to a higher moral standard, even that appears to be
changing: Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, with strong ties to the
religious right, recently survived revelations of a long-past
affair and was subsequently re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of other, perhaps more subtle factors now influence
whether the public will tolerate private indiscretion from any
given elected official.
</P>
<P>
   Other considerations for voters include how the (apparently)
wronged or exiting spouse reacts. And how well the public likes the
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep seeing Judith Nathan described as a nurse and a single
mom,'' Estrich said, referring to Giuliani's friend, who is 45.
``And I think the situation would be different if she were a
25-year-old aspiring model.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the candidate been hypocritical?
</P>
<P>
   Can he or she take the heat?
</P>
<P>
   How conservative are constituents? (Last year, supporters of
Gary Bauer, the ``family values'' presidential candidate,
criticized him simply for meeting alone with a female staff
member.)
</P>
<P>
   And most important of all: How well did voters like the guy in
the first place?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
