<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4088 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CHINA-TRADE-2Takes-LA     05-13 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S TRADE FUTURE MAY BE IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA HANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southern California's congressional representatives
stand in the way of a China trade vote that's a top priority for
Hollywood studios, the industries that feed the Southland's ports
and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional bill that would give China normalized trade
relations with the United States is opposed outright by one area
congressman, Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills. Democrats Howard
Berman and Henry Waxman and Republicans Elton Gallegly and James
Rogan all are undecided. Rep. Howard P. ``Buck'' McKeon, R-Santa
Clarita, is leaning toward a ``yes'' vote.
</P>
<P>
   House backers of the measure reported that, as of Friday, they
could count on ``yes'' votes from 140 to 145 GOP members and 70 to
80 Democrats. At least 218 votes will be needed for passage in the
435-member house, which is made up of 222 Republicans, 211
Democrats and two independents.
</P>
<P>
   Some representatives opposed to the measure cite the country's
human rights violations. Others - with the strong backing of
organized labor - say manufacturing jobs will be siphoned to China.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a black-and-white, Democrats vs. Republicans
issue. In fact, party allegiances are being shattered and ties to
constituents are being sorely tested as Congress heads toward a
scheduled May 22 showdown vote on the status of trade relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents, led by President Clinton, leading Republicans and
major business interests, argue that permanent normal trade
relations - or PNTR - will increase the pace of democratization and
reform in China while unleashing a multibillion-dollar trade boom
for Southern California and the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Foes, including many Democratic leaders, organized labor,
anti-communists and human rights advocates, say China cannot be
trusted to deal fairly with either its trading partners or its own
people. They advocate that Congress continue its policy of annually
reviewing China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised the stakes in the PNTR debate last November when
U.S. trade negotiators announced tentative new pacts with China.
The deals, including lucrative development and distribution
opportunities for Hollywood, are all contingent on congressional
approval of PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, Congress has held a yearly vote to extend or revoke
most-favored-nation trading status for China. It has been approved
each year, although several votes have been close.
</P>
<P>
   PNTR is expected to win easily in the Senate, where supporters
include California Democrats Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer.
But the House roll call is still too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of Southern California's delegation found six members in
favor of PNTR, three leaning toward a ``yes'' vote, five opposed
and 10 undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a difficult decision at all,'' said Rep. David
Dreier, R-Covina, who is leading the GOP's effort for PNTR
approval. ``The single most powerful force for reform in the
5,000-year history of China is economic reform. PNTR will help get
our American values in there and undermine political repression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have voted for most favored nation status for China, but I
can't support permanent status,'' said Sherman, the Woodland Hills
Democrat. ``Under this measure, resolution of our trade disputes
with China would be settled by the World Trade Organization. But
the WTO would only deal with problems that are on the table. I'm
worried about what China will be doing under the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and other foes (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and other foes say China has repeatedly violated past
trade pacts and copyright laws and has been heavily involved in
such activities as video piracy.
</P>
<P>
   They also note that China's business community continues to be
intertwined with the ruling Communist Party and the People's
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must keep China on probation until the `Made in China'
label stands for fairness,'' Rep. Joe Baca, D-Rialto, told a recent
Capitol Hill labor rally. ``They must respect people, not just
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman, D-Mission Hills, is among several undecided members who
want to place conditions on PNTR. Berman has indicated he will vote
in favor of the measure if it includes a provision for immediate
revocation should China attack or blockade Taiwan, a U.S. ally.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, R-Pasadena, has said he will support PNTR only if the
United States also agrees to give the same permanent trade status
to Taiwan. Such a move would be opposed by China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his supporters, who have made PNTR the top priority
for the president's last year in office, have so far rejected
placing any conditions on China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has produced strange political bedfellows, starting
with Democrat Clinton and Republican Dreier, who, as chairman of
the House Rules Committee, has been a leading critic of many of the
president's policies.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, both Reps. Loretta Sanchez, D-Garden Grove,
and Dana Rohrabacher, R-Huntington Beach, have announced their
opposition to PNTR - for vastly different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said she is concerned that freer trade will result in
the export of American jobs to China. She is also concerned about
China's treatment of its workers and political dissidents.
Rohrabacher sees China as a major threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not lock in advantageous trade status for the brutal
dictators in Beijing, who continually repress their own people and
threaten their democratic neighbors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Undecided Southland Democrats face the greatest quandary as they
weigh the economic benefits of increased trade against alienating
their longtime allies in organized labor. The AFL-CIO is vehemently
opposed to PNTR, calling it a ``blank check'' that would reward a
repressive regime.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rep. Juanita Millender-McDonald, D-Torrance, has
received $25,500 from union political action committees for the
2000 campaign. She also represents the Port of Los Angeles area,
which stands to directly benefit from increased trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission records show that labor, through its
political action committees, provides significant campaign cash to
Democratic incumbents. But, in fact, most Southland Democrats
receive more money from business interest PACs than they do from
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significant to undecided Democrats, including Rep.
Xavier Becerra, D-Los Angeles, who is also a candidate for Los
Angeles mayor, are the rank-and-file voters whom unions can deliver
on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lois Capps, D-Santa Barbara, summed up her decision to vote
for PNTR by stating that it ``will pry open vast new markets for
Central Coast citrus and beef producers, technology and service
companies and their employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponent Sherman offers a different bottom line on the China
trade issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is China going to ship all of their toys and shoes and
clothes to if we vote it down? We're their market,'' Sherman said.
``China's economy will crumble if it stops shipping to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4092 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CONSENT-DECREES-2Take     05-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSENT-DECREES-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSENT DECREES SHIFT CITY POWER TO FEDERAL JUDGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Are the feds taking over L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   It may look that way, with some of the most powerful players in
Los Angeles - responsible for spending local tax dollars and
overseeing local programs - at the federal courthouse, not the
Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of consent decrees in the past decade, the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, Los Angeles Unified School
District, the Sheriff's Department and city Sanitation Bureau all
have fallen under control of federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements significantly changed how these agencies operate,
forced them to collectively spend billions of additional taxpayer
dollars and diminished local government's authority.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Justice Department is seeking a consent decree for the
Los Angeles Police Department to correct a long pattern of alleged
civil rights abuses by officers. As a result, the city could have
to surrender some control over the LAPD and be required to spend
significant sums on specified programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pure transfer of power from elected officials to
unelected judges,'' said Ralph A. Rossum, director of the Rose
Institute of State and Local Government at Claremont McKenna
College.
</P>
<P>
   He and other critics say government agencies can become less
responsive to their residents when they surrender some of their
authority to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   They charge that government officials can be too quick to
abdicate their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes government entities need to bite the bullet and
fight vigorously against these lawsuits and take their chances,''
said Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association. ``It's a judgment call. We have seen districts just
chicken out.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say such settlements should be expected when local
governments are caught violating the law and failing to solve
problems over long periods of time. Having an outsider make
decisions can reduce those violations and improve service to the
disenfranchised. And in many cases, the result would have been much
worse if the agency fought the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case would've been litigated, it would've been lost and
there would've been a remedy imposed with less discretion to the
government than the consent decree (gave),'' said Erwin
Chemerinsky, a constitutional law professor at the University of
Southern California. ``Often these cases are started because the
city's violating constitutional law.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemerinsky added that while consent decrees typically involve
ceding some control to an outside authority, they address specific
problems and do not constitute a broad takeover of an agency.
</P>
<P>
   But as some of the active consent decrees involving government
entities around Los Angeles demonstrate, that's not always the
case:
</P>
<P>
   -- To settle a lawsuit over bus overcrowding, the MTA signed a
consent decree in 1996 agreeing to expand its service by hundreds
of buses and replace its aging fleet at a faster pace. By 2004, the
agency has projected, it will have spent more than $730 million to
comply with the consent decree, including the cost of buying and
running new buses, legal fees and the special master's salary.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides agreed to the terms, they were back in court
earlier this month arguing over an issue that illustrates one of
the dangers of consent decrees: the potential for micromanagement
by an outside authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the special master went too far,'' said MTA spokesman
Marc Littman. ``In essence he was almost running the MTA, where he
had no transit expertise. He wanted to buy particular buses and put
them on certain lines. That minutiae of detail, we felt,
overextended his authority.''
</P>
<P>
   But Constance Rice, a prominent civil rights attorney
representing the Bus Riders Union, said the MTA itself proposed
most of the consent decree, so it shouldn't be complaining about
its contents. She added that if the agency were living up to its
side of the agreement, the special master wouldn't have to be so
active.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not giving up any power,'' Rice said. ``Under the
decree, MTA always has the first crack at doing it the way it wants
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Chanda Smith Consent Decree, signed by the LAUSD in 1996,
resulted from a class-action suit filed by a parent whose daughter
twice flunked 10th grade after she was denied enrollment in a
special education program. The decree aimed to expand educational
opportunities for special education students as required by federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   The decree resulted in the creation of an independent office,
with 11 full-time employees and 20 consultants, that reports to the
courts, not school administrators. The district has spent $18
million on the consent decree, and expects to spend $34 million
next year out of a total special education budget of $888 million,
according to Assistant Superintendent Steven Mark.
</P>
<P>
   -- The city Sanitation Bureau (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   -- The city Sanitation Bureau agreed to a consent decree with
the Environmental Protection Agency in 1986 to end a lawsuit over
sewer discharge into Santa Monica Bay. The agreement set a
timetable for $2 billion in improvements at the Hyperion sewage
treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   -- In 1993, the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department agreed
to a consent decree to end a long-running class action suit
alleging sexual harassment and discrimination in hiring practices.
The department had to create an ombudsman office to deal with
sexual harassment complaints and spend at least $2.5 million on
improving working conditions and advancement opportunities for
women, among other changes.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Councilman Joel Wachs suggested that the best way
for government agencies to avoid consent decrees is to encourage
problems to be aired publicly from the beginning and then fix them
immediately, rather than letting them fester. For example, with the
LAPD, he noted that it has been clear the department has had a
civil rights problem ever since the Rodney King arrest in 1991, but
it appears little improvement has been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consent decrees are just like initiatives - they're what
people resort to when government doesn't clean up its own act,''
Wachs said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, when political resistance is encountered to
problem- solving, consent decrees allow politicians to avoid
criticism because they can blame the remedy on the courts, Rossum
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This absolves any elected politician from having to do
anything unpopular or politically sensitive,'' Rossum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're free to grandstand and complain about what the special
master and others are doing, and yet are free from having to step
up to the plate and take a swing at the ball themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency of courts to muscle in on local governments is not
just a Los Angeles phenomenon, of course, but is happening
throughout the country on an increasing basis, said Mike Alissi,
publisher of Reason magazine, put out by the conservative Reason
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem that I've heard in a number of municipalities,
even out here on the East Coast,'' said Alissi, who is based in
Connecticut. ``The courts have been very active and not hesitant at
all in going in and in a sense taking over those agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a source of never-ending frustration for the people who
used to be running those agencies to have no discretion and follow
the rules of judges who aren't in touch with the professions that
are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS A CONSENT DECREE?
</P>
<P>
   -- A consent decree is a legal term for an out-of-court
settlement. The plaintiffs and defendants in a lawsuit consent to
an agreement, which is then approved by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   -- In cases of government agencies being sued for alleged civil
rights violations, consent decrees typically focus on changes in
the agency's policies, but can also involve payment of monetary
damages if that is seen as an appropriate remedy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Consent decrees sometimes involve the appointing of a special
master, an independent authority whose job it is to interpret the
document, rule over any disputes, and make sure it is properly
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
