   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-LABOR (Washington) _ The American labor movement is
mounting its biggest lobbying campaign ever on trade matters in
seeking to defeat the Clinton administration's effort to normalize
commerce with China. Unions are holding dozens of meetings on
Capitol Hill, putting intense pressure on individual legislators
back in their districts, staging rallies and writing huge numbers
of letters across the nation. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has movedin ``i'' and ``w'' news files.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTIONS (Austin) _ Special Report: Gov. George W. Bush
is certain that the 127 people who have been executed in Texas
during his tenure were all guilty. But interviews with officials
who help administer the death penalty in the state, all of whom
believe in the death penalty and support Bush, reveal that the men
and women whose jobs involve reviewing case records, considering
inmates' appeal and weighing their final pleas for clemency are
less sanguine than Bush about both the fairness of the state's
judicial system and the risk Texas runs of executing innocent
people. By Sara Rimer and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
