<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4118 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-TEACHER-TAX-NYT     05-13 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TEACHER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PLAN WOULD EXEMPT TEACHERS FROM INCOME TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive) 
By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a striking gesture of support for public
education, Gov. Gray Davis on Saturday proposed to exempt all
California public school teachers from the state's personal income
tax, in what state officials said they believed was the first such
peacetime exemption for any occupation in American history.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the proposal, part of the governor's
revised budget package to be announced on Monday, would amount to
an income tax cut of $1,350 for the average experienced California
teacher, who earns about $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The state has about 283,000 public school teachers, and the
estimated annual cost of the program, which requires legislative
approval, would initially be $545 million out of a total statewide
budget of about $88 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the governor proposed to spend another $500
million a year to reward teachers whose schools show improvements
in student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Under this plan, teachers whose schools show an improvement rate
of 20 percent or more based on the state's new academic performance
index, which ranks schools according to standardized tests, would
receive bonuses of $5,000 each, while others would receive lesser
amounts based on their schools' performances.
</P>
<P>
   That amounts to a form of merit pay that rewards collective
achievement by an entire school, as opposed to individual teachers,
which education unions generally oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took office two years ago vowing to make education his
``first, second and third'' priority.
</P>
<P>
   But as a fiscal conservative, cautious to a fault, he has also
faced growing criticism for not moving swiftly enough in a booming
economy to redress the severe educational problems in a state that
once led the nation in per-pupil spending and investments in
education but that since the tax revolt of Proposition 13 in 1978
has seen itself slip toward the bottom in numerous national
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the first Democrat to lead the state in 16 years, had
faced pressure from fellow Democrats in Sacramento and especially
sharp attacks from the state's largest teachers' union, which had
threatened to sponsor a statewide ballot initiative this fall that
would have required California to return its per-pupil spending,
which has lagged in the bottom third of states in recent years, to
the national average over the next five years. Davis has opposed
that measure as requiring a costly tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the union agreed to drop the measure after the
governor proposed an additional $1.8 billion in discretionary
spending for education, intended to compensate for the lean years
of the early 1990s, when teachers were forced to do without
cost-of-living increases in wages to help close looming budget
deficits.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with a projected budget surplus of $11 billion to $13
billion, the challenge has been how to spend the unexpected money.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Davis aides said the idea of the tax exemption for
teachers arose at a brainstorming session in a staff retreat last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a huge statement about the importance of teaching,''
said one senior adviser, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
``What are the Republicans going to say? They and the teachers are
going to be hard pressed to oppose this.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, legislative Republicans have said they believe there is
room in the budget to spend perhaps an additional $3 billion on
education, and while they may well be wary of anything that looks
like special treatment for the teachers' unions, it seems likely
that they would have trouble objecting to the symbolism of Davis'
gesture, which was held in extraordinary secrecy by the governor's
staff over the last week so as to make a maximum public splash.
</P>
<P>
   Davis aides said their research had shown various past tax
exemptions for certain employee groups, but only in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Davis plan, public school teachers would be permitted
to deduct 100 percent of their teaching income on state personal
income tax returns. The estimated tax relief for a beginning
teacher would be $500 a year, rising to $1,350 for experienced
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break for teachers is just one element of Davis'
proposals for doling out the budget surplus. Other plans include a
$150 rebate for every income-tax payer to the state, and $300 for
couples who file joint returns, at a total cost of $1.76 billion.
Other measures include cutting state parks fees in half.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the State speech in January, Davis acknowledged
that California must spend more to return its schools to the
post-sputnik era achievements of former Gov. Edmund G. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even more important, we must spend wisely,'' Davis said
then. ``We cannot win this battle simply by throwing money at it.
We must not let taxpayer dollars be wasted on bureaucracy, but,
instead, we must invest them directly into the classroom: for
students and for teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
