<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much more pleasant weather is expected along the Atlantic
seaboard as drier air streams into the region on an active breeze
from the northwest. Colder air above 5,000 feet will move from the
Great Lakes across the northern Ohio Valley and into the
Appalachians. As a result, clouds will develop and a few light
showers will be scattered around the region Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and seasonably cool conditions will dominate the middle of
the nation. But a return flow of sultry air into the southwest
Plains will produce showers and a few heavy thunderstorms, mainly
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A large storm off the coast of Northern California will send a
plume of clouds across the Northwest with showers moving inland
from northwest California to Oregon. The Southwest will stay sunny
and seasonably hot.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: POTENT JET STREAM
</P>
<P>
   The mercury rose to 105 degrees in Del Rio, Texas, on Friday
afternoon for the highest reading there so early in May. At nearby
Laughlin Air Force Base, the temperature hit 108. Meanwhile, by
Saturday morning, the temperature plunged to a record low of 23
degrees at Denver's international airport, one of the lowest
readings so late in the season. These large thermal contrasts help
to drive the jet stream. Winds at 30,000 feet over the southern
Rockies were very strong last week. This powerful jet stream will
begin to reconfigure the weather pattern across the nation this
week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
