<HEADER>
A4134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MINN-WILDFIRES-ART-53     05-13 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-WILDFIRES-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLANKETED IN FELLED TREES, MINNESOTA BRACES FOR FIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ALONG THE GUNFLINT TRAIL, Minn. _ It took 20 minutes for the
fierce windstorm last summer to flatten the towering boreal forest
surrounding Bruce Kerfoot's Gunflint Lodge at the edge of the
boundary waters in northern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   As if a giant hand had swept across the lakeside resort his
family has owned for three generations, Kerfoot's 80 acres were
toppled into a litter of spruce, ash and centuries-old white pine
stacked like kindling and all eerily pointed east.
</P>
<P>
   ``It nails your psyche,'' he said, recalling the powerful storm
cell that produced downdrafts of 130 mph with the force of a
hurricane. In the end, 25 million trees were destroyed along nearly
half a million acres through the heart of Minnesota's remote and
treasured Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness near the Canadian
border.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one year later, as foresters and resort owners still
struggle to clear trails and restore cabins, they face the prospect
of large and destructive wildfires, made more likely by the thick
blanket of drying logs, leaves and needles left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of if a large fire happens,'' said Paul
Tine, a fuels specialist with the U.S. Forest Service in Grand
Rapids, Minn., who has studied the fire danger. ``It's a question
of when a large fire happens. So we're preparing people as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   For fire officials here, who have collectively tapped more than
$4 million in special state and federal funds, preparations to
fight such a fire are unusual in the state's history. Since the
start of the fire season last month, the area has been surrounded
by extra crews, firefighting aircraft, increased air patrols,
milelong mobile sprinklers, heliports and cooperative emergency
networks within range of the 1.1 million acres of wilderness, which
is the most visited of all protected wild lands in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to this is far different from the response to
other blowdowns I've seen,'' said Lee Frelich, a forestry
researcher at the University of Minnesota who has studied such
events for 20 years. ``The boundary waters has this mystique about
it _ this canoe country with the rocky islands and beautiful lakes.
It's a signature, an icon for the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires have always been part of the boundary waters ecology.
Every year, dozens of smaller blazes move within the islands amid
1,000 lakes, clearing deadwood for new growth.
</P>
<P>
   But a study commissioned by the U.S. Forest Service in January
shows a changed course of events for a fire in the blowdown,
particularly in the worst-hit section of the wilderness, where
drying trees are stacked as much as 20 feet high along a corridor
40 miles long and 8 miles wide. There, a fire could start more
easily, become hotter and spread more quickly, even on days when
humidity usually reduces the risk of fire, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   If the wind is swift and the air is dry, as it can be during the
northern Minnesota summers, computer models also show that a
wilderness fire might fan into a ``plume-dominated'' blaze like the
one that swept through Yellowstone National Park in 1988 _ a fire
so large it creates its own weather system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're talking miles of fuels without any break,'' said Olin
Phillips, who is in charge of fire suppression for the Minnesota
Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials are preparing for the worst as
Minnesota faces an unusually dry year. Campfires have been banned
in the blowdown area. The forest service is seeking congressional
approval for controlled burns in the wilderness to create
firebreaks on as much as 80,000 acres starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for this fire season, which peaks now and again in
late summer, the strategy will be ``aggressive, immediate initial
attack'' from the air, said Jim Thomas, fire and aviation manager
of the Superior National Forest, which oversees the wilderness
area.
</P>
<P>
   Forest officials say such air power is even more critical in the
wilderness, accessible only by canoe and where a large fire could
threaten Canadian commercial forests to the north or U.S. resort
areas in the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take hours to paddle people in,'' Thomas said. ``The
faster we get there, and the sooner we keep it small, the better
chance we have.''
</P>
<P>
   A major concern is the summer homes and resorts along the
Gunflint Trail, which runs 70 miles inland from Lake Superior on
the east side of the wilderness. In anticipation of this summer,
when the population swells with thousands of people who stay at
resorts or begin canoe treks, residents have updated evacuation
plans and installed sprinkler systems, and they are preparing to
warn visitors about fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joke that two cigarettes and a campfire and you'll have a
plane over you dropping water,'' Kerfoot said.
</P>
<P>
   The forest service reports no slowdown in the number of
wilderness reservations for this summer. But some canoe outfitters
say they are seeing as much as a 15 percent decline in their
bookings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about people panicking from incorrect
information,'' said David Seaton, who runs Hungry Jack Outfitters.
``We're hoping for a Y2K II. We'll be so prepared that nothing will
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
