<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-ENVIRO-865(2TA     05-13 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ENVIRO-865(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULE-SETTING POWER OF FEDERAL AGENCIES FACES SUPREME COURT
CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: D.C., Mass., N.J.)   By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The last time the Supreme Court ruled that Congress
had unconstitutionally given away too much of its lawmaking
authority to the executive branch, a majority of the justices who
sit on the court today had not even been born.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1935, and since then, the doctrine of
``nondelegation,'' which the court invoked to strike down part of a
major New Deal program, the National Industrial Recovery Act, has
appeared little more than a historical footnote. It lingered as a
quaint reminder of a formalistic approach to the constitutional
separation of powers, even as the modern administrative state, with
powerful regulatory agencies engaging in what often looks very much
like lawmaking, grew up around it.
</P>
<P>
   But while it disappeared from public view, the nondelegation
doctrine has not lacked for friends in high places: academics,
lawyers for regulated industries, as well as the occasional judge,
who found a disturbing lack of political accountability in
Congress' penchant for shifting important policy choices to
administrative agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 65 years, the issue has cycled back to the Supreme
Court. The court will announce, perhaps as early as Monday, whether
it will hear an appeal from a ruling last year that invalidated two
clean air standards issued in 1997 by the Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision last May by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia Circuit concerned an important issue
of environmental law, what set off shock waves was not so much the
actual ruling as its rationale: that the Clean Air Act, as
interpreted by the agency, ``effects an unconstitutional delegation
of legislative power.''
</P>
<P>
   After failing to persuade the full appeals court last fall to
reconsider the panel's 2-1 decision, the Clinton administration,
calling the case one of ``extraordinary governmental concern,''
filed a Supreme Court appeal in January. So did Massachusetts and
New Jersey, along with the American Lung Association, which had
participated at the appeals court level to defend the new clean air
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of industry groups that successfully challenged
the standards, including the American Trucking Associations, the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the American Farm Bureau Federation,
is also urging the justices to accept the case, for the purpose of
affirming the decision that the new standards are invalid. The
coalition, in fact, wants the court to broaden the scope of the
case and decide for the first time whether the Clean Air Act
requires the Environmental Protection Agency, in setting national
standards, to engage in some form of cost-benefit analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The industry coalition argues that by reading a cost-benefit
requirement into the statute, the justices would be providing the
``intelligible principles'' that the appeals court found lacking
and would thus be able to avoid the whole sticky nondelegation
issue. Whether the justices will find industry's invitation
attractive is highly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   But virtually everyone familiar with the case, Browner vs.
American Trucking Associations, No. 99-1257, assumes that the court
will grant at least the federal government's petition and decide,
in its next term, whether the nondelegation doctrine merits the new
lease on life the appeals court gave it in what Solicitor General
Seth P. Waxman's petition for the government calls a ``radical
departure from settled law.''
</P>
<P>
   The implications are enormous. ``It's the basic challenge to the
administrative state,'' Richard Lazarus, an expert in
administrative and environmental law at Georgetown University Law
Center, said in a recent interview. ``A huge amount of regulated
activity depends on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act is hardly unique in the amount of
administrative discretion it leaves in the hands of the agency; if
this law is unconstitutional on the basis of excessive delegation,
then so, plausibly, are many others, from the Communications Act of
1934, which authorized the Federal Communications Commission to
regulate broadcasting in light of ``public interest, convenience,
and necessity,'' to the Sentencing Reform Act of 1984, which
established and placed in the judicial branch a commission charged
with establishing the range of sentences for every federal offense,
an almost quintessentially legislative power.
</P>
<P>
   These delegations and countless others _ with the exception of
two New Deal-era initiatives struck down in 1935 _ have been upheld
by the Supreme Court under a test established in a 1928 opinion by
Chief Justice William Howard Taft. Under that test, a delegation of
legislative authority will be upheld as long as Congress ``shall
lay down by legislative act an intelligible principle'' to which
the agency ``is directed to conform.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Judges Stephen Williams and Douglas Ginsburg, over
the dissent of Judge David Tatel, found lacking in the Clean Air
Act. The law directs the Environmental Protection Agency to set
national air quality standards at levels that ``in the judgment of
the administrator'' and ``allowing an adequate margin of safety''
are ``requisite to protect the public health.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court majority said that for pollutants like those
at issue in the case, ozone and fine airborne particles, for which
there is no level above zero that does not pose a health risk, the
agency lacked ``any determinate criterion for drawing lines'' and
had ``no intelligible principle by which to identify a stopping
point.'' The agency's unconfined discretion ``leaves it free to
pick any point between zero and a hair below the concentrations
yielding London's Killer Fog,'' the decision said, referring to the
4,000 deaths that occurred in a weeklong pollution crisis in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tatel's dissenting opinion and the various Supreme Court
appeals assert that the agency's process for setting its new
standards, based on dozens of studies as well as review by an
independent scientific advisory panel, bore no relationship to the
casual and high-handed approach portrayed by the appeals court
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of broad agency discretion often argue that Congress
cannot possibly make the fine-tuned scientific judgments necessary
to keep modern regulatory programs up to date, a point that
Congress recognized in the Clean Air Act by instructing the EPA to
review national air quality standards every five years.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the government petition notes, agency regulations
are always subject to being set aside as ``arbitrary and
capricious,'' a well-known administrative law concept that serves
adequately as a judicial brake on agency behavior without calling
the entire regulatory structure into question.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court majority clearly had a more expansive game
plan than setting aside a regulation or two. In a 1995 essay in the
magazine Regulation, published by the libertarian Cato Institute,
Ginsburg offered a paean to the nondelegation doctrine, which he
said had existed, along with other concepts repudiated as the
Supreme Court acquiesced in the New Deal vision of a strong
national government, for 60 years ``only as part of the
Constitution-in-exile.'' He wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory of these ancient exiles, banished for standing in
opposition to unlimited government, is kept alive by a few scholars
who labor on in the hope of a restoration, a second coming of the
Constitution of liberty _ even if perhaps not in their own
lifetimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the eventual fate of the Clear Air Act case, Ginsburg's
words sound decidedly less out of context today than they did even
five years ago, just before the court began issuing a series of
decisions reviving a limited vision of federal power. Chief Justice
William Rehnquist has written many of those opinions, and if the
nondelegation doctrine resonates for any member of the court, it
does so for him. Twenty years ago, as an associate justice,
Rehnquist was a solitary voice in any earlier regulatory case when
he wrote, ``We ought not to shy away from our judicial duty to
invalidate unconstitutional delegations of legislative authority
solely out of concern that we should thereby reinvigorate
discredited constitutional doctrines of the pre-New Deal era.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
