u a BC-HEMINGS-STREET-720&AMP;AD     05-13 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGS-STREET-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET-NAME PROPOSAL SPARKS A JEFFERSONIAN DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ This American classic city is about to
acknowledge a Faulknerian chapter and consider naming a street
Hemings Way after Sally Hemings, the slave of Thomas Jefferson who,
the scholars of Monticello concede, was almost certainly the mother
of at least one of his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people raised with the belief that this was a moral
impossibility, it's not an easy transition,'' said Cinder Stanton,
one of the Monticello historians in the eye of a double storm.
</P>
<P>
   On one front, dissenters in the Jefferson bloodline are fighting
the latest DNA evidence of Jefferson's paternity as they heatedly
deny the kinship claims of Hemings' African-American descendants.
</P>
<P>
   On the other front, the street-naming proposal, which is
expected to move to the City Council next month, is being denounced
by some black residents as an affront to the countless other former
slave families who helped build this city.
</P>
<P>
   ``In naming Hemings to this supposed status, we are not honoring
her but Jefferson and the institution of slavery that defiled and
demeaned our ancestors,'' said Agnes Cross-White, editor of The
Tribune, the local black community newspaper. Cross-White has been
thundering against the street naming and arguing for a public
memorial far more inclusive of local slave history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we so devoid of self-esteem that we will accept and cling
to anything white because it makes us feel more valuable, more
American?'' Cross-White asked. She dismissed the street-name
proposal as an attempt to mine tourist gold from a bit of
underground history long denied by the white establishment until
modern science rendered the issue moot, at least for the keepers of
Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   On a human level, the controversy bubbling here suggests that
Jefferson's continuing legacy in this Blue Ridge Valley region
includes all the fighting that typically defines one man's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're white, we're black and we're in between,'' said Dorothy
Westerinen, prouder of bearing Hemings' blood than any tincture of
Jefferson's. She holds that both the Hemings family and American
history would be well honored by having the Hemings name on a strip
of West 10th Street, next to a Main Street motel on a plot where
Sally Hemings lived and where she died after slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Westerinen journeyed here from her home in New York last weekend
with other Hemings descendants from across the nation. They held
another inconclusive meeting with the Monticello Association, a
group of Jefferson descendants wrestling with the question of
whether to admit Hemings kin to membership, a privilege that
includes the right of burial in the cemetery on the Jefferson
estate in Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pretty ugly,'' Westerinen said of the closed meeting.
``Most of the association members were lovely toward us, but a
faction that's splintering off from the main group grew
particularly insulting, especially toward the Monticello historians
trying to explain the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the association said in a statement that the
delay was a result of ``the complexity of the issues.'' But the new
splinter group, led by John H. Works Jr., a Jefferson descendant,
is resolved to fight the paternity finding.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, DNA test results linked the two family lines
by way of Jefferson, and in January the likelihood was confirmed on
the basis of parallel historic evidence by scholars at the Thomas
Jefferson Memorial Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not pin it on Thomas Jefferson,'' Works insisted. He
is among those who deny the evidence and argue that even if it is
valid, some other Jefferson male might have been the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to see the truth remembered,'' said Kevin Cox, a
resident concerned that this city of 40,000 not shy away from the
rough edges of its history.
</P>
<P>
   As the two extended families ponder their disunity, the city
fathers will go ahead with consideration of the Hemings Way
proposal, Mayor Virginia Daugherty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supporting it because the whole Hemings family was very
important in our early history here,'' Daugherty said. ``Her family
eventually owned 12 different pieces of property around town. This
issue is all about our own sense of ourselves as a city and what we
would like to pass along to our children.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayor is supported by Dianne Swann-Wright, one of the
Monticello historians who confirmed the paternity evidence.
Swann-Wright stresses that the Hemings tale embraces ``unknown acts
of courage, discipline and steadfastness'' that are universal in
human experience. ``I say, name the corridor after all of them, in
honor of them and in honor of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-White of The Tribune raised the Groucho Marx question,
asking ``why anyone would want to belong to this association based
on the fact that Jefferson was a man who took lecherous advantage
of his property.'' Local blacks, the editor said, laugh off the
romantic television docudramas about the affair but pay tribute to
Hemings for having prevailed through unimaginably difficult trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she could make her life and the lives of her children more
tolerable by being the physical interest of the master, then more
power to the sister,'' Cross-White said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hemings' descendants emphasize that the issue actually
involves the larger family of America itself. They promise to
continue pressing Jeffersonian bluebloods to acknowledge their
black enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I couldn't care less about membership or where I'm
buried,'' Westerinen said. ``We want our family to recognize us, to
embrace us. And that's a very important symbolic gesture for the
rest of the nation to see. I'm proud of Sally Hemings. She put up
with a hell of a lot from him.''
</P>
<P>
   And so must this city, Cross-White said. ``We're living with
Thomas Jefferson every single day,'' she noted wearily. ``He's
still walking the streets of this city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
