<SLUG> BC-MOMS-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS MOTHERS, NOT GUN LOBBY, THE STRONGER VOICE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Ga.)  By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the nation's capital and other cities prepared
for Mother's Day demonstrations favoring stricter gun control laws,
President Clinton said the events on Sunday would show that the gun
lobby ``is no match for America's moms.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his regularly scheduled radio address on Saturday
to praise the Million Mom March, the label organizers have given to
nationwide demonstrations. The organizers expected to draw about
150,000 people to the main march in Washington. The president has
repeatedly spoken out for the march, urging Congress to act on gun
control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A counterdemonstration is also scheduled on Sunday in Washington
by a group of women who oppose new controls on guns. While the
larger crowd occupies the huge grassy Mall at the foot of Capitol
Hill, the counterdemonstrators, sponsored by a Dallas group called
the Second Amendment Sisters, will march nearby up Constitution
Avenue to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Million Mom March have said it is not, as
organizers characterize it, a true grass-roots movement but rather
a political operation in masquerade. But while some political
figures, including Hillary Rodham Clinton, are expected to join in
the march, the featured speakers are to be ordinary people whose
lives have been shattered by gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the organizers have lost children of their own and
other loved ones to gunfire,'' said the president, who met some of
them at the White House recently as part of his publicity campaign
on the gun issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the march is striking a deep chord in women
who have not been touched by gun violence, but who simply fear for
the safety of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is Caren Appel, a 38-year-old mother of three from
Atlanta. After coordinating a companion Million Mom March in that
city, she brought her family to Washington this weekend for the
main demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my way of showing complete support for this movement,''
Appel said. ``I just felt that I personally needed to do something
so that there were no more shootings in schools. I want my children
to be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Appel said she felt ``lucky that gun violence hasn't
hit me,'' she said she did have a scare recently. Her 8-year-old
daughter went to visit a friend, and came home to report that
children in the house had produced ``the family gun,'' which they
claimed was real. Appel did not pursue the issue with the other
parents.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``From now on, if I do not know the family, I
will ask if there is a gun in the house, and I will ask if it is
locked up, and then I will decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the counterdemonstration said that their keynote
speaker would be Suzanna Gratia-Hupp, a state representative from
Texas whose parents were among 21 people killed in a rampage
shooting at a restaurant in 1991. She has said that she might have
shot the assailant and prevented the massacre if she had been
allowed by law to carry her legally owned sidearm into the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Saturday, President Clinton credited the
Million Mom March as ``a grass-roots effort that has already put
stronger laws in place in states like California, Massachusetts and
Maryland. They're letting the gun lobby know it is no match for
America's moms. But our nationwide fight won't be over tomorrow, no
matter how many march. We have so much work still to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation that Clinton favors would close a loophole
allowing the sale of some firearms at gun shows without full
background checks of the buyers; mandate child safety locks with
every handgun sold; ban high capacity ammunition clips; bar the
most violent juveniles from possessing firearms as adults, and hold
adults accountable if they allow children access to guns. He has
also proposed research on safer ``smart guns'' and a state-based
licensing system, and sought $280 million for increasing
enforcement of gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association has countered with a pledge to
spend an additional $1 million on gun safety education in
elementary schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-WARLORDI     05-13 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-WARLORDISM-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE'S RETURN TO WARLORD RULE DRAWS IN U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ For years, warlordism has ruled Sierra
Leone, a state in name alone. With the authority of the government
barely extending beyond Freetown, warlords have been ensconced in
different corners of the country, each with access to enough
diamond mines to buy arms. The balance of power shifted
occasionally, depending on the energies of a Nigerian-led
intervention force or mercenaries hired by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the apparent collapse of a 9-month-old peace accord,
Sierra Leone is on the verge of slipping back into warlordism. The
Nigerians, whose departure less than two weeks ago led the top
warlord, Foday Sankoh, to challenge the U.N. force, are on their
way back.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference now is that U.N. peacekeepers are in the
middle of all this, and an increasing number of British
paratroopers are under pressure to provide more muscle.
</P>
<P>
   While the peacekeepers arrived with the understanding that they
would be a neutral force, they have become allied with the Sierra
Leone army, with the soldiers of another warlord, a born-again
Christian named Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma, and with a militia
controlled by Hinga Norman, nominally a deputy defense minister,
all against Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Having clambered over the back wall of his house last week when
U.N. peacekeepers were not around, Sankoh, a potbellied 63-year-old
with a reportedly bad heart, is on the run. Many suspect he has
somehow fled far from the capital, perhaps as far as Liberia, a
redoubt from which he has often marshaled his forces during this
country's 9-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, two men who have long commanded personal
militias of their own have re-emerged as power brokers. Their
troops helped repel an assault on Freetown by Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front, known as the RUF, when it became clear
that the U.N. force was unable to do that by itself.
</P>
<P>
   At ease inside his home office, wearing a green robe and
slippers, Koroma, who has retired from the Sierra Leonean army
since he briefly held power after a coup in 1997, smiled when he
was asked the number of soldiers at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say. But the number was significant, judging from
the thousands of loyalists who surfaced on the streets, armed with
automatic rifles, after he spoke on national radio. Koroma told his
men to rearm, though not before shouting, ``Jesus,'' for five
minutes at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Norman gave orders from his office inside the
Ministry of Defense. He derives his power from his Kamajor militia,
the thousands of tribal hunters who have traditionally sided with
the government. Norman's men gird themselves for battle by applying
oil to their skin, putting on wigs, mirrors and horns, and reciting
verses from the Koran and the Bible _ so that ``they will be saved
from RUF bullets,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe these things can work,'' the deputy defense minister
said.
</P>
<P>
   The re-emergence of warlordism in Sierra Leone has led experts
to draw parallels with Somalia, where the West had a traumatic
experience with peacekeeping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity is one reason that Washington seems ready to
weather criticism rather than become directly engaged in Sierra
Leone, and that the British keep insisting they are here merely to
evacuate Europeans and offer technical assistance, even as their
presence at the front line becomes clearer day by day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra Leone is in serious danger of being mired in violence
again, with the looming possibility of turning into another
Somalia, a state now being run by bands of warlords,'' Roble
Olhaye, the ambassador from Djibouti to the United Nations, said at
the Security Council's first public debate on Sierra Leone on
Thursday. Olhaye, whose country borders Somalia, added, ``We cannot
abandon Sierra Leone.''
</P>
<P>
   In Somalia, the United Nations also found itself trying to keep
peace in a stateless territory riven by clan warfare, alongside
U.S. troops under direct U.S. command. There, too, they came to
oppose one warlord, Gen. Mohammed Farah Aideed. The operation came
to a disastrous end when 18 American soldiers were killed during an
attack on Aideed, and one American's corpse was dragged through the
streets of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   Somalia traumatized the West, especially the United States, in
such a way that the United Nations remained paralyzed in the face
of large-scale massacres in Rwanda in 1994. At least half a million
Tutsi were killed in an event that directly led to the later war in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   If Sierra Leone is considered a test of the West's resolve in
African peacekeeping, it is because Congo presents the same
problems _ though on a grander scale. Congo, where the United
Nations is considering sending a peacekeeping force, is the size of
Western Europe. There, too, the government's authority is limited
to the capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, the late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko could
count on the West to provide money and arms. Now, Congolese
warlords, armies from five foreign countries, and innumerable
militias have carved up the Congo into various strongholds,
plundering its mineral riches to buy arms. President Laurent
Kabila, who was for decades a small-scale warlord in Congo's
northeast, is the head of the country's central government.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila may not be a warlord, technically. But in his persistent
efforts to block his country's peace negotiations, he is surely one
of the ``national leaders who are so insular, whose vision is so
narrow, that in their concerns about their own power and survival,
the interests of their people don't count,'' as U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Friday, describing leaders who
made peacekeeping a much more complex operation than it was in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, the warlords seem to be back at war with one
another. Even if the fighting is contained in the near future, the
warlords have gained legitimacy and power as the government and the
United Nations had no choice but to become allied with them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These are uneasy alliances, especially the one between the
government and Koroma. The government in theory has 5,000 soldiers,
but Koroma is considered the real force behind the military.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Koroma, now 40, overthrew the elected government of
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and then invited Sankoh's group to join him in
power. At his home on Friday, he said he had done so ``in the
interest of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we can end this war is to call these guys out of
the bush and talk to them,'' he said. ``So we invited them to come
out. If we said we are going to end it militarily, we will never
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his real motives, the Nigerians expelled him in 1998
and reinstalled Kabbah. Over the next year, Koroma and Sankoh's
followers fought fiercely together to regain power, culminating in
an attack on Freetown in January 1999, during which thousands of
civilians were killed, raped or maimed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the peace accord was signed last July, Koroma had served
as the chairman of the committee for the consolidation of peace in
a power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found him to be reasonably remorseful of whatever it is
that he may have done in the past,'' said Septimus Kaikai, Kabbah's
spokesman. He added that, for example, Koroma on his own had
visited a Freetown camp for amputees, whereas Sankoh never had.
``We found that he was willing to work with us to resolve the
crisis in the country. And we were reasonably happy with some of
the things that he has been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a risk here?'' Kaikai said. ``If you take note of the
fact that there is risk involved in everything we do, yes, there's
a certain amount of risk involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabbah, a former U.N. Development Program official, has proved
to be a powerless, nearly irrelevant, figure who seldom leaves his
hilltop mansion. So a greater amount of risk may derive from
Koroma's alliance with Norman.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups had fought each other fiercely for years, but now
find themselves allied against Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   The Kamajors, who are mostly traditional hunters from the south,
began fighting in the early 1990s. Norman, 60, a former soldier who
was convicted of treason and imprisoned from 1968 to 1974, became
the Kamajors' leader in 1994. Made up entirely of volunteers, the
Kamajor militia are thought to number around 15,000, though Norman
claims their real number is 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quarreling bedmates,'' Norman said of his new alliance
with Koroma. ``We are trying hard to build confidence. We are not
best friends yet, but the `best' should come later.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Sankoh, he has not been spotted in Freetown since
climbing over his back wall. Many believe that without him, his
rebel group will splinter into factions led by sub-warlords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
