<HEADER>
A4165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-DOCTORS-2TAKES-     05-13 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-DOCTORS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER FLORIDA EXAM PITS CUBAN EXILES AGAINST DOCTORS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  By PETER T. KILBORN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A decadeslong dispute over the licensing of a group of
Cubans who want to practice medicine in Florida is testing the
power of the Cuban-American lobby against that of the state's
medical establishment and is about to involve the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will affect the futures of Cuban refugees who have
been struggling for the right to be licensed as doctors in the
United States. Also at stake, representatives of the medical
establishment say, are standards of care for the profession.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the 400 immigrants are Cubans who came to
Florida in the 1980s. Nicaraguans make up about a third of the
group. While contending that they had medical training or had been
licensed in their homeland, they have been unable to produce
sufficient evidence to obtain licenses here or to pass a national
exam required for all doctors by all states.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate them, the Florida Legislature, at the urging of
the Cuban-American Caucus, has established a separate test for this
group, in the hopes of making it easier to pass. It has placed less
emphasis on pure science and more on treatment and diagnosis, and
it has made special courses available to help these immigrants
prepare for the test.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has also eliminated internships and hospital
residency as preconditions for licensing for this group.
</P>
<P>
   The test was actually revised twice. After more than 90 percent
of the immigrant doctors failed the modified exam when they first
took it last May, the state rewrote it again and translated it into
Spanish. Again, more than 90 percent failed the easier version when
they took it in November. With still further revisions, the exam
will be offered yet again late this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cuban-American doctors' lobby says it will press
the Legislature to eliminate licensing exams entirely for the group
and to require instead that the doctors work under the close
supervision of licensed physicians before setting off on their own.
</P>
<P>
   While many Cuban exiles have passed the test required of other
doctors, the fact that one group of exiles is getting so much
special attention has raised concerns among members of the medical
establishment in Florida and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   At its September meeting, the Florida Medical Association
adopted a resolution urging the Legislature to abolish the special
exam and rely solely on the national exam. And at its annual
meeting in June, the American Medical Association's House of
Delegates will vote on a resolution supporting the Florida
association's resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to open the medical system to testing for a
particular group,'' said Dr. Yank Coble, an endocrinologist in
Jacksonville, Fla., and a member of the AMA's board of trustees.
``It's important not to be perceived as making special exceptions
for political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Other medical organizations have expressed opposition as well,
contending that these accommodations are, in effect, unleashing an
underqualified group of doctors on an unsuspecting public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public needs to be concerned,'' said Dr. L. Thomas Bowles,
president of the National Board of Medical Examiners in
Philadelphia. ``No other state has found it necessary to create an
alternate pathway for a special cohort of physicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts contend that the fact that the Legislature has
persisted in its efforts to help these immigrants illustrates the
power of a relatively small group of Cuban legislators who make up
the Cuban-American Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Cuban-American legislators maintain that
they are trying to right injustices against their fellow exiles.
They say the Florida Medical Association and the American Medical
Association want to restrict competition for patients and exert
unfair influence over the State Health Department and its Board of
Medicine, which administers the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue of fairness,'' said state Rep. Rudy Garcia
Jr., a Republican from Hialeah and a prominent spokesman for South
Florida's 800,000 Cuban-Americans. The content and scoring of the
tests that the state devised for the immigrants seem to
discriminate against them, Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Camilo Lopez is typical of the group of immigrants
whom the Legislature is trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 39, said he fled Cuba for Miami in March 1980, having
completed a year of medical school in his homeland. Unable to
afford the high cost of medical school here, he went to the
Dominican Republic, where, he says, he completed his medical
studies at Utesa University. He then returned to Florida, where he
was granted a temporary license to become a physician's assistant,
which allowed him to provide much of the care of a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lopez, who is married and the father of two
teen-agers, has been trying to become a doctor. Like some of his
colleagues, he could not produce credible evidence of his training
and as a result could not be certified to take a national licensing
exam.
</P>
<P>
   In another special privilege that the Legislature created for
the group, a two-semester course was designed to prepare the Cubans
for the exam. The course was offered in 1990 and 1992 by the
University of Miami and by a private company.
</P>
<P>
   But as they were completing the course, the National Board of
Medical Examiners, Bowles' organization, and the Federation of
State Medical Boards in Chicago introduced a new national exam, the
U.S. Medical Licensing Examination, replacing the one for which the
students had been studying. The students, who had paid the
University of Miami $10,000 each for tuition, were ill-prepared to
take the new exam. Some took it and failed it; some did not take
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything they were supposed to do,'' said State
Sen. Mario Diaz-Balart, a Miami Republican who is leaving the
Senate this month because of term limits. ``And oops. Wrong exam.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature then asked the University of South Florida to
prepare a special licensing exam for the group. In spite of the
change, 250 of 260 candidates, including Lopez, failed the special
exam when it was offered last May.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Alberto Gutman, a Cuban-American Republican from
Miami who has been sentenced to prison for Medicare fraud and gave
up his seat last year after he was indicted, persuaded the Board of
Medicine to change some questions and translate the exam into
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In November, 87 candidates took the revised exam, and 79 failed.
Saying he believed that the second exam was stacked against him,
Lopez did not take it.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, about 40 percent of foreign-trained doctors fail the
national exam on the first try, four times the rate of U.S.-trained
physicians. Doctor organizations attribute the failures mostly to
differences in medical school training, difficulties with English
and unfamiliarity with U.S. medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In a comprehensive study of physician licensing and discipline
five years ago, the Florida Legislature's nonpartisan Office of
Program Policy Analysis and Government Accountability called the
licensing process neutral and thorough. ``If an applicant satisfies
all the requirements prescribed by statute and rule,'' the office
concluded, ``the license will be issued.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's special treatment upsets many doctors, including
some of the state's 12,000 other foreign-trained physicians, a
third of the total of 37,500 practicing in Florida, who earned
their licenses without special help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're are not bad doctors,'' said Dr. Juan Wester, a surgeon
in Hollywood, Fla., who was born in Argentina and went to medical
school there. ``They're probably as good as many of us. But we have
always felt that as international medical graduates, we wanted to
be treated exactly the same as anybody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
