<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-SANKOH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE SAYS REBELS WERE DRIVEN BY DIAMONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of fighting among rebel groups and government troops
in the capital of Sierra Leone, officials loyal to President Ahman
Tejan Kabbah are beginning to amass documents that they say show
the extent to which the rebel leader Foday Sankoh was
systematically exploiting the country's diamonds to pay for his
rebellion and enrich himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible people in history keep very good records,'' a
high-ranking government official said in a telephone interview
Saturday. On Monday, Sierra Leone's attorney general, Solomon
Berewa, plans to begin making public a large number of documents
found in the looted house of Sankoh, whose whereabouts is now
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of some of these papers dealing with the diamond trade
were made available to The New York Times by other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, whose forces are being held responsible for the
abduction of about 500 U.N. peacekeepers _ some of whom had begun
to be assigned to diamond-producing areas _ took over the mining
ministry last year after a peace agreement brought him into
government in return for ending his savage rebellion. Under
Sankoh's soldiers, many of them brutalized children themselves, the
limbs of civilians were hacked off and communities were destroyed
to send a deliberate message of terror throughout the population.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sankoh, leader of the Revolutionary United Front, had
been in government since last summer, some of his diamond deals
would have presumably been legal. Foreign companies, including some
from the United States, were known to have been negotiating with
him, or at least exploring the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But records that government officials say they are finding now
appear to be meticulous accounts of personal deals recording the
delivery to Sankoh of more than 2,000 stones of varying sizes from
last August, soon after Sankoh came into government, until the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the records they found _ along with letters from a
business associate abroad, identified only as ``Michel,'' who was
apparently trying to find a buyer for the diamonds in Antwerp,
Belgium, the center of the rough diamond trade _ officials in
Sierra Leone are more convinced than ever that the trouble with
U.N. peacekeepers began when the force's Indian commander, Maj.
Gen. Vijay Kumar Jetley, ordered some of his troops into the
richest diamond mining area, around Kono, in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as Sankoh saw that the U.N. was serious about
deploying in Kono, then he declared war on the U.N.,'' the senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The documents involving diamonds _ including handwritten lists
naming every courier who brought stones to Sankoh, with notes about
their color and size _ may answer other questions puzzling the
government about the rebel leader's relations with President
Charles Taylor of neighboring Liberia and with Sankoh's former
field commander, Sam Bockarie.
</P>
<P>
   Bockarie, who personally delivered many of the stones to Sankoh,
according to the records, opposed the peace agreement with the
government and fled several months ago to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Sankoh's records no longer included diamond
deliveries. Officials want to know why, as well as if and how,
these events may have been related. In recent months, Sankoh, whose
rebel movement was helped if not created by Taylor, appears to have
been trying to circumvent the Liberians as he sought partners for
diamond deals abroad.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, the Security Council, under the
leadership of the Canadian ambassador, Robert Fowler, has produced
a report on how the diamond trade fueled the rebellion in Angola of
Jonas Savimbi and his organization, the Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, or Unita. The council plans to act on that
report in the fall after further investigations, possibly seeking
punitive measures against countries or companies that have been
trading with Unita in violation of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, officials say they are now looking at evidence
of a similar gems-for-weapons system developed by Sankoh. Early
reading of documents shows all the same hallmarks _ local mining
operations, links to international traders and a marketing focus on
Antwerp, which until recently has been lax in examining the origins
of gems or the identities of sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone officials say that Sankoh may have been doing more
than merely enriching himself and buying weapons for his rebel
troops in the field. There is some evidence emerging, they say,
that he may have been planning to accumulate enough resources to
attempt to overthrow the government in Freetown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-POLITICS-950&AMP;ADD     05-13 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD AGAIN FEARED IN PERU'S RUNOFF ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Two weeks before the final round of Peru's
presidential election, international observers say they again have
serious concerns that President Alberto Fujimori may be preparing
to steal enough votes to ensure he wins a third term.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Peru came close to turmoil as opposition candidates
and election monitors accused the government of widespread vote
tampering after a campaign marred by smear tactics and dirty
tricks. A crisis was averted only when electoral authorities
announced that Fujimori had fallen just short of an outright
first-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now negotiations between the government and the opposition to
improve election monitoring have collapsed over the government's
refusal to replace poll watchers who reportedly took part in the
tampering of ballots in the first vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are disquieting signs that the scenario of the first
round may be repeated,'' said Eduardo Stein, a former Guatemalan
foreign minister who leads the election observation team for the
Organization of American States. ``We don't know if there will be
enough guarantees for a clean, transparent election.''
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, the business school professor who has staged a
surprisingly strong challenge to Fujimori, is threatening to pull
out of the race rather than lend credibility to a process he
characterizes as hopelessly flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Observers from the OAS say the government has set such an early
date for the runoff that there is not enough time to guarantee that
the count will be any more reliable now than in the first round on
April 9.
</P>
<P>
   They say they continue to receive reports that army and
government vehicles are being used to the advantage of the Fujimori
campaign and that officials involved in handing out milk and
cereals to poor mothers are mixing political propaganda with the
food aid.
</P>
<P>
   Independent observers say Fujimori's intelligence service
appears to continue to orchestrate coverage of the campaign in
several tabloid newspapers and a political magazine called Si,
which have depicted Toledo as unstable, a liar and a tool of Alan
Garcia, a former president who lives in exile to escape corruption
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of Toledo in the magazine typically show him with a
bottle or glass in his hand _ suggesting that the opposition
candidate, who is a heavy water drinker, is imbibing something
alcoholic. Several Si articles have reported sardonically that
Johnny Walker is the challenger's principal adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The independence of the election apparatus remains in question.
The senior officials who presided over the first round remain in
place. And a government investigation into evidence that the
Fujimori campaign forged a million signatures to get him on the
ballot has stalled. A few election officials have resigned and many
more are expected to be implicated in the scandal _ but only after
the vote on May 28 is tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Peruvian government officials continue to commit
themselves publicly to holding a clean election. Francisco Tudela,
Fujimori's vice presidential running mate, said last week, ``It is
everyone's concern to create better conditions in the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   International election observers, however, say privately that
they believe the government is manipulating them by agreeing to
make changes that are more cosmetic than real. For instance, the
government television network, which for months covered only the
Fujimori campaign, broadcast parts of a Toledo rally for the first
time last week. But only snippets of Toledo's speech were shown and
camera shots focused on the outskirts of the crowd, giving the
appearance that attendance was sparse.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Atlanta-based Carter Center and the nonprofit
National Democratic Institute, both of which have monitored
numerous elections around the world, said that unless there were
``immediate and comprehensive improvements'' in the administrative
and technical procedures of the runoff, ``Peru's election process
will ultimately fail to meet minimal international standards for
democratic elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Various opinion polls show the race between Fujimori and Toledo
to be very close, and there is a good chance that Fujimori could
win a majority without fraud. But the reports of new irregularities
suggest that a Fujimori victory could be seriously tarnished even
if cleanly won, igniting more street demonstrations and diminishing
the president's authority as he tries to fight drug trafficking and
promote investment through his third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   According to the official first-round count, Fujimori won 49.87
percent of the vote to Toledo's 40.24 percent. Recent polls show
that a majority of Peruvians, including those who support Fujimori,
believe there was fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fujimori wins, there still will be a crisis of
credibility,'' said Rafael Roncagliolo, director of Transparencia,
a Peruvian election monitoring group largely financed by the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has embraced Fujimori's anti-drug and
anti-terrorism efforts, could be put in the uncomfortable position
of either choosing to support a tainted government and compromising
on its commitment to uphold democracy in Latin America or cutting
back on cooperation that is in both countries' interests.
</P>
<P>
   The administration put heavy pressure on the Fujimori government
to hold a runoff after international monitors reported during the
first-round vote that ballots and tally sheets had disappeared and
election computer centers had shut their doors without explanation
for many hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials are again pressing for a clean
election and expressing cautious optimism that it is still
possible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They point to several modest signs of improvement, including an
opening of some government-allied television stations. They also
note that election officials appear to be moving toward giving
Toledo's party access to software that will allow it to inspect the
final computer vote count.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and independent monitors have praised
election officials for agreeing to retrain poll watchers and
refining the lines of command for officials responsible for
transporting and counting the ballots and vote tally sheets.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein, the OAS official who has emerged as the most
influential independent election monitor, is still expressing
serious reservations.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it would take three weeks to test the computer
software that the government is preparing to provide the opposition
to watch the vote count. But with only two weeks to election day,
the software still has not been made available for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that the government had so far agreed to only
one independent monitoring station capable of watching the
transmission of voting data from 16 vote tabulation centers,
leaving 40 tabulation centers uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that unauthorized people could transmit data or
corrupt data without observers knowing it,'' Stein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
