<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG0514-COX     05-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. governor teaches a lesson in flag compromise
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ As much as anybody, South Carolina Gov. Jim
Hodges may have determined the future of the Confederate battle
flag, one of Dixie's most enduring symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The argument has roiled privately and publicly for months in the
Legislature but now seems headed for a resolution that will remove
the battle flag from the Capitol dome July 1 for the first time in
38 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges has created a blueprint for compromise that can be
followed by fellow Southern Democratic Governors Roy Barnes of
Georgia and Ronnie Musgrove of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   When South Carolina lowers the Rebel banner, Georgia and
Mississippi still will be displaying the battle emblem of the
Confederacy on their state flags. Debate then will belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will say to Jim Hodges, `You did the right thing, that
you were a statesman,' '' said Georgia Rep. Tyrone Brooks
(D-Atlanta), a key member of the legislative black caucus who will
fight next year to change the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges massaged and managed the fiery debate within the cool
granite walls of the Capitol, pulling together both parties.
Through public comments dispensed at calculated moments, he steered
the Legislature. When the House threatened stalling to death a
compromise sent from the Senate, Hodges hinted he'd call a costly
and embarrassing special session.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING A PROACTIVE APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   So far, Barnes has spoken vaguely about Georgia's flag, changed
to include the Rebel design in 1956, a time when federal courts
were mandating school desegregation in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has said only that there's no legislative will to change
the flag _ a path Hodges walked until the NAACP enacted a tourism
boycott of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   While there remains considerable debate about whether the
boycott has hurt South Carolina economically, it undeniably brought
the state a lot of negative media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be proactive on it. It's not an issue that's
going to go away,'' Hodges said in his office Thursday, the morning
after the state House passed its version of a Senate compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy Barnes and I have talked a couple of times about it, not
at length,'' Hodges said. ``It's an issue that needs to be resolved
for the image of the states and for the people as well. Our states
need to be focusing on educational improvement, health care. To be
distracted and spend the amount of time that can be consumed on an
issue like this, it's not good for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, Republican Gov. David Beasley, and
former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller, a Democrat, Hodges minimized his
public comments until he had worked privately to achieve broad
support among a number of leaders _ blacks, whites, Republicans,
Democrats, big business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only get so many bites of the apple with public
pronouncements,'' Hodges said. ``Pretty soon, people start ignoring
you if you say the same thing over and over. A leader _ a governor,
particularly _ has to be careful that he or she has something
significant to say. I tried to measure my public pronouncements
very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain Barnes' comparable silence on the issue. The
battle flag helped Beasley lose his job and nearly cost Miller his.
Though not up for re-election in November, Barnes is worried
Republicans could use the flag to chisel away at Democratic
majorities in both legislative chambers.
</P>
<P>
   HOPES BIPARTISAN COALITION WILL PROMPT ACTION BY GOVERNOR BARNES
</P>
<P>
   Among those ready to hold Democrats accountable on the issue is
Georgia House Minority Whip Earl Ehrhart, a Republican and flag
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they think it's such a big issue, then they should go to
every Democrat and say we'll withdraw support this November if you
don't pledge to change the flag,'' Ehrhart said. ``If they don't do
that, they're hypocrites.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Barnes nor his spokeswoman, Jocelyn Butler, will be
drawn into the flag mire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Barnes continues to focus on a number of important
issues,'' including education reform, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   That was how Musgrove in Mississippi dismissed the issue until a
legal challenge to the state flag prompted the state Supreme Court
a week ago to rule that the flag had no official standing. Musgrove
immediately called for a 17-member commission to study redesigning
the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and other black legislators said they'll have a political
plan in place when the Georgia General Assembly returns in January.
Until then, and not before November's elections, he expects Barnes
to remain mute on the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the governor sees there's going to be a bipartisan
coalition of legislators who come together and address the flag
issue, at that point I think the governor will want to say
something,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   After months of meeting privately with all sides of the issue,
Hodges used his January State of the State Address to say in no
uncertain terms the Legislature must bring the flag down.
</P>
<P>
   Learning from Beasley and Miller, Hodges avoided a personalized
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be ownership for the solution beyond the
governor,'' Hodges said. ``I'll be the first to pat the Republican
speaker of the House on the back and a number of others who cast
difficult votes that split them with members of their own party.
They deserve credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate engaged in three months of name-calling before
passing a plan last month that had bipartisan and biracial support.
Last week, the House modified the bill. Lawmakers decided to fly a
smaller, squarer battle flag at the Confederate Soldiers Monument
in front of the Capitol. The slight disagreement is over how high
the flag will fly. The Senate version specifies 20 feet; the House
version, 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Final tinkering either in the Senate or a conference committee
is left before Hodges can sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SPORTS-POLITICS0514-C     05-13 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-POLITICS0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political hay reaped from playing fields
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On March 20, 1980, Craig Masback was standing near the
starting line of a race in San Francisco with aspirations of
representing the United States in the 1980 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Before Masback stepped to the line, a television reporter
approached. Masback, one of the world's best middle-distance
runners, can't forget what he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Carter has just announced a boycott of the Moscow
Olympics,'' the reporter said. ``He says it's a matter of national
security. Do you support your president?''
</P>
<P>
   Masback, who in 1979 had the sixth-fastest time in the world in
1,500 meters, knew his Olympic dream was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would contend that it's impossible to say no to that
question,'' said Masback, chief executive officer of USA Track &AMP;
Field. ``No American could say no to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, athletes often have been forced to choose
sides in the sports-politics debate. And sporting events often have
been the pawns of those political struggles.
</P>
<P>
   That collision soon could reach Georgia. The South Carolina
Legislature voted last week to remove the Confederate battle flag
from the dome of the statehouse, deterring a threat by the NCAA to
remove all NCAA-sponsored events from the state. Now, many believe
the NAACP and other civil rights organizations will turn their
attention to Georgia, which incorporates the Confederate battle
flag on its state flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can expect a long, hot summer,'' said South Carolina Rep.
John Scott, a black Democrat from Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   With Atlanta scheduled to host several national sporting events,
including this summer's Major League Baseball All-Star Game and the
2002 NCAA men's basketball Final Four, Georgia's flag debate could
make South Carolina's look like a blip on the radar screen.
High-profile events create leverage; sports becomes the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports tend to be invested with the most deeply felt
sentiments and values of America,'' said Dr. Harry Edwards, a
professor of sociology at the University of California. ``There's
patriotism, courage and even religion in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports and politics are no strangers. From the 1936 Berlin
Olympics to the raised black-fisted gloves of the 1968 Mexico City
Games, the two have collided throughout history. And it has often
been a volatile mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sports mirror society,'' Masback said. ``I'm not
fundamentally opposed to politics being involved in sports. I
believe the sports boycott of South Africa helped overturn
apartheid. I think the white citizens of South Africa were
fanatical about sports and when they became ostracized by the
sporting world, it opened people's eyes about the injustices that
were occurring in their homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 20th century, the Olympics often were used as a
forum for political protest. The casualties were often the lifelong
dreams of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games, set in motion by President
Jimmy Carter in response to the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in
December 1979, still evokes bitterness among many athletes who feel
they were victims of a sports-politics war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe an opportunity was wrongfully taken from a group of
people, and it can never be returned,'' said Anita DeFrantz, a
member of the 1980 U.S. women's rowing team. ``It was the athletes'
right to decide, and that decision was taken away by very powerful
political forces. People worked their entire lives (to participate
in the Olympics). It's something that you believe in and you make
life-changing decisions to work for it. And then someone says you
can't go. You can't give that back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics were canceled twice because of world wars, and the
Games also have been overshadowed by disputes over race, religion
and nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all of us understand that the Olympic Games are rare,''
said DeFrantz, a vice president of the International Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0143 </DOCNO>
