<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOCKINGBIRD-FEVER0514     05-13 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOCKINGBIRD-FEVER0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mockingbird's' Scout comes to Monroeville
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``I just found my Truman!''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy McCoy's exultant chuckle leapt through the phone line,
making Monroeville, Ala., feel like right next door. And in a way,
the little (population 7,000) town on the western side of the state
has always felt familiar to millions who know it as the real-life
inspiration for Maycomb, where Harper Lee's classic novel ``To Kill
a Mockingbird'' is set.
</P>
<P>
   Lee still lives very privately in Monroeville, also the hometown
of late novelist Truman Capote, one of her closest childhood
friends. After much searching, McCoy, director of the Monroe County
Heritage Museums, cast a diminutive Capote doppelganger for a
walking tour of the town, ground zero for Mockingbird Fever.
</P>
<P>
   The town's Mockingbird Players are midway through a 12-show run
of a two-act stage version of Lee's book, directed by McCoy and
performed in the 400-capacity historic Courthouse. (All 12 shows
sold out the first day tickets were available.)
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the all-amateur production moves to Washington for
five shows at the Kennedy Center. But first, Monroeville gets to
welcome into its midst Saturday perhaps the biggest ``Mockingbird''
fan of all, Mary Badham. A Birmingham native who lives in Virginia,
she played Scout in the Oscar-winning 1962 film version of
``Mockingbird.'' Her character was the emotional eyes and ears of
the story of a 1930s small-town Southern lawyer (Gregory Peck)
defending a black man falsely accused of rape _ yet Badham has
never been to Monroeville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very excited to see the town, the courthouse and
experience the play in that setting,'' said Badham, who will attend
Saturday night's closing performance and gala afterward. ``I feel
that I will need to prepare myself for a very emotional
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   She should be getting used to it. Indeed, she's just back from
Kansas and an event with the Winfield Regional Symphony titled
``Scout Remembers `To Kill a Mockingbird.' '' Several years ago,
the symphony's director asked Badham to talk about making the movie
during a performance of selections from the film score. Invited
back this year, Badham brought along two other actors from the film
_ Philip Alford, who played Scout's brother, Jem, and Brock Peters,
who played Tom Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Badham, 47, is booked through October with ``Mockingbird''
events. And though she occasionally feels ``overwhelmed,'' she says
she completely understands the growing fascination with a
4-decades-old work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get fan mail from all over the world from people that have
been touched by this story,'' said Badham, who made only one other
film (1966's ``This Property Is Condemned,'' with Robert Redford).
``As human beings, it seems that we keep having to learn these
lessons over and over again. . . . To learn the meaning of, and the
feelings of, tolerance, love, understanding, valuing education,
honor, dignity _ it's all there, in this story.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
