<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GIULIANI &LR; - &UR; (2TAKES)-N     05-13 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVINCIBLE' MAYOR ACKNOWLEDGES HIS WEAKNESSES
</HEADLINE>
 - (2TAKES)-NYT By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He has been the man so in control that he could
almost be heard setting his jaw. He has been the man who knows what
is best for everybody, the man who takes it upon himself to restore
morality to Gomorrah on the Hudson. For better, for worse, for
seven years, he has been the man.
</P>
<P>
   Then, over a span of a few days that culminated with an
extraordinary news conference on Wednesday, he became someone other
than the mayor a city thought it knew. That aura of confidence had
evaporated; in its wake was revealed a man in pain, ailing and
dispirited. Suddenly, Rudolph Giuliani seemed on the verge of
tears.
</P>
<P>
   The very qualities that some admired and others loathed seem to
have been turned upside down. Here was the man who had advocated
posting the Ten Commandments in public classrooms, now admitting to
a relationship with a woman other than his wife. Here was the
champion of public integrity now accused by his wife of having had
a relationship with a third woman, a much younger aide who now
heads a city-financed agency. Here was the invincible mayor now
acknowledging human weakness.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to separate what all this might mean for Rudolph
Giuliani the man as opposed to Rudolph Giuliani the presumed
candidate for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   So blurred is the line between his private and public lives that
he announced his desire for a legal separation from his wife, Donna
Hanover, at a news conference. Not only did his public announcement
take his wife by surprise, it recalled the many times he dismissed
some government study because it had been released before he had
been given a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later why he had delivered the news in a manner that
wounded his family and flabbergasted the public, Giuliani suggested
that his performance reflected his sense of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most honest, direct and decent way to deal with
something that is enormously complex,'' he said. ``So I felt that
was the moment that it had to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of last week, some people were saying that Giuliani
has handled his personal crises with his typical decisiveness.
Others are saying that his performance was typical in its
harshness; he had devastated his wife in a public forum. Then there
were those who were talking as though a new mayor _ a new man _ had
been revealed to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he seemed like a dictator _ you know? _ like iron,''
said Orlando Cienfuegos, 37, an auto mechanic in Nyack, N.Y. ``But
now he looks like he wants to cry. Can you see that? Rudy crying?''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Pettingel, a graphic designer on a break from jury duty in
Brooklyn, said that she too was struck by Giuliani's
uncharacteristic display of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought of Rudy as some cold-blooded reptile kind of
thing,'' she said. ``Not to be insulting, but that's how he came
off. But now he has problems that all of us can relate to. And
watching him on the TV last night just nearly broke my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's friends and advisers agreed. A few say they
do not care whether he runs for the Senate; they are more concerned
about his wife, his two young children, his overall well-being.
Matters have temporarily spun out of control for the controlling
mayor, they say, and understandably so.
</P>
<P>
   He has an extremely difficult job, he is running for higher
office, his own actions have led to the probable breakup of his
marriage _ and he just learned that he has the disease that killed
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer has a way of getting one's attention, even if early
detection means a likely cure. In cases of prostate cancer, the
kind that the mayor has, treatment can also lead to impotence or
incontinence. And the blithe discussion in some quarters of the
mayor's cancer being treatable does not reflect the terror he may
feel.
</P>
<P>
   As with any person faced with such issues, someone close to
Giuliani said, ``he has started to review his life.'' The wrinkle
is, that review is unfolding in public.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, not so long ago, when Giuliani's friends and
advisers struggled to convince skeptical reporters that the mayor
did indeed have a warm, personal side. Fault him for not always
being empathetic, they would say, but know that he is a dedicated
family man whose moral leadership is needed by a city at sea.
</P>
<P>
   But the comments of the mayor and his wife last week confirm
what has been long suspected. Despite his ``Father Knows Best''
public persona, Giuliani's private decisions were far from black
and white.
</P>
<P>
   A shaken Hanover announced that for a long time she did not
participate in her husband's public life because of his close
relationship with his communications director, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mayor and his former aide repeated their denials of
an affair, Hanover's comments indicate that at the very least, the
emotional attachment the mayor shared with Lategano-Nicholas
unnerved her.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover said that last May _ the same month that
Lategano-Nicholas left the administration _ she made a ``major
effort'' to restore her marital bond with Giuliani. ``Rudy and I
re-established some of our personal intimacy through the fall,''
she said. ``At that point he chose another path.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover was referring to a relationship that her husband had
developed with Judith Nathan, a divorced executive who lives with
her teen-age daughter on the Upper East Side. Through the fall and
into this year, Nathan has been, in effect, hiding in plain sight _
attending various events at Gracie Mansion and City Hall, dining
with the mayor at restaurants and having him as a guest at her
condominium in Southampton.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
