<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GIULIANI-2NDTAKE-NYT     05-13 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: in Southampton.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a side of Giuliani never quite seen before. Having long
maintained that his private life was no one's business but his own,
he was now stopping just short of flaunting a relationship with
someone other than his wife.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Giuliani was running a Senate campaign that
seemed to rely more on verbal brickbats than on statewide travel. A
traditionally moderate Republican, he suddenly sought to
distinguish his views from those of his Democratic opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, by attacking her as hostile to ``America's
religious traditions'' and opposed to posting the Ten Commandments
in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   He then delivered a curious taunt: As a joke, he flashed a
picture of the Ten Commandments at the end of a slide presentation
at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the laughter ended 18 days ago when, with refreshing and
reassuring candor, Giuliani revealed that he had prostate cancer.
Since then, it seems, time has been marked by tabloid headlines:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer News Moved Rudy To Tears, Pal Says''; ``Dinner Belle:
Rudy Eats With Gal Pal `Every Night'''; ``Donna's Dilemma: Mayor's
Wife Says `Decisions' Have To Be Made''; ``GOP Honcho's Advice to
Rudy on Marriage Mess: Work It Out.''
</P>
<P>
   That last headline, from The New York Post, referred to concerns
that the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, had expressed about
the state of the mayor's Senate campaign, concerns that are said to
be shared by other state Republican leaders. Giuliani later said
that it was the headline that moved him to go public with his
private problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me that I had to move forward, and that something
had to move forward,'' he said. ``Because the whole complex of the
decisions that I have to make _ including about my health _ and I
guess part of that is also straightening out your personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   And so last Wednesday, at Bryant Park, a different Rudy Giuliani
spoke to reporters: one with averting eyes and an apologetic
demeanor. He said that he would be seeking a legal separation from
his wife; that he accepted responsibility for everything he had
done; that he and those close to him had been going through a very
painful period; that given his illness, he might rely on Nathan
``more now than maybe I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My emotional state is, I'm very sad,'' he said. ``And I feel
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, even those close to him asked why he had done it. He
had rattled the Republican leadership, given tacit license to the
media to delve further into the lives of those around him, and all
but invited Hanover to lash back.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is clearly in the throes of a personal evaluation, they
say _ about his political future, about his sources of comfort,
about the preciousness of life. And such personal evaluations are
rarely neat _ especially those partially conducted in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough time,'' one adviser said. ``Certainly his human
side is showing in a way he's never allowed to be shown before. If
anything, it shows that he has that side _ that he's mortal like
the rest of us, vulnerable like the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have not been so understanding. One former public
official said that what the mayor presented to the public last week
was ``puritanical self-destruction _ a rigid, remorseless
prosecutor now turning on himself.'' Another former official said
that the mayor was in the midst of learning what the mighty and
sanctimonious sometimes forget: ``Yo, you too are a human being,
and no one's bigger than the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Orlean, a 40-year-old bank teller in Nyack, said she
had been left with a different impression, one formed by the fact
that she is going through an amicable divorce after 10 years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the mayor,'' she said. ``I think he runs the city
like it was his own, and not the people's. But if I don't vote for
him _ and I really don't think I will _ it won't be because of his
marriage problems. That part of him I sort of understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
