<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN FLORIDA; RELIGION IN UTAH; STUDENTS READY TO VOTE;
LATEST POLL RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Utah, Fla., Colo.)  By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida looks like Bush country. The presidential preference
polls there have Gov. George W. Bush of Texas leading Vice
President Al Gore by half a dozen points or more. One reason:
George W.'s brother Jeb is the Sunshine State's governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore says he nevertheless intends to compete for Florida's
big trove of electoral votes. And he insists he has a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Or maybe he's just bluffing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, if he is to have any reasonable chance of
carrying Florida, he must overwhelmingly carry Broward County, on
the state's southeast coast. Broward is Democratic country, home to
thousands of condo-dwelling retirees from the Northeast,
particularly the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   On election days, they vote by the thousands, spurred to turn
out by the county's 40 or so Democratic clubs. In a country and
state in which election turnout has dropped to an embarrassing low,
election day in Broward is a political sight to see.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there is trouble in Broward. Rather than
concentrating at this point on drumming up support for Gore, the
county's Democratic clubs are locked in a divisive squabble over
who is to be chairman of the Council of Presidents, the umbrella
organization for the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Broward is still teeming with retirees. But as in
much of the rest of Florida, more and more young people are moving
in (including some Republicans, though Democrats still
predominate). Some of the new young Democrats think it is time for
the Broward old guard to move aside and let them run things,
including the Council of Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, when they tried to install 40-year-old Randy
Fleischer, the head of the county's Young Democrats organization,
as council president, the old guard, many in their 80s, balked, and
the meeting ended in an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Another meeting has been called for June, and the county's
Democratic leader, Mitch Ceasar, is working to cool tempers and
restore unity lest Al Gore be the ultimate loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clubs are a critical element in our get-out-the-vote
campaign in the fall,'' he warned the other day.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION IN UTAH ON THE HIGH COURT?
</P>
<P>
   Utah was founded by Mormons. Two of every three residents of the
state are Mormons, members of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints; and Mormons, most of them conservative
Republicans, dominate Utah politics. The congressional delegation
is all Mormon. The state Legislature is predominantly Mormon. The
governor, Michael Leavitt, is a Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1926, the year when the five justices on the Utah
Supreme Court began to be appointed (before that they were
elected), the unwritten rule in Utah government has been that at
least one non-Mormon would always sit on the high bench.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that was the understanding until February.
</P>
<P>
   Then Leavitt broke with tradition. When the sole non-Mormon on
the court stepped down, he filled the slot with a Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Society of Separationists, which tried unsuccessfully
in 1993 to persuade the court to forbid opening prayers at
governmental meetings, strongly objected to the appointment. But
Leavitt stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   The society's director, Christopher Allen, contends that the
court was ``spineless'' when it was dominated by four Mormon
justices, and that it henceforth will be even more so. Utah, he
argues, is not a state but ``a solid theocracy'' with a theocratic
high court.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice, Richard C. Howe, disagrees. He told The
Associated Press the other day in a rare interview that he saw
nothing wrong with an all-Mormon court, and then added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you belong to one church or another shouldn't make any
difference. What we want on this court are men and women of good
character and legal ability, and their own private view on religion
really doesn't enter into their decisions. There may be an
exception once in a while, but it would be very subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   STUDENTS READY TO SPEAK WITH VOTES
</P>
<P>
   The way the freshman class at Northglenn High School in suburban
Denver saw it, if Gov. Bill Owens was so dead set on joining the
national rush to test students at various grade levels to see if
they are learning anything, or their teachers are teaching them
anything, he should come in and take the test himself.
</P>
<P>
   They sent him an invitation. After all, they reasoned, a lot of
them oppose assessment tests, along with their teachers, and the
Colorado Legislature might well have rejected the bill that made
the tests mandatory had Owens not bulled it through.
</P>
<P>
   The governor didn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, last week he sent back a letter that stung worse than a
whack on the hand by a 12-inch ruler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certainly not concerned with my ability to pass a test,''
he wrote, ``but I will certainly not take a test because a group of
students _ or others _ demand that I do so. If interest groups feel
that I can be threatened, pressured or intimidated, then that is a
formula for a weak governor. I will not give in.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough the sting wore off. And the freshmen, having
learned a thing or two, were ready to counter when a reporter from
The Rocky Mountain News showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of immature,'' said Kaitlin Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Setting a really bad example,'' added Brittany Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon the governor's spokesman, Dick Wadhams, chimed in with
some Politics 101.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't have it both ways,'' he said. ``If you wade into the
public arena and make demands of a public official, then this is
the kind of response that might be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesson learned _ and then some, said Jessica Quimby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be threatened, either,'' she said. ``He's just our
governor. We'll be turning 18 pretty soon, and if he keeps this up,
we'll probably kick him out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   LATEST POLLS SHOW BUSH THE WINNER
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, the popular Internet political tip sheet, keeps a
running tab of presidential preference polls in various states as
they become available. Last week, 13 polls were added to the list.
Here is how things stood overall a week ago:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush led in 23 states, worth 271 electoral votes.
Vice President Al Gore led in 11 states, worth 160 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Needed to win: 270 electoral votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
