<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-A.L.WEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.500 RECORD A RARE FEAT IN A.L. WEST
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's beginning to smell a lot like 1994. That would be the aroma
coming from the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1994 season ended prematurely, courtesy of a labor
dispute between the players and the owners, no AL West team had a
winning record. None had even a .500 record. The Texas Rangers were
in first place, and their record (52-62) was far from .500.
</P>
<P>
   Check the division's developments in the early weeks of the
season, heading into Saturday's games:
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (16-19) had their best winning percentage after they
won the first two games of the season. The last time they had a
.500 record was at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   When the Oakland Athletics (19-17) sneaked one victory over .500
at 18-17 on Thursday night, it was the first time since they had a
2-1 record that they had climbed above .500.
</P>
<P>
   The best the Anaheim Angels (18-19) had done was get two
victories above .500. They were one under.500 before Saturday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Seattle Mariners (17-16) had a 12-7 record, they had
won five games and lost nine.
</P>
<P>
   The teams, however, aren't ready to play down to their past. ``I
don't think it's going to reach that,'' Pat Gillick, the Mariners'
general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin, the Rangers' general manager, said, ``I think
somebody will be at .500 to win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team has had its problems. The Mariners put together what
promised to be the best starting pitching rotation in their
history, but the leaders of that rotation, Jamie Moyer and Freddy
Garcia, are on the disabled list, having started a combined seven
games. The Mariners think Moyer, recovering from a strain behind
his left shoulder, can return before June 1. Garcia, who fractured
a leg, isn't expected back until the latter part of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it,'' Gillick said, ``but it will come down to
who can stay injury-free. There have been a lot of injuries in this
division already. If you lose a significant contributor, it puts a
crimp in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began the season with Tim Belcher, one of their
veteran starting pitchers, on the disabled list. He has since been
joined by two other starters, Ken Hill and Jason Dickson, as well
as shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who had hit .395 in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer and Gabe Kapler, two-thirds of the Texas outfield,
are on the disabled list, as is Frank Catalanotto, a .500-hitting
platooned second baseman. The Rangers also learned last week that
Justin Thompson, the primary pitcher they received in the Juan
Gonzalez trade, needs rotator-cuff surgery and won't pitch at all
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's offensive catalyst, second baseman Randy Velarde, only
recently came off the disabled list, where he had been since the
start of the season. Their current contributions to the list are
Kevin Appier, one of their veteran starters, and John Jaha, one of
their productive hitters.
</P>
<P>
   But the Athletics have no shortage of productive hitters. The
division, in fact, boasts an offensive orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lead the league in hitting, while the Athletics lead
in runs scored despite having one of the lowest batting averages
and the most strikeouts, and they are second in home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics' Jason Giambi entered the weekend No. 1 in the
league in home runs (15) and runs batted in (42) and second in
slugging percentage (.735), Darin Erstad of Anaheim had the highest
batting average (.388), the highest home average (.461) and the
most hits (59), Alex Rodriguez of Seattle was first in runs scored
(36), on-base percentage (.483), road batting average (.435) and
walks (29), David Segui of Texas was second in batting average
(.378) and Ivan Rodriguez of Texas was second in total bases (92).
</P>
<P>
   Pitching, then, must be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin readily acknowledged that the Rangers' relief corps has
undermined the team's efforts to attain a winning record. John
Wetteland squandered a couple of ninth-inning leads over Cleveland
and the Yankees, and Jeff Zimmerman, who last year was virtually
unhittable, gave up game-losing home runs to Clay Bellinger of the
Yankees and Greg Vaughn of Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Just as damaging, some of the relievers' earned run averages
look like they were attacked by a severe siege of inflation: Mike
Munoz 13.50, Matt Perisho 10.50, Tim Crabtree 9.18. The Angels have
some of those, too: Mark Petkovsek 8.84 and Shigetoshi Hasegawa
6.98.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starting pitching, for the most part, has been good,''
Bill Stoneman, the Angels' general manager, said. ``Our relief
pitching started off poorly, but it looks like it's coming along.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman said he believed the Angels were better than a .500
team. ``We haven't been able to separate ourselves from the .500
mark,'' he added, ``but I see ourselves doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of Ken Griffey Jr., the Mariners are not the
same offensively explosive team they have been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't bludgeon anybody,'' Gillick said. ``Our offense is
sporadic. Our game is get a well-pitched game and good defense and
hope we score enough runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillick said he didn't think there was any real difference
between his division and the Central. Melvin offered a similar
view, noting that the West was ``a good division from the
standpoint of being competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Yankees,'' he added, ``everybody has problems. If
you take away what the Yankees have done, I'm not sure there are
any other great teams. That's the way it is in our league right
now. It looks like there's parity.''
</P>
<P>
   With parity comes mediocrity. Mediocrity breeds .500 teams, or
worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
