<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASS   
</HEADLINE>
  
 A RARE PAIR OF 1-0 SHUTOUTS ;  LEFT-HANDERS CAN'T HIT JOHNSON;
HERNANDEZ HOMER RATIO UP; KIM'S GLOVE FULL OF STRIKEOUTSBy MURRAY c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as some baseball people believe, the ball has been altered
to allow batters to hit more home runs, which balls must Steve
Trachsel have used in his last two starts for Tampa Bay? An 18-game
loser last year who did not win two successive starts until
September, Trachsel has pitched two consecutive 1-0 shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   He did not complete the second one, against the Yankees and
Orlando Hernandez on Thursday night, but his seven-inning,
three-hit performance was impressive nonetheless, especially
following his complete-game three-hit shutout against Boston last
Saturday in a matchup with Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The only 1999 performance that came close to Trachsel's
achievement was a pair of 1-0 complete-game shutouts Jose Jimenez
pitched for St. Louis against the Arizona Diamondbacks, whose
pitcher in both games was one Randy Johnson. Just to make the feat
more spectacular, Jimenez pitched a no-hitter in the first shutout
and allowed only two hits in the second. The only problem was
Jimenez made a start between those 1-0 shutouts, losing to Houston,
11-3.
</P>
<P>
   According to research by Elias Sports Bureau, the last pitcher
to win two consecutive starts by 1-0 scores was Zane Smith of
Pittsburgh in 1992. Smith pitched a complete-game five-hitter
against St. Louis, then permitted five hits in 8 1/3 innings
against Houston. Stan Belinda got the last two outs in that game.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs may be up from last season, but so are 1-0 games.
Eight such games have been played this season compared with seven
in the corresponding period last year. The Devil Rays have won
three of them. The Red Sox, the Angels and the Dodgers have each
lost two.
</P>
<P>
   Left-Handers Can't Hit Johnson
</P>
<P>
   In Randy Johnson's first seven starts for Arizona this season,
the relatively few left-handed batters who faced him did not fare
well. But then left-handers seldom do. Rafael Palmeiro, for
example, made no pretense about not wanting to play when Johnson
pitched against his team. Palmeiro has batted against the
left-hander 21 times and has only one hit to show for his futile
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   This season Todd Helton of Colorado and Mark Grace of the
Chicago Cubs had the only two left-handed hits against Johnson in
left-handers' 25 times at bat. Then last Wednesday night Johnson
pitched against Los Angeles, and the Dodgers put only one
left-handed hitter in their lineup. That hitter, Shawn Green, who
had not had a hit in five American League at-bats against Johnson,
stroked three singles in four tries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see a left-hander stay in there against Randy
the way Green did,'' said Sandy Johnson, the Diamondbacks'
assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez Homer Ratio Up
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu was not the most popular pitcher who ever played
for the Yankees. One element of his game that aroused criticism was
his penchant for giving up home runs. Last season he allowed an
average of one home run for 6.5 innings. The popular Orlando
Hernandez, meanwhile, permitted one per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching for Montreal this season, Irabu has basically
maintained his 1999 pace, giving up one home run every seven
innings (5 in 35 1/3 innings). But look who's giving up more?
Hernandez has thrown 11 home run pitches in 56 2/3 innings, or one
every five innings. He is tied for second in the American League
for most home runs allowed, only one behind Mike Mussina of
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's Glove Full of Strikeouts
</P>
<P>
   Byung Hyun Kim, a Diamondbacks relief pitcher from Kwayngsan-ku
Songjung-dong, South Korea, committed a no-no in a game against the
Dodgers last week. As a bunt by Alex Cora rolled past him, Kim
flung his glove at the ball to try to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Kim, his aim was not good and the glove missed
the ball. Had he made contact, Cora would have wound up at third
base with one out in the 10th inning of a tied score. The rules
award three bases to a batter if a fielder throws his glove at a
ball and hits it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah yes, three bases, no more,'' Kim said the next day when he
was asked about the play.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old right-hander might not have known about the
glove-throwing rule, but ask him about strikeouts and he could
already write his own book. In six appearances from April 27
through last Wednesday, Kim pitched a total of six innings and
struck out batters for 17 of the 18 outs.
</P>
<P>
   His only miss? A tapper back to the mound by Todd Hundley of Los
Angeles in the fifth of those six games. Kim pitched to two San
Diego batters Friday night and both grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a fastball in the low 90s and an assortment of sliders,
Kim dazzled batters for Philadelphia, Milwaukee, San Diego and Los
Angeles. He gave up four hits, and the lone run he allowed cost the
Diamondbacks the first of those games, but his string of strikeouts
represents one of the most impressive performances of the season.
In 13 games overall, he has struck out 28 in 16 2/3 innings and has
a 1.62 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   What happened after the glove-tossing display? He had struck out
Adrian Beltre before the bunt, and afterward he struck out Dave
Hansen and Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
