<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MAJERLE KEEPING THE KNICKS COVERED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (Eds: In 2nd graf ``SETI'' stands for the Search for
Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence program) 
By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dan Majerle heard a whistle and looked at Hue Hollins
the way Scottie Pippen and Phil Jackson once did, with incredulity
and rage. A foul? You called that a foul?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a reach-in foul 20 feet from the basket, contact with
Patrick Ewing that SETI might not have detected, with 2 seconds on
the shot clock and 13.6 seconds in overtime and the Knicks and
Heat, after 52 minutes and 46.4 seconds, still tied at the bargain
basement score of 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I really didn't hit him,'' Majerle would say
after fate had heard his case and adjudicated in his favor. ``And
that's a tough call to make with the game on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing missed a free throw. Anthony Carter made what may very
well have been an illegal shot from the Dolan family seating area
and no-trespassing zone. The 41 minutes to which Majerle had
sacrificed a couple more octogenarian years of jogging by the
beachfront were not lost in the final entanglement of angles and
issues, in Miami's 77-76 victory in Game 3 of the Eastern
Conference semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The box score couldn't tell us all we needed to know about
Majerle and Allan Houston, about an exhaustive perimeter dance most
reflective of a series that perhaps will not be decided by sheer
talent after all. The box score could only tell us that Houston had
come home with his best game, on 24 points on 9 of 18 from the
field. He had ignited an explosion of sound in Madison Square
Garden with a face up 3-pointer that gave the Knicks a 73-71
overtime lead and left an exasperated Majerle staring at his bench
and wondering how much more of Houston's release space he could
steal. ``I've been saying for a while now that he's my toughest
cover,'' Majerle would say. ``Once he gets his legs under him, he
can just go up and score from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Lewis Majerle, born Sept. 9, 1965, in Traverse City,
Mich., has never been a great professional basketball player. Like
most of the very good contemporary white players, his reputation
has at times exceeded his game. At his very best in the early
1990s, in Phoenix, he was worth about 17 points, six rebounds and
three assists a game. They called him Thunder Dan. He could shoot
from way out and had a strong, purposeful stride. He relished a
defensive challenge and didn't back away from the matchup with
Michael Jordan in the 1993 NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thunder Dan, my behind,'' Jordan snapped when the series was
over and Majerle had measured a clear second to a true basketball
great.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle played basketball in those days the way Lenny Dykstra
played baseball, and he, too, paid for his abandon with injuries,
with a body sapped too soon of offensive skill. He left Phoenix,
unhappily, for Cleveland. He migrated south to Miami, just in time
for the start of the Knicks-Heat wars. He is 34 now, healthy again,
but with more clouds than thunder in his sinewy, 6-foot-6-inch
frame. On the final possessions of a long, draining night, Houston
became obscured in Majerle's defensive cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how the Knicks wanted the ball in the pure shooter's hands,
leading by 75-73, needing a basket to put Miami away, maybe once
and for all, after pushing into overtime on Ewing's clutch jumper.
Latrell Sprewell had given up his dribble out front. Houston tried
desperately to create a passing lane.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle would not give him room. The Knicks took a timeout, and
ultimately settled for a shot they didn't want, a missed Marcus
Camby drive.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning tied the score with a baseline jumper. Now here
came the Knicks, waiting for Houston to break free of Majerle,
again on the left side. And Majerle wouldn't let Houston get away,
wouldn't let him breathe. The shot clock ran down. Ewing turned the
ball over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' Jack Ramsay, the former Portland coach and Miami
television analyst would say. ``How often do you see defense where
the guy can't even go out 20 feet from the basket and get the
ball?''
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Brown knew why. ``When you come down to this point of your
career,'' he said, ``every game becomes the game of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   In career twilight, Majerle has become, more than any other
player, more so with each passing season, the embodiment of Pat
Riley's Heat. There is no champion in this team. In Majerle, there
is only the heart of one.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat has the Knicks good and scared going into Game 4
Sunday. Miami is an outfit patched together with sticks and glue,
with offensive alignments that could be a Regis question for $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Which of the following Heat players is capable of scoring a
basket in a crucial half-court set? a)Otis Thorpe. b)Anthony
Carter. c)Bruce Bowen. d)Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   Given the circumstances of his defensive attrition, Riley could
forgive Majerle's 1-for-6 shooting Friday. He did have a game-high
seven assists and six rebounds and, of course, the final answer for
Houston on defense. And Anthony Carter somehow found the basket,
negating the cheap call that put Ewing on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle wasn't tired, he said, but he was counting on ``being
exhausted'' by morning. If he were home, he would have played 18
holes after practice Saturday. He would instead spend the afternoon
and evening relaxing, eating right, getting ready for Houston in
Game 4, which is a game the Knicks, of course, are certain to win
because Miami and Majerle cannot keep this up.
</P>
<P>
   They can't, right?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
