<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI CANCELS FUND-RAISING TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (With GIULIANI) 
 By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani canceled an upstate campaign
trip on Saturday as aides said he wanted to devote the weekend to
making a decision on both his treatment options for prostate cancer
and whether he wanted to proceed with his campaign for the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides said that the mayor could decide whether to
continue his campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton as soon as
Monday. Giuliani was said to be receiving conflicting advice about
what to do, though several people close to the mayor said it seemed
increasingly unlikely that he would stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Giuliani has announced that he has
prostate cancer, is separating from his wife of 16 years and has
established a relationship with a 45-year-old sales manager for a
drug company who lives on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had been scheduled to make a speech Saturday night in
Oneonta, N.Y., at a fund-raising dinner sponsored by Delaware
County Republicans. Giuliani's campaign announced Saturday morning
that he was canceling the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's entitled to some time for himself to contemplate his
medical treatment,'' said his campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum.
``This is the first day in a long time that he'll have an
opportunity to sit back and to think seriously about his medical
treatment, and he's certainly entitled to the time.''
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, the mayor's spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel, echoed
Teitelbaum's comments, saying the mayor was taking it easy. ``He's
pulling his schedule back,'' she said. ``He's focusing on reviewing
his medical options.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is scheduled to make a midweek fund-raising visit to
California, though aides said the chances of his going through with
that trip were remote. And he is scheduled to appear at a town hall
meeting on Thursday night in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's decision to cancel his trip was just one sign that he
was moving into the final phases of making a decision about the
race. Campaign and City Hall officials said the mayor, who
customarily makes himself available to reporters on Saturdays, had
no plans to make any public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   However, at City Hall on Saturday, a mayoral spokesman said that
Giuliani might appear at an event in Manhattan on Sunday, but he
had no further details. Campaign and City Hall officials said
Giuliani was expected to stay in New York City over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's advisers acknowledged that in this intense
environment, he might have difficulty maintaining much privacy. On
Friday night, Giuliani had dinner on the Upper East Side with
Judith Nathan, the woman whom he has called a ``very good friend,''
before strolling the streets of Manhattan, trailed by
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing his cancer diagnosis two weeks ago, the mayor
acknowledged a relationship with Nathan and said that she had been
a comfort to him during a difficult time and that he would continue
to rely on her support as he contemplated his medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Hanover, the mayor's wife, is spending the weekend in
California with her parents, her aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
