<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-MASCOT-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COLUMN: INDIAN MASCOT STIRS CULTURE WAR IN CATSKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOICEVILLE, N.Y. _ The once-dominant Onteora Indians high school
football team sank so low that it did not even play one recent
season. Seeking to stoke athletic prowess in 1997, boosters painted
a mural in the gym of a tomahawk-wielding Indian, with war paint,
bulging muscles and gritted teeth, bursting through a brick wall.
The team is still struggling, but the Indian seems to have turned
everyone else here into warriors.
</P>
<P>
   If the New York race for Senate is a soap opera, the Onteora
school board race is the World Wrestling Federation. Body-slamming
has broken out in Woodstock and surrounding Ulster County towns
that share the high school. One side sees the Indian mascot as a
racist stereotype; the other sees a symbol of local pride under
attack by the political correctness militia.
</P>
<P>
   There are accusations of punctured car tires, swiped campaign
signs and telephone threats. Police reports have been filed, and
Justice Department mediators have been called in to ease tensions.
School board meetings have gotten loud and ugly, with names like
``racists'' and ``freaks'' flying freely. About 700 people signed
petitions demanding the ouster of the superintendent of the mainly
white school district, Hal Rowe, who calls the mascot
``institutional racism.'' Joseph Doan, a board member who supports
the Indian mascot, said a woman took her son off a baseball team
Doan coaches, in protest.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's school board election, there are two competing
slates, one favoring the mascot, one opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say this pejoratively,'' Donna Boundy, an anti-mascot
candidate, said of the other side's mind-set, ``but it's less
intellectual, more Reaganesque.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Perry, a pro-mascot candidate, said: ``The Indian head is
on a new silver dollar. Is that wrong?'' He added, ``Forty-nine
years it was not a problem, and then you have these strange-looking
Rastafarians coming in cursing.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Perry is referring to members of Color, a group of
interracial families in Woodstock who asked that the board remove
the mural. To their surprise, the board voted 4-3 in January to
phase out the Indian name, beginning next school year. It was the
first shot of this culture war in the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's appropriate for four people to reverse 50
years of history,'' said Martin Millman, the board president.
</P>
<P>
   Indian mascots are controversial elsewhere, but here, at least,
the fight is less about Indians than about who rules.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock is, well, Woodstock, and much of the rest of the
school district consists of rural towns where it is not quite as
easy to find a good tofu burrito. Hundreds of people have attended
recent board meetings seeking to undo the vote. Millman said he
proposed removing the mural yet retaining the name, but opponents
wouldn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rosato, a board member, said he opposed the mascot after
realizing that Indian symbols were as sacred as a crucifix or Star
of David. ``They're flesh-and-blood human beings,'' he said of
Indians. ``They're still alive. They work, they have families,
they're our neighbors, and they're telling us they're not honored
by this.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side was expressed by a man at an auto supply store in
the village of Phoenicia. ``It's not worse than Vikings or Spartans
or Trojans,'' said the man, who insisted on not being identified.
``This all existed. What kind of society is this if we suppress
reality?''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Yerry, a musician and one of the few people with Indian
blood involved in the dispute, objected to the mural a few years
ago. To him, the mascot is typical of the white man's odd
relationship with Indians. ``My idea is when you come to an area
and wipe out all the trees and deer, you then call it Deer Lane,''
he said. He said that Onteora is a name invented by a white man in
the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   But Onteora High is ``Indian'' territory. There is a totem pole
painted on the cafeteria wall, the school's coat of arms has three
dancing Indians, and the spring social event is the Tomahawk Dance.
In a straw poll students strongly favored the mascot, but student
leaders are considering other names _ the Thundercats, the Storm.
They are overlooking the obvious local symbol of unleashed
ferocity. How about the Battlin' Board Members of Onteora High?
Fight, team, fight!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
