<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FLA-FLATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: MAKING STRIKES AMID SILENCE OF THE FLORIDA FLATS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN C. SAUTNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARPON SPRINGS, Fla. _ Just beyond the endless shopping centers
and housing developments that now typify much of Florida's western
Sun Coast lie the remnants of a true wilderness, the sprawling
shallow water bays and sand flats of the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, where beds of aquatic turtle grass gently wave in
the tide and prehistoric-looking spider crabs scuttle slowly along
the bottom, that I recently waded out from shore, a light spinning
rod in hand. Mottled brown and olive flats covered in warm,
thigh-deep water spread monotonously to the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   For the tourist angler not visiting such well-known hubs as the
Florida Keys, the Everglades or perhaps the Ten Thousand Islands
region, Florida's vastness can easily overwhelm. I spent the
previous few weeks trying to glean as much information as I could
from guide books, the Internet and friends who had fished the area.
But the best I could find were vagaries about ``decent fishing''
and ``lots of different kinds of fish.'' So, with little to go on,
the particular flat I chose seemed as good (or as bad) as any.
</P>
<P>
   Now 200 yards from shore, I rummaged through the tackle stuffed
down the pouch in my waders. Tangled in the middle of high-tech
looking plugs and soft plastic ``jerk baits'' hung a somber brown
bucktail. Baitfish often match the color of their surroundings, so
I tied the jig and began casting and retrieving it over the tops of
the grass beds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flats' finest attribute may be their virtual silence. Except
for the distant roar of an occasional boat whizzing across the
horizon and the tiny wavelets lapping against my waders, I heard
nothing for minutes on end. Individual sounds became distinct. A
loud ``thwack'' behind me turned out to be a brown pelican
performing its signature headlong crash into the water, arguably
one of nature's goofiest moments. Then a single mullet
splish-splashed along in graceful leaps 50 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Below the surface, stingrays of various sizes flapped past every
few minutes, reminding me to shuffle, not step, as I moved, or I
might risk pinning one to the bottom with disastrous results. One
particularly large and docile ray allowed me to approach within a
rod's length. I stared at it for a few moments (and it at me,
presumably), then decided to pass the shadow of my arm over its
eyes to see what might happen. Instantly, it burst across the flat,
leaving a trail of marl and muck as it headed back out to the Gulf.
If a stingray could scream, this one was shrieking the entire way.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a cast exactly like the hundred previous ones I had
just made, the lure jerked to a stop, and I set the hook into an
unseen fish that plowed past me in low gear and continued across
the flat. I held the rod high trying to keep the line from tangling
in the grass or chafing on a submerged rock.
</P>
<P>
   After a long initial run, I finally wrestled the fish into
turning its head. Its tail then kicked on the surface, revealing a
single dark spot at the base _ the telltale mark of a redfish. Also
called red drum or channel bass, redfish are frequent visitors to
tidal flats, where they root around for crabs, shrimp and baitfish.
</P>
<P>
   They are also known to fight like mules, and this one was no
exception. Even though it weighed only 6 or 7 pounds, it clearly
outbattled a similar-sized striped bass or weakfish that I might
catch in more northern waters.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the fish tired and I managed to slip my hand under
its belly and hold it against my waders. It looked more copper than
red, and its underslung mouth and thick sides reminded me a little
of a freshwater carp. I then popped the jig from its rubbery lip
and watched it dash away, my first-ever flats-caught fish.
</P>
<P>
   The tide had now dropped to knee-deep level and I began spotting
swirls and miniature wakes being pushed by unseen fish. Redfish
will sometimes rise to surface lures, so I switched to a small bass
popper trying to send it on a collision course. It worked. The fish
engulfed the lure with a loud slurp, then set off on a powerful
run.
</P>
<P>
   But this fish felt different; it seemed faster but did not have
the sheer pulling strength of the redfish. I drew it closer and saw
it was a 2-pound jack crevalle, a fish as ubiquitous to Florida
waters as it is strong. I felt a slight pang of disappointment, but
got over it quickly as the jack zipped off on yet another run
across the flats. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
