A4229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FAMILY-LAWYERS-285     05-13 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FAMILY-LAWYERS-285&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF LAWYERS CRIPPLING NYC FAMILY COURT, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A growing docket and a dwindling pool of lawyers
available to represent the poor have so crippled the New York City
Family Court system that judges are forced to adjourn cases
repeatedly, children are forced to remain in foster care far longer
than they ought to, and parents accused of child abuse are
frequently denied their due-process rights, according to a report
to be released Sunday by the city's public advocate, Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and judges agree that the shortage of court-appointed
counsel for the indigent, known as the 18-B panel, is driven
chiefly by the low reimbursement rates. Since 1986, hourly fees
have remained at $40 an hour for in-court services and $25 an hour
for time preparing out of court. And while the shortage affects the
entire state court system, in Family Court, the quality of legal
representation _ and delays in getting any representation at all _
can profoundly disrupt children's lives. They can be separated from
their parents, sometimes unjustifiably, for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the current beleaguered system, everyone loses,'' the
report reads. ``The parents suffer an injustice, the children
languish in care, and the judicial process is sorely undermined.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrative judge of the city's Family Court, Joseph M.
Lauria, said court officials had themselves drawn attention to the
shortage of lawyers, although he added that he did not think due
process was necessarily being violated. In addition, Lauria noted,
the chief judge of the state courts, Judith S. Kaye, has repeatedly
pressed the governor and the Legislature to raise reimbursement
rates to $75 an hour, to be paid for partly by criminal surcharge
fees collected by the state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report, titled ``Justice Denied: The Crisis in Legal
Representation of Birth Parents in Child Welfare Proceedings,'' is
the latest in a series of critical assessments of the Family Court.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a report by the Vera Institute of Justice, a
nonprofit research institution, found that parents who used the
Family Court most frequently complained about long waits _ an
average of three hours in Manhattan before seeing a judge _ and
about representation. Some lacked lawyers; others said their
lawyers were either unhelpful or unavailable to meet with them
about their cases.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Special Child Welfare Advisory Panel, an
independent group of experts charged by a federal court with
investigating the Administration for Children's Services, turned
its gaze to the Family Court, unexpectedly and to the chagrin of
court officials. The panel was particularly critical of judges who,
it said, frequently placed children in foster care even when the
city child welfare officials failed to provide sufficient evidence
of abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Green's report walks a delicate political line. It criticizes
neither judges nor the quality of lawyers on the 18-B panel, and it
takes pains to note how the lack of counsel can affect children,
not just their parents.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as Green pointed out, it is politically difficult to
advocate for lawyers who represent parents who are accused of child
abuse. That is chief among the reasons, he said, why there has been
such tepid political will in Albany to raise reimbursement rates
for the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends raising reimbursement rates to $75 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no obvious political coalition or political capital to
pay lawyers more money on behalf of parents who might be possible
abusers,'' Green said. But, he added, ``the current system is not
merely unfair to them. It also hurts kids who stay too long in
undesirable foster care. And it hurts taxpayers who spend too much
for unnecessary foster care.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring national trends, the Family Court caseload in New York
City has grown by a third in the last decade alone, according to
the report. At the same time, the number of lawyers available to
represent the poor has shrunk by 15 percent. Lawyers carry a load
of up to 100 cases each. On days when there are no 18-B lawyers
available in a particular courtroom, judges frequently dispatch
their court officers to scour the building for a lawyer who may be
free to take on a case.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, in each borough, 10 to 20 cases are adjourned
because there are no lawyers available to represent a parent, the
report states, citing an interview with Lauria. On average, it can
take six months before the court can determine if charges against a
parent are substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the problem of representation is suggested by the
rare instances in which parents accused of child abuse win their
cases: 1.6 percent of the time, according to the public advocate's
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can know with certainty whether parents should prevail
20 percent or 50 percent of the time,'' Green said. ``But 1.6
percent is so stunningly low as to be a thermometer of the illness
of the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
