u i BC-KOREA-AP-STORY-NYT     05-13 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-AP-STORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AP STRUGGLED WITH DECISION TO PUBLISH MASSACRE STORY
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It was a story no one wanted to hear.'' Those were
the opening words of The Associated Press' Pulitzer-Prize winning
report documenting the massacre in 1950 of hundreds of South Korean
civilians by U.S. troops at No Gun Ri. When they were crafted by an
editor during one of the numerous rewrites, the report's authors
found them an apt description of the response from AP executives to
their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Now attacks on the credibility of three witnesses have given the
words an even more ironic cast. U.S. News &AMP; World Report and Web
site Stripes.com are citing documents that undermine the
credibility of three of a dozen soldiers cited by the AP report.
All the soldiers' accounts dovetailed with those of two dozen
Korean survivors also cited by the AP.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment in April 1998 when the wire service's special
projects unit decided to check Korean civilians' claims of a
massacre, to the publication of debunking reports by an Internet
site and by U.S. News &AMP; World report, the No Gun Ri reporting has
been something of a battlefield in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, six months before the report's publication, wire
service executives moved to shelve it, according to a reporter and
an editor who worked on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to win, because we had such a powerful
story, powerfully reported and we were not going to let it be
killed. Period,'' said the reporter, Charles J. Hanley, who has
spent most of his career at The Associated Press, once serving as
deputy managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Port, who was the initial editor on the project until he
left the wire service in June, said: ``I'm surprised it took this
long for the attacks to begin. We expected it. I was certainly
ready for it. The reporters were ready. I am not sure the
leadership of the AP will ever be ready. They are too restrained in
defending their own work, out of a sense of remaining objective and
neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the No Gun Ri account will stand up under scrutiny, Jon
Wolman, the executive editor of the wire service, said: ``It's been
a complicated and important project, and we've always felt it
deserves full scrutiny. We're confident that the reporting is sound
and that the central information will be borne out by the
investigations by governments in both the United States and
Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   The internal struggle over No Gun Ri, as members of the
reporting and editing team describe it, reflected in part a clash
of cultures in a large and journalistically conservative
organization that sets fairness and balance as its core values.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflected the difficulty of adapting such values to
the messy and contradictory business of reconstructing 50-year-old
events.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the internal struggle account played out during the
year of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, when a series of embarrassing
journalistic missteps had put the whole profession on the
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most publicized and criticized missteps also involved
accounts of witnesses of an apparent military atrocity: the
``Tailwind'' report, investigated and retracted by CNN, which
claimed that U.S. troops in Vietnam had used nerve gas in a mission
to kill defectors. In fact, in the aftermath of Tailwind, the No
Gun Ri team sent a memorandum to their superiors explaining how
their evidence differed from the material supporting the
discredited Tailwind report, according to two members of the group.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters on the No Gun Ri story were Hanley, Martha Mendoza
and Sang-Hun Choe; the editors directing the project were first
Port, who left to join APBNews.com, then Kevin Noblet, who left to
spend a year teaching at an Ohio college, and finally Nick Tatro,
deputy international editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a difficult and frustrating process,'' said Mendoza,
who is working in the AP's bureau in San Jose, Calif. ``None of
that takes away from the significance of the story, which is
something I'm very proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Port and Hanley, the most consistent objections to
the project were raised by the former executive editor of the AP,
William Ahearn. Hanley said that at a meeting in the fall of 1998,
Ahearn was skeptical about the importance of the incident. Ahearn
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, on March 2, 1999, according to the two men,
Ahearn told the team that he did not believe that the account, by
then redrafted and re-reported several times over, should be
published. Port said he had appealed to Louis D. Boccardi, the
president and chief executive of The Associated Press, who
suggested that if further changes would damage the report, Port
should consider abandoning it. Boccardi also could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Port then talked to Wolman, then the managing editor. As Wolman
recalled, ``I know I told him it was an important story, and I was
sure we'd make it to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   It took six more months, however, for the report to be published
in its final form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
