<SLUG> BC-ART-DAMAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 ART DYNASTY'S SUIT OVER REPORTS OF NAZI DEALINGS IS REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A Paris appeals court has rejected a claim for damages
brought by the Wildenstein family, the New York-based dynasty of
international art dealers, against an American writer who in a
recent book described business dealings between the French-Jewish
family and Nazi officials during Germany's wartime occupation of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding a lower court ruling last year, the court said Friday
that it was up to ``historians and the public'' to judge the
allegations made by Hector Feliciano in his book, ``The Lost
Museum: The Nazi Conspiracy to Steal the World's Greatest Works of
Art,'' published in France in 1995 and in the United States in 1997
(Basic Books).
</P>
<P>
   In its written findings, the court went out of its way to praise
Feliciano's method of research and dismissed the Wildensteins'
argument that he had acted irresponsibly and negligently.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Wildensteins said the family was
``extremely shocked'' by the ruling and was studying whether a
further appeal was justified.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the court had not endorsed the charges contained
in Feliciano's book.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from his home in New York, Feliciano
said: ``I used reliable documents. The lawsuit has backfired for
the Wildensteins.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the suggestion of collaboration related to Georges
Wildenstein, who died in 1963, the case was brought by his son,
Daniel, 82, his two grandsons, Guy and Alec, and Wildenstein &AMP; Co.,
which has its headquarters on East 64th Street in Manhattan. They
sought damages of 6 million francs, or $850,000 at current exchange
rates, as well as the removal of all references to the Wildensteins
in future editions of ``The Lost Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit formed part of a broader campaign by the
Wildensteins to improve their image after a wave of bad publicity
had begun to affect their business, one of the wealthiest and most
powerful in the art world.
</P>
<P>
   Most embarrassing was the tabloid coverage of messy divorce
proceedings involving Alec Wildenstein in New York three years ago.
But, apart from Feliciano's allegations, the Wildensteins'
reputation is also under attack in a separate lawsuit in New York
charging that after World War II the Wildensteins recovered several
medieval manuscripts looted by the Nazis from the home of a
French-Jewish art collector, Alphonse Kann.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Feliciano said that Georges Wildenstein had
business contacts with a well known Nazi art dealer, Karl
Haberstock, shortly before the war, immediately after the
occupation of France and sporadically during the course of the
conflict, even while in exile in New York. Feliciano's lawyer,
Antoine Comte, presented both the lower court and the appeals court
with documentary evidence supporting these charges.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing these documents, the appeals court said it could
not share the Wildensteins' claim that Feliciano's writing was
``manifestly erroneous.'' It said the documents prove that Georges
Wildenstein exchanged letters, did business and had meetings with
Haberstock.
</P>
<P>
   It said that ``it is also possible to deduce'' that Georges
Wildenstein maintained contact throughout the war with Roger
Duquoy, a former employee who ran the Wildensteins' Paris gallery
during the war and who also did business with Haberstock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-JAZZ-NYT &LR;      05-13 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS AND JAZZ ARE GETTING THE RESULTS THEY PAY FOR
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace was flying down the lane, cocking the ball back
as an earthbound Karl Malone watched futilely. Damon Stoudamire
scooted past a backpedaling John Stockton and laid the ball in with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time the Portland Trail Blazers were on their way
to postseason redemption, the Utah Jazz was writing its own
obituary, several years after most observers forecast its demise.
</P>
<P>
   Their second-round Western Conference semifinal has been rife
with symbolism the past week; the titleless, aging veterans who
simply don't have enough left versus the deeper, younger team that
may issue a sincere challenge to the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Utah-Portland series goes beyond merely the players.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's championship pursuit for much of the last decade was
about a small-market franchise that gave the others hope. Unlike
Minnesota or Orlando, the Jazz showed it could hold on to future
Hall of Famers, make a profit and still give Michael Jordan a
genuine scare. It was about a maverick owner like Larry Miller
trying to figure out his finances so he could pay Karl Malone
enough to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Portland is considered a small market, too. But the Blazers are
owned by one of the world's richest men, Paul Allen. Regardless of
a luxury tax that teams will have to pay if they go over a certain
threshold next season _ irrespective of a collective bargaining
agreement that makes it easier for teams to hold on to their own
free agents _ owners like Allen will pay for success.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the NBA has leveled the playing field for many of its
teams, it is in many ways still a league of haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scary part of it is, Larry Miller has done a terrific
job,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said by telephone on Friday. ``He's
run it as a business rather than just a toy. I've always admired
him for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and Karl made a little more money as they got older,
which they should. They've stuck through all the tough times and
come back. I don't know if we'll ever see that again in this
league, players sticking with the same team that long. Patrick
Ewing is the only player I can think of right now who's like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, The Salt Lake Tribune pointed out the incredible
discrepancies in payroll and talent between the Blazers and the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers spent an NBA-high $73.8 million on their
roster this season, $53.5 million to their starting five. They have
somehow acquired seven top-10 draft picks. In three more seasons,
Scottie Pippen will earn $19.7 million, Wallace will earn $17
million, Stoudamire will get $12.4 million and Steve Smith will
earn $9.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz, meanwhile, spent $49 million this season. That is
nearly double the Utah payroll in years past. Malone, Stockton and
Jeff Hornacek combined to take up nearly $30 million of that
figure, money that Miller forked over partly for their longevity
and loyalty. Six of the players in their rotation were taken 28th
or lower in the draft. Howard Eisley, Bryon Russell and Hornacek
were all picked in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Allen's money, Bob Whitsitt, Portland's team president
and general manager, made some strong moves to acquire certain
players.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that Utah has been completely outplayed. Greg
Ostertag went from being referred to as Chamberlain-like by the NBC
analyst Bill Walton one game to Frankenstein by one writer the
next.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2-inch Eisley has been forced to guard bigger guards,
and he just does not physically stack up. For all the big shots
Russell has made, he has missed many more.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek is retiring, but you wonder if Sloan is fed up enough
to finish the remaining year of his contract in 2000-1. Stockton
had to coax him into staying after the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you know something I don't, I'll be back,'' Sloan said.
``Now, can we still compete? I think so. These guys won 50-some
games this year. You get young guys and you work with them. They
get better. That's how it's always worked here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan added: ``You'd like to say it's unfair, but these guys
have played hard. They've given a lot to basketball in my opinion.
The losing, though, leaves a sorry taste in your mouth. At the same
time, you also understand the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan would never say it. But part of the reality is this: For
$24 million more than the Jazz, the Blazers bought themselves a
better team.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
