<HEADLINE>
RILEY, VAN GUNDY FORM A MUTUAL ADMIRATION SOCIETY 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As in every postseason, they have been playing politics the past
few days: Miami coach Pat Riley wondering aloud why the officials
are calling the games so tight and why Jamal Mashburn does not
receive as much respect from referees as players like Allan Houston
and Latrell Sprewell; and Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy countering
that the games are not called tightly enough, that Alonzo Mourning
is doing his share of dislodging his players, that the Knicks do
not have the same leeway.
</P>
<P>
   It is the usual postseason fare for these two. Yet the games
coaches play away from the court took on a very personal tone two
years ago, when the relationship between Van Gundy and Riley, his
former mentor in New York, changed for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   If the Heat and the Knicks were publicly feuding, the pupil and
the teacher were feuding privately: Riley taking shots at Van Gundy
for his woeful attempt at a peacemaking role in the Mourning-Larry
Johnson fight; Van Gundy seeing a cold, impersonal side to a man he
admired more than almost anyone else in the profession.
</P>
<P>
   But after last season's Game 5 playoff thriller, the tension and
ill feelings subsided, replaced by the same respect that once
characterized their working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a simple note Riley sent to Van Gundy via Federal
Express after Houston's shot sank his team. Through all the
conflict and adversity and uncertainty, ``You had a play,'' the
note read.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was so proud of Van Gundy's cool under fire, how he yelled
to his players from courtside to run the series-deciding play with
4.5 seconds left with no timeouts, and how his players responded.
Van Gundy carries the letter everywhere with him, along with two
notes from his father.
</P>
<P>
   As much as their relationship has been tested by the rivalry _
and will continue to be the next week _ Riley has now put in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of Jeff,'' he said last week. ``Nobody knows how
much the Van Gundys have helped me. Nobody. They think I've helped
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's brother, Stan Van Gundy, the Miami assistant, is Riley's
choice to take over the Heat after he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff was the savior for me in New York,'' Riley said. ``The
work he did, what he could take off my desk, his ideas, his
commitment, his loyalty. When you're in this job, you got to have
those kinds of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said Jeff actually recommended Stan Van Gundy for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jeff called me about Stan, he said: `You're not going to
believe me. You think I'm just selling you my brother. Well, he's
better than I am. If you had any respect for me, I'm telling you,
he's better than I am.'
</P>
<P>
   ``People who throw these assistant coaches' names out there, new
blood out there, they have no idea what this guy is about,'' Riley
said of Stan Van Gundy. ``He's not about politicking. This guy is a
coach. Jeff is a coach. See, I wasn't a coach. That's why I
appreciate the two of them. Lifelong coaches. They've been saviors.
They've helped me to grow and do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflective about their days together in New York, Riley
remembered how he once staged a shouting match with Jeff Van Gundy
to make a point to his feuding Knicks players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those days I had to do something because they
were being very selfish and childish,'' he said. ``They were
bickering and yelling at one another on the court
</P>
<P>
   ``So I said to Jeff: `Look, I don't want you to be surprised.
When I start on you, I want you to give it to me like you've never
gave it anybody. I want all your venom. I want all your hate. I
want you to criticize me. I want you to be sarcastic. I want you to
swear, I want you to say: ``You don't want to know what you're
talking about, I've had it with you,'' just like these players.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the locker room, in front of grumpy Anthony
Mason, John Starks and Charles Oakley, Riley laced into his
assistant about an unfinished scouting report he deemed sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just like the players,'' Riley remembered saying. ``And
he started yelling at me. We're yelling at one another and the
players said, `What's going on?' We went on for three minutes. It
was a very, very uncomfortable moment for them. Then finally we
stopped yelling at one another and blaming one another, and I
looked at Patrick and I just stared at him. And stared at him. And
then he got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Is that how we are?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `That's exactly how you guys are. Did we make you feel
uncomfortable, Pat?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `God, yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how do you think you make us feel? How do you think you
make everybody else feel out there when they see a team of guys
yelling and screaming at one another, criticizing each other,
backbiting one another?''
</P>
<P>
   Riley smiled at the memory, especially Van Gundy working himself
into a frothing rage to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff had a ball with that one,'' he said. ``He was a little
bit nervous about throwing obscenities at me. But he did it,
because that's coaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
