<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERS TEST TEAM NEW ZEALAND'S ALLEGIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Dobbyn is New Zealand's answer to Bruce Springsteen, a
populist singer and songwriter whose homeland and countrymen are
the source of his creative wellspring. Last March, when the Team
New Zealand America's Cup squad paraded into an Auckland
amphitheater to accept their awards for defeating Italy's Prada
Challenge and defending the cup, a Dobbyn tune called ``Loyal''
provided the soundtrack for an open-air video montage of the crew's
nautical heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out in the battle, where does allegiance lie?'' Dobbyn sang.
``We are loyal. Keep it that way now.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Kiwis, Dobbyn's lyrics have since taken on a special
poignancy. For in the last two weeks, published reports in the
United States, New Zealand, Europe, and on the Internet have said
more than 20 Team New Zealand crew members have been offered
lucrative contracts to defect and sail in the next cup, in 2003,
aboard boats entered by overseas syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   One persistent storyline is that the American businessmen Bill
Gates, Jim Clark and Bill Koch _ either individually or in some
combination _ have formed a Seattle-based syndicate targeting Kiwi
sailors to make up the team's core crew. The reported offers,
collectively in the tens of millions of dollars, would test the
loyalty of the staunchest patriot, never mind a sailor with a
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, Clark and Koch have all denied any interest in mounting a
cup challenge. Nevertheless, there is evidence that
behind-the-scenes machinations are in full swing in Europe, and
other reports, wholly unsubstantiated, have named another
Seattle-based entrepreneur as a cup player.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to TNZ's inner circle says that the Kiwi skipper
Russell Coutts has received substantial offers from multiple
European-based syndicates. And Brad Butterworth, who has joined
Coutts in the New Zealand team's administrative ranks, has fielded
a seven-figure offer to plot onboard strategy for Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these stories is particularly surprising. Along with
the legendary turn-of-the-century captain Charlie Barr, Coutts is
the winningest cup skipper in history. And in the war of wits in
the 5-0 Kiwi sweep of Prada, Butterworth clearly outmatched the
Italian tactician Torben Grael, much to the disgust of the
syndicate chief, Patrizio Bertelli.
</P>
<P>
   But it was surprising to hear persistent rumors that the TNZ
grinders Craig Monk and Andrew Taylor, and the mastman, Matthew
Mason, were also in line for major paydays. Though all are
unquestionably superb sailors, they do not fill glamour positions.
In the National Football League and in the America's Cup, the men
in the trenches do not earn quarterback paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Such speculation has fueled the notion that a backer with an
unlimited cash supply is behind a major challenge, and the
spotlight was turned on the Seattle billionaire Craig McCaw, who
earned his fortune in the cellular-phone business.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw, a yachtsman who contributed $500,000 to TNZ's 2000
defense fund and who docked his boat at Koch's cup compound in San
Diego in 1995, seemed a likely candidate. But despite several
reports to the contrary, a McCaw operative last week insisted that
McCaw did not intend to field his own cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been discussed but it's gone no further,'' said Gary
Wright, a McCaw associate in charge of international projects, who
is based in the United Kingdom. ``We haven't put together anyone in
a syndicate or made a challenge. There's absolutely no basis for
lots of things being said in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright also stated that McCaw had no involvement with the New
Zealand lawyer Sean Reeves, a former TNZ member who is allegedly
recruiting Kiwi talent for an overseas syndicate. ``Certainly over
the next few years we may well get interested in some of this
stuff,'' Wright said. ``But for now we're flabbergasted that this
rumor has grown.''
</P>
<P>
   Should McCaw change his mind, he still has time. In a phone
interview from Monaco, Pierpaolo Gardella, the general-secretary
for the next challenger's association, said that potential
challengers had until March 2002, to announce their intentions.
Gardella also confirmed that, thus far, the only official challenge
to the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron has come from Prada.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no question that the Italians will continue to
pursue talent from the international ranks. In addition to
purchasing both boats sailed by the New York Yacht Club's Young
America campaign in the last cup, Prada has scored a major coup by
enlisting the services of the Hall Spars and ex-Young America
marine engineer Scott Ferguson to oversee mast and spar
development. Prada, which built six complete rigs for the recent
cup, will keep Ferguson busy.
</P>
<P>
   The cup scene in Europe surpasses anything officially under way
in the United States, although the news is chock full of innuendo
and tales of potential intrigue. Last week, the Swiss banker Pierre
Essig announced the formation of a syndicate that may be partially
funded by high-end Swiss watchmakers. And the pharmaceutical heir
Ernesto Bertarelli, who has both Swiss and Italian passports, is
said to be near an official campaign announcement, but must first
decide under which flag he will sail.
</P>
<P>
   As the crews take shape, there will no doubt be more than
passing interest in the veterans from TNZ When it comes to loyalty
versus opportunity, every New Zealander will be anxious to see if
the song changes, or the chorus remains the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
