u a BC-COX-ERGONOMICS-$ADV14     05-13 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-ERGONOMICS-$ADV14 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSHA WEIGHING PLAN TO RESHAPE THE AMERICAN WORKPLACE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Workers at the 911 center in Rochester, N.Y., used
to respond to emergency calls while seated in stiff chairs at
neck-straining work stations where lights glared down on their
computer screens. Almost 50 of the 119 employees reported serious
muscular problems. Nine required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Then the city built a new facility. Planners consulted employees
and installed chairs with special back supports and consoles with
adjustable lifts for monitors and keyboards. Each worker was given
controls for light, heat and air conditioning, not to mention a
switch to supply soothing ``white noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years after the center opened, claims for work-related
injuries have plummeted. Only one worker injury was reported in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Such success stories are at the heart of a long-simmering
national debate over whether employers should be required to follow
federal mandates on ``ergonomics,'' which means making workplaces
fit the workers. The goal is to prevent common on-the-job injuries
from repetitive action or over-exertion.
</P>
<P>
   A move by the Clinton administration to set ergonomics standards
reached its final phase last week as the Labor Department's
Occupational Safety and Health Administration wrapped up public
hearings on a rule that would cover 27 million working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As of early May, OSHA had heard from 1,000 witnesses in hearings
held in Portland, Ore.; Chicago and Washington, and the agency had
a stack of more than 25,000 pages of public comments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation's businesses would be affected, including
poultry plants, hospitals, package delivery services, mom and pop
grocery stores and funeral homes _ every sector except agriculture,
construction and maritime. Not surprisingly, hundreds of employers
are battling the new regulation, even as unions are urge its
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Employers and their backers on Capitol Hill are offering three
chief objections:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mandating ergonomics programs and standards would cost
billions more than the government estimates, they say. Although
OSHA has pegged the cost to industry at $4.2 billion a year,
business coalitions have put the cost as high as $100 billion
annually.
</P>
<P>
   A detailed analysis for the Food Distributors International,
which represents warehouses, concluded that the rule would cost its
members $26 billion a year. Even the U.S. Small Business
Administration reports that business expenses will be several times
as much as OSHA is predicting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Government regulation is unnecessary, the foes say, since
repetitive stress injuries have sharply declined since 1994 without
new rules. For example, carpal tunnel syndrome cases, traced to
repetitive movements, have dropped by 31 percent over five years,
according to the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scientific evidence is too unsettled to justify a rule now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one-size-fits-all regulation that would deal equally
with a baker in Sacramento as it would with Dell Computers in
Austin or a bottling company in Peoria as well as a dance studio in
Miami,'' said Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla sponsored legislation to forbid OSHA from finalizing the
rule until the National Academy of Sciences has completed a
congressionally ordered study on ergonomics. His bill, which has
passed the House and now awaits Senate action, would delay
implementation until next year at the soonest.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker said he sees a ``race to the finish'' as the
administration tries to complete the rule before President Clinton
leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomic regulation has long been a top priority for labor
unions, who say the benefits will outweigh the expenses. Among
their arguments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ergonomics works, the proponents say, as evidenced by a 1997
study of five private companies by the U.S. General Accounting
Office, the investigative arm of Congress. The report concluded
that these employers reduced injuries and illnesses at modest cost
by applying the standards of ergonomics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ergonomics programs can prevent many work-related
musculoskeletal disorders that currently cost employers as much as
$20 billion a year in compensation costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many workers have been seriously hurt while performing routine
duties that would be redesigned under the federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   At the OSHA hearing last week, Rebekah Rice, a slightly built
registered nurse from Washington, hobbled into the Labor Department
room leaning on a cane. She was unable to sit because of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Tearfully she told how she had sustained a career-ending injury
when she tried with only one helper to move a 350-pound patient in
the intensive care ward. She said she could have been spared her
ordeal if the hospital had been required to have specialized ``lift
teams'' or mechanical lifting devices.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla acknowledged the power of such testimony, but countered
that ``we have to look at the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rules were implemented and they put a hardship on
hospitals, there's a real possibility that patients would go
unattended because they'd have to check with OSHA before they lift
a patient off a bed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting viewpoints are illustrated even by the case of
the Rochester 911 center. The American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees touts it as evidence that ergonomics
programs are effective and should be required by federal
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a textbook case on how to do things right,'' said
Jim August, the union's assistant director of research.
</P>
<P>
   But the center's director, John Merklinger, is less certain
about a federal rule telling employers what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautious to say there should be a mandate,'' Merklinger
said. ``However, I clearly see the benefit since we've done it
here, and the money savings'' for reduced injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps they would be better spending the money on educating
business leaders about the benefits of an ergonomics program,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Occupational Safety and Health Administration,
www.osha.gov; National Coaliton on Ergonomics, www.ncergo.org
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
