<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-NEW-PATHWAYS-$ADV     05-13 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEW-PATHWAYS-$ADV14 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROGRAM OFFERS TROUBLED WOMEN INMATES A 'NEW PATHWAY'
 &HT;    1070&AMP;add. For release Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Calif. _ ``If I wouldn't have came(cq) to prison, I'd be
be dead right now,'' said Eshelle Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Following a therapy session, part of a ground-breaking program
aimed at helping female inmates, Scott said she was trapped in an
abusive relationship with a man who introduced her to witchcraft
and beat her nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   Depressed, she found comfort in drugs and killing animals. Angry
about a beating, she said, she once decapitated her boyfriend's
mother's cat and left it on the woman's doorstep. Finally, she was
convicted of burning churches and sentenced to a 63-month term.
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Correctional Institution here, Scott participated
in the inaugural class of New Pathways, a pilot program aimed at
addressing the special needs of female inmates who have been
physically or sexually abused.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``best thing that ever happened to me,'' said the
25-year-old Corpus Christi, Texas, native.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for New Pathways was born in 1994 after a study here
found that 55 percent of the prison's inmates had been abused
physically or sexually as children or adults, said Dr. Davina
Kotulski, co-creator of the program.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of slowing a rapid rise in the national prison
population _ and an even faster rise in female inmates _ a team of
psychologists at the prison submitted a proposal to the Federal
Bureau of Prisons in 1998. The first New Pathways class started
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The program fits in with the bureau's plans of addressing
special needs for female inmates, said spokesman Daniel Dunne, and
prison officials here said it may be expanded to other prisons
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   New Pathways has four phases. In the first, which lasts 12
weeks, inmates are encouraged to open up and trust others. They
also learn techniques for managing anger and stress, such as deep
breathing and taking ``time outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The second phase focuses on helping the women recover from their
past traumas.
</P>
<P>
   They practice ``expressive art,'' making collages illustrating
their abuse and anger and playing games that encourage openness in
personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   In another exercise, each group member chooses a past traumatic
experience, and the classmates re-enact it as she watches. The
class then acts out the same scene with a positive twist.
</P>
<P>
   This allows the women to get ``feedback from group members and
it helps them see their own trauma,'' said Tracy Henderson, prison
trauma specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very challenging. It's very emotional. But it's one of
the most cathartic and healing aspects of the program,'' Kotulski
added.
</P>
<P>
   Phase three teaches the inmates ways to build their self-esteem
and think positively.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth and final phase is after care. Until they leave the
prison, inmates who successfully complete the first three phases of
the program will meet monthly to discuss topics that encourage
continued development of the techniques they learned.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other prison reform programs, inmates volunteer for New
Pathways, said Dr. Stephen Formanski, chief psychologist at
FCI-Dublin. There is no financial incentive, nor are inmates'
sentences reduced for participating, he said.
</P>
<P>
   New Pathways' $8,000 price tag in its first year is far less
than the prison's $45,000 drug rehabilitation program, in which
most New Pathways clients also take part.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said New Pathways' unusual group setting is more
helpful than one-on-one therapies they've had in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to have treatment and everything, but this
right here has been more treatment than I had ever had, and it's
helped me cope with a lot of things,'' said Jo-Lynn Anderson, 39,
who was sexually abused by her stepfather and physically abused by
her mother. ``For a long time I didn't want to share with anybody''
the problems she had experienced. Anderson was nearing the end of a
four-year sentence for drug distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in this group, it's taught me that other people have
problems,'' added Anderson, who prior to the program inflicted pain
on herself, breaking all her knuckles by punching her cell walls as
a way to relieve her mental pain. ``It might not be the same, but
we all have different problems and it really helped me to be able
to talk to these ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie, 40, who asked that her last name not be published, said
the program had transformed her into a new person. She was
convicted of using an automatic weapon during a bank robbery, the
latest in a series of offenses for which she has been imprisoned
over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My crimes over the years have gotten worse,'' said Debbie.
``Until I came to this program, my feelings were pretty much cold
and heartless as far as valuing other people's lives. I didn't
understand what empathy was until I went through this program. I
didn't realize I had victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think that the crimes I did really affected other
people. It was a job to me,'' she said. ``I went to work every day
and I did these crimes and they were violent. But if I was to
continue the way I was going, I would have gotten released from
here and gone out and committed more crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Chacon, 24, of El Paso, Texas, also said she had gone
through a rebirth because of the program. Mental abuse and too much
responsibility forced on her by relatives led Chacon to sell drugs
to support her family, she said. She has served two years of a
three-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wouldn't have came(cq) here, many other things could have
happened to me out there, and I wouldn't have learned everything
that I learned about myself in here,'' she said. ``I didn't come to
realize who I was till I got here. I have learned a lot in this
group. I've learned that before you can give to other people you
have to give to yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural set of classes ended April 28, and it is too early
to determine the success of New Pathways.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials are optimistic that many graduates will become
productive members of society. Kotulski said several have
aspirations, once they are free, to help women like themselves. But
officials realize the inmates are not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that every woman who graduates from this program
is going to go out and live a perfect life and be totally drug- and
crime-free and not go back to abusive relationships,'' Henderson
said. ``But at least I know that there are a few out there who know
how to get themselves out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said New Pathways may eventually be expanded to
other prisons around the country. Formanski said he has already
gotten calls from a few prisons, including the Federal Correctional
Institution in Bryon, Texas, that are considering starting similar
programs.
</P>
<P>
   None of its programs are structured quite like New Pathways, but
the state of Georgia has group therapy programs that officials say
have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``During each of these classes, inmates are able to talk about
their problems with other inmates who have similar problems,'' said
spokeswoman Abigail Morgan. ``It gives them another way them to
better cope with their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with reform programs at the nation's prisons and jails,
more people are being locked up. About 1,860,520 adults were
imprisoned in 1999, an increase of 60,000 over the previous year,
according to a recent Bureau of Justice Statistics report.
</P>
<P>
   The number of women prisoners doubled since 1990 to more than
87,000 in 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Scott, the convicted church burner, life will be
completely different when she is released. She plans to get a job,
a home and try to be a mother to her 3-year-old daughter who she
has seen once through a glass since giving birth to the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to her on the phone but she still doesn't know me, and
that's going to be very, very hard for me,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Bureau of Justice Statistics, www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
