<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COX-UNIVERSE-$ADV14     05-13 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-UNIVERSE-$ADV14 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'ANTIGRAVITY' MAY DOMINATE THE UNIVERSE, SCIENTISTS SAY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    Eds: Part three of the occasional ``Window on the Universe''
series.
 &HT;    With photos and logo.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although it has nothing to do with the evil
compulsions of science fiction villains, there appears to be, after
all, a dark side of the force.
</P>
<P>
   Something is causing the universe to expand _ not at the speed
scientists would expect from the Big Bang explosion that created
everything and flung it all apart, but faster. And faster.
</P>
<P>
   After locking horns with such thought-defying concepts such as
extra-spatial dimensions and ``dark matter'' that exists separate
from the ordinary stuff that stars and planets and human beings are
made of, cosmologists have taken up the idea of a ``repulsive''
force.
</P>
<P>
   Acting against the universal gravitational pull that causes
matter to be attracted to other matter, the repulsive force seems
to cause distant galaxies to be pushed away from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Some astronomers are calling the theorized repulsive force
``dark energy,'' but others prefer to call it ``repelling energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The existence of this repelling energy _ if in fact it does
exist and is not merely the result of some astrophysical equivalent
of failing to carry the two _ does not mean that Newton's apple
will fall back up to the tree. Galaxies will continue to collide,
and meteors will continue to fall on the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the repelling energy may overcome the force of gravity
only in great open areas of space, where galaxies are far apart and
have only weak gravitational attraction. In any case, the apparent
discovery has rocked the world of physics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that there are fundamental issues that our physics
cannot explain,'' Shaul Hanany, an astrophysicist at the University
of Minnesota, Minneapolis, said last week. ``We have known that two
masses attract each other. Now we have learned that there are forms
of energy that repel, and we don't know what this energy is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanany was one of the authors of an article published last week
in the Astrophysical Journal Letters(cq) describing measurements
made by a high-altitude balloon launched from the National
Scientific Ballooning Facility in Palestine, Texas, to study
something called the cosmic microwave background.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are convinced this dim glow of radiation, which
pervades all space, was left behind by the formation of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas balloon flight, a two-hour experiment in 1998,
measured something called the ``anisotropy'' of the cosmic
microwave background. The term refers to tiny but distinct
differences in the temperature of the microwave radiation at
various points in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Texas experiment, known as MAXIMA for
``Millimeter Anisotropy eXperiment IMaging Array,'' were almost
identical to those from a balloon flight over Antarctica announced
by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration in late April.
</P>
<P>
   By measuring the side-by-side differences in the microwave heat,
both groups were able to produce a ``snapshot'' of small areas of
the universe a few hundred thousand years after the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   The differences in heat, both teams of scientists said, were
left behind by clumps of early, hot matter that eventually cooled
and expanded to become galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   However, in addition to these baby pictures of the universe, the
temperature measurements allowed scientists to make complicated
calculations that show what kind of matter and energy make up the
cosmos today, Hanany said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanany and other scientists from the University of California,
Berkeley, and universities in Italy, Portugal, Poland and England
said their analysis of the fluctuations convinced them that 60 to
65 percent of all the matter and energy in the universe consists of
the newly theorized ``repelling energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal matter and the energy associated with it _ heat, light,
and so forth _ make up only about 5 percent of everything, the
MAXIMA team reported. The rest appears to be something called
``dark matter,'' which evidently has nothing to do with ``dark
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the everything is expanding at an increasing speed
doesn't work with the traditional Big Bang concept, which had the
the universe more or less coasting along because of the original
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Under one set of assumptions, gravity would someday halt the
expansion and pull everything back together again into a ``Big
Crunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Other assumptions held that the expansion would go on forever,
constantly slowing but never quite stopping, until all matter and
energy had evaporated into nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is true, scientists now think.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, two teams of astronomers from several
universities announced that, after studying the light given off by
supernovas, the enormous explosions of stars, they had discovered
that the expansion is not slowing down at all. It is speeding up.
</P>
<P>
   The results staggered the astronomy world. Something _ some
called it ``antigravity'' _ is overcoming the force of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The supernova experiments confirmed what astrophysicists had
already believed _ that space is being ``stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a car traveling on a rubber highway that is being
stretched. A car setting out on a 60-mile trip at a constant speed
of 60 miles per hour would not arrive in one hour, because the
distance would be stretched during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   As light from the stellar explosions plods along at its
customary speed of 186,000 miles per second, its arrival at the
Earth is delayed by the expansion of space.
</P>
<P>
   What was not expected was the discovery that light from the more
distant supernovas is being delayed at a greater rate that that
from the nearer. The further one travels, the faster space is being
expanded. The only explanation that works, Hanany said is that
repulsive ``dark energy'' of empty space is forcing everything
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the 1800s, people thought everything about the
universe was understood,'' he said. ``Immediately afterward came
quantum mechanics and Einstein's theory of relativity, and they saw
how little they knew. Now we are in a similar position.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their ability to measure temperature differences of as
little as a one hundred-thousandth of a degree, the two balloon
experiments took their microwave ``snapshots'' of only a tiny patch
of sky.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center on the outskirts
of Washington are putting the final touches on a new satellite that
is to be launched next year on a mission designed to map the cosmic
microwave background across the entire sky.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite, known as the Microwave Anisotropy Probe, will
provide the first detailed picture of the entire universe as it
looked 12 to 14 billion years ago. The results may or may not allow
for more precise calculations that could eventually explain the
nature of ``repelling energy,'' said NASA physicist Charles
Bennett, a principal scientific investigator on the project.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it does, it may not prove the existence of anything
that could be called ``anti-gravity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we may find is that it's just gravity, but gravity that
is behaving in a way that we're not accustomed to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: NASA's upcoming Microwave Anisotropy Probe,
map.gsfc.nasa.gov/index.html. MAXIMA balloon experiment,
cfpa.berkeley.edu/group/cmb/
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
