<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-TAUZIAT-BOOK-NYT &LR;      05-13 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TAUZIAT-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAUZIAT WIELDS THE PEN AS DEFTLY AS THE RACQUET 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The epigram that opens Nathalie Tauziat's new book about women's
tennis reads: ``One is not born a champion. One becomes one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an appropriate choice of maxim for a Frenchwoman who has
had to soul-search and tinker constantly to quell the rotating cast
of skeptics during her 17-year career. And even if Tauziat has
never quite succeeded in becoming a major champion _ her seven
singles titles have all come in relatively minor professional
events _ she has managed to achieve much more than anyone,
including she, would have predicted when she turned up in St.
Tropez at age 13 with unimposing technique and physique to train
with a little-known coach, Regis de Camaret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trained at least 15 other girls who had talent far superior
to what Nathalie had at the beginning,'' writes De Camaret, who
remains her coach. ``But she made it to the highest level thanks to
the intensity she managed to put into her work.''
</P>
<P>
   That intensity, along with the tardy but fruitful decision to
rush the net, has propelled her to a career-high No. 3 ranking last
week at an age, 32, when most tennis careers are already over. It
also helped her reach her first and only Grand Slam final at
Wimbledon in 1998, which would surely have had much more impact in
France if its soccer team had not been on its way to winning the
World Cup at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could say I have done everything possible to remain in the
shadows,'' Tauziat writes.
</P>
<P>
   Her failings at the French Open have not helped either: she has
never made it past the quarterfinals in her nation's most
significant tournament. Mary Pierce's decision to represent France
despite her strong U.S. roots and accent also stole some of
Tauziat's thunder.
</P>
<P>
   But this book, a blend of autobiography, trenchant peer review
and informed advocacy, is a conscious effort by Tauziat to step
into the light. Written in French with the help of the reporter
Dominique Bonnot, the book is titled ``Les dessous du tennis
feminin'' (The Underside of Women's Tennis) and the cover features
Tauziat coquettishly clutching a pillow on a bed while dressed in a
nightgown. ``Les dessous'' also means ``underwear'' in French.
</P>
<P>
   It is an out-of-character pose, a tabloid pose, but though
Tauziat addresses most of the tennis topics that frequently receive
sensationalist treatment _ lesbianism on tour, overbearing parents,
teen-age burnout and the telegenic Anna Kournikova _ this is not a
paperback exercise in bottom feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Her thesis _ which her provocative cover photo strangely
reinforces _ is that style has triumphed over substance and that
the culture of celebrity and, above all, the players' agents are at
fault.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tauziat, the tournament directors have a
confidential list called ``the commitment list,'' which grades
players not by their ranking but by their marketability. Tauziat
says that some of the top 20 on the list, which includes the
teen-ager Alexandra Stevenson, who is not yet ranked in the real
top 20, receive bonuses for playing a certain number of events each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in the 1970s, aesthetics and charisma are winning out over
sporting performances,'' Tauziat writes, ``and we don't run much
risk of changing that around as long as the box office will put
Kournikova ahead of Lindsay Davenport only because she is
prettier.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, who has not won a tournament, earned more last year
than Davenport, who has won three Grand Slam titles. But Tauziat
does not let that injustice define her view of Kournikova. She
writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can speak without jealousy or nastiness, because I like her.
She is fun and rather nice, even if she unfortunately does not show
respect to everyone. In my opinion, she's already had enough of
being worshiped. Enough of always being told that she's the
prettiest, the best this, the best that. Even if she plays up her
charm and her physical attributes, the dream of her life is to play
tennis. It's her passion. A true one. What she wants is to finally
win a tournament and be recognized for that, or play in a Grand
Slam final, and it's for that reason I like her a lot. In the end,
we've arrived at an absurd situation where she has become the
victim of a system that she herself has helped develop more or less
willingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Squandered talent bothers Tauziat, who has not had the luxury of
squandering much of hers since she moved to France after spending
the first nine years of her life with her family in French-speaking
Africa. Her dislike of waste is the reason she has mixed emotions
about Yannick Noah, the charismatic Frenchman with the short
attention span who was captain when France and Tauziat won the Fed
Cup in 1997. ``The talent he had!'' she writes. ``He could have
been so much better! Why didn't he invest in the long term?''
</P>
<P>
   She sees the same tendencies in the newest French star, Amelie
Mauresmo, who reached the 1999 Australian Open final at 19 and has
since had flickering results. As for Mauresmo's decision to
announce her lesbianism, Tauziat accepts it completely, but is
uncomfortable with the public assumption that most women's tour
players have the same sexual preference. ``When the WTA and women's
circuit began,'' she writes, ``the proportion of homosexuals among
the top 10 was significant. Now there must be no more than two
among the top 10. But the idea that we are all more or less that
way is so powerful that one must always justify oneself. How many
times have I felt in the eyes of others this heavy and indelicate
question, `Are you or aren't you?' No, I am not, and I am neither
proud nor sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat is grudgingly complimentary of the Williams sisters,
writing: ``Luckily the Williamses are not (yet) great technically.
If they were they would be unplayable.'' But she has more unabashed
admiration for the ever-improving Martina Hingis, whom she supports
despite the Swiss teen-ager's chronic lack of diplomacy and
petulant performance in defeat against Steffi Graf in last year's
French Open final. Tauziat was in the locker room afterward holding
a sobbing Hingis while Hingis told her she was convinced she would
never win the title she wants most.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat suspects the use of banned performance-enhancing drugs
is fairly widespread and not being effectively combated by the
sport's governing bodies. She also does not like the tendency to
reduce tournament fields and squeeze out the marginal pros, a trend
pushed by top players' agents. She believes it will reduce the
talent pool from which stars emerge.
</P>
<P>
   But what she really dislikes is that she lost her only Grand
Slam final. She is convinced she lost it before the match even
began against Jana Novotna. ``I didn't tell myself, `Nat, this
final is yours for the taking,''' she writes. ``I told myself,
`Nat, you've made it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Tauziat will long watch the video of that 1998
Wimbledon final with regret, the fact that she lost explains why
she, unlike Novotna, is still playing, still trying to take the
ball a split-second earlier, still trying to make arriviste youth
wait its turn, still consumed by the labor-intensive process of
becoming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BKN-KERMIT-WASHINGTON     05-13 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KERMIT-WASHINGTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUDDEN, VIOLENT MOMENT THAT STILL HAUNTS A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Kermit Washington played 10 seasons in the NBA. He now
owns a restaurant in Vancouver, Wash.)  
 By KERMIT WASHINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro basketball is a different game these days, and it isn't
simply what happens on the court. When I see the way Latrell
Sprewell has turned around his image after the much-publicized
confrontation with his coach, P.J. Carlesimo, it reinforces my
belief that you can overcome something negative provided someone
wants to help you.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years ago, it was very different. You didn't have
the public relations machine you have now. Pete Newell and Red
Auerbach stood up for me and helped me stay in the NBA as a player.
But I was never able to live down the one mistake I made as a
player, or even explain it so that people would understand I wasn't
some kind of animal who would just turn around and hit someone for
no reason.
</P>
<P>
   The story began on Dec. 9, 1977. I was playing for the Los
Angeles Lakers. We were in the middle of a game in Los Angeles
against the Houston Rockets. It was your typical basketball game. I
was checking Moses Malone, something I did regularly because we
would always try to keep Kareem Abdul-Jabbar out of foul trouble.
As a player, I was expendable and Kareem was not. This didn't
bother me. It was an honor to play against one of the game's
greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   The situation started with a rebound that came off the board. It
would have been an offensive rebound if I had gotten it, but I did
not. There were two other people under the basket _ Kareem and
Houston's Kevin Kunnert. I turned to get back on defense and tried
to pull my way past Kevin. What I did would have been a foul if it
were caught, but it wasn't. As I tried to pull my way past Kevin,
he elbowed me in the face. For a second, I didn't know what had hit
me. When I realized I had been elbowed, I turned to him thinking it
had been an accident. His second reaction was not what I expected.
He turned and hit me in the face.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the first elbow was not unintentional. After he hit me, I
heard Kareem say, ``Oh no!'' He knew a fight was about to ensue.
Kevin and I scuffled, with not much damage to either side because
people had jumped between us. While this was happening, I saw Rudy
Tomjanovich running straight at me. After being attacked by
Kunnert, I did not think Rudy's intentions were good either. I just
saw someone running at me and reacted. My punch landed on his face
and he fell. As Rudy Tomjanovich fell that night, so did my
basketball career and a lot of the rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   After everything stopped and I realized Rudy was hurt, I was
sorry I had hit him. Not knowing the extent of Rudy's injuries, I
drove home after being thrown out of the game. I tried calling the
hospital that night to apologize and check on him, but my calls
were turned away. I did not expect the reactions that followed
because I thought I had just been defending myself. Unfortunately,
Kunnert's elbowing and hitting me were not on film. The only parts
that were caught were Rudy running at me and my hitting him. I knew
I was in trouble. The news reports of my attacking Rudy were
everywhere, but there was no mention of Kunnert and his
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   I went to practice and played in the next game. The reports of
the story and Rudy's condition worsened. (He eventually needed
facial reconstruction surgery.) The clip of my turning and hitting
Rudy was played continuously all over the nation. I was portrayed
as an out-of-control player who attacked another player for no
reason. I knew something bad was going to happen. It did. The press
completely turned on me. I was fined $10,000 and suspended
indefinitely for three months without pay, a large sum in those
days of $100,000 annual salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But my nightmare was just beginning. Besides having no money, I
was public enemy No. 1. In 1977, racial diversity was almost
nonexistent; racial slurs about me became everyone's favorite. I
was humiliated. I was an embarrassment to myself and my family. Not
even the university I attended wanted anything to do with me.
Everyone who was once so proud of me now could not even say my name
in public.
</P>
<P>
   During my suspension, the Lakers never called me. My lawyer at
the time, David Falk, advised me not to comment on anything about
that night. I couldn't even defend myself to the public. A few days
later, as a result of the fight, I was traded to the Boston Celtics
with Don Chaney. Before I went to Boston, I had to meet with
Commissioner Larry O'Brien in New York. O'Brien made it clear that
I was not welcome anymore. His actual words were: ``We don't need
your kind in the league. You are not good for the league.'' I
realized then that if I wanted to continue playing basketball, I
would have to keep my mouth shut and not appeal my suspension or
trade. For reasons I now regret, I chose to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, I had to have FBI agents sit next to me at the games
for fear of being attacked. I was warned not to order room service
for fear of being poisoned. I finished the rest of my career
without incident and retired in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I have applied for various coaching jobs from high
school to the pro level, but have always been turned down because
no one wanted to be associated with my reputation, or with me. My
name stood for violence and bad publicity. I was blackballed
everywhere. I've made it this far only because I have owned my own
business, a restaurant. No one would hire me. I couldn't do summer
camps because parents didn't want their kids around someone like
me. Schools were hesitant to let me speak because all the kids ever
wanted to hear about was the famous fight.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 23 years, the clip of my hitting Rudy is played
every time there is any type of violence in sports. I can't count
how many times it ran during the Sprewell incident and just
recently with the Marty McSorley hockey incident. Everything I've
ever accomplished in life is overshadowed by this incident. No one
stops to ask me about my charities or the work I do in the
community.
</P>
<P>
   I can't come back and play and have someone like a sneaker
company or the NBA start a marketing campaign to help me overcome
the one blemish on my resume. After I quit playing, guys who were
my best friends in the league would say, ``Kermit, we can't hire
you as an assistant coach because of the publicity it would get.''
I never drank, never did drugs, never got in trouble. I was an
academic all-American at American University, started Pete Newell's
camp for big men and helped run it for 10 years, started Project
Contact and have been doing charity work in African countries.
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against the league. I understand that 23 years
ago the NBA had a reputation to protect and that it felt it had to
sacrifice me. But all people are ever going to remember me for was
this one blemish.
</P>
<P>
   How do I make people believe that, yes, I did throw a punch that
I sincerely regret, but that it was in a fight that I didn't start?
How do I change the way people look at me every time there's a
violent act in sports?
</P>
<P>
   I took a lie detector test last month to prove I was telling the
truth. The doctor who administered the test said it was two to
three times higher than it needed to be to be an honest statement.
I hope this is the first step in salvaging my name and reputation.
When I die, I hope the legacy I leave behind is not one of
violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
