<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RHEINGOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIET LANGE RHEINGOLD, INFANT BEHAVIOR EXPERT, DIES AT 92 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., N.Y., Ill., Md.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harriet Lange Rheingold, a child psychologist and research
professor emeritus at the University of North Carolina, died on
April 29 at a retirement center in Chapel Hill, N.C. She was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold did not begin her specialized research until she was
45, after 20 years of patient care and undergraduate teaching. She
made a name for herself nationally in the next 20 years with her
work in developmental psychology.
</P>
<P>
   She focused on the social and exploratory skills of infants and
young children. Her interests ranged from infant sociability and
responsiveness to independent behavior and the development of
valued traits like sharing, helping and caring.
</P>
<P>
   Her teaching and writings helped to change the way psychologists
view normal infant behavior by helping to shape the recognition
that infants interact with their environment from birth. Her books
included ``The Infant Separates Himself From Her Mother,''
published by the American Association for the Advancement of
Science in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, she graduated from Cornell in 1928 with a
degree in philosophy and earned a master's in psychology at
Columbia in 1930. She then was a research fellow, psychologist and
assistant professor at Rockford College in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 she received a Ph.D. in psychology at the University of
Chicago. She was a research psychologist at the National Institute
of Mental Health in Bethesda, Md., before joining the North
Carolina faculty as a research professor in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 she organized a symposium, ``Toward a Unified Science of
Behavioral Development,'' for the Society for Research in Child
Development. The same year she also addressed the 18th World
Congress on Early Childhood Education in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold is survived by her husband, Don W. Hayne, two sons,
six grandchildren and two great-grandsons. Her first husband, Dr.
Joseph Rheingold, a psychiatrist, died in 1978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BOWERY-REHAB-585&AMP;A     05-13 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOWERY-REHAB-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAGGING SPIRITS FIND RESPITE IN SHRUBBERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alfred Spurlock, shot in the head by the police
during a burglary, and in prison most of his life, did not know he
was HIV-positive until after he wandered drunk on railroad tracks
in New Jersey and got clobbered by a train that knocked him into a
pond.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the first sentence of an exceptionally depressing
hard-luck story.
</P>
<P>
   This is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Spurlock is one of a group of formerly luckless people, all poor
and infected with the virus that causes AIDS, who in the past year
have hung out on a balcony in the Bowery and witnessed the coming
of a paradise that replaced a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   It's a garden center where Billie Holiday sings over
loudspeakers for young professionals who are hunting potted plants.
Weeping Japanese maples sell for $600. Hoes that Wal-Mart sells for
$14.96 sell in the former parking lot for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Chelsea Garden Center is exactly the kind of place that
Spurlock and his fellow clients at the Bowery Residents' Committee
Adult Day Health Center would not be able to enjoy unless fate had
offered them a perch that looks down upon, among other things,
yuppies buying mulch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see people in there you don't even know existed,'' said
Eduvige Rosario, 39, who was told 15 years ago that he had the AIDS
virus. ``It is like seeing monkeys in the zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the greenery, more than the credit-card-carrying humanity,
that brings pleasure to the men and women who sit on a warm spring
afternoon, smoking cigarettes and gazing at a Thundercloud Purple
Leaf Plum tree (the tallest item in the garden store) swaying in
the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say without a doubt that the attitude of our clients has
changed since Central Park moved into the parking lot,'' said
Josephine Gilliam, a substance-abuse counselor at the center.
``They are more friendly, more open, and they started to rally
around each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That's no exaggeration, says Gilliam, who herself sits and
smokes on the second-story porch between counseling sessions and
admires the Thundercloud Purple Leaf Plum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch it blow in the wind, and my stress goes away,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stress usually goes up, not away, when businesses that cater to
the affluent rub shoulders on the Bowery with agencies that serve
the poor, the sick and the previously incarcerated. A dot-com
invasion has sent rents climbing in the neighborhood. Cheap
housing, even cheap bad housing, is increasingly scarce on the
formerly infamous skid row where fancy restaurants now sell grilled
paillard of veal for $18 a plate.
</P>
<P>
   But the adult care center at 317 Bowery is lucky. Four years
ago, just ahead of the dot-com curve, the center signed a lease
that guarantees 50 years of affordable rent, according to John
Sheehan, acting director of the center, which is financed by its
clients' Medicaid benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Garden Center, too, has had an atypical stress reaction.
Its owner, David Protell, moved last summer to the corner of Bowery
and Second Street not knowing who his neighbors would be and
certainly not anticipating that they would hang out on a reviewing
stand, eyeballing his customers and loving his shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had concerns about the neighborhood for all the obvious
reasons,'' said Protell, who was forced to move from Chelsea to
make room for an apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these people up there,'' he said, casting his eyes in the
direction of the smokers on the balcony, ``are excellent neighbors.
I am sure we amuse them. We are the animals in the zoo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Chelsea Garden Center has given a Christmas tree and some
plants to the day care center. Protell said he might be interested
in offering jobs, too, but that he has not yet been asked.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Spurlock, the man who got knocked into the pond by
the train, only to learn from doctors who put him back together
that he was infected with HIV?
</P>
<P>
   He has healed and, he said, has been clean of drugs and drink
since last July _ about the time the Chelsea Garden Center moved in
next door. Spurlock does not believe coincidence is causality, but
he loves looking at the greenery. He describes its arrival as ``the
best thing that could have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   One doleful concern of Spurlock and his fellow clients is the
long wooden shrubbery planters that they see stacked on the roof of
the garden center's office. On the edge of a parking-lot paradise,
the planters look like coffins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
