</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-HOUSING-REAL-4TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE ELDERLY FACE HOUSING CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three-story Tudor on tree-graced Maryland Road in the
Douglaston section of Queens, New York City, often reverberates
with the clamor and clatter of Frances Toner's dozen grandchildren
and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have friends on the block,'' said Toner, who has lived
in her four-bedroom house for nearly 60 years, ``which is why I
don't want to move.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, precisely because she decided to remain in the big,
old house that her father bought for $10,000 in 1943 _ and is now
worth ``at least $350,000,'' she said _ Toner made what in legal
parlance is called ``a gifting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given the house to my children,'' Toner, 83, said, ``but
I can live in it until I die _ who knows when? _ or if I go into a
nursing home. I assume all the responsibilities for repairs and
taxes and insurance. It's all done in case I need Medicaid. If I
have to go into a nursing home it would not be considered my
property.''
</P>
<P>
   In many facets of her life, Toner, a retired schoolteacher,
reflects the range of choices, the possibilities and pitfalls, that
older people, along with their offspring, must be aware of _ and
sometimes be wary of _ in negotiating the added complexities of
real estate that come with age.
</P>
<P>
   Stay or sell? Move in with the children or stick by those dear
friends? Downsize in the suburbs or go co-op in the city? Head
toward warmer climes? Buy or rent?
</P>
<P>
   Take on new debt? If so, how does one evade the clutches of
predatory lenders? And just what are those newfangled reverse
mortgages?
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the questions typically confronting the healthy
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   If health declines, other complicated issues arise: If mobility
abates, is the right course to remodel the old house and hire a
home-care aide, or to move into some sort of assisted-living
accommodation? What if one spouse needs assistance while the other
does not?
</P>
<P>
   And how does one keep the government from ``taking the house,''
a common fear of the elderly, when Medicaid requires that most
assets be liquidated? Or keep the tax collector from clobbering the
children on capital gains?
</P>
<P>
   Such issues, to be sure, confront many people venturing into a
real estate transaction, not only the elderly. But they are of
particular concern to those who are likely to have lived in their
homes for decades, may be on fixed incomes, and may not be familiar
with the vicissitudes of the current market.
</P>
<P>
   They are issues for increasing numbers of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, one thing relevant about seniors is that there is
going to be more of us,'' said Professor Nicolas Retsinas, director
of the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Retsinas said, 34 million Americans are 65 or older; in
1970, it was 20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even more spectacular,'' he said, ``is that the growth
will surge to almost 70 million by 2030.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Harvard center released a two-year study,
``Housing America's Seniors,'' which, among other conclusions,
reported that people 65 and over, with ownership rates of nearly 80
percent, currently account for about one-quarter of all home
owners, and 1 in 10 home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One misconception about the elderly is that most of them live
in age-restricted housing,'' Retsinas said. ``The reality is that
most live in the same kinds of homes everybody else does.'' Ten
percent of the elderly live in age-restricted communities, the
Harvard report says.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, as the population ages, ``we're not going to be
immune from health and mobility problems,'' Retsinas said,
``decisions about buying and selling homes are something more and
more of the elderly will face.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the concerns raised in the report are that elderly people
are increasingly living in suburban, auto-dependent areas; that
they have had fewer children and, therefore, now have fewer primary
caretakers than previous generations had, and that access to
services will prove increasingly difficult for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge in the marketplace is that while seniors are
often not as well informed about their options, they increasingly
need homes that are modified to accommodate mobility
restrictions,'' Retsinas said, ``and because of that they are more
susceptible to predatory lending.'' At the same time, he said, ``as
tomorrow's seniors face choices of whether to stay or move, they
may not be as aware of revolutionary changes in housing finance
that have opened up an array of options.''
</P>
<P>
   THE REVERSE MORTGAGE: Unlocking Values In Home Equity
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most revolutionary development in the field of
housing finance for the elderly is the reverse mortgage, which
offers a range of possibilities for homeowners 62 or older,
particularly those who are equity rich but cash poor.
</P>
<P>
   By tapping into the long-accumulated equity of their home,
elderly people can remain in their residences while financing a
major remodeling _ perhaps installing wider doors for wheelchairs,
access ramps and grab bars. Or they can buy a new home and no
longer be fettered to monthly mortgage payments. Or take a lump sum
at the time the reverse mortgage is closed and use that money for
any personal project, or to pay medical expenses. Or they can
simply enhance their incomes with monthly payments into their
pockets or by drawing down a line of credit as needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can really use it for anything,'' said Naomi Bayer,
director of the New York office of Fannie Mae, the federally
chartered home-financing corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse mortgages, which have been on the market for less than a
decade, require no repayment while the elderly person is living in
the house. ``When they no longer occupy the home, the loan is due
and payable with all the accrued interest,'' Bayer said. ``And any
heirs may repay it by either selling the home or with other
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, a 75-year-old homeowner whose house is worth
$200,000 takes out a reverse mortgage at an interest rate of 10
percent and lives in the house for 10 more years, the borrower
could have access to a line of credit of about $100,000. The
borrower could either draw down that line of credit at will or take
monthly payments of about $900.
</P>
<P>
   If, at the end of the 10 years the full line of credit has been
used up, a total of about $200,000 would be owed _ including the
$100,000 the borrower received over the years, the closing costs of
$10,000 and accrued interest of about $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverse mortgages are structured so that the borrower will
never owe more than the value of their home at the time the house
is ultimately sold,'' Bayer said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scenario differs, somewhat, when a reverse mortgage is used
to buy a new home. ``Let's say they are 73 and sell their home for
$200,000,'' Bayer said, ``and they want to move closer to their
children and buy a smaller home for $150,000. They could get what
we call a Home Keeper loan in the amount of $65,000, and would
contribute $85,000 from the proceeds of the previous sale'' _
leaving $115,000 in liquid assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are using it to buy another home, they don't get money
for their current use,'' Bayer said, ``but it allows them to buy
the new home without monthly mortgage payments. And when they die
or move into other accommodations, the loan and the interest become
due and payable.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers should learn as much as possible about reverse mortgages
before making a decision, Bayer said. ``There are counseling
agencies approved by Fannie Mae that can provide individualized
information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   They should decide themselves whether to take a reverse
mortgage. ``Get advice from family members, but don't let anyone
make up your mind,'' Bayer said. Borrowers should also insist that
all reverse mortgage funds be paid directly to them, she said;
``don't let anybody persuade you to sign over the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   And borrowers should choose themselves how to use the loan
funds. ``Sometimes seniors hear about reverse mortgages that offer
a particular product or service, like home remodeling or an
annuity,'' Bayer said. ``That decision is totally up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   PREDATORY LENDING: Targeting The Unsophisticated
</P>
<P>
   Some of these loan products are foisted on people by
unscrupulous lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The basic pattern, said Josh Zinner, coordinator of the
foreclosure prevention project for the elderly at South Brooklyn
Legal Services, ``is that people who are financially
unsophisticated are targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a contractor comes to the door ``making all sorts
of promises about helping with affordable repairs,'' Zinner said,
``and people end up with vastly inflated home-improvement
contracts, often for repairs that are not needed.'' The contractors
work in conjunction with mortgage brokers who refer the loan to
high-rate lenders. ``And then all sorts of fees and costs are piled
on,'' Zinner said.
</P>
<P>
   People are sometimes persuaded to consolidate other debt into
the principal of the mortgage so that it, too, is tied to their
home. ``If somebody had credit-card debt or a hospital bill, it's
all replaced by the high-rate mortgage,'' Zinner said. ``So people
end up with huge monthly payments they can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't lose your home because of an unpaid hospital bill,''
he said, ``but if you can't pay the mortgage because the hospital
bill was added in, you can lose your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, to push the loan through and collect their fees,
mortgage brokers falsify income information on the loan
application, ``and the lenders who work with these brokers simply
look the other way,'' Zinner said. ``What results is a very high
rate of foreclosures with these types of loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers sometimes commit to a series of predatory loans,
Zinner said, ``until all the equity in their home is swallowed
up.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Louise Nathan, 61, was the victim of a hammer attack in
her East New York, Brooklyn, home. She underwent years of therapy
to regain some ability to speak, read and write.
</P>
<P>
   That elicited no sympathy from three successive lenders who came
to the door of her three-story, aluminum-sided row house four years
ago. ``The first was a typical home-improvement scam,'' said Nancy
Slahetka, a staff lawyer with the foreclosure prevention project.
</P>
<P>
   The contract _ to install a new floor, a ceiling, a bathtub,
cabinets, and repair a faucet in the bathroom _ was for $34,900.
But the mortgage was for $60,000, with monthly payments of $711.
Nathan's monthly income, from Social Security, is $948, Slahetka
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broker got a $13,690 fee,'' Slahetka said. ``They paid off
her old mortgage, which only had $6,828 left and would have matured
in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, the first loan was ``flipped,''
Slahetka said, ``when the same broker got her to sign another loan,
for $75,000 at 10.95 percent. And there's a balloon payment of
$63,000 after 15 years.'' A balloon payment means that until that
point the borrower has, essentially, only paid interest on the
loan, and not the principal. For Nathan's second mortgage, the
broker got $4,100 in fees and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   And then came a third mortgage with a different broker, for
$28,563 at 12.59 percent. ``She says that when she signed the
papers she could hardly read and talk,'' Slahetka said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan said: ``They wanted to do things to the house they said I
wanted done. I feel bad about what it's doing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal Services is currently seeking to devise a workout plan for
Nathan's debt problems and, citing possible deceptive lending
practices, challenging foreclosure proceedings filed against her.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL DEAL: Some Rules For Success
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate transactions are perfectly legitimate, which is
not to say that every party to the deal is not trying to maximize
profits. So Dominick Pompeo, who knows what houses should cost,
offers some basic advice _ good for buyers or sellers of all ages
but, particularly, for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times,'' said Pompeo, a former chairman of the New York
State Appraisal Board and the president of Diversified Valuation
Group, an appraisal company in South Ozone Park, Queens, ``older
folks purchased their homes or apartments 30, 40 years ago and are
not really up on current market conditions. There's the chance they
will go to a broker who is not as experienced in their particular
community as he or she should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1 _ go to a well-established local broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition,'' Pompeo said, ``if they should relocate to a new
community, our first advice is that they rent for a time, to see if
it suits their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   In that instance, because potential buyers are unfamiliar with
the local market, Pompeo recommends that they have an appraisal
done. But only by an appraiser who is certified or licensed by the
state and, again, can demonstrate experience in the community.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get burned choosing an appraiser,'' Pompeo said.
``They can be unscrupulous, biased, if they are retained by the
mortgage broker or the sales broker. Those individuals do not
realize their remuneration unless the deal is consummated, so they
may look for an appraiser who is willing to make sure the number
comes in at the contract value.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, most appraisers were retained directly by lenders.
But now, with streamlined, computerized mortgage programs, brokers
are retaining them. ``And if the appraiser does not insure that the
deal is done they are not hired again,'' Pompeo said.
</P>
<P>
   When the elderly relocate, he said, ``they take their knowledge
and parameters about their own market and judge their new area by
their previous standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they are coming from somewhere in the Northeast, where
prices tend to be higher,'' he continued, ``there's a possibility
they may pay more than the market commands and still think they are
getting a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are coming to this area,'' Pompeo said, ``they may get
sticker shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly shocking, said Sylvia Shapiro, is buying an
apartment in Manhattan. Shapiro, a real estate lawyer and author of
``The Co-op Bible'' (St. Martin's Griffin, 1998), said, for
example, that since her building converted in 1991, a one-bedroom
has jumped from about $130,000 to $360,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are several things a potential co-op or condominium buyer
should watch for. ``These pertain to most buyers, but are of
greater concern to people on a fixed income,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer should be sure the building ``has a history of fairly
constant maintenance and monthly charges, not huge spikes like the
Dow Jones,'' she said, and should find out if the underlying
mortgage is coming due. If the board has to refinance, Shapiro
said, ``that could result in a substantial maintenance increase and
put a crimp in a retiree's budget.''
</P>
<P>
   A building's ``personality,'' Shapiro said, should also be
considered by an elderly buyer. ``There's one building in my
neighborhood where I think you need an AARP card to gain
admission,'' she said. ``Different generations often have different
agendas. Depending on who holds the upper hand, these differences
can lead to skirmishes before the board.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These days, with bidders outnumbering available apartments in
Manhattan, boards are being finicky in vetting an elderly buyer's
finances, particularly if someone is on a fixed income and may not
be able to afford additional monthly charges.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Baker, a retired State Department foreign service
officer who, tongue slightly in cheek, described himself as
``ancient, over the hill, falling apart,'' confronted that kind of
skittishness when he bought a one-bedroom in a co-op on East Ninth
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had rented for 23 years, a fourth-floor walkup,'' Baker, 65,
said. ``But the aches and pains, it was too much.'' He was paying
about $1,000 a month for the rent-stabilized apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out to rent another place and found absolute dregs in
my price range,'' Baker said. ``The worst was a one-room
efficiency; you came through the door and on the right was a
curtain with a john behind it, and on the left was a counter with a
hot plate and one of those mini-refrigerators underneath. They
wanted $1,750. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's broker then said that if he could make a down payment he
probably could buy an apartment and afford monthly charges within
his $2,000 limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other intelligent thing I've done in my life is a buy
a little house in Sag Harbor,'' Baker said. He paid $40,000 for
that two-bedroom cottage in Southampton, and it is now worth, he
estimates, $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a pension from the State Department and Social
Security, so my annual income without lifting a finger is
$65,000,'' Baker said. He also has a $5,000-a-year adjunct
professorship in United Nations studies at Long Island University.
``Not really the biggest slice of my pie, is it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, given the possibility of future maintenance increases,
that job became a bit of an issue before the board of the East
Ninth Street building.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seemed to be concern about whether I would keep the job
or not; they kept asking for records,'' Baker said. ``From my
perspective, I have zero debt, a house fully paid for, a clean
credit record for 35 years, blah, blah, blah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, it all worked out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, in early December, Baker made a $60,000 down payment on the
$195,000 apartment. With mortgage payments of $800 and maintenance
of $500, he said, ``That's manageable _ $1,300 for a clean
apartment, with elevators.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker is single, and does not have to worry about his heirs.
Others do.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE PLANNING: Keeping the House, Minimizing Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Typically, when a husband and wife own a home and one spouse
dies, the home will automatically be owned by the surviving spouse,
and no estate taxes will be assessed. When the second spouse dies,
however, the value of the home will become part of the estate and
could be subject to estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal estate laws, every individual has a credit of
$675,000, which allows them to leave property valued up to that
amount to their heirs without it being subject to estate taxes.
That credit amount is scheduled to increase to $1 million in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   For many elderly people, however, the focus is not on what will
happen after they die, but on preserving their ownership through
the rest of what increasingly is a lengthening life span.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people,'' said Brian Treacy, an elder-law lawyer in
Rutherford, N.J., ``often have this paranoia about the government;
they don't want `the government,' in quotes, `to take my house.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It might be the hospital, a nursing home, the Internal Revenue
Service, ``they all blur together,'' Treacy said, ``and seniors
will go to great lengths to prevent `them' from getting their
property.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, perfectly legal lengths to which anyone is
entitled to go to protect their home for themselves, for a healthy
spouse or for their heirs _ precisely what Toner, in her stately
Tudor home in Douglaston, Queens, had in mind when she opted to
give the house to her children.
</P>
<P>
   Toner is healthy; her husband, Hugh, 84, recently entered a
nursing home. The ``gifting'' _ linked to what is called a
life-estate clause _ gives her peace of mind, she said, ``a sense
that I know it won't all go to the nursing home, that the children
will have something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they can't put me out,'' she said with a touch of glee.
</P>
<P>
   The papers were drawn up by Ronald Fatoullah, an elder-law
lawyer in Nassau County's Great Neck. ``Once Mrs. Toner's husband
was approved for Medicaid,'' Fatoullah said, ``we wanted to do
estate planning for her. Now the home is protected for herself,
should she ever need care, and for her children in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nursing-home costs can range from $80,000 to more than $130,000
a year, Fatoullah said, ``and if the home remains in the name of
the senior who has received Medicaid benefits, the government would
recoup dollar for dollar everything it spent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So if there was, let's say, $500,000 in Medicaid dollars spent
_ and that's not atypical _ there likely would be no home left,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Treacy, the lawyer in Rutherford, pointed out that the idea of
transferring a home to an adult child is a common and simple
transaction for any lawyer to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' he said, ``is that because that transaction is
so easy and incurs no expenses it is usually conducted without one
very important sentence: a life-estate clause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, in it's entirety, 23 words _ `The grantor reserves to
himself a life estate in the subject property for his use and
enjoyment for the entirety of his lifetime' _ that can mean a
difference of thousands and thousands of dollars in taxes that will
have to be paid by the children upon the house's eventual sale.''
</P>
<P>
   It is here that the burden of capital gains taxes comes into
play.
</P>
<P>
   Fatoullah offered a for-instance: ``A client comes into my
office and wants protection for the home, and one of the first
questions I ask is, `When did you buy the home and what did you
pay?' The response I typically get is, `Oh, we scrimped and saved
and the house cost $10,000 back in the 40's; and we got such a big
mortgage, for $8,000.'''
</P>
<P>
   What elder-law and estate-planning lawyers want to determine, at
that point, is the basis for capital gains taxes on the elder
person's home, which is calculated by taking the purchase price and
adding the cost of capital improvements (though not basic repairs)
that have gone into the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, a senior will say, `I just want to transfer my home to
my children,''' Fatoullah said. ``But that's a problem. When you do
that you are also transferring, along with the home, the senior's
low tax basis. Meaning that when the child goes to sell the home,
let's say for $350,000 or $400,000, it could trigger a huge capital
gains burden for the child _ the tax on the gain.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, someone bought their home for $10,000 back in
the 1940s _ as Toner's father did _ and $40,000 worth of capital
improvements were made throughout the years, the tax basis would be
$50,000. ``Which means that if the home is sold for $350,000,
there's a gain of $300,000,'' Fatoullah said, ``and the child will
be responsible for paying the capital gains tax, at varying
percentages, when the home is sold.''
</P>
<P>
   But with a life-estate clause, upon the death of the parent the
home would be reappraised, and the market value of the home at that
time would be become the new tax basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if that $10,000 home is valued at $300,000 when the parent
dies and the child sells it for that amount,'' Fatoullah said,
``then there is absolutely no capital gains tax involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a difference,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
