<HEADLINE>
TIMOTHY KILEY, DIRECTOR OF VARIETY SHOWS, DIES AT 74 
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Tenn., Wis., Ill.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timothy M. Kiley, who directed television variety shows in the
1960s and '70s, died April 29 at a hospital in Beverly Hills,
Calif. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from lung cancer, his son Timothy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley directed ``The Ed Sullivan Show,'' ``The Smothers Brothers
Comedy Hour'' and ``The Flip Wilson Show,'' and was nominated for
three Emmy Awards. He received the Directors Guild award for best
director of a musical variety series in 1971. He also directed
``The Sonny and Cher Show,'' ``The Mac Davis Show'' and ``Star
Search.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiley was born in Milwaukee. During World War II he was a
sergeant in the 342nd Infantry. He went to Northwestern University
and began his directing career in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two sons, three daughters, a brother, two
sisters and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
