<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURIE BATTLE, EX-CONGRESSMAN LINKED TO A COLD WAR BILL, DIES AT
87
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ala., Va. Md.)  By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laurie C. Battle, a former representative from Alabama who was
linked to an important piece of Cold War legislation, died May 2 at
Bethesda Naval Hospital in Maryland. He was 87 and lived in
Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Battle, a Democrat, served four terms in Congress, representing
Birmingham from 1947 to 1955. An opponent of Communism, he was best
known as the principal sponsor of the Mutual Defense Assistance
Control Act of 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, called the Battle Act, blocked the United
States from giving aid to countries that shipped goods ``of primary
strategic significance'' to the Soviet Union and other nations in
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave the president the authority to waive the ban, and
Harry S. Truman promptly notified Congress that several countries,
including Britain, Denmark, France and Italy, would continue to
receive aid from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Calvin Battle was born in Wilsonville, Ala. He received a
degree in psychology from Birmingham-Southern College in 1934 and a
master's in sociology from Ohio State University in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a laborer and clerk for a natural gas company
during the day and taught sociology at Ohio State at night. He
joined the Army Air Forces in 1942 and was sent to the Pacific,
where he rose to the rank of major, and was awarded a Bronze Star
Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Battle won his first congressional race in 1946 on a shoestring
budget. Once elected, he demanded strict ethical standards for
Congress, insisting that members must not solicit or take favors
from people trying to influence votes.
</P>
<P>
   After four terms, he ran for the Senate in 1954 but lost in the
Democratic primary to Sen. John Sparkman. He also ran for governor
of Alabama in 1958 but lost in a primary election that included
George Wallace and John Patterson, who went on to win a runoff and
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Battle worked in the insurance business in Birmingham and then
as a government relations representative and legislative consultant
in Washington. He was staff director and counsel of the House Rules
Committee from 1966 to 1976 and was a special adviser to the U.S.
League of Savings Associations.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 55 years, Janis Hunt Battle, four
sons, two daughters, three brothers, three sisters and 19
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
