<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DELIVER, BUT SEE NEED TO IMPROVE
</HEADLINE>
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The stars lived up to their billing. The supporting
actors delivered award-winning performances and the defense awoke
for a climactic finish. The Los Angeles Lakers also won on the
road, a place that suspiciously had brought out the playoff worst
in them.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, they weren't satisfied. Despite preserving a 105-99
victory Friday night over the Phoenix Suns with clutch free throws,
the Lakers sounded like Hollywood executives panning their own
blockbuster release.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has them believing that perfection is the
only way to win a championship ring, and even with a 3-0 lead in
the Western Conference semifinals, he still has their rapt
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some measure of happiness may come Sunday if the Lakers can
sweep the Suns in Game 4 at the America West Arena. Then again,
anything less than a 30-point stomping might be viewed as weakness
in the Los Angeles camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can cut down on mistakes and turnovers, we can do what
we did in Game 1,'' center Shaquille O'Neal said, referring to the
Lakers' 105-77 victory in the series opener. ``It's not what
they're doing to us, it's what we're doing to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who owned a four-game road losing streak going into
Game 3, had hurt themselves with slow starts at Sacramento in the
previous round and suffered the consequences while being taken to
five games by the Kings. That was the case again on Friday night
during an 18-point first quarter in which the Lakers shot an
embarrassing 27.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they recovered their shooting touch, quickly rallied from 12
points down and beat the Suns for the seventh consecutive time,
including four games in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the joke in the locker room, that we're not a good
road team,'' O'Neal said. ``We still didn't play a great game. We
still had a lot of mistakes. But with six minutes to go, we just
clamped down and went to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' script was true to the usual story line. O'Neal
devastated the Suns with 37 points and 17 rebounds and put on what
for him was a free-throw shooting exhibition. The Suns tried
bearhugs from Oliver Miller and forearm shivers from Luc Longley,
but O'Neal made them pay, knocking down 9 of 15 foul shots (8 of 10
in the first half).
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant scored 25 points and provided a crucial spark with
6:08 to play. Driving down the lane for a basket, he was fouled by
Penny Hardaway and completed the 3-point play to pull the Lakers
into an 87-87 tie. From there, the teams traded leads until Bryant,
Glen Rice and Brian Shaw combined for six free throws to put them
ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, Kobe's play was a big lift for us,'' Jackson
said. ``It allowed us to catch up with them and turned it into a
six-minute game.''
</P>
<P>
   The backups helped bail out the Lakers, too. Robert Horry, the
ex-Sun whose exit from Phoenix was hastened when he threw a towel
in the face of Danny Ainge, then the coach, while coming out of a
game, silenced boos from the crowd with 15 points, 5 rebounds and 4
assists in 39 minutes. Horry began the Lakers' comeback early in
the second quarter with 8 points in 68 seconds, including two
3-pointers that quickly cut the Suns' lead to 30-26. Rick Fox also
came off the bench and scored all 6 of his points in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert carried us back in the ballgame singlehandedly,''
Bryant said. ``After that, it was like, OK, we know what happened
on the road in Sacramento, let's go and not let that happen again.
Just the experience of a sweep would be something for us. It would
show the rest of the league that we're learning to close teams
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway led the Suns with 31 points on 11-of-15 shooting. Cliff
Robinson added 23 and Rodney Rogers scored 15, but the Suns could
not match the Lakers at the free-throw line. The Lakers made 35 of
51 free throws while the Suns were 25 of 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're desperate right now, but it's not impossible,'' Hardaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said: ``It's a long weekend for them, waiting for that
Sunday game. That's the exciting part for us, the opportunity to
close them out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
