<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT     05-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S RESERVES STEP INTO THE VOID
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Alonzo Mourning was forced to the bench early in
the third quarter on Friday night after collecting 3 fouls in 23
seconds, Tim Hardaway tried to step into the void and provide the
Miami Heat with the spark they desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   But Hardaway, after trying and failing over the next two
minutes, walked slump-shouldered to the bench without a field goal,
and the Heat were falling further behind the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning and Hardaway had carried the Heat through the years of
this passionate rivalry, an inside-outside threat that seemed to
fade all the other players into the scenery. Now, they were both on
the bench and the Heat were trailing in Game 3, appearing ready to
fade out of the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   But then, a unit comprised of the undrafted rookie Anthony
Carter, the 37-year-old backup Otis Thorpe and Clarence
Weatherspoon, joined starters P.J. Brown and Jamal Mashburn and
began to chip away. Weatherspoon and Thorpe, both of whom had been
almost invisible in Game 2, drawing the ire of Heat Coach Pat
Riley, went to work inside.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon scored the next two baskets for the Heat, and then
Brown uncharacteristically started to shoot, scoring 6 of his 14
points in an 18-8 run that turned a 7-point deficit into a 3-point
Miami lead. Bruce Bowen would later join the unit, eventually
making the biggest defensive play of the game, deflecting an
inbound pass by Charlie Ward off Latrell Sprewell to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, Carter was doing the little things that a
rookie is not supposed to be able to do, carefully running the
offense and finishing the game with 10 points, 8 assists and just 1
turnover. That is, until he took over the hero's mantle with the
most unlikely of shots, a courageous drive along the baseline with
2.2 seconds remaining in overtime that the Knicks thought sailed
over the backboard as he was almost sitting in the first row,
giving Miami a 77-76 victory and a two-games-to-one lead in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the whole game plan, for the bench to step up and for
the other guys, like me, to step up,'' Carter said after the game.
``That's part of our job. That's what we get paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is unlikely that game-winning shots in the heat of the
league's most intense rivalry, with 19,763 fans screaming him down,
are in the league-minimum contract that Carter signed, it is
contributions like this from other sources that the Heat have been
searching for. And this resourcefulness is something that they may
need, with Hardaway wondering aloud after Game 3 whether he will be
available for Sunday's Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what team basketball is all about,'' Bowen said.
``Sometimes you're not going to have your guns. We don't have Tim,
but we can't just say: `Oh well, we don't have Tim, so we can't do
what we need to do. It's still up to us to make plays.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brown added about the Knicks' attitude when they faced this
unit: ``I knew they were going to exhale, think this is their
chance to get those guys. I think they did kind of relax and I just
kind of said: `Hey we're not going out like that. We're going to
fight. We're going to fight to the end.' I took a couple of shots
and it was feeling good. I think that was tremendous heart and
courage by our secondary guys to continue and keep the game going
and keep us in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Riley spoke about how he had stressed the
importance of his bench to the team, and joked about the
consequences if they did not step forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will hang them by their thumbs from the Freedom Tower on
Biscayne Boulevard,'' Riley deadpanned. ``So they know the
consequences are very dire if they don't perform a little bit
better. We need more out of Spoon and Otis and Bruce, and we have
to find the right balance of what starters are on the court with
them, what offense we are running to them. They're all capable.
They've been a very good bench for us. As a matter of fact, they
helped us win the first game. We need a little bit more out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley pounded on the Heat through practice on Wednesday and
Thursday. And though his words seemed like a joke, the players
obviously did not want to find out if it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great tonight, our bench,'' Riley said Friday night.
``Otis played hard. Spoon played hard. I thought Anthony Carter,
playing the last 22 minutes of the game, played the game of his
young life, and we got the win. So we are pleased with that, but
there is so much more work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hung in there. We played hard. We came up here to win and a
lot of people have been writing us off; we are not this, we are not
that, and our guys take that a little bit personal. It is a great
group.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
