u s BC-HKN-STEVENS-DEVILS-NY     05-13 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STEVENS-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS PIVOTAL IN SUCCESS OF NEW JERSEY DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Stevens is an 18-year veteran and Brian
Rafalski is a rookie, and they work well as a pair on the Devils'
defense. Their experience differential is not the only contrast
that makes them an odd couple of roommates during the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   On the night before a game, Rafalski prefers to relax by
watching television shows like ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
because, he said, ``I get sick of watching hockey games every
single night.''
</P>
<P>
   His roommate has different preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I have to say, `Scotty, we're just not going to
watch another game,''' Rafalski said. ``He'll come up and point at
the TV and say: `This guy should have done this! That guy should
have done that!' He gets into it and then he's all wound up and
then it's hard to get him to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens laughed when he heard this tale. ``He's right,'' Stevens
said. ``Brian is pretty calm and cool. I probably watch hockey a
little too much and get caught up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In deference to Rafalski, Stevens has been using the players'
recreation room at the hotel to watch only two periods.
``Otherwise,'' Stevens said, ``I'm too wound up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils hope both men rested well Saturday night _ despite
the telecast of the Colorado-Dallas game _ because New Jersey plays
at 3 p.m. on Sunday in Philadelphia in Game 1 of the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the 36-year-old captain, was the team's central figure
in the first two rounds, a four-game sweep of Florida and a
six-game ouster of Toronto. He keyed on stopping Pavel Bure of the
Panthers and the combination of Mats Sundin and Steve Thomas of the
Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Flyers, his assignment will be more diffuse because
Eric Lindros, a big center, is out with post-concussion symptoms,
and Keith Primeau, another big center, is doubtful because of a
concussion. But forwards like John LeClair and Mark Recchi are
dangerous in different ways. As a group, the Flyers are bigger and
more rugged than the Devils' previous two opponents.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 1 inch and a sturdy 215 pounds, Stevens has led the
Devils with clean, solid body checks, many of them in open ice.
Despite this, he has only 4 penalty minutes in 10 games because he
has turned down invitations to extend hostilities beyond the
whistles of officials, sometimes skating backward with a tight
smile above his goatee as rival players taunt and challenge him.
This is remarkable for a man who got 283 penalty minutes one season
in his younger days with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got maybe a bit of a temper, sometimes,'' said Scott
Niedermayer, another Devils defenseman. ``Right now, he's really
got that under control. It takes a lot of discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Restraint like this will be especially important against a
Philadelphia team that is among the National Hockey League's
roughest. Ken Daneyko, another hard-hitting Devils defenseman, said
Stevens is ``like a shark who smells blood'' and ``has been our
physical and emotional leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, Daneyko and Niedermayer were Devils in 1995, when the
team won its only Stanley Cup. In recent years, the Devils have
made early playoff exits after good regular seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this year is very important to him,'' Daneyko said of
Stevens, ``because it's been a tough few years and he has taken a
lot of it to heart and some of the heat. He's taken some flak about
leadership and about maybe the way he's played in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played well of late, and Scott Stevens deserves all the
credit in the world. He's been a real dominant force. We have
followed him. He has lifted us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has been a Devil since 1991 and the captain since 1992.
As a veteran with talent and free-agent leverage, he might have
made more money elsewhere, on a team with a higher profile. But he
chose to stay and work for Lou Lamoriello, a general manager known
for tight budgets and strict control of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Earning $4.152 million a season in the second year of a
four-year contract, Stevens might be getting less than he could.
Why did he choose to stay? ``I like the system, I like the team, I
like the travel,'' Stevens said. ``I've learned a lot playing here.
My kids are in school and doing very well. I'm very happy with
that, and that is important to me. I don't think it's worth moving
your children.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Donna, have three children under the age of 11.
John Hauser, Stevens agent, said, ``Money was important to Scott,
but he did not want to end up on a team and in a city where it was
unknown how his family would react to the town and the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauser also said that Stevens also knew that with the Devils he
would have a chance to compete for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello, rarely one to gush about those who work for him,
said Stevens was a valuable example to teammates. ``He eats right,
he sleeps right, he works hard,'' Lamoriello said. ``I don't think
you'll see Scott Stevens go to a fast-food restaurant often. He
takes care of himself. It's not by accident that he plays the way
he does and sustains it night in and night out. He is, without
question, one of the elite players in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he tried to stay away from sweets and other dubious
food. Stevens has played in more than 95 percent of the Devils'
games since joining the team. Referring to Lamoriello, Stevens
said: ``Lou likes hard-working people and gritty guys who come to
play. The blue-collar type of hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens may also have benefited from playing with Rafalski, who
is quick and nimble and experienced from four professional seasons
in Scandinavia and four before that at the University of Wisconsin.
``He knows if he steps up, I'll be back there,'' Rafalski said.
``It allows him to be more active at the blue line. He reads me
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not known as an offensive attacker, Stevens has two
goals and four assists for 6 points in the playoffs, tied for third
on the team. Larry Robinson, who replaced Robbie Ftorek as coach
with eight games left in the season, said Stevens and other Devils
became too attack-oriented during the regular season. Robinson has
refocused Stevens' attention ``on doing the things that you do
well,'' such as checking and positional defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, Scotty got us some big goals in the first
series and made some great offensive plays in the last series,''
Robinson said. ``He's playing very intelligently. He's really taken
the leadership role and gone with it. He has shown by example.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer said that Stevens ``is not the most vocal guy
around'' but that he will speak to teammates when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   No longer the wide-eyed kid who broke into the NHL with the
Capitals in 1982, Stevens speaks now as if he has his eyes on the
prize. Comparing the Devils of 2000 with the champions of 1995,
Stevens said: ``We're similar. We're a close bunch of guys. We're a
focused and disciplined hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens added: ``It's the final four. It is pretty prestigious
and very exciting. We've eliminated a lot of those past doubts and
failures. We've won two big rounds. We're playing great hockey.
We're going to try and grab the next round. The stakes get higher
and higher now.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
