<HEADLINE>
J. EDWARD CAROTHERS, 92, METHODIST LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Colo., Vt., Maine, Calif.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. J. Edward Carothers, a retired minister and former
chief executive of national ministries for the United Methodist
Church, died on May 1 at his retirement home in Doylestown, Pa.,
near Philadelphia. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Carothers, who took a keen interest in theology's relationship
to economics, science and technology, published seven books, among
them ``Keepers of the Poor,'' published by the church in 1966;
``Can Machines Replace Man?'' (Friendship, 1966); and ``To Love or
to Perish: Technological Crisis and the Churches'' (Friendship,
1972), of which he was co-editor with Margaret Mead, Roger L. Shinn
and Daniel D. McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   He held a number of positions with the National Council of
Churches from 1952 to 1964, including member of the general board
and secretary of the department of church and economic life. He was
the drafting editor of major documents that the council issued on
labor policy, among them one in 1965 that called for the repeal of
statutes that outlawed union shops.
</P>
<P>
   Carothers was chief executive of his denomination's national
missions from 1964 to 1972, when he retired to teach, write and
serve as an industrial consultant on family welfare. He lectured at
Drew University in Madison, N.J., and at the Iliff School of
Theology in Denver, where he had earned his postgraduate degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, until last September, he wrote monthly reviews of
books on Christian theology, in a bulletin distributed by the
church's board of global ministries.
</P>
<P>
   John Edward Carothers was born in Las Animas, Colo., about 60
miles east of Pueblo, and graduated in 1930 from Asbury College in
Wilmore, Ky., before earning his master's and his doctorate in
theology at Iliff. He was ordained a minister in 1932 and served
congregations in Colorado, Vermont and New York. Even after rising
to national prominence, he regarded himself as a pastor first.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as chief executive of the church's national missions, he
established the Methodist Urban Service Training program to prepare
clergy for the ministry in a changing urban climate. In 1970, he
was named executive director of a task force on the future of
humanity and the role of the churches, a project sponsored by the
National Council of Churches and Union Theological Seminary in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Carothers is survived by his wife of 70 years, Leta Hicks
Carothers; two daughters, Bettie Lee Thomas of Portland, Maine, and
Joan Marsan Murphine of Laguna Beach, Calif.; seven grandchildren,
and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
