<HEADER>
A4276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      05-13 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: LETTING SELLERS DO THE SELLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y., Pa.)   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, people who wanted to sell their homes had two
basic options: they could list their home with a broker _ and in
most cases pay a 6 percent commission _ or they could avoid a
commission by putting a ``For Sale by Owner'' sign on the front
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, with the Internet available to anyone with a
computer and a telephone line, the options have increased. Real
estate brokers say that homeowners can now fine-tune the marketing
of their house _ and determine the commission they will ultimately
pay _ by actively participating in the selling process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide sellers with the opportunity to market their homes
at a fair price and on their own terms,'' said Glenn Cohen,
president of YourHomeDirect.com, a real estate brokerage company
based in West Long Branch, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen says that his company offers sellers throughout New Jersey
various levels of service for commissions that range from 2 to 3.9
percent. He said that since his company's sales agents were both
licensed real estate agents and registered loan officers in New
Jersey, they could provide whatever level of service a seller and a
buyer needed.
</P>
<P>
   With YourHomeDirect's ``Seller's Choice Package,'' he said, a
company sales agents visits the seller's home to get an idea of the
size, location and condition. The agent then conducts an analysis
of sales of similar homes in the area to give the seller an idea of
the appropriate price range.
</P>
<P>
   Once the price is set and the property is listed with
YourHomeDirect, the company then advertises in major newspapers,
and lists home on its Internet site (www.yhd.com) and many of the
larger real estate Web sites and provides the seller with a yard
sign.
</P>
<P>
   The agent who visits the home will also photograph it to create
a virtual tour that can be viewed on the Web site. The listing and
the sign will usually have the company telephone number _ rather
than the owner's _ and a code number to allow prospective
purchasers who have seen the listing or the lawn sign to take the
virtual tour of the home on their computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prequalify all buyers,'' Cohen said, adding that once it
had been determined that the potential buyer was both serious and
qualified, the sales agent contacted the seller to arrange for the
house to be shown. ``Then it's up to the sellers to decide whether
they want us to show the house or whether they feel comfortable
showing it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Any offers that are made, Cohen said, go through the sales
agent, who then negotiates on behalf of the seller. If a deal is
struck, he said, the agent does all the things a full-service
broker would do, including preparing the necessary paperwork,
arranging financing if necessary and scheduling the usual
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   If a seller shows the house himself, Cohen said, YourHomeDirect
charges a 2 percent commission. If the seller prefers having an
agent escort buyers through the home, he said, the commission is 3
percent. And since YourHomeDirect is a licensed real estate broker,
it can also submit listings to the local Multiple Listing Service,
making it likely that local brokers will bring their potential
buyers to the property. The fee for the ``MLS Plan'' is 3.9
percent, Cohen said, adding that of that amount a 2.5 percent
commission is paid to the selling broker, and YourHomeDirect keeps
the rest as the listing broker.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added that while his company was now licensed only in New
Jersey, he expected to be licensed in New York and Pennsylvania by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that allows sellers to choose the services they
want from a real estate broker is Help-U-Sell, a nationwide
franchise company with East Coast headquarters on in Syosset, Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``My company is based upon the premise that sellers can save a
tremendous amount of money by simply doing some of the work of the
sale themselves,'' said Rick O'Neil, president of Help-U-Sell. The
company's Web site is www.helpusell.com.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil said that the commission charged by Help-U-Sell
franchisees _ a flat fee agreed on in advance between the company
and the seller _ usually ends up being anywhere from 2.1 percent to
2.8 percent of the sale price. For that, he said, sellers get their
house listed on the company's Web site, a yard sign, and whatever
hand-holding they need once an interested buyer shows up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically do everything a full-service broker would do,''
O'Neil said, ``except show the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet-based company that caters to sellers who would
rather not pay a full 6 percent commission is the Realty Exchange
Network in Ossining, N.Y. ``What we're doing is creating a portal
that will provide instant access to discount real estate brokers
across the country,'' said James Troia, president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Troia said the company recently entered into agreements with 23
large discount brokerage companies in which the companies
automatically posted all their listings on the Realty Exchange
Network's Web site, www.REXnetwork.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely the wave of the future,'' Troia said.
</P>
<P>
   One place that wave is unlikely to hit with any real force,
however, is Manhattan. Frederick Peters, president of Ashforth
Warburg, a Manhattan full-service brokerage, said that while
discount brokers who have access to a local Multiple Listing
Service might be attractive to some sellers, they would most likely
have little success in Manhattan's co-op and condominium market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process that brokers have to go through here is much more
complicated than it is in the suburbs,'' Peters said. ``You really
do need an experienced broker who is able to screen buyers not only
for sellers and lenders, but for co-op boards as well.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that it was unlikely that a discount broker who did
not have an intimate understanding of the co-op and condominium
market would be able to provide the level of service needed to
usher such deals through to completion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, even sellers of luxury homes outside Manhattan
have grown used to having their brokers provide them with copious
amounts of personal service and attention. And it is unlikely,
Peters said, that such sellers would be willing to compromise on
the level of service they are accustomed to in exchange for paying
a lower commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of people who can drive a car who don't mind
paying to have a driver,'' he said. ``It's really a question of how
you can best use your time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
