<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The raging Social Security debate
between Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the
clearest contrast yet in their philosophy of individual versus
shared responsibility for the future. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday in both (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CHECKS _ WASHINGTON _ Most states have a higher rate of
rejecting ineligible persons from buying guns than the FBI,
according to state and federal statistics. (Schultz).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Stories MOVED Wednesday for Florida, Georgia and Colorado,
the three Cox states that have their own programs for checking gun
buyers. A general story MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ERGONOMICS _ WASHINGTON _ Businesses large and small _ and their
allies in Congress _ are up in arms over ``ergonomics'' standards
proposed last fall by the Occupational Health and Safety
Administration. OSHA says 27 million workers would be affected by
the new rules involving repetitive motions, awkward reaching or
heavy lifting. OSHA said the rules would cost businesses about $4.2
billion a year to implement, while saving $ 9 billion annually
through increased productivity and lower absenteeism. Industry
groups responded that the cost would be much higher. (Malone, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday in both (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE _ WASHINGTON _ Astronomers have for several years
believed that most of the matter in the universe is ``dark
matter,'' which we can't see or perceive in any way other than in
the gravitational pull it exerts on ordinary matter. Now, to
explain the strange way distant galaxies appear to be racing away
from us at ever greater speeds, they have come up with the concept
of ``dark energy,'' something that seems to be acting in defiance
of the usual laws of gravity. Without it, these faraway objects
should be gradually slowing down from the momentum of the ``Big
Bang.'' Instead, they are flying away at speeds that now approach
the speed of light. Dark energy may be a kind of reverse gravity,
cosmologists think. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH LOGO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Third in the occasional ``Windows on the Universe'' series.
MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON _ KIBBUTZ MENARA, Israel _ When the loud thuds
started sounding every couple of minutes, residents here calmly
made their guesses. Katyusha rockets from Lebanon? Israeli
artillery toward Lebanon? Both were wrong. They were land mines,
blown up under the tread of an armored Israeli bulldozer that was
making room for a new border post a few hundred yards away. Israel
plans to pull out of southern Lebanon soon, and the road work is
under way. They're clearing mines, building new roads and, near one
Arab village, taking land for a new post. Residents founded these
farms to stake out the border in the 1940s. Now, they will lose
their buffer of Israeli-occupied land. They will be on the edge
again and wonder if it will be safe to go out at night, to use
their roads and whether they will be on the frontline of a lasting
peace or continuing war. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With map information in database, and map faxed to Cox
newspapers to build locator map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   US-CHINA _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton calls it ``a
hundred-to-one win'' for the U.S. economy. Chinese economists
already worry that it could result in massive unemployment across
the world's most populous country. Viewed from either side, the
stakes are enormous for Permanent Normal Trading Status, linked
with World Trade Organization admission, for China. The White House
expects victory when the issue comes up for a vote in Congress the
last week of this month. What would a ``yes'' vote mean for
American workers and consumers? (Deans, Cox News Service). With
chart information on U.S.-China trade growth over the past decade.
How the White House thinks selected U.S. exports might be expected
to grow if the bill is approved.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday in both (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories. The chart information is available in the database.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INTERNET _ BEIJING _ Take the frenzy of Silicon Valley and
square it, and you'll come close to capturing Internet fever in
China. Competition to become the Yahoo of China _ not to mention
the Amazon of China and the eBay of China _ is fierce. Foreign
investors, many of them American, have poured a big chunk of money
into Chinese startups. Also wanting a piece of the action is the
Chinese government, which has backed its own Internet companies but
is also looking for a way to maintain control over this
free-wheeling thing known as the Web. We look at the state of the
Internet industry and predictions for growth _ and failures. (Chao,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday in both (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ZIMBABWE _ LONDON _ Britain finds itself in a complex
political situation in dealing with its former colony Zimbabwe.
With 20,000 British nationals in the country and deep sentiments in
Britain favoring the country's besieged whites, the country is
taking a hawkish stance toward the former Rhodesia and is even said
to be making military plans in case it must intervene on a
protection mission. Meanwhile, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
has taken to painting British leaders as would be neo-colonialists
looking for an excuse to again dominate the country. (Roughton, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in both (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAGFLAP _ South Carolina now has a plan to take down the
Confederate flag by July 1. What was the role of South Carolina
Gov. Jim Hodges? And what lessons might Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes
have learned and how might he help manage the debate here? Story
also will weave in what Mississippi Gov. Musgrove is doing _ he has
appointed a commission on the issue. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-POLITICS _ Most people expect the Vs. the Flag coalition
to march into Georgia as soon as their work is completed in South
Carolina. The object will be to force Georgians to remove the
Confederate flag from the State of Georgia flag, and the group will
try to accomplish that with sports boycotts, etc. The Sports vs.
Politics battle has existed throughout Olympic history, and it has
always been a volatile mix. From the 1936 Berlin Olympics to the
raised black-gloved fists in 1968 in Mexico City to the Jimmy
Carter-led boycott of the Olympics in 1980. But states also have
fought their battles _ Arizona had to adopt a Martin Luther King
day to keep the Super Bowl. Officials with the NCAA and NFL kept
close tabs on Louisiana, when David Duke was on the ballot for the
statehouse. And writers left the pressbox in the Georgia Dome
during the 1994 Super Bowl to protest the Georgia flag. We provide
the history lesson. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General news and (s) Sports categories. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-LAWYERS _ ATLANTA _ Ray Lewis is a criminal defense
lawyer's dream come true. Flush with a $23 million contract and a
$7 million signing bonus, he surely has paid out an extravagant
legal fee. His case provides a national platform of publicity for
his lawyers and, better, his is a case they can win. Ed Garland and
Don Samuel, Lewis' lead lawyers, are a ying and yang partnership.
Both have their own strengths. A look the ``dream team'' of sorts
of lawyers in the case. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
WITH PHOTOS of all lawyers in the case: Ed Garland and Don Samuel
(Lewis), Steve Sadow and John Bergendahl (Sweeting) and Bruce
Harvey and David Wolfe (Oakley)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Trial starts Monday, May 15.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-PATHWAYS _ DUBLIN, Calif. _ ``If I wouldn't have came(cq) to
prison, I'd be be dead right now,'' said Eshelle Scott. At a
therapy session, part of a ground-breaking program aimed at helping
female inmates, Scott said she was trapped in an abusive
relationship with a man who introduced her to witchcraft and beat
her nearly every day. Depressed, she found comfort in drugs and
killing animals. Angry about a beating, she said, she once
decapitated her boyfriend's mother's cat and left it on the woman's
doorstep. Finally, she was convicted of burning churches and
sentenced to a 63-month term. At the Federal Correctional
Institution here, Scott participated in the inaugural class of New
Pathways, a pilot program aimed at addressing the special needs of
female inmates who have been physically or sexually abused. (Turay,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week. The layout is
available now. Art will include two color photos and one color
illustration
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0513: THE NEW URBANISM -- One of the key buzzwords
of the 2000 political season is sprawl. Newspapers, magazines and
television are increasingly featuring stories about growth and
development and how they affect our lives. Smart-growth advocates
advocates do not want to force you out of your subdivision and into
a high-rise apartment building. What they are trying to do is to
answer some of the toughest questions facing modern metropolitan
areas. How can cities and suburbs grow in population while avoiding
the potentially devastating environmental and other consequences of
asphalt-heavy sprawl or of poorly planned density? (Goldberg,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 3-column color arial
photo of a high-density community, a 2-column photo of a woman
walking to the store and a 2-column information graphic
illustrating how sprawl affects traffic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRUTHS OF GROWTH BOX _ A list of five truths about urban
growth, as expressed by the authors of ``Suburban Nation: The Rise
of Sprawl and the Decline of the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The raging Social Security debate
between Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the
clearest contrast yet in their philosophy of individual versus
shared responsibility for the future. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSITION _ For incoming administrations, transitions entail
massive planning on a scale that dwarfs even the successive
nationwide campaign that brought the winning candidate to victory.
Few presidents have entered office fully aware of what was about to
befall them, though the first steps are often crucial in
determining whether how a new president will perform. A look at
what the next president-elect, be it Bush or Gore, can do to
provide for a successful transition and a productive presidency.
(By Alvin Felzenberg of the Heritage Foundation/Special to the
Austin American-Statesman). (With mug of Felzenberg).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: For use by Cox papers and NYTNS clients. (mug available in
American-Statesman's database)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
