<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-INTERNET-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: COMBINING A DATA CENTER WITH A `TELCO' HOTEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEONIA, N.J. _ A deceptively bland-looking building in this
Bergen County suburb about 35 minutes from New York could become
one of the engine rooms of the Internet if the plans of its
operators are realized.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most visible part of the Internet is the
fast-growing companies with clever names and oscillating stock
prices. And perhaps the least visible can be found behind locked
and well-guarded doors.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world of the electronics boxes and powerful
computers, known as ``big iron,'' that house the information
available on the Net and provide two-way access to it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Infocrossing Inc. say they are combining operations
of traditional data centers, which house and service computers for
client companies, with the telecommunications hotels that have
sprung up because competing companies find it convenient to be
physically near one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the Internet sits,'' Joseph Germanotta, the
president of Infocrossing, said during a recent open house in
Leonia, just across the George Washington Bridge from New York.
``Here is where the servers, the routers and the switches are.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the interior of the building, much of it still vacant,
has wire cages filled with electronic equipment, and a control room
to monitor operations and fix problems as they arise. The Internet
data center occupies 15,000 of the 30,000 square feet the company
has leased in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Like the so-called ``telco hotels'' that have developed in New
York, notably at 111 Eighth Ave. and 75 Broad St., Infocrossing
offers clients multiple choices of carriers and elaborate
assurances that operations will be sustained on a 24-hour-a-day,
seven-day-a-week basis.
</P>
<P>
   Data centers are similar to telecommunications companies from a
real estate standpoint, said Paul Pariser, one of the principals in
Taconic Partners, the owner of 111 Eighth Ave.
</P>
<P>
   They require raised floors capable of bearing heavy loads and
lots of electrical power and cooling capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But he said some tired old industrial buildings, particularly in
other cities, are being marketed as telecommunications headquarters
despite their limitations. ``You see derelict buildings in
neglected areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William G. Cohen, an executive vice president of Newmark &AMP;
Company Real Estate, who is marketing 75 Broad St., said the
building is nearly full, largely with telecommunications companies.
He said some of the companies there are adding data-center
operations to their telecommunications businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Leonia building is equipped with auxiliary generators and
batteries to keep equipment running in case of a power failure or
brownout.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a ``meet me'' room in the building where customers
can connect to a number of carriers, including Bell Atlantic, MCI
Worldcom, Level 3, Teligent and Winstar.
</P>
<P>
   Having multiple carriers, with high-capacity fiber lines on
premises, means that carriers will have to compete with one another
for the business of the dot-coms and other Internet companies that
have their equipment in individual cages in the building, said John
Stewart, Infocrossing's senior vice president for real estate.
</P>
<P>
   And having the multiple carriers allows the company to build
redundancy into the communications system, which is an important
feature for companies that are literally out of business if
communications equipment fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a Bell Atlantic line is cut, we can transfer them to Level
3 to minimize the time of outage,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Germanotta said, ``We have multiple on-ramps to the
information superhighway.''
</P>
<P>
   Having the extensive telecommunications connections in the
building means that a tenant company can increase its capacity
quickly if its business takes off. ``We can provide the equivalent
of one telephone line to thousands of telephones lines,'' Stewart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zack Lonstein, the chairman of Infocrossing, which was formerly
named Computer Outsourcing Services Inc., said the company plans to
build a network of 20 Internet data centers like the one here to
participate in the growth of online businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is publicly traded on Nasdaq, recently
received an investment of $60 million from an affiliate of Deutsche
Bank and from Sandler Capital Management, which specializes in
communications investments, to build the network of centers.
</P>
<P>
   The service the company offers is to take over what amounts to
Internet companies' technological back offices and to keep the
systems up and running, allowing the clients to concentrate on
building their businesses. Infocrossing gets paid for the use of
its space and services, but Infocrossing and concerns like it
contend that grouping the equipment of many companies in one place
and sharing services lower costs for the individual Internet
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It cites a study by Sun Trust Equitable Securities Research,
which found that a simple Web site would cost $42,500 to set up and
$12,400 a month to operate if an Internet company did it alone.
</P>
<P>
   But since a service center already has battery backup, fire
walls to protect data from outside intrusion and technical support
in place, the study said that using a service center would spread
start-up costs across many clients and would reduce the monthly
costs to $2,000 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to telecommunications capacity and technical
competence, there is a lot of emphasis at Infocrossing's building
on physical security. Guards are stationed at the entrances around
the clock and they escort visitors to their destinations. The
windows are even covered by metal-mesh screens.
</P>
<P>
   Security is important, particularly for companies that handle
sensitive personal financial information, said Mark Zona, the chief
technical officer for Market Technologies Corp. of Wilton, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Market Technologies, which handles credit screenings on
individuals for insurance companies and other financial
institutions, has six very large computers known as servers at
Infocrossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to be able to pass an audit by credit bureaus,'' Zona
said. ``Our business hinged on passing that audit, because
otherwise they would not give us data.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the biggest concern for people in his line of work is
the potential for identity theft: The thief learns enough about
somebody else to pose as that person and run up debts under the
assumed name.
</P>
<P>
   Physical security is important, of course. ``Data is data,'' he
said. ``If someone could pick up the tapes from a drive, they could
take thousands of identities.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic security is also important. Zona said that executives
at Infocrossing arranged for a secure telecommunications link
between the machines in New Jersey and Market Technologies' home
office in Connecticut to keep anyone else from gaining access to
the company's data.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, Infocrossing's vice president for real estate, said the
company decided to open its first Internet center in Leonia because
it was the corporate headquarters, even though Leonia is not close
to the main fiber corridors in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an `out of the box' location,'' he said. ``We had to
make a commitment to the fiber providers to bring fiber to this
site.'' He said it cost the telecommunications companies $250 to
$300 a foot to install high-capacity fiber lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other cities we are going to look for buildings that are
located along fiber routes,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
