<SLUG> BC-FBN-ASSISTANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL AND ASSISTANT COACHES AT ODDS
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service      
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NFL could soon face one of its most difficult challenges, as
an association made up of dozens of head coaches and hundreds of
assistants is preparing to file a lawsuit against the league early
next month seeking improved working conditions and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   While there remains a solid chance the situation could soon be
settled without court action, several owners and members of the
association believe a legal battle may be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, assistant coaches have been fighting for
better benefits packages and an earlier retirement age. And while
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue has been open-minded about the demands
of the assistant coaches, ownership has been reluctant, and the
slow pace of negotiations for an agreement has irked the assistant
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, members of the NFL Coaches Association, which
represents 18 head coaches and more than 400 assistant coaches,
said they recently informed the league that unless an agreement is
reached by the beginning of next month, the association would file
a lawsuit seeking improved retirement and benefit packages. The
suit might also allege age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL maintains that it knows nothing of a possible lawsuit
and is hopeful an agreement can be reached with the association.
The issue will be revisited at the owners' meetings later this
month in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches suing owners _ their employers _ would lead to a rather
uncomfortable if not bitter situation. Action on the field would be
unaffected, but it would be impossible for the chemistry among
ownership, management and coaches not to be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the coaches association say they have been all but
forced to consider taking legal action, because ownership has
reacted slowly to their concerns. It is true, however, that the NFL
and the association have had amicable discussions, and the league
respects Larry Kennan, the association's executive director. And,
in fact, some progress has been made on several of the more minor
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But on the larger differences there remains a considerable gap.
The association began as a way to address the concerns of assistant
coaches, a group that does not have the same financial certainties
as head coaches, who make more money and have long-term, guaranteed
contracts. Kennan, a former longtime assistant coach who used to be
the offensive coordinator for the New England Patriots, was the
catalyst who turned the organization from a squabbling group into a
powerful, unified force.
</P>
<P>
   The association says that assistants are fired, on average,
every one to three years, and fewer than 7 percent of the coaches
in the league are age 60 or older. Since benefits begin at 65, most
never see their full retirement package. The association wants a
system in which a coach can collect benefits when his age and years
of service add up to 75.
</P>
<P>
   The association also wants to establish health insurance for
retired coaches and working contracts to run through March, as
opposed to February, when they usually expire. Why? The association
says that when assistant coaches are fired, it usually occurs in
mid-January, immediately following the season, and most contracts
end in February, so the fired assistants basically get a two-week
paycheck. That money must last until another job opens up, which
could be months away. The association wants its members to have a
larger cushion.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are also asking that independent arbitrators, as
opposed to the league, settle contract disputes. They also want a
$250,000 life insurance policy to carry over into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the association maintain that making the changes
they want would cost around $250,000 a team, about the same price
to sign a low-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coaches are certainly not crying that they are
destitute. They know they make good money, even if their salaries
have not risen in proportion to the athletes they coach. In 1982,
the average player earned $150,000 a year, while the average coach
made $50,000, a 3-to-1 ratio. Now the average player earns about a
million dollars a season, to the $130,000 a year for the average
coach, which is an 8-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks Peyton Manning and Drew Bledsoe recently filmed an
instructional football video, the proceeds of which would help
former assistants facing financial difficulty and not eligible for
pension and medical benefits. It seems remarkable in this age of
skyrocketing franchise values and $10 million players that former
coaches would need assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem for owners, several said last week, was that if
they give the assistant coaches what they wanted, then the trainers
might be next in line, or the office secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   But few in football _ not even the players _ put the sort of
hours into the job that assistant coaches do. Their work ethic
places them in a special class. Most owners realize and appreciate
this fact. The association hopes that the few owners who do not,
soon will.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
