<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE BEST OF THE '90s; HOW MUCH FOR FISHER?; MONITORING FREE
AGENCYBy MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame Board of Selectors has been asked by the NFL to
pick the team of the 1990s. So far, about one-third of the votes
are in and there are only a handful of unanimous choices. They are:
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver, Cris Carter and Jerry Rice; guard, Bruce
Matthews; running back, Barry Sanders; defensive end, Bruce Smith
and Reggie White; defensive tackle, John Randle; linebacker, Junior
Seau; cornerback, Deion Sanders; and safety, LeRoy Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Other voting leaders by position include quarterback Brett
Favre, tight end Shannon Sharpe, offensive tackle Gary Zimmerman,
center Dermontti Dawson, kickers Morten Andersen and Gary Anderson,
punt returner Deion Sanders and kick returner Michael Bates.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching leaders are Marv Levy, Bill Parcells and Mike
Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   How Much for Fisher?
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest blunders of the off-season is happening in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fisher, one of the game's brightest head coaches, has a
year left on a contract that will pay him $1 million a season. That
is a lot of money, but by NFL standards, for the coach of the
defending AFC champions, it is the equivalent of earning minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had been in negotiations with the Titans' owner, Bud
Adams, looking for a new contract that would pay him about $2
million to $2.5 million a year, a fair amount, but those talks
recently broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher wants a new deal from Adams before the coach leaves for
vacation in June, or he will not talk contract until after this
season. Waiting that long would be a disaster for the Titans, who
would have to sign him for even more as a free agent or risk losing
him.
</P>
<P>
   There is one man who is probably watching the situation closely,
and hoping Tennessee blows it with Fisher. His name is Charley
Casserly, general manager of the Houston franchise, which does not
play until 2002. Casserly would love to swoop in and steal Fisher
from the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are the Titans will work something out with Fisher
before his deadline. If not, and if Fisher does end up leaving, it
will be Tennessee's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring Free Agency
</P>
<P>
   While, in some instances, free agency may be hurting some teams
in the game _ see Keyshawn Johnson leaving the Jets for Tampa Bay _
it may not be hurting the sport as much as many think. Free agency
started on March 2, and so far 105 unrestricted and restricted
players have changed teams, which is only about three players a
team. ... Denver continues to monitor the Steve Young situation in
San Francisco. If the 49ers release him, the Broncos will very
likely try to gobble him up. Meanwhile, running back Terrell Davis
has looked great in spring workouts as he attempts his comeback
from reconstructive knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0212 </DOCNO>
