<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-LOOP-REAL-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PUTTING `THAT GREAT STREET' BACK INTO STATE STREET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Mich., N.Y.)  By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After 20 years of on-again off-again urban renewal
efforts, State Street, which was for generations Chicago's premier
retail area, appears ready to reclaim its heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the JMB Realty Corp. unveiled plans for a new $251
million mixed-use project on a square block across from Marshall
Field's, the department store. The project will include a
five-story retail mall anchored by a Lord &AMP; Taylor department
store, a 34-story tower containing condominiums and a Marriott
Suites Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which is to break ground by the end of the year and
is expected to be finished in stages starting in 2002, is the
climax of what has already been an extraordinary year on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Directly across Randolph Street from JMB Realty's project, a new
theater and dormitory complex for the School of the Art Institute
is nearing completion. It includes a 17-story tower as well as a
renovated former office building that will have 34,000 square feet
of retail space.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks to the south, Sears, Roebuck and Co., which has
been absent from State Street for 17 years, is preparing to open a
large new store on the first five floors of a recently renovated
office building.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a number of national chains and local retailers _
including Kinko's, Radio Shack, Potbelly Sandwich Works and Nuts on
Clark, a candy and nut shop _ have recently signed leases in other
buildings on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at State in four years,'' said Tyrone Tabing, an
assistant planning commissioner and the point man for the
redevelopment of the street, ``it will be a dramatically different
street than it is today. And it's dramatically different now than
it was four years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be an understatement. In the early '90s, State Street
``was being kept alive on a ventilator,'' said Bruce Kaplan, the
president of the Northern Realty Group Ltd., a large real estate
company in the Loop. ``It was in horrendous condition,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After a century-long run as the most prominent retail district
in Chicago, if not the Midwest, State Street went into a decline in
the '70s and '80s. That decline was brought on by the rise of
suburban shopping and the simultaneous development of nearby North
Michigan Avenue as the new retailer to the carriage trade.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing significantly to State Street's decline was the
urban renewal project in 1979 that closed the street to vehicles
and turned it into an enormous _ and usually deserted _ pedestrian
mall.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '80s, State Street, which had boasted seven major
department stores a decade earlier, was down to two: Marshall
Field's and Carson Pirie Scott. What little specialty retailing
that remained was increasingly of the fast-food and adult-bookstore
variety.
</P>
<P>
   There matters stood until the early '90s, when two things
happened. The first was a housing boom, which resulted in some
12,000 new apartments in and around the Loop. The second was the
city's willingness to jump-start the redevelopment process on State
Street. It approved $44 million in incentive grants to 10
developers, and in 1996, a $25 million streetscape improvement
project that reopened State Street to auto traffic, spruced it up
with numerous planters and added lampposts and subway entrances
with a turn-of-the-century look.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been striking. Statistics complied by the
Northern Realty Group show that annual rents for retail space on
State Street have doubled in the last five years, to $52 a square
foot, while the vacancy rate is just under 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The street now has 2.5 million square feet of retail space; 1.6
million of that is accounted for by Marshall Field's and Carson
Pirie Scott. In addition, another 750,000 square feet is under
construction or on the drawing boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail is driving the street, and it's driving it harder every
week,'' said J. Paul Beitler, the chairman of Douglas
Elliman-Beitler, the developer of the Sears project. Beitler is
also the developer, along with the Prime Group, of Dearborn Center,
a new 1.8 million-square-foot, 37-story office building under way
at the corner of State and Adams Streets, which will have 100,000
square feet of retail space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loop is becoming a 24/7 living environment, and people
need somewhere to shop,'' Beitler said. ``State has become a
community center. The whole emphasis is on providing the kinds of
goods and services that you find in the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sears project is often mentioned by developers and real
estate brokers as an example of what State Street will be like in
the future. Sears opened its first store on State Street in 1932,
at the corner of State and Van Buren Streets. The building still
exists, but it is now occupied by Robert Morris College, a business
school. The new Sears store, scheduled to open next spring, is four
blocks farther north, at the corner of State and Madison Streets
and diagonally across State Street from Carson Pirie Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think State Street customers tend to be a little more
mainstream and mass America than those on Michigan Avenue,'' said
Milton Mooney, the senior vice president for Sears stores in the
north-central region. ``We're going to merchandise the space in a
way that will play to the strengths of that market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The store, which is costing about $30 million, will have 250,000
square feet of space, about twice as much as an average new Sears
store, Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   The just-announced Lord &AMP; Taylor project is also being described
as one that will harmonize with the newly residential character of
the Loop. The project brings to a close a troubled chapter in the
street's redevelopment. JMB has owned the site for over a decade,
and it has been vacant _ except for a Commonwealth Edison
substation and an ice-skating rink in the winter months _ for
nearly that long.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bluhm, the chairman of JMB, said that the collapse of the
real estate market in the early '90s led to the cancellation of an
office project planned for the site. Several other projects also
came and went. ``Then the city decided it wanted more retail to
energize State, so our project changed to reflect that,'' Bluhm
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new project, which is being designed by Kohn Pedersen Fox
Associates, the New York architectural firm, has a distinctly
modern look, a departure on a street where most of the buildings
date from the 1920s and earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The new building nearing completion as part of the School of the
Art Institute project across Randolph Street is an echo of the
architect Daniel Burnham's historic Reliance Building, now called
the Hotel Burnham, a block south at the corner of State and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute's architect, Larry Booth of Booth Hansen &AMP;
Associates in Chicago, said he very much had turn-of-the-century
Chicago architecture in mind when he designed the project. ``I feel
like Louis Sullivan and Daniel Burnham and John Root are old pals
of mine,'' Booth said, ``and this was my chance to join the
party.''
</P>
<P>
   The project, which is costing about $55 million, will have
34,000 square feet of retail space, 300 dormitory rooms, two movie
theaters for the Art Institute's Film Center and a legitimate
theater that has been leased to the Noble Fool comedy troupe.
</P>
<P>
   The retail anchor for the project will be Borders Books, which
will open a 30,000-square-foot store on three levels next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted to be on State, based on what's been going on
there for the last few years,'' said Alex Lelli, the vice president
for development of the Borders Group Inc. in Ann Arbor, Mich.
``There's a lot of activity both during the day and at night and on
the weekends. It's a very attractive street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
