<HEADLINE>
LENDING CRACKDOWN SAID TO FALL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ga.)   By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When government regulators announced recently that
they were protecting homeowners by cracking down on an abusive
nationwide lending company, Margaret C. Roundtree hoped they would
intervene to save her home in Queens from foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did expect to get some help,'' said Roundtree, 68, a
hospital technician. ``But nothing has been done.'' So now she
faces the loss of the house where she has lived since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Three federal agencies settled their joint lawsuit against her
lender, Delta Financial Corp. of Woodbury, on March 30. They
portrayed their decision as an industrywide warning to the booming
but loosely regulated market in high-cost loans.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for victims like Roundtree say the officials let
Delta off the hook. The critics also say the federal settlement
gave no help to the thousands of suffering borrowers, many of whom
have been forced into foreclosure or bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   And consumer groups are also attacking Delta's earlier
settlement with two New York state regulatory agencies. While the
state did extract some restitution for victims, critics say the
amount is merely a token, considering Delta's $1 billion-a-year
operation. Only a fraction of the victims will be aided, and
nothing will go to those who must lose their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta operates in 26 states, and in New York it grew to become
the largest subprime lender, a type that makes high-cost loans to
people with limited credit ratings. But critics called Delta a
predatory lender that focused on minority neighborhoods. Its
victims, often elderly women, were targets of high-pressure pitches
for loans with exorbitant fees and interest that they could not
afford.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the complaints, regulators accused the company of
violating various lending and civil rights laws. But the
settlements of those charges have frustrated Delta's critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta admits no wrongdoing and agrees to comply with the law _
which it's supposed to do anyway _ while many victims are stuck
with horrendous loans for years to come, and people who already
lost their homes and their life savings are completely left out,''
said Sarah Ludwig, director of the Neighborhood Economic
Development Advocacy Project, a nonprofit group in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Alan M. White, the supervising attorney of Community Legal
Services in Philadelphia, said, ``These settlements send exactly
the wrong message to the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state officials defend their decisions, saying they
imposed heavy sanctions and stopped the abuses now, avoiding years
of litigation and possibly keeping thousands more from being
victimized. The restitution is the most ever won in the U.S.
banking industry, the regulators say. Delta also agreed to
restrictions beyond statutory requirements and is subject to civil
and criminal penalties for new violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many companies where five agencies come down on
them and get this kind of redress,'' said David Medine, an
associate director at the Federal Trade Commission, one of the
agencies. ``This is not just a slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Another agency, the Department of Justice, said, ``This suit
sends a clear message that the United States won't tolerate
discrimination or illegal lending practices.'' The Department of
Housing and Urban Development declined to reply to the critics. But
earlier, Secretary Andrew Cuomo praised the settlement, saying,
``Lenders and mortgage brokers are put on notice by this settlement
agreement that HUD and the federal government are prepared to fight
for borrowers who are being victimized.''
</P>
<P>
   The first official to go after Delta was the state attorney
general, Eliot Spitzer. At first he tried to place Delta in
receivership because ``we cannot trust them to abide by any
agreements,'' but eventually his office settled. His civil rights
chief, Andrew Celli, said: ``We started with one goal, to change
the way the largest subprime lender in the state does business, and
we met that goal. We made a conscious choice to reform this
industry going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   His deputy, Mark Peters, added: ``Delta is now bound by a
265-page code of conduct, requiring a whole bunch of things the law
doesn't require.'' For example, refinancing fees are limited,
credit-card debt consolidation is allowed only if the borrower
benefits, and a borrower must have enough income to cover
repayments with money left for essentials like food and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer pushed for $6 million in restitution, which the Banking
Department raised to $7.25 million, plus 525,000 shares of Delta
stock it valued at nearly $5 million. ``The governor instructed us
to obtain the maximum amount of restitution to the victims,'' said
the acting bank superintendent, Elizabeth McCaul. ``We took the
most from the company we possibly could,'' achieving ``by far the
largest consumer restitution'' ever in banking.
</P>
<P>
   Under that settlement, 600 Delta borrowers were recently offered
reductions in their monthly payments of $50 to $400, or 5 percent
to 40 percent, McCaul said. In addition, foreclosures were halted
for 75 homeowners, who will also be offered reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Delta issued this statement: ``While Delta does not believe it
has done anything wrong, it has acceded to these agreements in the
best interests of our shareholders, customers and the communities
we serve. Delta is committed to maintaining the best fair-lending
practices in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the restitution pales in contrast to the victims' losses and
Delta's billions of dollars in loans, critics say. The
reduced-payment benefits end when borrowers die, sell their homes,
refinance or are foreclosed. And the value of the Delta stock has
shrunk to barely $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny money, all flash and no cash,'' said Patricia
Sturdevant, director of the National Association of Consumer
Advocates, a nonprofit group. ``This case sets a dangerous
precedent for going soft on lenders who are cheating people out of
house and home. The message is that crime pays.'' Since the federal
agencies won no restitution, she said, there is no aid for victims
outside New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The regulators should have gotten $30,000 to $40,000 per victim,
said William Brennan Jr., a lawyer for the Atlanta Legal Aid
Society who specializes in lending abuse cases and is familiar with
lawsuits against Delta. ``These settlements end up being window
dressing to make it look like the regulators are doing their job,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the settlements were court-approved, there is no
apparent recourse to challenge them. Despite their long efforts
against predatory lending, consumer groups say they were not
consulted on the actions. The federal agencies filed their suits
against Delta and _ simultaneously that same day _ announced their
settlements with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Most disturbing, the critics say, is a state requirement that
victims who accept restitution must promise not to seek any other
legal redress. They cannot sue Delta, and if they eventually face
foreclosure, they will not be allowed to raise a defense in court
that their loans were improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's terrible, terrible,'' said Lee Squitieri, a Manhattan
lawyer who is organizing a class-action suit for Delta borrowers.
He is seeking to release them from bad loans, get compensation for
excessive charges and impose punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the restitution offers that the critics have heard
about are for $50 a month. ``It's not nearly enough,'' said Nancy
Slahetka, a lawyer who fights foreclosures for South Brooklyn Legal
Services. Those offers are not only paltry, she said, they are also
too few. ``There are thousands of victims, not hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   Each case has its own details. Roundtree said she fell behind on
her bills when she was out of work because of two car accidents and
her resulting hip surgery. Her lawyer, Jeffrey Rosenberg, said she
was talked into a loan of $92,000, ``far more than she needed,'' to
pay her debts, plus $20,800 for a home-improvement contractor, with
cash supposedly left over for her. The interest rate was 12.15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Roundtree said she reluctantly signed blank papers when sales
people threatened that ``they were going to take my house away.''
Soon after, she said, she tried to invoke her right to cancel but
was ignored. She never got the final papers, she said, and most of
the promised renovations were never done.
</P>
<P>
   Although technically Delta did not originate the loan, the
company was involved at the outset and took over the loan at the
closing, the lawyer said. Inevitably, the payments fell into
arrears, and now Delta is demanding $137,000 or the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
