<HEADLINE>
AFTER FUROR OVER BOOK, A WELCOME EPILOGUE  
 NEW STRATEGY IN GAME OF DUCK, DUCK, GOOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The obvious question: In her cheerful new life as a
teacher at a Queens County school with students from 40 cultures,
does Ruth Sherman, known for teaching a book called ``Nappy Hair''
to a class in Brooklyn, still use the book? Do her new students
learn about the little girl with ``the nappiest, the fuzziest, the
most screwed up, squeezed up, knotted up'' hair in the world?
</P>
<P>
   Or did the threats from parents that caused the white teacher to
change schools keep her from teaching what she had hoped would be a
diversity-affirming book?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Sherman, 29, does not teach the book by Carolivia Herron
that caused such controversy in 1998. Not yet, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not because I have anything against it,'' she said,
adding that the book is still in her library. ``I haven't gotten a
chance to do a unit like that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents at Public School 75 in Brooklyn objected to her use
of the book and, calling her a racist, threatened her.
</P>
<P>
   In her new school, Sherman, who married in the meantime and
enjoys the relative anonymity of her new name, has not looked into
teaching other books that might ruffle feathers. ``I do
second-guess everything now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy also affected her teaching style. ``I was
extremely open-minded before, and I'd look through a child's eyes.
Now I think, `This one might be insulted, this one has a little bit
of an attitude about this,''' she said. ``Something as simple as a
child's book might offend someone, which is something I never
thought about before. It is a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I will do anything in my power not to insult or
disrespect anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new school feels like home now. ``I joke around all the
time, I want a T-shirt that says `I died and went to P.S. 131,'''
she said. ``It's heaven here.''
</P>
<P>
   New Strategy in Game of Duck, Duck, Goose
</P>
<P>
   They've tried shaking them. They've tried baking them. They've
tried spraying the home fields with goose-repelling grape juice.
Now they've added three border collies with a fervent work ethic.
And still, it's a dead heat in the continuing battle of Canada
Geese vs. The People of Clarkstown.
</P>
<P>
   For a while there, the score was tilted in favor of the People,
in their attempts to rid their grassy areas of goose droppings. In
1996 and 1997, Clarkstown, in Rockland County, got permission from
the state to round up a total of 451 geese and convert them to
gooseburgers for the homeless and elderly. But in 1996 the meat was
contaminated, and in 1997 the elderly complained that it was tough.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the plan wasn't worth the hassle. It reduced the number
of nests in the parks, but it brought out animal-rights protesters,
and people complained that new geese would move in to replace the
cooked ones.
</P>
<P>
   The town is now resorting to an earlier goose-fighting
technique, addling eggs by shaking them and piercing them, so they
will not hatch. And now, dogs belonging to Mary Felegy of Fair Game
Goose Management Services patrol the town's parks daily, running
and swimming after the birds.
</P>
<P>
   There is less ``goose grease'' in the parks, said Charles
Holbrook, the Clarkstown supervisor. ``The dogs keep the geese off
the park property, which is good, but in reality they're just
chasing them to someone else's property, so it's not really a
solution,'' he said. And it costs $36,000 to chase the geese, but
only $10,000 to catch them and prepare the meat, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Felegy said the parks were cleaner now. ``It's safe to sit
on the grass,'' she said, ``it's safe to slide into home base, and
you can bounce your basketball on the court without it coming up
covered in green, slimy goo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
