<P>
   (NYT5) BEIJING -- May 13, 2000 -- CHINA-INTERNET-COX-1 -- While
overseas investors are now showing somewhat more restraint towards
Internet start-ups, analysts say they don't seem to have the
patience in China that they did with the U.S. market, where they
allow a few years to build an audience before worrying about
profits. People attending a high-tech industry trade fair in
Beijing check out the latest in computer developments. (Julie
Chao/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW ORLEANS -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-ORLEANS-TERMITES-4 --
Despite regular termite inspections, Janet and Scott Howard and
their children discovered a terrible infestation in their 1920s
federal house in the city's historic Garden District. Termites had
turned their joists, in Mrs. Howard's words, ``into straw.'' They
say it will cost around $400,000 to repair the damage. Mrs. Howard
holds photos of their once beautiful home in a room which has been
gutted and is soon to be rebuilt. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW ORLEANS -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-ORLEANS-TERMITES-3 --
Bugs are eating their way through landmarks along the Gulf Coast,
from barracks at the Citadel in Charleston, S.C., to cast-iron
fronted stores in Galveston's Strand Historic District. And they
are heading north, having been confirmed in North Carolina.
Formosan subterranean termites, pictured, with an insatiable taste
for irreplaceable historic structures have been devastating New
Orleans' French Quarter, drawn to its moist porous bricks and
centuries-old wood. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW ORLEANS -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-ORLEANS-TERMITES-2 --
Formosan subterranean termites with an insatiable taste for
irreplaceable historic structures have been devastating New
Orleans' French Quarter, drawn to its moist porous bricks and
centuries-old wood. With powerful mandibles, Formosans are
intrusive foragers who can tunnel through plaster, asphalt,
electrical high-voltage wire, utility poles and even espresso
makers, to find food and water. Edward D. Freytag, an entomologist,
inspects a wall at Perseverance Hall in The Quarter, where Formosan
termites made a carton nest in early May. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW ORLEANS -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-ORLEANS-TERMITES-1 --
Formosan subterranean termites with an insatiable taste for
irreplaceable historic structures have been devastating New
Orleans' French Quarter, drawn to its moist porous bricks and
centuries-old wood. The Quarter is ground zero in the federal
government's $15 million effort to thwart the Formosan, the most
destructive species of termite in the world, capable of building
colonies of up to 10 million writhing white bugs, which devour an
average of 1,000 pounds of wood a year. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
