<P>
   (NYT15) PURCHASE, N.Y. -- May 13, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-VANGUNDY --
The debate over the Miami Heat's 77-76 victory with 2.2 seconds
left on Friday raged anew on Saturday. Anthony Carter's
game-winning shot from behind the backboard was questionable to
many. Of course, the New York Knicks still believe the basket
should have been waved off, and the Miami Heat still insist it was
good as called. Jeff Van Gundy talks to reporters at the Knicks
practice facility at SUNY Purchase in Purchase, N.Y., Saturday.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AUSTIN, Texas -- May 13, 2000 -- TEXAS-EXECUTIONS-2 --
Paddy Lann Burwell, a retired Exxon manager who was appointed by
the governor two years ago to the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles, which reviews all clemency requests in capital cases and
makes recommendations to Texas Gov. George W. Bush. ``I believe in
the death penalty and I don't want to do anything that will cause
George Bush to lose the election,'' says Burwell. ``But I worry
that we may execute an innocent person. Any person would know that
is a possibility. I think our system needs to be improved.''
(Phillippe Diederich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) AUSTIN, Texas -- May 13, 2000 -- TEXAS-EXECUTIONS-1 --
In the state of Texas, which under Gov. George W. Bush has executed
more people than any other state, some of the officials who
administer the death penalty, review the case records, considr
inmates' appeals and weigh final pleas for clemency, also believe
Texas runs the risk of executing an innocent person. The death
chamber in Huntsville, Texas, where 20 people are to die in the
next four months. (Phillippe Diederich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GREENBELT, Md. -- May 13, 2000 -- UNIVERSE-COX --
Blanket technician Tereva Adams, left, and quality engineer Bob
Calvo work on microwave antennas that will sit atop the the
Microwave Anisotropy Probe satellite. The MAPS satellite will
provide the first detailed picture of the entire universe as it
looked 12 to 14 billion years ago. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DUBLIN, Calif. -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-PATHWAYS-COX-2 --
Isabel Chacon, left, talks with Tracy Henderson at the Federal
Correctional Institution in Dublin, Calif., during a therapy
session as part of New Pathways, a pilot program aimed at treating
female inmates who have had traumatic experiences. Unlike other
prison reform programs, inmates volunteer for New Pathways, says
Dr. Stephen Formanski, chief psychologist at FCI-Dublin. There is
no financial incentive, nor are inmates' sentences reduced for
participating. (Ismail Turay Jr./Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DUBLIN, Calif. -- May 13, 2000 -- NEW-PATHWAYS-COX-1 --
In hopes of slowing a rapid rise in the national prison population,
and an even faster rise in female inmates, a team of psychologists
at the Federal Correctional Institution in Dublin, Calif.,
developed New Pathways, a pilot program aimed at addressing the
special needs of female inmates who have been physically or
sexually abused. Inmates (l-r) Jo-Lynn Anderson, Elida Lopez and
Eshelle Scott chat with New Pathways co-creator Dr. Davina
Kotulski. (Ismail Turay Jr./Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- May 13, 2000 -- ERGONOMICS-COX-2 --
Businesses large and small are up in arms over ``ergonomics''
standards proposed last fall by the Occupational Health and Safety
Administration. If passed as law, OSHA says 27 million workers
would be affected by the new rules involving repetitive motions,
awkward reaching or heavy lifting. OSHA said the rules would cost
businesses about $ 4.2 billion a year to implement, while saving $
9 billion annually through increased productivity and lower
absenteeism. Industry groups responded that the cost would be much
higher. A worker in a Washington, D.C. food warehouse stacks crates
of corn. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MOUNT OLIVE, N.C. -- May 13, 2000 -- ERGONOMICS-COX-1 --
A move by the Clinton administration to set ergonomics standards
reached its final phase last week as the Labor Department's
Occupational Safety and Health Administration wrapped up public
hearings on a rule that would cover 27 million working Americans.
The goal is to prevent common on-the-job injuries from repetitive
action or over-exertion. Industry groups have stated that the cost
for implementing the new rule will be much higher than government's
estimate of 4.2 billion a year. Workers process turkeys at a plant
in Mount Olive, N.C. (George Bridges/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BEIJING -- May 13, 2000 -- CHINA-INTERNET-COX-2 -- Eleven
years ago, Steve Sun was a student hunger-striker on Tiananmen
Square being interviewed by CBS News's Dan Rather on why China
needed democracy. Today, with an American MBA and three years of
Wall Street experience, he is chief executive of Sinobit.com, an
Internet start-up, with a 14th-floor corner office in one of
Beijing's newest high-rises. (Julie Chao/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) RANDALLS ISLAND, N.Y. -- May 13, 2000 -- NY-SCHOOLS-RODEO
-- New York City school children taking part in rodeo activities on
Randalls Island in New York, Saturday. The New York City Riding
Academy sponsors the rodeo for school children so that they can
learn about horses. Fred Brothers of the Federation of Black
Cowboys helps Jawuana Thomas, 13, with roping technigues. (Ozier
Muhammad/The New York Times)
