<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-LAWYERS0514-COX     05-13 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-LAWYERS0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspects enlist top legal teams
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ray Lewis is a criminal defense lawyer's dream.
</P>
<P>
   The All Pro NFL linebacker can pay mountainous attorneys' fees.
His case has generated the kind of sensational publicity most
lawyers crave. And, even better, his case may be one his attorneys
can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exhilarating time,'' Ed Garland, Lewis' lead attorney,
said recently. ``It's a great challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Smooth, cunning and calculating, Garland has for decades been on
everyone's short list when a high-profile criminal indictment hit
town. That is, if the defendants could afford him.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with a $7 million signing bonus, Lewis can.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and co-defendants Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting are
charged with murder and aggravated assault in the stabbing deaths
of two men after a night of post-Super Bowl partying. Their trial
starts Monday with jury selection.
</P>
<P>
   The three defendants have assembled what amounts to be a dream
team of Atlanta defense lawyers: Garland and partner Don Samuel
lead the Lewis team; Bruce Harvey and David Wolfe represent Oakley;
and Steve Sadow will work with Miami lawyer John Bergendahl on
behalf of Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   While the array of legal talent is impressive, the lawyers will
have to achieve a delicate balance during the trial. They will have
to aggressively defend their own client without antagonizing the
co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   If one defendant tries to blame another, the trial could
suddenly become treacherous for all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense lawyers hate a case where multiple defendants have an
incentive to point the finger at one another,'' Atlanta lawyer Jack
Martin said. ``Usually, in that situation, everybody goes down in
flames.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these lawyers possess strong personalities that could
lead to a few clashes during trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got three defendants with excellent lawyers, all of
whom have strong egos,'' Atlanta lawyer Craig Gillen said. ``I
think it will be vital their theories do not clash at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, disharmony in the defense camp has surfaced, such as
the unsuccessful motions by Lewis and Oakley for separate trials.
But the lawyers appeared to get along amiably Tuesday during lunch
shortly after a pretrial hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' team of Garland and Samuel compliment each other well.
Garland revels in the spotlight and has a way of connecting with
jurors. In the courtroom, he can look into a jury box and not have
the jurors feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best trial lawyers in the country and an
extremely charming guy,'' famed lawyer F. Lee Bailey said. ``And
he's got that very rich Southern accent that he has no desire to
get rid of at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland, 58, is the son of Reuben Garland, a theatrical
courtroom lawyer and orator who died in 1982. The elder Garland was
known to feign heart attacks in court and infuriate judges who
sometimes cited him for contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal thing about my father was that he was a free
human being,'' Garland said recently. ``He was without fear. So
when he defended someone, the thought never crossed his mind about
what someone thought about him _ only what actions by him would
help his client.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland has his own brand of zealous advocacy, although he is
more measured and accommodating than his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel, 46, is a bit more reserved. The scholarly half of the
team, he is a walking encyclopedia of criminal defense law, having
written books on federal and state court decisions. Many defense
attorneys have at least one of the books an arm's reach away in
their office.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Assistant District Attorney Sheila Ross Finley
took the occasion to bring Samuel's book to Tuesday's motions
hearing and quote from it in successfully arguing an issue before
Judge Alice D. Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel is often seen leaning back at the defense table, twirling
a pen as he conjures up innovative legal theories. He is a master
at winning over judges when arguing the finer points of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, he fills in all my weak spots,'' Garland said
recently with a hearty laugh. ``If Don had any, I'd fill those
in.''
</P>
<P>
   A high point in Samuel's legal career occurred in the
sensational federal trial of millionaire James Sullivan, accused of
hiring a hit man to kill his estranged wife, Lita. After
prosecutors rested, Samuel argued for a directed verdict, saying
there was insufficient evidence for the case to reach the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Marvin Shoob wanted to defer a ruling, but Samuel argued
that he had to decide it right away. Shoob agreed and then granted
the motion, acquitting Williams and stunning prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel won a big victory in the Lewis case, too, convincing
Bonner that allegations of prior assaults by the linebacker cannot
be put before the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Garland is sparing little expense in his defense. He employs a
troupe of private investigators, led by Joe Pagani, once second in
command of the Internal Revenue Servies' criminal investigations
division. Other members of the Lewis legal team are highly regarded
Atlanta lawyer Tony Axam and certified jury consultant Jana Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Sadow, 46, once worked for Garland and, he admits, got his first
case by swiping a phone message off Garland's desk. Sadow returned
the call and was hired to represent a man charged with the fatal
shooting of his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The jury accepted Sadow's self-defense arguments and acquitted
his client. The young prosecutor trying the case was Paul Howard,
now Fulton County district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Intense, brash, gifted with an almost total recall, Sadow first
wanted to be a lawyer at age 11 while watching the TV courtroom
drama ``The Defenders.''
</P>
<P>
   In the stabbings case, Sadow is co-counsel to Bergendahl, who
was initially hired by Sweeting and then brought Sadow into the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the ponytailed Harvey and the shaggy-haired Wolfe will
share duties in Oakley's defense. The two men have tried numerous
cases together.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, 49, is one of the city's most prominent lawyers. He
recently was appointed as one of the lawyers defending Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin, the former '60s radical once known as H. Rap
Brown who faces death penalty charges in the killing of a Fulton
County sheriff's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, who has tried his hand at stand-up comedy, won acquittals
