<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MBEKI-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S MBEKI TO PRESS US COMMITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ President Thabo Mbeki, preparing for his first state
visit to the United States in a week, said Saturday that he would
challenge US political and business leaders not to disengage from
his troubled continent.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Saturday with a small group of foreign correspondents,
Mbeki said that in particular, the United States should do more as
the world's only superpower to eradicate global poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no shortage of capital in the world economy, but we
are failing as a human society to take advantage of what exists
indeed to address all of these problems associated with poverty
around the world,'' he said. ``The capacity is there. The country
that needs to take a lead in addressing this type of issue is the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki will make his trip, which includes a stop in Britain, at a
time when old conflicts have flared up again across Africa. In
addition to the wars in Angola and Congo, political violence has
spread across Zimbabwe, rebels have captured and killed UN and
regional peacekeeping forces in Sierra Leone, and Ethiopia has gone
back to war with its neighbor, Eritrea. Soldiers from Rwanda and
Uganda, normally allies, have turned their guns on each other
inside Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The South African leader, who will be in the United States from
May 22 to 26, will meet with President Clinton, Congress, and both
presidential candidates, Al Gore and George W. Bush. He will also
travel to San Francisco, Austin, Texas, and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges he faces in the United States, Mbeki said,
is to ensure that investors and the public in general do not lose
sight of progress amid the chaos. ``There is a mood which sees
Africa as one entity,'' he said. ``Despite the battles we are
carrying out here to build a better society, the way the Nigerians
are trying to do something for themselves, to change their
situation for the better . . . we tend to get overshadowed by these
spectacular bad things, and so you get a kind of pessimism that
persists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do about Africa?'' he said. ``Not to deny the bad
things that are happening, but also not, then, to allow that those
bad things overshadow the . . . work that is being done? What
additional things do we need to do to assist in this process of
African renewal?''
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki spent much of the meeting defending policies on AIDS and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself a champion of the notion of an African
``renaissance,'' Mbeki has drawn fire from critics at home for not
denouncing turmoil in Zimbabwe, where progovernment mobs have
invaded hundreds of white-owned farms and have turned against
members and supporters of the opposition ahead of parliamentary
elections, due before August. At least 18 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has been accused of coddling Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, who, analysts say, has encouraged the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki said he had sent a delegation from his African National
Congress Saturday to speak with Mugabe's party and the opposition
Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the first time that the South African governing
party has engaged Mugabe's political opponents publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In recent speeches, Mbeki has decried the violence in Zimbabwe,
and he said he has urged Mugabe to allow election observers to come
in as soon as possible to monitor the process. But he has rejected
the criticism that by not making more forceful comments publicly
about Zimbabwe's crisis, he is sending a mixed message to his
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our neighbor,'' he said. ``I have said to Mugabe we
must have an end to the violence, that there must be the rule of
law, land reform, and transparency. But we need a comfortable,
cooperative approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about AIDS, an issue on which he has drawn criticism
for inviting scientists to debate, among other points, whether HIV
caused the disease, Mbeki said he had dispatched his health
minister to Geneva to discuss a deal announced last Friday by
pharmaceutical companies to slash the costs of their antiretroviral
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the cost reductions, he said, the South African
medical community did not have the capacity to administer
complicated, daily treatments throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
