<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-13 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS CANNOT AFFORD TO DWELL ON GAME 3
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One year _ almost to the day _ after Allan Houston's
magical jump shot bounced high off the rim and fell majestically
through the net, sending the Miami Heat to a devastating
first-round playoff exit, the New York Knicks find themselves
dealing with a crushing circumstance of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The improbable game-winning baseline runner that the Miami
rookie Anthony Carter bounced into the rim with 2.2 seconds left on
Friday gave the Heat a 77-76 overtime victory. It was the type of
shot that can send an opponent spiraling into emotional oblivion.
To the superstitious, it must have seemed like payback.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between Carter's shot and Houston's shot,
which came in Game 5 last year, is that the Knicks have a chance to
regroup this year in the Eastern Conference semifinals. Victims of
a knockdown rather than a knockout, the Knicks face only a 2-1
deficit in this best-of-7 series rather than a summer of
nightmarish flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they can put the discouraging loss behind them when
they take the floor for the most critical contest of the series
thus far, Sunday's Game 4 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to gather ourselves and not get down,'' Latrell
Sprewell said after Friday's game. ``Right now, guys are really
down and upset, so we need to channel all of this frustration in
the right direction. There's no doubt about it that it's tough.
Guys are frustrated and upset. There's no other way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the frustration came from the manner in which the Knicks
lost, the anger stemmed from the teamwide feeling of injustice. The
Knicks believe that Carter's shot flew over the back of the
backboard before hitting the rim and therefore should have been
ruled illegal and called off. The officials never considered the
Knicks' argument and, in fact, were more concerned with whether
Alonzo Mourning tipped the ball into the rim while it bounced
within the cylinder. Initially, they called the basket off because
they thought Mourning had touched the ball, but they quickly and
correctly reversed their call, as replays showed that he did not
interfere with the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Replays seemed to be inconclusive in determining whether
Carter's shot went over the backboard, but the Knicks were
convinced, disputing the officials' no-call to a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it on replay,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``It was
definitely a shot from behind the backboard. They got the right
call for the wrong reason. Unfortunately, that is how it is. They
called it no good and they called it for goaltending, which is
wasn't. But the ball was shot from behind the backboard, which
should result in our ball out of bounds on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as clear as day on the replay.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their exasperation, the Knicks wisely admitted to being
done in by more than a wild prayer of a shot. They scored seven of
the first 10 points of overtime to take a 75-71 lead and the
momentum with 2 minutes 13 seconds remaining, but could not hold
on. They were beaten badly on the backboards, losing the rebounding
battle by 45-34 and allowing Carter to grab seven rebounds from his
point guard position.
</P>
<P>
   They blew a golden opportunity to open a large lead in the
second half, failing to capitalize on Mourning's foul trouble when
he went to the bench with four fouls with 8:13 left in the third
quarter. Leading by 44-40 when Mourning left, the Knicks actually
trailed, 58-57, when he returned 11 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   With Mourning, an All-Star center, on the bench, the Knicks
should have broken the game open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the turning point really,'' said Marcus
Camby, who blocked six shots but had just four points and five
rebounds in 32 minutes. ``I think we started to think that the game
was over. We never took advantage when he went out of the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything positive the Knicks can take out of the
game it is that Houston and Sprewell seemed to solve the Heat
defense. After being slowed offensively over the first two games,
they combined to score 47 points. Sprewell attacked the basket hard
to earn 11 foul shots (he made them all) and scored 23 points, and
Houston made 9 of 18 field goal attempts to score a game-high 24.
Mourning scored 23 for the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, who shot just 36 percent in the first two games,
continued to struggle, hitting just 4 of his 10 shots in scoring
nine points, but he nearly overcame his lack of productivity by
canning a game-tying 17 footer with 2.6 seconds left in regulation.
A hero at that point, Ewing floundered near the end of the overtime
period, missing 1 of 2 free throws with 13.7 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   While his made foul shot put the Knicks ahead, 76-75, it left
the door open for Carter's heroics, which in addition to costing
the Knicks the game and the home-court advantage, may very well end
up costing them the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT &LR;      05-13 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS LOSE AGAIN TO TIGERS, AND CAN'T BLAME WIND
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Hot dog wrappers drifted by like tumbleweeds inside
Comerica Park Saturday, bouncing and hopping from right field to
left. When fly balls went into the air, the players turned
helplessly, as if caught in the whirl of dust devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are still learning about their new home, and it may
be that the wind will never blow the same way it did on this spring
afternoon _ steady, from the southwest and over the right-field
wall, curling along the upper decks of the park. If this is the
norm, however, players will draw comparisons with Mother Nature's
favorite haunt, San Francisco's Candlestick Park, where pop flies
were an entertainment staple before the Giants escaped this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit beat Andy Pettitte and the Yankees, 6-3, and would have
done so with or without the wind. But first impressions are still
being formed about Comerica Park, and on this first warm day game
of the season, players on both sides waged war with the wind, some
losing and others prevailing. ``I have never seen fly balls move
like that,'' Yankees right-fielder Paul O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who have lost the first two games of this series to
the last-place Tigers (11-23) and three straight overall, will try
to salvage the final game Sunday, with Orlando Hernandez set to
face the former Mets pitcher Dave Mlicki. The Yankees are 22-12 and
are on a pace to win 105 games, but they continue to struggle to
score runs, and to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   If Houston's cozy new Enron Field is the Rhode Island of
ballparks, then Comerica Park is Alaska, an expanse of outfield, so
large that the outfielders must play a little deeper than they
might in other parks. That dynamic was complicated by Saturday's
wind: Comerica Park is built into the ground and right field is
mostly unguarded by structure, so that the breezes and gusts blew
unencumbered into the outfield and wreaked havoc.
</P>
<P>
   Positioned deep in right field, O'Neill could not reach the
bloop double Dean Palmer hit in the second; in most ballparks,
O'Neill could have kept Palmer from reaching second. Three batters
and one walk later, second baseman Jose Macias _ unknown to
Pettitte before Saturday's game _ rolled a grounder inside the
first-base line, and by the time O'Neill retrieved it deep in the
right field corner, Macias had a two-run triple. Pettitte prolonged
the inning with the second of his two throwing errors, and Detroit
carried a 4-1 lead into the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the fourth, Palmer lifted a high pop toward
right field. Pettitte began moving off the field, assuming this
would be the last out. O'Neill set himself in right field, for what
looked to be an easy play. The second baseman Chuck Knoblauch never
moved.
</P>
<P>
   The ball suddenly dropped; it had hit the wall of wind blowing
in from right field. ``It was like a duck that was shot and went
right down,'' said Lee Mazzilli, the first base coach.
</P>
<P>
   And it fell about 100 feet from O'Neill, closer to Knoblauch
than the right fielder. ``I had absolutely no chance,'' O'Neill
said. ``I wouldn't have caught that ball even if you told me where
it was going to drop. It's like it took off sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Another run scored. O'Neill kept looking around in right field,
staring at the fluttering flags built high above the center field
wall, shaking his head. Pettitte was relieved two outs into the
fifth inning, having allowed six runs on 10 hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams hit a high fly toward left in the sixth inning
and began sprinting toward first, knowing left fielder Rich Becker
might be fooled by the wind. Before the game, Becker asked
teammates about the wind's effect on fly balls in Comerica Park,
and manager Phil Garner replied, honestly, that he had no idea.
They haven't played enough games here to know.
</P>
<P>
   Becker moved in for a moment, started backpedaling, faster and
faster, and the ball fell about five feet behind him. Williams was
at second base, Becker was charged with an error _ mistakenly,
manager Joe Torre thought, given the adverse conditions.
</P>
<P>
   This is Comerica Park. There's no place like home, Dorothy once
said, and she lived in a pretty windy place, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
