<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4330 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MCCARTHY-PROFILE0514-     05-13 2123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-PROFILE0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tragedy spurs congresswoman to fight back
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sound of C-SPAN follows her as she flits around
her office, which makes perfect sense. You can't exactly tune in to
Oprah from your office on The Hill, although she does allow herself
a couple of flickering candles. She's got staff here and staff
there _ young kids who think the world of her. Hillary's picture is
hanging on the reception-area wall. Newt's birthday card is framed
in her inner-office.
</P>
<P>
   She has a view of concrete government offices from the giant
window behind her.
</P>
<P>
   She has a heart that hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Congresswoman Carolyn McCarthy has just finished her lunch, the
one quiet moment she allows herself each blurred day of her life.
She's a wisp of a woman, and here's how to stay fit the Carolyn
McCarthy way:
</P>
<P>
   Leave the house where you raised your only son. Leave the house
where you gardened with your husband. Leave your best girlfriends
and your local hardware store and your favorite pizza joint.
</P>
<P>
   Kiss it all goodbye, including your anonymity. Especially your
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't be forced into it the way she was.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, 56, came to the U.S. House of Representatives in the
worst way possible: through murder. Her husband and son were shot
on the Long Island Rail Road on Dec. 7, 1993. Her husband, Dennis,
died. Her son, Kevin, lived. On Dec. 6, everything was fine and
dandy at the McCarthy household on Long Island. They'd just gotten
back from their annual trip to Vermont. They were getting ready for
Christmas. She loved her job as a nurse. Kevin now had a job at
Dad's office in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Then father and son hustled out of their offices at Prudential
Securities in New York and onto the 5:33 train out of Penn Station.
Suddenly, everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, she's still a nurse. She's still a mother. But, through
life's frantic design, Carolyn McCarthy is a whole lot more. A
member of Congress. An enemy of the National Rifle Association. A
made-for-TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   All of those things _ tragedy and joy alike _ have put her at
the front of today's Million Mom March, a day-long outcry in
Washington and 67 other cities that has been engineered mostly by
America's women. The message? This country has to get control of
its guns. McCarthy acquired this belief the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   The second-term representative sits amid the televised drone of
Washington at work, her Washington now. And she talks. About that
day.
</P>
<P>
   She was at a Christmas concert with some friends. She was
heading home. The car radio was off. She always did that _ drive
time was her alone time, like her lunches are today. She walked
into an empty house. She noticed the guys hadn't put up the
Christmas tree. The phone started ringing. There'd been an awful
massacre on the train. People with white stricken faces started
streaming into her house, streaming into her life.
</P>
<P>
   She stops. She remembers. She reminds herself to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Because she's getting to The Part.
</P>
<P>
   The Part where her boys didn't come home.
</P>
<P>
   A LIFE CHANGING TRAGEDY
</P>
<P>
   The floor of the subway. That's the first thing Kevin McCarthy
talked about when he opened his eyes in the hospital bed. The
floor. And Dad? Where is Dad? His mother, Carolyn, a nurse, soothed
him, quieted him. She told him he was going to be fine and that was
all that mattered right now. And then she started. She moved his
legs. She moved his fingers. She moved just about anything that
could move even when her dear child flinched with pain.
</P>
<P>
   She had already lost one man in her life. She was not about to
lose the other.
</P>
<P>
   The father and son had just begun a whole new chapter of their
lives when they kissed her goodbye that Tuesday morning. Kevin was
still living at home, an only child content within the careful
confines of where he'd grown up. He had graduated from college with
a degree in hotel management and had played around with a couple of
jobs. But only recently had he started working with his father.
``It was a very special time for the two of them,'' Carolyn says.
</P>
<P>
   They would take the subway to and from work, father and son,
looking handsome in their two-piece suits. They would discuss
business in the back yard. Dennis McCarthy had always been the big
voice in the family; everyone loved him _ his humor, his outgoing
personality. Carolyn and Kevin had always been two peas in a pod,
the two quiet mice.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives had been so regular, so predictable, so mundane.
Tennis and church and dinner with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Then everything changed:
</P>
<P>
   Gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   They began just after the train pulled from the station. One
minute, everyone was packed on the subway, briefcases and Christmas
packages piled at their feet. The next second, it was a war zone.
His name was Colin Ferguson, and he was out to settle his imagined
scores with the world. He pulled a semi-automatic gun from his gym
bag and started firing at point-blank range. An expectant mother. A
young Christian woman who had just lost her husband to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A father. A son.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, six people were dead, 19 injured. The
housewife from Mineola had to bury one and teach another how to
walk again. Today, gun advocates like to suggest to her that if
someone else had had a gun that day on the subway, maybe they could
have stopped the madman. Maybe they could have shot Ferguson dead.
</P>
<P>
   But McCarthy is convinced otherwise. She's done her homework,
looked at the reports, read the witness statements. ``There was too
much confusion for anybody to know who was who,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW LIFE IN WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   I 'd like to thank Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, Sen. Chuck Schumer,
Bill and Hillary Clinton and Al Gore. They have made me see the
light. After 30 years of gun ownership, they have forced me to join
the NRA. I could have used that $35 on something else, but because
of them I had to use it to uphold my rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Letter to the editor, New York Daily News, March 24, 2000
</P>
<P>
   At first, they were always catching her by surprise. In a crowd.
In the halls of her congressional office building. At community
meetings in her home district. They were forceful. McCarthy
describes them as mean and rude and threatening. Now when she
addresses a crowd, she can pick them out in one glance. Recently,
they've started sending women. The NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I just let them be rude the way they are and let the
audience turn on them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Funny things happen when you leave your old life and start a new
one in Washington. It's not just that you're walking four and a
half miles a day and forgetting to eat right. It's not just that a
trip to the grocery store back home can take double the time.
Constituents like to talk!
</P>
<P>
   It's that _ suddenly, without any special schooling _ you find
yourself meeting with people you'd only before read about in the
newspaper. The president. Teddy Kennedy. Sarah Brady. Your Rolodex
is filled with the names of powerhouses. By the time Rosie
O'Donnell called _ the day after the Columbine shootings _ McCarthy
knew just what to do. She told her staff she wasn't voting on
anything that day. She was going on Rosie. The two women, now
friends, are scheduled to speak today in Washington, before an
expected crowd of more than 150,000. Supporters are hoping for a
national turnout of 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who ever had a mother is invited to march,'' McCarthy
likes to tell anyone she sees.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of running for Congress didn't come to her until Kevin
was out of the hospital. Indeed, she thought of nothing but him all
the way through the long 12 months of hospitalization and
rehabilitation. ``Dennis was gone. There was nothing I could do
about Dennis,'' she says now. She threw herself into Kevin's
recovery. Sometimes, the nurses thought she was nuts. But she
didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 and 1995, after her son's release from rehab, she threw
herself into Long Islanders Against Gun Violence. She made her
first trips to Capitol Hill. She felt her first rush of rage at the
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Then her congressman, Republican Dan Frisa, voted against a ban
on assault weapons. McCarthy was livid. A reporter from the New
York Daily News stumbled upon her in a stairwell after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you mad enough to run for office?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get an Irish woman mad enough, she'll do anything,'' she said.
In May of 1996, she announced her candidacy in the back yard of her
modest Mineola home, relying on advice from her friends and family
_ a group she coyly called her ``kitchen cabinet.'' Her plan? Run
against Frisa as a Democrat, even though she was a lifelong
Republican. It worked, and she was reelected in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She's half-way through her second term, and while nursing is a
good preparation for life, what could have prepared her for this?
The pretend smiles in the hallway, the back-stabbing on the House
floor. She tries hard to play the game the way she thinks it should
be played. She tries hard to be kind and sensible and strong. She
tries hard to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell my staff that when I start acting like a
politician, they need to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Cecelia Prewett, her communications director, ``She's just
precious, isn't she? She's so real.''
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING THE PROMISE
</P>
<P>
   We have an opportunity in Washington to stop playing games. That
is what I came to Washington for. I am sorry that this is so very
hard for me. I am Irish, and I am not supposed to cry in front of
anyone. But I made a promise a long time ago. I made a promise to
my son and to my husband. If there was anything that I could do to
prevent one family from going through what I have gone through and
every other victim that I know have gone through, then I have done
my job.
</P>
<P>
   Let me go home. Let me go home.
</P>
<P>
   _ McCarthy speech on the floor of Congress, June 17, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Her speech came _ after much choreographed delay, her staff
insists _ at 1:30 in the morning. Even before the speaker of the
House gave her two minutes of floor time, she knew it was going to
be the toughest speech of her life. She was right. The Gun Show
Loophole Amendment was her baby. It made so much sense! Guns kill
30,000 people and cause 100,000 injuries in America each year.
Those deaths and injuries cost the health care industry $2.8
billion annually. The government foots half that bill. She passed
the statistics out like candy. She lined up her votes.
</P>
<P>
   She explained it all until she was beyond blue in the face:
</P>
<P>
   She was not trying to take guns away from anyone. Hunters could
hunt. Protectors could still protect. All she wanted was a waiting
period when people bought guns at trade shows. It was that simple.
But in the end, her not-so-quiet politicking wasn't enough. Even
her fellow Democrats split off from her. The next week, Minority
LeaderDick Gephardt, D-Mo., sent her a handwritten note. She found
out later it was straight from his heart; his staff didn't know a
thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were magnificent,'' Gephardt wrote. ``I have never heard a
better speech on the floor in my 22 years. You made us all proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The victories are slow, which is to say they are very much
cherished. Both the House and Senate versions of the latest
Juvenile Justice Bill contain provisions that require child safety
locks on all new guns, something she's fought for since she came to
Congress. She's helped get more money allocated for tracing guns
used by juveniles who commit crimes. And she wants Congress to
instruct the U.S. Department of Education to collect data on gun
violence in their schools, then start classroom programs about guns
and safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to make a difference,'' she said during a recent
luncheon speech. ``I just didn't know it would take this long.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what McCarthy has learned about guns and politics.
``Nothing is going to change until we reach out and get everyone
involved,'' she says. Her treasured prototype for today's march is
not the woman with the dead sister or murdered son. It's the mother
who is simply scared out of her wits. The mother who stands beside
her child, not on the emotion of a grave.
</P>
<P>
   Today, on the National Mall, the nurse with the sweet grandbaby
and a second on the way, will pull back her hair with her trademark
scrunchee, and she'll give a speech. About a father. About a son.
About an Irish mother who's not in Mineola any more.
</P>
<P>
   She'll look at the sea of faces. She'll hear the applause.
</P>
<P>
   She'll remember to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always takes me right back to that moment,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That moment when her two boys didn't come home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
