<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PEEK AT POSSIBLE NBA FIRST-ROUND PICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While tears erupt from Dick Vitale's good eye, the NBA has
declared its underclass in session.
</P>
<P>
   Right, today is the deadline for players who have yet to
extinguish their college eligibility to officially tell the world
they intend to compete for even more loot than a top-ranked alumnus
can stuff into the folds of an unsanctioned, off-campus burrito.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these status-quo-disturbing rascals will skip college
completely, just like baseball star Ken Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Some can't speak English, but they believe the NBA is a good
excuse to escape from Europe. A few prospects who can speak English
will end up doing 5 to 10 in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Some will refuse to ``hire'' an agent, realize they aren't
first-round timber, then withdraw their names before another
deadline on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Some will stink. Some will achieve greatness. Others will become
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   With another week before the lottery Ping-Pong balls deliver a
draft order, it would be foolish to stir up a mock draft now.
</P>
<P>
   So we're crawling to within an inch of foolish by serving up a
preliminary look at possible first-round sections in tier-group
fashion. Your mileage may vary. Defections and individual workouts
eventually will alter this list by, oh, 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And away they go:
</P>
<P>
   1-4, not necessarily in this order: Kenyon Martin (Cincinnati),
Marcus Fizer (Iowa State), Stromile Swift (LSU), Chris Mihm
(Texas).
</P>
<P>
   5-9: Courtney Alexander (Fresno State), DerMarr Johnson
(Cincinnati), Darius Miles (East St. Louis, Ill. HS), Morris
Peterson (Michigan State), Joel Przybilla (Minnesota).
</P>
<P>
   10-17: Iakovos Tsakalidis (AEK, Greece), Mateen Cleaves
(Michigan State), Jerome Moiso (UCLA), Erick Barkley (St. John's),
Quentin Richardson (DePaul), Etan Thomas (Syracuse), Keyon Dooling
(Missouri), Mike Miller (Florida).
</P>
<P>
   18-23: Desmond Mason (Oklahoma State), Hanno Mattola (Utah),
Chris Carrawell (Duke), Scoonie Penn (Ohio State), Hidayet Turkoglu
(Efes Pilsen, Turkey), Speedy Claxton (Hofstra).
</P>
<P>
   24-29: Soumaila Samake (IBL), Jamal Magloire (Kentucky), Jason
Collier (Georgia Tech), Jamal Crawford (Michigan), Donnell Harvey
(Florida), Chris Porter (Auburn).
</P>
<P>
   Bubble: Mamadou N'Diaye (Auburn), Michael Redd (Ohio State),
Corey Hightower (Indian Hills JC, Iowa), Ernest Brown (Indian Hills
JC), Schea Cotton (Bosco Tech, LBCC, Alabama), Jason Kapono
(Artesia HS, UCLA), JaRon Rush (UCLA), Dan Langhi (Vanderbilt),
Jimmie ``Snap'' Hunter (Life College, Ga.), Fred Hickman (CNN/SI).
</P>
<P>
   If your son is not ranked to your specifications, blame the many
scouts consulted before this list was compiled. Then buy the kid
some ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Another pre-draft wild card is held by DeShawn Stevenson
(Washington Union HS, Fresno), a shooting guard with superhero
athletic ability. A Cliff Notes look: verbally declared for the
draft; received a qualifying college-board test score, announced he
would honor his commitment and play at Kansas; test score reported
to be over 500 points higher than the previous result, provoking a
possible demand to retake the test, the results of which would not
be known until long after today's NBA deadline. So Stevenson is in
limbo; but if he re-enters the draft in time for a few private
workouts, he still could be selected midway through Round 1, three
scouts insist. ... The aforementioned list includes a 20-year-old,
6-foot-8 Turk named Hidayet Turkoglu, described by one personnel
director as a mini-Toni Kukoc. Not sure if that's praise or an
indictment. ... Iakovos Tsakalidis, as was written here several
weeks ago, is a 7-2, 20-year-old center from Soviet Georgia (where
he's known as Tsakalov) with Greek citizenship. ...
</P>
<P>
   According to emissaries of agent David Falk, Clippers free agent
Maurice Taylor could end up in Miami. Well, not without accepting a
fraction of Mo's market value, or working a sign-and-trade with the
Clips involving P.J. Brown. Not bloody likely. ... According to six
NBA talent snoops, it's a good thing Jason Kapono has 3-point
range, because he'd be a long shot for selection in the first
round. ... ESPN.com has reported that Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins
turned down an offer to coach the Clippers. That's a hoot, says one
Clipper spokesperson, who doubts that owner Donald T. Sterling even
knows who Huggins is. ... According to a league source, Clips GM
Elgin Baylor may not be anti-Mike Fratello, after all. Baylor
simply wants to hire someone responsible enough to do the job, and
Fratello may qualify. Sterling probably agrees, but still figures
to have a difference of financial opinion. ...
</P>
<P>
   One NBA personnel sharpie said four of his colleagues reverently
closed their notebooks after watching Dominguez High junior Tyson
Chandler for only one quarter during a recent tournament in
Virginia. Three scouts (out of three asked) think the 7-foot Don -
with added strength and additional low-post chops - could be the
first pick in the 2001 draft. ``I like him more than (Darius) Miles
right now,'' said one scout, ``and Miles could go top five in
June.'' ... While he remains a solid candidate to replace Larry
Bird in Indiana, Pacers assistant coach Rick Carlisle does have
history with the new regime at Vancouver. General manager Billy
Knight just left the Pacers, while Chuck Daly who was hired for
some mystery front-office Grizzlies job had Carlisle on his
coaching staff at New Jersey. ... With not quite enough assistant
coaches to declare war on a small country, the Mavericks last week
hired Sidney Moncrief. While allegedly being groomed to replace Don
Nelson in the big chair, Moncrief (according to sources beyond our
control), also will be the official coach in charge of defensive
rotation on the north end of the floor every other Tuesday. ...
Cincinnati lottery locks Martin and Johnson are booked for Pete
Newell's Big Man Camp, scheduled for August in Hawaii. These
Bearcats, represented by L.A.-based agent Dan Fagan, have been
Staples Center guests of Corie Blount, the Phoenix Suns forward
with a Bearcat pedigree. ... A reporter for CNN/SI doesn't vote for
Shaquille O'Neal as the league MVP, then receives death threats.
Lenny Wilkens says he was offered the Wizards' head-coaching job,
then admits his announcement was premature. Many NBA watchdogs
believe the Wizards job qualifies as the death threat. ... Agent
Bill Duffy reports that Joey Przybilla (ranked in our top 9) has
added nine pounds to his 7-1 frame, but while reducing his body fat
by six percent. More importantly, Przybilla the Minnesota sophomore
who bolted late last season - is living in northern California and
investing hours in developing a low-post game. ... A recently
published favor (not here) for Darrick Martin (St. Anthony's HS,
UCLA) announced the backup Sacramento point guard's interest in
returning to the Clippers. Martin's only shot to suit up with the
Clips would require changing his first name to Kenyon.
</P>
</TEXT>
