<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING PENALTIES IS CRUCIAL FOR DEVILS AGAINST FLYERS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Eastern Conference finals between
the Devils and the Flyers that will start Sunday afternoon in
Philadelphia will be decided on physical strength, goaltending and
special teams, with the special teams perhaps the key factor in the
best-of-7 series.
</P>
<P>
   While the Flyers have been the most effective team in the
Stanley Cup playoffs with the man advantage, the Devils have been
the most efficient at killing penalties. They extinguished all 20
Toronto power plays and have allowed just one goal in 34 power
plays in the playoffs for a remarkable 97.1 efficiency. The only
power-play goal the Devils allowed was to Florida's Pavel Bure in
the fourth game of the sweep of the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have had such remarkable success thwarting the
opposition with the man advantage, avoiding penalties against the
Flyers is a priority for the Devils. With John LeClair and Mark
Recchi leading the way, the Flyers have been deadly on the power
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penalties is a no-no for us,'' Bobby Holik said after Saturday
afternoon's practice before the Devils traveled to Philadelphia.
``They're too dangerous on the power play, and we don't want to put
ourselves in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers have scored 13 goals in 52 chances (25 percent) with
the man advantage for almost half of their total playoff goal
production of 29. LeClair leads the team with four power-play
goals, while Recchi and the rookie Simon Gagne are next with two
each.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair leads the Flyers with six goals in the playoffs, and his
10 points are second to Recchi, who has three goals and nine
assists for 12 points. Recchi plays the point on the power play,
and his quarterbacking ability has been a key to its success.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are good hockey players,'' Devils defenseman Scott
Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play them tough because they capitalize on their
opportunities,'' said Stevens, who will be paired with the rookie
Brian Rafalski against Philadelphia's top line.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was the best player in the first two rounds for the
Devils. He said he was looking forward to the series with the
Flyers ``because they are more of a rivalry'' than Toronto and
Florida. ``It's almost like the Rangers,'' Stevens said, ``and,
personally, I go back a long way against them when I was in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and the Devils have lost just once in their last eight
games to the Flyers. They beat Philadelphia four of the five times
the teams met in the regular season, but only once since Brian
Boucher, the rookie sensation, became the No. 1 goaltender for the
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't win in the playoffs without goaltending and special
teams,'' said Ken Daneyko, who pairs with Stevens on defense on the
Devils' primary penalty-killing unit, which has John Madden and Jay
Pandolfo at forward. Claude Lemieux and Sergei Nemchinov are the
other two forwards killing penalties, along with defensemen Scott
Niedermayer and Vladimir Malakhov.
</P>
<P>
   While the Devils are healthy with the exception of Krzysztof
Oliwa, who was not expected to play in the playoffs, the Flyers are
without Eric Lindros, who has been out with a concussion throughout
the playoffs, and Keith Primeau. Primeau practiced with the Flyers
Saturday, however, and there is an outside chance he will play
Sunday. If not in Sunday's first game, Primeau will most likely
play on Tuesday in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure he will play sooner or later,'' Devils coach Larry
Robinson said. ``They are more physical with him, but what makes
them so good is that their power play is so dangerous. Our penalty
killers will have to do their best against them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
