<HEADER>
A4339 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GRADS-FUTURE-KAN &LR;      05-13 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN AND OPTIMISTIC, THE CLASS OF 2000 PREPARES TO GREET THE
WORLD  
</HEADLINE>
 BC- GRADS-FUTURE -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and LYNN FRANEY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Call them the click, click, click class,
raised to the fast pace of pagers, cell phones, video games, the
Internet and the TV remote control.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, thousands of members of the Class of 2000
_ possibly the most scrutinized graduates in generations _ will be
handed their high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the students, and they will tell you they are focused,
ambitious, confident and optimistic about their future. They also
say they are more worldly, independent and technologically savvy
than graduating classes of just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are nowhere near as naive about what happens in our
world,'' said Nadia Curren of Northeast High School.
</P>
<P>
   That self-assessment is backed by research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen-agers today are optimistic, recognize they're going to
have several different jobs during their lifetime and are very
competitive academically,'' said Barbara Schneider, a University of
Chicago professor and co-author of The Ambitious Generation:
America's Teenagers, Motivated but Directionless. The book is based
largely on a comprehensive study of 7,000 teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could they be studying more? Sure,'' Schneider said. ``Could
they be kinder to each other? You bet. But these are not slackers,
these are not kids that do not have dreams, and to me that's very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers who have watched the class since it entered
kindergarten in 1987 worry that the pace of life and the
bombardment of media and computer images are taking a toll on these
children of the information age.
</P>
<P>
   They say students might be too busy for their own good. Many
teens are overscheduled _ after-school play has given way to jobs,
community service, sports and other activities. That is especially
true for girls today, compared with their mothers and their
grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists, counselors, parents and others are still anxious
about the all-too-familiar dangers of alcohol, tobacco and teen
pregnancy. But new perils, including school massacres and hate
crimes, now crowd into their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   They also worry about the pressure students place on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these teens have grown up with two working parents, or
parents involved in multiple marriages and divorces. They have
learned to fend for themselves and take responsibility at a younger
age.
</P>
<P>
   Many have their own cars and their own incomes, and spend many
more hours with their friends than with their families.
</P>
<P>
   They are bull-market babies accustomed to the prosperity of a
soaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   All that has made them believe they are more self-reliant. But
some observers worry that the newfound independence is creating a
generation that is too materialistic, less civil and less
respectful of adults' wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Even teens themselves say a decline in social and moral values
is the biggest problem confronting their generation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is no surprise to an age group immersed in the images
of Jerry Springer, the O.J. Simpson trial, the presidential sex
scandals and the murderous rampage at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're mentally older than even the senior class of ten years
ago because of what we've witnessed,'' said Taryn Hodison, senior
at Lincoln Prep High School.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to members of the Class of 2000, and they'll tell you
they can feel the pressure to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I sit down and think, `Gee, I'm going so fast,
everything around me is going so fast,'' said Angela Liu of
Pembroke Hill School. She won a four-year scholarship to attend the
University of North Carolina and already has earned credit for 11
college courses. ``Sometimes I feel like I just can't relax and
breathe. But it's so exciting _ just the things happening around us
right now. We have so much opportunity to learn things and get
involved in things.''
</P>
<P>
   And most plan to keep on learning.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company that administers the ACT college
entrance test, three-fourths of the Class of 2000 said two years
ago that they would go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Marybeth Kravets, president-elect of the National Association
for College Admission Counseling, said students today saw college
as essential, not an educational bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finding that, statistically, the ability to make a
living is directly related to how much education you have,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the competition for admission to prestigious schools is
growing, and teens seem more fixated on grades than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   That trend troubles Kravets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep reminding parents that these are 16- and 17-year-olds.
We need to let them be 16 or 17.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu sees another disadvantage to students being so driven.
</P>
<P>
   ``People become way too competitive and try to bring others down
and really hurt other people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some even break the rules to get ahead in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent survey of high achievers conducted by Who's
Who Among American High School Students, 80 percent of students
admitted cheating in school. More than half of those said they
considered cheating no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to members of the Class of 2000, and they'll tell you
they're a diverse, creative, independent bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I describe our class, I don't try to put people in
groups,'' said Melissa Hollon of Grandview High School. ``We're
flexible. We fluctuate from one group to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollon's parents divorced when she was in the sixth grade, and
she has lived since then with her mother. Hollon said she had
worked for several years and usually came home on weeknights by 11
p.m. and on the weekends by 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Young people today seem more independent and focused, agreed
Dennis Schemmel, director of the UMKC Counseling and Placement
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seems to be coming earlier,'' Schemmel said.
``There's lots of opportunities for these kids to see the bigger
world out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But some high school counselors say the students have been on
their own for so long that they have an inflated sense of
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see that they feel they can do things, but they don't want
to be responsible for them,'' said Bob Tessman, counselor at Blue
Valley Northwest High School. ``They think they're more mature than
they are.'' Adjusting to change
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the members of the Class of 2000, and they'll tell you
they will thrive in a digital, high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   The ACT survey found that the most popular career choices for
the class of 2000 were science-related.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the changing times, almost as many females as
males are interested in careers in science and mathematics, an
increase from previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Barrows, a Grandview High counselor, said the boom in
computers and technology had positive and negative effects on the
Class of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good part is we have some independent learners who seek
out things,'' she said. ``But it does create less of an attention
span for traditional kinds of things _ a little more impatience to
get to some relevant things.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Pinizzotto, dean of the new Missouri Academy of Science,
Mathematics, and Technology, said some students today were too
dependent on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe, `If we can't find it technologically, we aren't
going to find it,'' he said. ``They want information
instantaneously. If they can't find it on the Web, they oftentimes
won't go to the library, even though there's so much more detailed
information in the library.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Swagerty, teaches the multimedia class at Broadmoor
Technical Center in Overland Park. Formerly an accounting teacher,
he has had to learn the programs right along with the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've noticed more than anything else from the Class of
2000 is that they're able to adjust to change so much faster and so
much easier,'' he said. ``They were raised in an era where change
was the norm. They're more flexible. In the real world, there's
change in workplaces too, and a whole lot of it is being driven by
technology. These students are going to fit in just fine with that
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
