<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KEMPER-SAVED-KAN &LR;      05-13 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS' FUND-RAISING DRIVE GIVES KEMPER MILITARY SCHOOL NEW LIFE
 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- KEMPER-SAVED-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY OSCAR AVILA, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOONVILLE, Mo. _ This year's graduates of Kemper Military School
and College received more than diplomas from school President
Edward Ridgley on Saturday. They also earned his gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   At the school's commencement, hundreds officially learned that
Kemper's 156th graduating class would not be its last. By
bombarding alumni with written pleas, students helped raise about
$650,000 in the last two weeks, enough to keep Kemper open for the
next academic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for me,'' Ridgley said, his voice
breaking. ``Your actions and conduct over the last two weeks have
proven a great example for all of us. You inspired me and many
others. For that, I thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will proudly move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridgley's announcement turned what could have been a sad final
chapter for Kemper into a day of celebration at the oldest military
school west of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper's crisis was made public May 1, when officials announced
that the school would close unless it raised $1.3 million. Students
wrote hundreds of letters and posted pleas on the schools Web site,
www.kemper.org.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account the recent fund raising, the board of
trustees voted unanimously Friday to keep the school open. The
school plans a reduced summer schedule but a full academic year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials offered few details on how the additional $650,000
would be raised but said some expenses would be cut. In addition,
they think that, based on the success of the students' fund
raising, more donors will come forth.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of the reprieve began circulating Friday night, but the
official word did not come until the graduation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday students _ most dressed in dark-blue coats, pressed
white slacks and shiny black shoes _ marched crisply to their seats
as the commandant barked orders. They saluted as they passed school
officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the ceremony, an officer shouted, ``Dismissed!''
Students immediately hurled their hats to the heavens. The band
broke into a lively song, punctuated by gun salutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These students have a lot of soul,'' said graduate Andrew
Kulas of Titusville, Fla. ``I knew they would pour out all their
blood, sweat and tears to keep the school open.''
</P>
<P>
   Students, alumni and officials said the crisis had strengthened
the ties among the Kemper community. Tradition is never far away at
the school, where plaques commemorate alumni known as ``old boys.''
Even first-year students can rattle off a list of prominent
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ike Skelton, a graduate of Wentworth Military Academy
in Lexington, conceded in his commencement address that after the
announcement, ``anything I have to say today is anticlimactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Skelton urged the students to keep their tradition alive and
never back away from doing their duty in life.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Mackey of Kansas City, a first-year junior college
student, said he thought it was his duty to help keep the school
alive.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled seeing boxes of letters to alumni in the school's
mailroom. At Kemper, he said, he feels part of something important.
The sacrifices of previous students are never far from his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our duty to uphold the standards they set,'' Mackey said.
``It was our duty, and our privilege, to keep the school open for
them. It's also for the students coming 10 years down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   John William Rhodes III, a 1961 graduate, does not know any of
Kemper's current students. His son graduated in 1989, but he
considers all of Kemper's students part of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes came to Boonville this weekend from Grand Rapids, Mich.,
with the assumption that Kemper would close. His mother died
recently, and he had hoped to honor her by establishing a
scholarship at Kemper. Because of the possible closure, he feared
he would never get that chance.
</P>
<P>
   He thanks the current students for giving him the opportunity.
Now he plans to repay future students with the scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not know them, but we all feel the connection of
Kemper,'' Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes said he hated Kemper at first but now loved the school
deeply. That is a common sentiment among students and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Pieper, the high school's valedictorian, said she clashed
with teachers in her early days. But she said that rebellion had
turned into respect for Kemper, especially in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was once in my prayers that Kemper would close,'' she told
the crowd. ``I now pray that it will always remain open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
