r a BC-MOMS-MARCH-KAN &LR;      05-13 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS-MARCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCHING MOMS SEEK TO UNLEASH COLLECTIVE CLOUT ON CONGRESS  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY By DAVID GOLDSTEIN, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mother's Day or not, the Republican-led Congress is
unlikely to give the moms gathered in Washington today what they
want _ tougher gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind how many thousands show up.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a year brimming with causes and marches. How long
will the political voltage last after the TV cameras are turned off
the Million Mom March?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a recent poll shows two out of three women think
gun control is more important than the rights of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Up there in the Capitol, current gun legislation is tightly
corked. Any congressman swayed by the movement on the mall can
expect a flush and angry National Rifle Association to write checks
for their opponent this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the so-called soccer moms _ suburban Republican
and independent women _ voted Democratic in 1996, as did the
so-called waitress moms _ blue-collar women _ in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It is two years later, and guess who is worried about how women
voters _ particularly the married ones _ are leaning? Al Gore, the
Democratic candidate, despite his calls for strict, new gun
measures.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, President Clinton rooted for the mothers and their
cause, contending that the gun lobby ultimately would be ``no
match'' for their passion and organization. But he warned that the
``nationwide fight won't be over tomorrow, no matter how many
match.''  &LR; brk:Hoping for an effect
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to save lives, march supporters argue.
</P>
<P>
   But if even new gun laws do not materialize, perhaps political
power will.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous power once a collective of women set
their minds to change something, especially when they feel it is
related to the safety of their family,'' said Swanee Hunt, director
of the Women and Public Policy Program at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the voices heard today will be those of mothers who have
lost family members. Others will express fear that their own
children could become victims of random gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   But with each public shooting _ in a school, an office or a
restaurant _ the emotional debate and polarization grow more
intense.
</P>
<P>
   Require gun show background checks, many demand. Enforce the
laws we have now, others say.
</P>
<P>
   As the marchers gather on the mall, a gun rights group, the
Second Amendment Sisters, will be staging a counterdemonstration
nearby. Its keynote speaker will be Suzanna Gratia Hupp, a Texas
lawmaker who lost her parents when a gunman killed 23 persons in a
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   And Barbara Ledeen, executive director of the Independent
Women's Forum, a nonpartisan policy group, views the Million Mom
March as a ``cynical manipulation of women's desire to protect
their children.''
</P>
<P>
   The march organizers look to Mothers Against Drunk Driving,
which started out as a small, grass-roots group by one mother whose
daughter was killed by a drunk driver. It has caused a sea change
in attitudes toward drinking and driving, ushering in new laws and
limits on what is considered publicly acceptable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would never have thought of being able to defeat someone
because they voted against lowering the legal limit for drunk
driving, and now you can,'' said Celinda Lake, a Democratic
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control supporters also point to the defeat last year in
Missouri of a proposed law to allow the carrying of concealed
weapons. Women voters in Kansas City and St. Louis apparently
helped reject the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Lynn Martin, a Republican from Illinois, was less
convinced that the march would do all that its supporters
predicted. Martin, who voted against gun control in her decade in
Congress, also wondered whether the march, with all the hoopla
surrounding it, was ``turning into a kind of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   If the marchers can build momentum, said Harriett Woods, a
former Democratic lieutenant governor from Missouri and veteran
women's political activist, ``they could have a tremendous
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, it could be like the Million Man March,
which was a one-day sensation.''  &LR; brk:Powerful voting bloc
</P>
<P>
   This year it is the so-called supermoms _ women juggling work
and children _ who could decide the election.
</P>
<P>
   White men have tended to vote Republican in recent elections,
leading Democrats to rely heavily on the gender gap. `` Women's
issues,'' such as education, health and safety worked well for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush appears to be upsetting those
equations. His approach of ``compassionate conservatism'' on issues
from schools to Social Security has neutralized Democratic attacks
on his record.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has strong support among mothers in general, while Gore
does best among unmarried, retired and minority women. A Los
Angeles Times poll last week showed Bush leading by two points
among women, by 15 points among men.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and gun control advocates have tried to paint Bush as being
in the NRA's pocket. He signed a bill allowing concealed weapons in
Texas and does not favor lawsuits against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has retaliated, again alleging hypocrisy by Gore, who was
more supportive of the NRA as a senator from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's stance on guns _ from a proposed ban on Saturday night
specials to a call for photo licensing of handgun purchasers _ is
one reason he appears to be driving away white men voters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a survey by the Pew Research Center showed a
sharp increase in men favoring gun rights over regulation, probably
a reflection of campaigns by Second Amendment proponents.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush announced in a televised interview Friday that Texas
would begin to distribute free trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys show Bush is ahead among women voters on
education, which Republicans believe is a bigger advantage than gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, said Dana Bartimus, the Million Mom March coordinator for
Kansas and Kansas City. Women are ``much more likely to jump ship
for one party or another if a candidate speaks to the cause that
really touches them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in voting for education if you think your
child might be dead. That's the reality. That has scared women down
to their very core.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
