<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-MAPS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS HIGHWAYS AND ROAD MAPS ENGENDER PASSION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Now comes the summer season, travel, and the
chore of folding and unfolding the Kansas Department of
Transportation's outsized highway map, the guide to Interstate 70,
U.S. 281, Kansas 156 or even some solitary back road.
</P>
<P>
   The map has blue highways, which indicate paved county roads.
Purple _ unpaved. Black and red _ U.S. and state routes. Green _
interstates. Gold _ the Kansas Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   An attractive map. Colorful, functional, informative. Although
sometimes awkward.
</P>
<P>
   For some, though, the map is an instrument of impending doom.
Especially out-of-staters who view the passage across Kansas as
equivalent to spanning the Stygian creek or running, over and over,
the movie version of ``In Cold Blood,'' with its endless highways,
flat land and telephone poles. Kansas, for some, is to be endured.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Richie Kennedy, a senior studying computer science at
the University of Kansas here. Want to know about Kansas roads? Ask
Kennedy. He knows where they are.
</P>
<P>
   All of them.
</P>
<P>
   And more.
</P>
<P>
   Take Kansas 96, favored by generations of drivers to go from far
southeastern Kansas all the way to Tribune on the far western edge
of the state. This year the eastern half of Kansas 96 was lopped
off the map and replaced by a new designation called U.S. 400. Now
Kansas 96 runs only west of Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy knows something about Kansas 96 most don't. Its
designation comes from a telephone number, specifically that of
F.W. ``Woody'' Hockaday's auto parts store in Wichita back in the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Before seven-digit dialing and area codes, Wichita
``automobilists'' asked the central operator for ``96.'' Hockaday
provided everything from a Model T's planetary gear to upholstery
for a rumble seat,
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Hockaday, incidentally, is voluminously chronicled
at the State Historical Society in Topeka. He bought the first
ticket at Kansas City's new Union Station, marked Kansas roads at
his own expense (his ``H'' signs cleverly led back to his
emporium), once tried to jump in a car carrying President Franklin
D. Roosevelt so he could ``shine his shoes'' and died in a Missouri
sanitarium in 1947, age 63. His name was put forth in the 1950s as
one fitting for the new toll road between Kansas City and Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   So Kennedy knows that. Then there's Kansas 1, a route most
Kansans don't even know exists. Kansas 1 runs 13 miles north from
the Oklahoma border, through the wondrously named hamlet of
Buttermilk, and to just south of Coldwater in Comanche County.
Kansas 1, says Kennedy, was once far more conspicuous on Kansas
road maps, running all the way from Oklahoma to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Does Kansas 12 strike a bell? A few years ago Kansas 12 was
supposed to carry motorists from Interstate 435 west to Kansas 7.
That plan was axed when the Department of Transportation turned
over the road to Shawnee, which called it Shawnee Mission Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, according to Kennedy, Kansas 12 once spanned the state from
Cherokee County in the southeast to Morton County in the southwest
and was a feeder route for the Dust Bowl refugees heading west in
their old jalopies, looking for work and a better life. In the
1930s, Kansas 12 was renamed U.S. 160.
</P>
<P>
   Then, says Kennedy, there's Kansas 238, a true oddity. When the
Missouri river flooded in 1951, it left behind an oxbow called
Browning Lake. To get to St. Joseph's Rosecrans Memorial Airport, a
motorist must take U.S. 36 to west Elwood, Kan., turn north on
Kansas 238, cross the oxbow and re-enter Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy thinks that Kansas 238 is an example of how road maps
aren't just large pieces of paper with colored print on them. Road
maps, he says, are stories.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kennedy is the first to admit that a zeal for Kansas
highways is hardly on a plane with presidential politics, the
latest Hollywood epic, or a $360 million-dollar lottery drawing,
events that fascinate the media.
</P>
<P>
   But then Kennedy subscribes to the theory that lots of people
have other, interior lives than the ones they're pigeonholed with.
While he intends to make a living from computer science, he says
he'll still have a zest for roads, road signs, trains, sports, and
the ins and outs of local radio.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Kennedy has created a good-sized Web site,
www.route56.com, that showcases his avocations.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the site is revealing, The 20-year-old Lawrence
native admits to being taken by U.S. 56, (old 50-North) that cuts a
bias across Kansas from Mission Hills to Elkhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the green signs,'' said Kennedy. ``Years ago
they experimented with white numbers on green signs, then went to
black on white. I still think the green signs look a whole lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   On Kennedy's Web site the armchair motorists can type in a route
number and see where it goes, what counties it passes through, what
roads it intersects with, view photographs and find a smattering of
the history behind the road.
</P>
<P>
   Such as Kansas 10, the Lawrence to Kansas City road for those
who want to avoid tolls on the Kansas turnpike. Kansas 10 once ran
all the way to Herington in the middle of the state. And parts of
it were north of the Kansas river.
</P>
<P>
   Or U.S. 24. It used to be U.S. 40 North. U.S. 69? For a number
of years it was U.S. 73 East.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also likes what he calls remnants, such as Kansas 8. On
the map that road is clearly visible northwest of Smith Center,
where it runs 16 miles from Kensington to the Nebraska border. But
look down at the bottom of the map, Kennedy says, and there's a
tiny, 1.7-mile-long stretch of road _ also numbered Kansas 8 _
running from Oklahoma to the town of Kiowa.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, reveals Fred Holthaus, a cartographer for the
Transportation Department, the state is limited to 10,000 miles of
road by legislative statute. That's a lot of roads _ the third-most
in the nation _ and it takes some jiggling to keep the mileage at
that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Add a road, and we have to turn the old road over to a county
or city,'' he said. ```But usually it works out about even. We
build a bypass, say, around Pleasanton, and we take off the road
that used to pass through town.''
</P>
<P>
   The only exception to the 10,000-mile rule, adds Holthaus, are
roads to state lakes. They are exempt from the count.
</P>
<P>
   The longest state routes are Kansas 4 and Kansas 9, both
starting in Atchison County and running well over 300 miles out to
western Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   And the shortest route? That honor goes to Kansas 247 at Ellis,
which is 649 feet in length from I-70 to the Ellis city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's the kind of stuff Kennedy and the thousands who have
visited his Web site like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spend some time on it,'' said Kennedy, ``and you'll never get
lost. I guarantee it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
