f a BC-COS-SURGERY-KAN &LR;      05-13 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COS-SURGERY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS BECOME MORE EAGER TO UNDERGO COSMETIC SURGERY  
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JULIUS A. KARASH and JOYCE SMITH, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Spurred by rising disposable incomes and an
ongoing obsession with youth, more and more Americans are climbing
onto surgical tables for face lifts, liposuctions and other
cosmetic surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Demand more than doubled between 1997 and 1999, to 4.6 million
surgical and nonsurgical procedures, according to a survey by the
American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And while women account for the great majority of cosmetic
procedures _ 89 percent were performed on females in 1999 _ men and
even teen-agers are growing markets for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Geraghty, a Kansas City plastic surgeon, said the surge
in cosmetic procedures was largely due to greater awareness by
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are articles and advertisements for cosmetic surgery in
every magazine and newspaper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening in Overland Park, Kan., more than a dozen
people showed up for wine, hors d'oeuvres and a cosmetic surgery
seminar presented by plastic surgeon John Michael Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn showed his audience before-and-after slides of patients
who had undergone procedures such as breast implants, breast
reductions and liposuction, or the removal of fat.
</P>
<P>
   Such procedures can lift a person's self-esteem, Quinn said. ``I
think it's important that, six months or six years down the road,
you feel that you got your money's worth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we care to admit it or not, looks are a major component
of our everyday decisions on how we spend our money. And Madison
Avenue knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers take these 16-year-olds and make them look like
they are 21, and even then they are airbrushed,'' said Georgianna
Reid, who operates an international cosmetics company in Kansas
City. ``Then they go crazy over them. Why, after a certain age, do
they make us feel like we are over the hill?''
</P>
<P>
   Some worry that too many consumers are getting cosmetic surgery
for the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Zerbe, a psychiatrist and professor at the Menninger
Clinic in Topeka, Kan., said interest in cosmetic surgery was
``certainly related to our youth-obsessed culture. We all want to
be one of those 50 most beautiful people on the cover of People
magazine, and we're not going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Zerbe said some of those seeking cosmetic surgery were afflicted
with body dysmorphic disorder, an obsessive preoccupation with an
imagined or slight defect in appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetic surgery industry frequently generates controversy.
While people seldom die in cosmetic surgery, some tend to look at
such deaths differently than, say, someone dying in heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This difference in outlook occurs because cosmetic surgery is
the patient's choice, Geraghty said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week women's health advocates sharply criticized a
government ruling that saline-filled breast implants made by two
California companies could stay on the market despite warnings that
they broke open at ``alarmingly high'' rates.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said statistics were limited regarding medical
complications that resulted from cosmetic surgery. In 1998 the
group now known as the American Society of Plastic Surgeons
reported that out of 24,295 liposuctions performed by
board-certified plastic surgeons, there were 70 cases that involved
significant complications, representing less than 0.3 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing legions of cosmetic surgery patients point up
that many of us flinch when we see wrinkles and bulges in our
mirrors. More and more, we are willing to get our skin stretched
and our fat sucked out to improve the way we look.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bottom was about an inch or two lower than it was 10 years
ago, and I had a little paunch,'' said Shawn Bergen, a 38-year-old
Prairie Village, Kan., resident who recently had body contouring
and upper eyelid surgery. ``They were minor flaws, but they
bothered me.''
</P>
<P>
   Advances in techniques, such as laser technology for skin
resurfacing, have blossomed amid the bumper crop of cosmetic
surgery patients. Geraghty said that laser technology was less
painful and was safer than older methods, and that patients
recovered from it faster.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors include better overall surgical techniques that
use local anesthesia, Geraghty said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the growing demand, more and more physicians are
performing face lifts, eye lifts, tummy tucks, liposuctions and
breast augmentations.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery,
some of the most popular procedures performed in 1999 were chemical
peels, laser hair removal, liposuctions, breast augmentations and
face lifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing growth in all segments of our cosmetic surgery
practice,'' said Thomas Faerber, an Overland Park cosmetic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is this work lucrative, with typical procedures costing
thousands of dollars, but those who perform them typically get paid
in cash because health insurance companies do not cover most
cosmetic surgeries. Some consumers take out personal loans from
companies formed specifically to finance cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   While some choose cosmetic surgery to feel better about their
appearances, such procedures also can help patients with
disabilities or those dealing with the impact of accidents or
cancer surgery. Other patients have business reasons to improve
their appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendant June Young, who had cosmetic surgery in Kansas
City, works in a youth-oriented industry and felt she would be
taken more seriously if she looked younger.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons are just personal. Some people have cosmetic
surgery because they feel they are aging much more quickly than
their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said she had cosmetic surgery to get rid of what she called
a ``tired appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Faerber said many of his patients were going through a major
change, such as a divorce or new job.
</P>
<P>
   And more men are going under the cosmetic knife, laser or
suction tube. Last year 11 percent of cosmetic procedures were
performed on men, according to the American Society for Aesthetic
Plastic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Faerber said some men were doing this in response to competition
from younger men on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Other men just want to look and feel better. ``I was putting on
weight in areas that made me feel terribly uncomfortable, and I
couldn't take it off,'' said Steve Bolton, who owns a Kansas City,
Kan., engraving business with his mother and his sister.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton, 46, had liposuction in 1998. ``Right off the bat, I lost
7 pounds,'' he said. ``And I feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite many patients' being happy with their results, critics
still raise concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Peter S. Obetz, a Kansas City lawyer who specializes in medical
malpractice cases with the firm of Bartimus, Frickleton &AMP; Presley,
said prospective patients ``should not be swayed by a physician's
yellow pages ad or by the appearance of their building. You can
have a flashy, beautifully decorated building in a nice
neighborhood, and that doesn't necessarily mean you're going to get
good quality care.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some members of the industry say they are bothered by some
marketing strategies. Some of that marketing is geared toward
teen-agers, who currently represent only a small percentage of
cosmetic surgery patients.
</P>
<P>
   Geraghty said he was opposed to breast augmentation or
liposuction being performed on teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a travesty,'' Geraghty said. ``They haven't lost their
baby fat. They're not at their height of maturity physically and
mentally and emotionally. And if they have a complication, it would
be very hard for them to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Geraghty decried what he called the ``sleazing'' of
cosmetic surgery. By that, he said, he means ``false advertising,
too much hype, selling unnecessary procedures to patients and being
driven by the dollar rather than a good surgical result.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons themselves caution prospective patients not to expect
too much from cosmetic procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone puts too many expectations on the surgery, that can
be disappointing,'' Faerber said. ``It can make them feel better
about their appearance, but it won't guarantee them a new job or a
new spouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
