<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LOCKERBIE-MOTHER-BOS &LR;      05-13 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A WINDSWEPT SCOTTISH HILL, MOTHER RECALLS LOST CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE, Scotland _ Sarah Philipps and Julianne Kelly fell to
earth here, on a wee hill that the local folk call Powhaffet.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Dec. 21, 1988, when a terrorist bomb blew apart
Pan Am Flight 103, Philipps and Kelly, college roommates, were
hurtled into space, 31,000 feet above the ground, strapped into
their seats.
</P>
<P>
   While the 257 other passengers and crew were each scattered,
alone, into the troposphere, Sarah and Julianne, two self-described
Boston girls, remained strapped side by side, falling silently
toward the sleepy town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   Across the North Sea, less than 1,000 miles away as the crow
flies, the two men accused of planting the bomb that killed the the
259 people on board Pan Am Flight 103 and 11 people on the ground
in Lockerbie are standing trial.
</P>
<P>
   The legal proceedings, held at a former US air base in the
Netherlands, seem a world away from the sheep pasture where
Philipps and Kelly came to rest, face down in the frost-covered
grass, their seats on top of them.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Philipps, Sarah's mother, sat through two weeks of
testimony at Camp Zeist, her emotions on a roller coaster. She
stared at the two suspects, reputed intelligence agents of Libya
whose motive is said to be an abiding hatred of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She took notes and tried not to take it personally when Bill
Taylor, the chief defense counsel and Scotland's most prominent
defense lawyer, suggested that the suspects should be acquitted
because authorities had not done a good enough job sealing off the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   But here, at that very crime scene, Elizabeth Philipps seemed at
peace with herself and that awful night more than 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She comes here every year, usually with her husband and two
sons. But Saturday she was alone, pulling on her wellies and
tramping across the hilly moors for more than a mile until she
reached the precise spot, amid bleating sheep and singing larks,
where Sarah and Julianne landed. It is a pilgrimmage as sacred to
her as any Muslim's walk to Mecca, as any Christian's visit to the
Holy Land, as any Jew's touch of the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah was from Newton, Mass., and Julianne from Dedham, Mass..
They were 20 and did everything together on the Syracuse University
study-abroad program in London. They lived together. They went to
museums and galleries together. They took the train up to Edinburgh
together.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in the middle of this pasture, a cairn, a mound of
stones, which marks the place where Sarah and Julianne came to
rest. It is a traditional memorial, a marking suited for the
windswept moors where Scottish rebels once built cairns for their
warriors who had died at the hands of the English.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Elizabeth Philipps knelt and began rebuilding the
cairn, partially collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think it would be taller,'' she said. ``But when it's
windy, the sheep lie behind it for shelter, and they knock it
over.''
</P>
<P>
   She used scissors that friends from Lockerbie, Bill and Jess
McTaggart, had lent her to trim back reeds that have obscured the
cairn. She paused to listen to the larks. Whenever she comes here
the larks sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nicer than a graveyard,'' Elizabeth Philipps said,
tossing the reeds into a pile.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, nine miles away, she had placed a bunch of roses at the
gray wall with black names that forms the Garden of Remembrance.
Sarah Susannah Buchanan Philipps' name is mispelled on the wall.
There is a ``z'' instead of a second ``s'' in Susannah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it our Scottish variant,'' Elizabeth Philipps said,
shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Philipps walked over to a headstone for Sarah and
placed a dime and two Dutch coins at its foot. Five fir trees
stand, like sentinels, on either side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah was always looking for money,'' she said, offering a
mother's explanation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Shakespeare sonnet on Sarah's headstone: ``Shall I
compare thee to a summer's day.'' Elizabeth Philipps likes it
because it contains a line that suggests as long as that poem
lives, ``so too shall you live.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall, Sarah's name is next to Alex Lowenstein's. Sarah
and Alex met on the study-abroad program. They liked each other.
They were flying home on the same flight. A year after they died,
Ervin Philipps, Sarah's father, went to a gathering of victims'
families and stared hard at a man he recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Lowenstein,'' Erv Phillips said to a friend he had not
seen since they were children in Manhattan. ``What are you doing
here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a son on the plane,'' Peter Lowenstein replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a daughter,'' Erv Philipps answered, before the two men
fell silent, unable to say any more.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, the authorities returned the journals that
Sarah and Alex had kept. Both had written fondly of each other.
There was a spark. Both died not knowing their fathers were
childhood friends.
</P>
<P>
   An act of barbarity brought Elizabeth Philipps here for the
first time, but it has been the humanity of this place that has
kept bringing her back. The people of Lockerbie are decent folk.
Ladies in the town ironed the rumpled clothes of the dead that had
been recovered from the fields, trees and rooftops. The women
mailed the clothes back to America, with humble notes, apologizing
that it was all they could do.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Philipps has never felt sorry for herself, has never
asked why Sarah, why their family. She struck up a correspondence
with a newspaper columnist whose college student son had thrown
himself to his death from a dormitory window while under the
influence of LSD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envy you,'' he told her, ``because you have the other
families. I feel so alone.''
</P>
<P>
   If she feels alone in the pasture where her daughter died,
Elizabeth Philipps doesn't show it. She sometimes fights back
tears, and sometimes talks to her daughter, the chit-chat they
loved to exchange in their kitchen back in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   A jet flew overhead, on its way from Heathrow to America, as Pan
Am Flight 103 did nearly 12 years ago. As the jet's dull roar
faded, the only sound was the wind, which sometimes sounded like
waves lapping up against the shore, and the larks, who always grace
Elizabeth Philipps with song.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Sarah's hill,'' she said, turning to survey the land
where her baby, her youngest, fell. ``She died here, next to a good
friend, surrounded by good friends. This is Sarah's hill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
