<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0514-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Straight Talk Express back for one night
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They surrounded him: USA Today, The Washington Post, U.S. News &AMP;
World Report, the Houston Chronicle, the Chicago Tribune, the
Philadelphia Inquirer, The Associated Press. Heck, even Weekly
Standard writer Tucker Carlson, fresh from captivity in Vietnam
(where he was briefly detained while traveling with McCain), was
there.
</P>
<P>
   Over smoked salmon, veal and just-done filet, the one-time
denizens of the Straight Talk Express leaned in. . . . Would he
confirm the story or wouldn't he? That he would he endorse his
former rival the very next morning.
</P>
<P>
   He did confirm it, of course. And it seems somehow fitting that
Sen. John McCain, the man who granted virtually unprecedented
access to political reporters, decided to dine with them the night
before his much-touted meeting with Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters gathered at the Carlton, a swanky-enough
Pittsburgh restaurant, along with McCain, Rick Davis, the former
campaign manager advising Bush, political director John Weaver,
spokesman Todd Harris, administrative assistant Mark Salter and
campaign aide Lanny Wiles.
</P>
<P>
   After McCain said good night, the hardiest souls headed across
the street for more drinks in the chandeliered lobby of the Westin
William Penn Hotel, scene of the next day's summit. Even Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer, who crashed and then never seemed to stop
spinning, was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   McCain hasn't ruled out another run for the White House. He made
it clear in an e-mail sent Wednesday to the approximately 120,000
folks on his database that he remains committed to being ``the
torchbearer of the reform crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Monday night feel poignant for message man Harris, like
it was the end of something?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to me,'' he said. ``It didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   STATES DIVIDED OVER PRIMARY PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders set up a battle between big states and small
states over the GOP's primary calendar last week, in a dispute that
could result in a floor fight at the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   The approval by the Republican National Committee's Rules
Committee is the first step toward party acceptance of a
population-based plan for presidential primaries and caucuses. It
calls for voting to begin with less populous states and relegates
the largest to the back of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   The committee agreed on starting dates for the four groups of
states in the inverted pyramid plan. The smallest could vote no
earlier than the first Tuesday in February with the other states
given start dates of the first Tuesdays in March, April and May.
The original time frame of March to June was moved up in response
to big-state opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several large-state leaders said the nomination race will
be over before their primaries or caucuses are conducted _ even
though 47 percent of the delegates would be chosen in the final
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a `big state vs. everybody else' battle. We feel we're
getting the short end of the stick here,'' said Ohio state Chairman
Bob Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Among other states voting against the plan were such political
powers as Texas, California, New York, Florida and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   SYNAGOGUE AT THE GRAND OLE OPRY?
</P>
<P>
   What if Jewish people wrote more country music?
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, speaking to a group of Jewish activists
last week, noted his presidential campaign is headquartered in
Nashville, Tenn., and dished up what he called the latest top
``Jewish country-and-western'' tunes to come out of Music City:
</P>
<P>
   No. 4: ``I was one of the chosen people until she chose somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 3: ``The second time she said `Shalom' I knew she meant
goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 2, ``I've got my foot on the glass, now where are you?''
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the No. 1 song title, Gore sang out: ``Mommas,
don't let your ungrateful sons grow up to be cowboys when they
could very easily just have taken over the family business that my
own grandfather broke his back to start . . . that doesn't mean
anything now that you're turning your back on such a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   WHITMAN APPARENTLY NOT ON SHORT LIST
</P>
<P>
   When Bush was asked about vice-presidential candidates in an
interview with the Lifetime women's cable channel Friday, he had
notably different reactions to two names, suggesting that he was
concerned about appearing too open to the idea of a running mate
who supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Elizabeth Dole, an opponent of abortion rights, was on
his list, he said that she was and then praised her as ``a good
friend of mine who has had a great career.'' But when asked about
Gov. Christine Whitman of New Jersey, who supports abortion rights
and whose selection would undoubtedly provoke many religious
conservatives, Bush's response seemed conspicuously restrained.
``There's a lot of people on the list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
