<HEADLINE>
METS RID OF RICKEY, BUT WOES REMAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New York Mets got rid of one major distraction
in Saturday's expected releasing of Rickey Henderson, but it
doesn't solve every problem on the team or in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who lost to the Atlanta Braves in the National League
Championship Series last season, went out and got lefty Mike
Hampton to bolster the staff and were expected to give the Braves a
fight in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mets are 19-19 and in fourth place. They trail
Florida and Montreal, and it's not just Henderson who's expressing
concern over what's transpiring.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Armando Benitez, who signed a four-year, $22-million deal
during the offseason, is off to a hideous start and was bypassed
for John Franco in a closing situation last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Benitez said. ``All I know is that
(manager Bobby Valentine) better respect me. I give (Valentine)
respect, and he better respect me, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would Bobby do that to me? I don't deserve that. I love
John and have nothing against him. But I don't think Bobby should
have got me up in the eighth and then have me sit down so somebody
else could save. What is that?''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Benitez allowed a grand slam to Preston Wilson,
who took his time rounding the bases and then jumped on home plate.
Wilson said he was delivering a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benitez always goes through his antics (a finger-snap), so I
made sure I did that,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mets grew tired of Henderson's act and got rid of
him after Saturday's loss to Florida. Earlier in the week,
Henderson said Valentine ``didn't have a plan'' to keep the Mets in
pursuit of the Braves and the Mets, ``aren't a family right now,
we're not a unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The already out-of-control issue spun crazily Friday and
Saturday. Henderson didn't run out a ball he thought was a home run
in Friday's game against Florida, and he caught heat from Valentine
afterward. Henderson said he'd do the same thing again.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, Henderson took umbrage to something
written in the New York Post about the at-bat and yelled at a
reporter. Henderson, who was hitting .219 with two RBI, was
released after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After considering everything that happened (Friday and
Saturday), something had to be done,'' Mets general manager Steve
Phillips told reporters in New York. ``I think the reasons are
fairly obvious. No matter how much talent you have, if you continue
to create problems and situations, you wear out your welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive offenses: Like nearly everyone else in the game,
Montreal manager Felipe Alou understands the number of runs being
scored in baseball is ridiculous. But he also knows where the
problem lies.
</P>
<P>
   It's not because there are bigger and stronger hitters, but
rather there is such a shortage of pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is pitching,'' Alou said. ``We are
desperate looking for pitchers everywhere. We look for them on
rafts washing up (on) shore in Florida. We're looking for them in
Korea, Japan, Australia. That tells you the whole story. Don't tell
me it's the juiced baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is not producing enough pitching. When we go
to Japan or Korea or guys defecting from Cuba, I never hear about
anybody looking for sluggers.''
</P>
<P>
   What pitch count?: Phillies ace Curt Schilling came off the
disabled list and, in his second start in his return from shoulder
surgery, pitched a complete-game shutout for his 100th career win.
He allowed 11 hits but threw 125 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up that if a pitcher has a chance for a shutout,
you want to give him a chance to go for it,'' Phillies manager
Terry Francona said. ``Because of the (rehab) program he went
through, he's probably prepared to throw more pitches now than any
of our other pitchers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
