<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA: PUDGE BEST CATCHER EVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Ivan Rodriguez was the MVP in the American League
last season, and he did it playing the toughest position in
baseball - catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Why he won the award was simply a matter of his overall effect -
offensively and defensively - on any given game.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia caught more games than anybody in
Dodgers history. He ended his career in 1994 while with the
Rangers, though he never got into a game with them. But he did have
a chance to work with a young Rodriguez, then 22 and already a
three-year major-league veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw how much pride he took in catching, you knew it was
just a matter of time,'' Scioscia said. ``We talked a lot about the
importance of handling pitchers and setting hitters up. He was
already on his way. There was no doubt he had the capability of
being a great catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez does it better than anybody now, but where does he
stack up all time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only talk about the guys I've seen, like (Johnny) Bench,
(Carlton) Fisk, (Mike) Piazza, (Gary) Carter and Lance Parrish,''
Scioscia said. ``Bench was the best from that whole group.
Comparing Bench and Rodriguez, Bench had more power. But when you
take everything into consideration, in my book, (Rodriguez) is the
best of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's durable - he's been doing it since he was 19, and he's
showing no signs of slowing down. As for calling games, John was
doing it at an early age. Pudge is acquiring that. They never had a
great pitching staff in Cincinnati, so it says a lot for what John
did for them.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Rodriguez stand out more than anything is his arm.
Opposing managers have to alter their game plan when Rodriguez is
behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the best arm I've ever seen,'' Scioscia said. ``And
that includes Steve Yeager. I never thought I'd see an arm stronger
than Yeager's, but Pudge is lights out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, at 28, still has 10 years or so left in his career,
and Scioscia says there is one more measuring stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pudge retires, it's important when we judge him to count
how many championships he has under his belt,'' he said. ``He's
capable of doing it. I just hope it's not at our expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorable save?: Texas' John Wetteland became the 12th pitcher
in baseball history to get 300 saves when he saved the Rangers'
13-11 victory Friday night over the Angels. But Wetteland probably
won't be eager to tell his grandkids about the milestone moment.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland entered the game with two on and two out in the eighth
inning, the Rangers leading 11-7. He gave up an RBI single to Darin
Erstad then got the third out when Adam Kennedy flied deep to
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers increased their lead to 13-8 in the top of the
ninth, but in the bottom of the ninth, Wetteland yielded a homer to
Mo Vaughn, a double to Tim Salmon and a homer to Garret Anderson to
make it 13-11. He finally got the save, but not before the Angels
had another baserunner and brought the tying run to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very fortunate,'' Wetteland said. ``I've worked this
hard for a save lots of times; there are 300 of them in my career,
so you're going to have a lot of these - even more than I care to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Next stop, Seattle: He's a future Hall of Famer who seems to
wear out his welcome everywhere he goes. But Rickey Henderson,
released by the Mets, could be headed for the Northwest and find
himself in another pennant race with the Mariners, who are short on
outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Rickey once before (in Toronto), and there were times
then when I thought he might be finished,'' Mariners GM Pat Gillick
told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer. ``Obviously, he wasn't. But
you don't know how much you are going to get from him. There's
always a chance that you could get a real good burst of 30 or 60
days, something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella was the Yankees manager when
Henderson made a stop in New York in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Twins manager Tom Kelly recently got his 1,000th
career win, all with the Twins. His most memorable? Win No. 96.
That was the win that clinched the AL West in 1987, Kelly's first
full season. ... Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez has only five
losses in 1999-2000, and two have come vs. the Devil Rays. Martinez
was beaten by Dave Eiland last season and Steve Trachsel this
season. ... Royals outfielder Johnny Damon had a streak of leading
off the first inning with a hit in 10 consecutive games. According
to the Elias Sports Bureau, it's the longest such streak in 25
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
