<HEADLINE>
CONTINENTAL RIFT IN CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for the kinder, more diplomatic Ryder Cup competition
that had been promised in the aftermath of last September's WWF
mentality at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Van de Velde, of all people, delivered a few salvos that
have torn apart the myth that the Europeans are able to compete
with the Americans in large part because of team harmony. What set
off Van de Velde was the naming of Mark James as an assistant to
captain Sam Torrance in 2001. Yes, the same Mark James who, as
captain last September, apparently lost his team roster and didn't
discover that Van de Velde, Jarmo Sandelin, and Andrew Coltart were
part of the team until Sunday's singles matches, at which time he
sent them out as sacrificial lambs against Davis Love, Phil
Mickelson, and Tiger Woods, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect me to be pleased at Mark James being involved in
the next Ryder Cup,'' Van de Velde said before the start of this
week's Benson &AMP; Hedges International, being contested,
coincidentally, at The Belfry, where the 2001 Ryder Cup will be
played.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde's criticism of James has been consistent for
months, but it took on added intensity when the Englishman was made
part of the 2001 picture. Ian Woosnam is the other assistant, and
having a trio of Brits is something Van de Velde doesn't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were six continental players on the team last year and
there have been many since 1979 who have played a big part in our
success,'' said the Frenchman, who is playing regularly in the US
this year and proving a huge hit with fans because of his humor and
accessibility. ``But there have only been three continental players
involved in the captaincy. We continentals think differently than
the Brits. You should have somebody there who understands us. We
are more fiery, more temperamental than the Brits.''
</P>
<P>
   James did take a huge gamble last September, not playing three
team members until the singles and thus wearing down key personnel
such as Jesper Parnevik, Sergio Garcia, Paul Lawrie, Lee Westwood,
and Darren Clarke. It was a gamble that backfired when the rusty
rookies went out early and got trounced, adding to the US momentum.
</P>
<P>
   While Van de Velde overlooks the fact that it is common for a
captain to lean on a countryman (Seve Ballesteros picked Spaniard
Miguel Angel Jimenez in 1997), he has a point. If Torrance has
Woosnam, why does he need a second? Particularly James, who managed
to alienate not only the three players he benched, but also
Bernhard Langer (who should have been the captain's pick over
Coltart to begin with) and Robert Karlsson (who was higher in the
standings than Coltart and also felt snubbed).
</P>
<P>
   Give Van de Velde credit, too, for speaking out in 1997 _ even
when he wasn't a team member _ for the shabby treatment afforded
Miguel Angel Martin. The Spaniard had earned a spot on the team,
but a hand injury gave Ballesteros an opening to oust Martin in
favor of Jose Maria Olazabal. After Van de Velde expressed his
displeasure, other European players followed suit, though Martin
was never returned to the competitive team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of this comes 16 months before the first tee ball
will be struck in the next Ryder Cup, and most likely the flap will
settle down. Torrance, for one, wishes it never started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would sooner Jean had come straight to me, rather than told
the world,'' said Torrance, who nonetheless defended his choice of
James. ``Let me say it is a European team: Woosnam is European,
James in European, and Van de Velde is European. I don't care about
personalities. I want them to play their best golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is all Van de Velde wanted to do in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed last year that the captain didn't have
trust in me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   My suspicion is the new captain won't, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Driver hits a red light
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers can get the meters running, because the first of
what figures to be many lawsuits was filed last week by Callaway
after the Royal Canadian Golf Association ruled that its ERC driver
was nonconforming, agreeing with the US Golf Association. The
controversial club, with a loft of 11 degrees, had been turned down
by the USGA, which cited the infamous ``springlike effect,'' though
Callaway has never tried to sell the club in this country. It has
been on sale in Japan and other parts of the world, where the
governing body is the Royal &AMP; Ancient, not the USGA. The R&AMP;A has
said it will examine the club further before rendering a decision.
Meanwhile, you have to wonder what to believe when one player
(Eduardo Romero) said he hit it 25 yards farther with the ERC while
Golf Digest released a study that reported a minimal difference.
The magazine recruited a PGA Tour player for its test, and he
delivered nine solid drives with a new ERC (9 degree loft) and nine
with the Callaway Hawk Eye; the ERC got about 7 yards more. Even if
Romero is to be believed, then the added distance didn't help him
much, for the Argentine made seven bogeys and a double bogey to
finish well down the list at last week's French Open. Apparently,
the ERC is of no help on the greens, where Romero needed at least
32 putts in three of the four rounds . . . Of course, if and when
the ERC silliness is settled, don't look for Laura Davies to grab
one. She played all 72 holes at last week's Philips Invitational
without once hitting a driver . . . Old-time New England names Joe
Carr, Bob Menne, and Jay Dolan are overseas this weekend, taking
part in the Irish Seniors Open. Bruce Fleisher also is taking a
week off from his American tour of duty to join Christy O'Connor
Jr. in the event at Tulfarris GC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bogey men
</P>
<P>
   We bring you the struggles of the young and old alike. The names
you will recognize _ Justin Rose and Ballesteros _ for they are
quite often making news for the wrong reasons. Rose, the teenager
whose dramatic near-win at the 1998 British Open prompted him to
turn pro, did not earn a spot in this weekend's Benson &AMP; Hedges _
and for good reason. He has missed the cut in eight of his last
nine starts and has qualified for weekend play just five times this
season in 14 attempts. His best finish? A 29th. Four times in 37
rounds he has shot 80 or worse, and as he approaches his 20th
birthday (July 30), he's got to be wondering how it all came
together so easily those four days at Royal Troon. Maybe, in
hindsight, it would have been better in the long run had it not
gone so well that year. As for Ballesteros, his round of 87
Thursday in the Benson &AMP; Hedges featured back-to-back triple
bogeys; most players at that level will play an entire season
without making two triples. He also finished with the dreaded
snowman (that's an 8, folks) on the par-4 18th. For the day,
Ballesteros made more bogeys or worse (nine) than pars (seven) . .
. Chad Campbell returned to the winner's circle at a Hooters Tour
event last week, giving him four victories in five weeks and five
for the season. The former UNLV star has earned $109,682.22, which
is $78,000 clear of the next best on that circuit. Old friend
Andrew Morse of Needham finished in a tie for 36th last week and is
well down the money list (49th, $4,690) . . . Officials at Augusta
National announced that they had donated more than $3 million to
various charities, including $1 million to The First Tee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senior circuit
</P>
<P>
   Paul Parajeckas, the head pro/superintendent at Woburn CC, will
play in a qualifier Monday for next week's Senior PGA Tour stop in
Kansas City. ``It's the hard road, but you have to follow your
dream,'' said Parajeckas, who turned 50 April 26. He's been the
most dominant club pro in recent years at the NEPGA level, or since
his friend Dana Quigley left to find fame and fortune with the
over-50 gang. And what advice did Quigley provide? ``He said to do
it, because you belong out here, but he said whatever happens (in
the qualifier), don't get discouraged because there'll be plenty
more chances,'' said Parajeckas, who figures he'll try at least
five and perhaps as many as seven of these Monday qualifiers. Only
three spots are available each week, with the fields sometimes as
deep as 144 players, which prompts Parajeckas to carry one thought
with him: ``Try and shoot 67 or 68 and win the thing.'' . . . The
titanium will be out in force Monday when 96 teams (that's 192
golfers) tee off in the 20th State Four-ball Championship at
Walpole CC. Dean Godek of Agawam Municipal and Alistair Catto of
The Orchards will try to defend their title (they also won in 1989)
against a stellar field that includes four-time winners Jon and
Carter Fasick. Other former champions teeing it up: Burton Page and
Ken Whalley (1985), Steve Tasho and Bruce Chalas (1988, 1994), Cy
Kilgore and Bill Jenks (1995), and Jim Ruschioni with son Jason
(1996) . . . Entries for the State Open topped off at 501, which is
about what the Mass. Golf Association expected given two factors
that worked against getting a lot of participants: 1. the handicap
index was lowered from 4.4 to 2.4; 2. the tournament will be at the
Country Club of Pittsfield, which eliminates many club pros from
Eastern Mass. since they can't commute and are unable to commit to
three days. Three former winners of the event _ Kevin Johnson,
Geoff Sisk, and Fran Quinn _ did not submit applications, choosing
instead to concentrate on their BUY.com Tour seasons . . . The New
England PGA's weekly television show will make its debut next
Sunday in three time slots: 7 a.m. on Channel 56, 11:30 a.m. on
Channel 10 in Providence, and noon on NESN. Pros throughout New
England will be profiled and offer instructions in the show's
10-week run . . . Some pretty hot stuff Thursday by the Quashnet
Valley duo of Bob Chase and Kevan Evangelista, as they combined for
a 63 to win the Cape Cod Chapter NEPGA pro-pro stroke-play event.
Evangelista carded five birdies in a six-hole stretch at Ballymeade
in North Falmouth. The next-best team _ Craig Garris and Mike
Ghelfi of the host course _ shot 69 . . . The University of Rhode
Island's men's team will make its fifth straight appearance in the
NCAA East Regional, joined by Yale and Dartmouth in the 27-team
field. The 54-hole competition starts Thursday at Glenmaura
National GC in Moosie, Pa. . . . The Cape Cod Open is scheduled for
June 7-8 at Olde Barnstable and Hyannis GC, and entries are due by
June 2. Check the Web site (ccopen.com) or call 508-775-1798 for
information.
</P>
</TEXT>
