<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT'S TIME UP IN INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reports are coming in from all precincts. Former players,
assistant coaches, secretaries, members of the sports information
staff, even family members. All are linked to Indiana University
coach Bob Knight, and from what we have been hearing over the past
several weeks, the linkage is not necessarily good.
</P>
<P>
   Knight is back home in Indiana, reportedly having cut short a
fishing vacation in the Bahamas to hear what the university's
trustees have to say about all this.
</P>
<P>
   The board will meet Sunday morning in Indianapolis and the
rumors are running rampant. It could come up with everything from a
dismissal to a reprimand to a shrug of the shoulders that life will
go on as it has for the past two decades at Indiana, where Knight
runs the show the way he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   Knight bashing has become popular. Knight threw a vase in the
direction of secretary. Knight attacked his son in a family
argument. Knight physically attacked his sports information
director. Knight kicked IU president Myles Brand out of practice.
</P>
<P>
   These stories have surfaced from time to time, and they are
usually followed by the opposing forces lining up against each
other. The Knight loyalists, apologists _ whatever you want to call
them _ talk about how Knight's players graduate and they don't
break the rules, two things often missing among the elite of
college basketball. His critics say he is a control freak, a bully,
and much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are right. Knight can also be charming and engaging
when he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   What he has been recently, however, has been mysterious. Even
his friends don't know what to make of the man now. Said one coach
who has known Knight and coached against him for years, ``I think
he's a good guy. I like him. But do I understand what he does, why
he acts the way he acts? I haven't a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line seems clear. At 59, Bob Knight still has many
productive years left in coaching. No one argues his basketball
acumen, which ranks with the game's best.
</P>
<P>
   But lately even that has come into question. One of the
trademarks of Knight's teams has been the ability to improve as the
season progresses, peaking in March when the NCAA tournament
arrives. All great coaches strive for that trait in their teams.
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Jim Calhoun has been particularly good at getting
his teams ready in March in recent years, a prime reason why the
Huskies kept closing in on the Final Four the past 10 years, a
trend culminating in their national championship in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for IU, March has been a one-and-done type of
affair lately, with the latest setback coming when the Hoosiers
were knocked out by Pepperdine, 77-57, in the first round this
year. That followed a second-round loss to St. John's a year ago, a
second-round loss to UConn the year before that, a first-round loss
to Colorado the year before that, a first-round loss to Boston
College the year before that, and a first-round loss to Missouri
the year before that.
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing is to see the difference in Indiana teams
from December, when they seem fresh and eager, as compared with
late February when they seem lifeless and dazed. It's almost as if
they are saying, ``We've had enough of this guy for this season.
Let's just end it and get back to normal college life.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight backers contend that the firestorm is completely outside
the program. Sophomore guard Dane Fife told the Indianapolis Star
last week that if Knight resigned or was fired, he would be gone
from Indiana almost as quickly. ``It's a done deal with me,'' Fife
told the Star. ``I came to Indiana University to play for Coach
Knight. If they force him out, I'm gone, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Knight will be gone when all of the meetings are
finished remains uncertain. He is not about to step down of his own
volition, as evidenced by his statement Saturday. And chances are
the trustees will not take the quantum leap and fire a coach who
has a record of 763-290 and has done it cleanly, while maintaining
the school's academic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   So that leaves IU, as has been the case when Knight's other
moves have become public, in a state of limbo. Only this time, the
focus is much more intense and the national outcry is louder that
the school must control someone who seems clearly out of control.
</P>
<P>
   What IU must understand is that it is still the dog in this
case, not the tail. Yes, Bob Knight has done some marvelous things
for IU and brought the school fame and a modicum of athletic
fortune. But he has also brought some more ominous, malodorous
debris on the school and its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   No one _ whether it be a president, a coach, or a sportswriter _
is bigger than a great country, university, or newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana needs to say goodbye to Bob Knight and move on, thanking
him for his contributions and looking forward.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup may be painful, it may be ugly. But it needs to be
done.
</P>
<P>
   For the good of Bob Knight, for the good of the players, and for
the good of the school.
</P>
</TEXT>
