<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-GASTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASTON SPECULATION NOT A HARD SELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is the business home of Paul Gaston, the man who
runs the show for the Boston Celtics. He has consistently,
unequivocally, and emphatically stated that he will continue to be
that man.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, are we hearing that he is at least listening more
intently to offers?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because he sees skyrocketing prices ($280 million for
the Mavericks and half of their new arena) and, well, he always has
said he has a ``fiduciary duty'' to stockholders, most of whom are
friends or family.
</P>
<P>
   But there also might be a legitimate basketball reason. We can
only speculate, but, a year from now, Gaston might well be without
a coach, without a basketball operations staff, and with the ideal
opportunity to cash in his chips.
</P>
<P>
   We know Larry Bird is interested in becoming part of a new
ownership group. He told the Globe that in February. He has
expressed an interest in building a team, another ``signal'' that
he's ready and willing. He has not given much of a hint as to what
he will do next season. Another ``signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston has said the team is not for sale, and Celtics financial
boss Rich Pond reiterated that position on Friday. But could Gaston
turn his back on $300 million or more? Would that be in the best
interests of stockholders? Would it take $400 million? There's a
lot of money out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul runs it as a business,'' Pond said. ``In that regard, if
someone came to him with an extraordinary offer, he would have to
consider it. But as far as I know, there's no real hard-and-fast
number on what that would be. I can't venture a guess as to what it
would be, but it would have to be more than Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that the Celtics do what we expect them to do next
season, which is to say they play hard but fall short of the
playoffs. (They did finish seven games behind No. 8 Milwaukee this
season.) Let's take Rick Pitino at his word _ always a risky
proposition _ and say that he leaves and takes his people with him.
What does Gaston do? Hire Brian Hill? Del Harris? Don Chaney? Bill
Hanzlik? Dick Motta?
</P>
<P>
   Gaston is, above all, a businessman. The Celtics would be a
mess. They'd be capped out and have limited trading opportunities.
But they'd still be the Celtics, which means $$$. That would seem
to be an ideal time to sell. The new group, with a reputable,
credible front man like Bird, would be given serious honeymoon
time, such as Michael Jordan is now getting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Celtics could get hot next season, make the
playoffs, fill the FleetCenter to the rafters, and Pitino would
stay right where he is. Which do you think is more likely?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After sale, you get change
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Grizzlies are under new ownership, and former
Pacers coach, Pistons assistant, and general gadfly Dick Versace is
actually running the operation. That's a scary thought. Meanwhile,
former boss Stu Jackson, who was on life support for basically the
whole season, jumped before he was pushed, landing a job in the NBA
office. ``Honestly, the whole year was bizarre,'' Jackson said.
``There were two sales. There were some real extreme circumstances
we had to deal with. There was uncertainty all season that
surrounded the team.'' How bizarre? Well, even before the second
sale to Chicago-area businessman Michael Heisley was consummated,
the new boss had his men scouting for the Grizzlies, even though
Jackson was still, theoretically, in charge of the basketball
operation. ``It was unnerving to see that,'' Jackson said. ``But
(personnel director) Larry Riley and his staff rose above all that
and remained dignified and professional. All my staff did. So did
the players and the coaching staff.'' Jackson said he knew there
would be major changes. ``That's part of the deal when you change
owners,'' he said. ``It would be abnormal for it not to happen.''
But the new boss has the same large problem as the old boss _
making a go of it in Canada. ``There are issues, big issues, in
Canada,'' said Jackson. ``The exchange rate is a major, major
deterrent. The players are paid in American dollars, but all your
revenue is in Canadian dollars. It's tough.'' Players also are
taxed at a higher rate in Canada, which the NBA always has
downplayed, comparing it to high-tax places like New York. ``They
can say that, but it's not the same,'' said Jackson. ``It's not
even close.'' The Grizzlies also are finding it hard to generate
revenue from broadcasting and sponsorships; Jackson said the team
is last in the league in both departments. He noted that Toronto at
least is a major corporate headquarters city, so it has the
advantage there in sponsorship money. Vancouver might as well be
Medicine Hat . . . In their playoff history, the Utah Jazz have
been swept, 3-0, by a No. 7 seed, lost another best-of-fiver after
leading, 2-0, and nearly blown a 3-0 lead to an eighth seed before
prevailing in seven games. But one thing they have never done is
get swept in a best-of-seven series. Unless something dramatic
happens in the Delta Center Sunday, that distinction will end.
Portland won the first three games of the series by margins of 19,
18, and 19 points. (Utah has lost its last 13 playoff games in
Portland.) The Blazers are making the Jazz look like a bunch of
grumpy old men, which, of course, is what they are. Even the
normally supportive Utah fans got frustrated in Game 3, during
which Utah fell behind by 21, rallied to tie the game, then
collapsed in the fourth quarter. There actually were boos directed
at the estimable John Stockton, which might have been a first. You
have to wonder what will happen to the team. Jeff Hornacek is
leaving. Stockton and Karl Malone will be back, another year older,
and the team historically has trouble attracting free agents. Then
again, speculating on the demise of the Jazz has been an annual
rite for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two MJs in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis to the Wizards? The New York papers were in a lather
last week over that possibility. Jarvis hosted a charity function
in New York and guess who was the featured speaker? None other than
Jordan himself, the basketball boss of the coachless Wizards.
(Wonder if MJ gets $50,000 a pop, like Pitino.) Jarvis interviewed
last year for the Washington job, which went to the
since-jettisoned Gar Heard. Jordan wants a coach in place before
next Sunday's lottery, even though the Wizards' pick, which
probably will be No. 6, will be assigned to the Bulls unless it's
in the top three. (Seasoned cynics figure the NBA will find a way
to get the Wizards into the top three as a favor to MJ and to keep
him interested.) . . . The Suns got a first-hand lesson in home
cooking in the waning seconds of their Game 2 loss to the Lakers at
the Staples Center, and it could have dramatically affected the
outcome of the series. With Phoenix leading by 1 point, Penny
Hardaway drove to the hoop and was taken down by the newly minted
MVP, Shaquille O'Neal. There was no call on a clear foul. The
Lakers then won the game on a great shot by Kobe Bryant. The Suns
went back to Phoenix down, 0-2. ``It's frustrating,'' said coach
Scott Skiles. ``All year long, we've had trouble getting to the
foul line for whatever reason. So I guess maybe that reputation is
hurting us or something, and we're just not getting them. That was
clearly a foul. But it's just one of those things. I mean, they can
point to plays that are clearly fouls on us. It's not like there's
any conspiracy or anything. It was just, in my opinion, a call that
should have been made.'' But it wasn't, and probably won't be, when
the MVP is deemed to be the perpetrator. Just ask Larry or MJ . . .
Have the Blazers finally turned it around and started to look like
the 45-11 team that opened the season rather than the 14-12 team
that finished? Center Joe Kleine thinks so. ``Definitely,'' he
said. ``I think our defense, even in the bad stretch, stayed
decent. We were still rotating and trapping pretty well, although
it's much better now. Offensively is where the big difference is.
We're moving the ball and executing so much better. Our spacing is
100 percent better. We're much crisper. Guys are getting open,
getting the ball, and knocking down the shot.'' Kleine is not on
the playoff roster; the team kept Gary Grant, fearing an injury to
backup guard Greg Anthony (who didn't miss a game all season). That
may come back to haunt them if they meet the Lakers in the
conference finals. Kleine represents a big body and, more
important, six fouls. ``It wasn't my decision,'' Big Joe said.
``I'm disappointed, but if that's the worse thing that happens to
me in my life, I should be OK.'' And it could be a good omen for
Portland. In 1997-98, Kleine appeared in 46 games for the Bulls.
But he was kept off the playoff roster and watched in civvies as
Chicago wrapped up the NBA title in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kicking football around
</P>
<P>
   Longtime basketball agent Steve Kauffman is branching out. He
represents Brian Urlacher, the New Mexico linebacker who was taken
by the Chicago Bears with the ninth pick in the recent NFL draft.
Kauffman says it's too early in the process to notice any
difference in bargaining, but he did note that the Bears are coming
out to see him at his Malibu office to talk contract. That's a
difference . . . You can't blame Minnesota for feeling jinxed. The
Timberwolves won 50 games, but that was good enough for only the
sixth seed in the talent-heavy West. (It would have tied for third
in the East.) They recorded the best record within their division,
going 18-6, including 6-2 against Utah and San Antonio. Then they
pushed Portland in four tough games; their three losses were by a
combined 15 points. And they're out in the first round for the
fourth straight year. ``There's no question there's frustration on
our part,'' says coach/GM Flip Saunders. ``We definitely want to
take that next step.'' . . . Pat Riley says he wonders when Jamal
Mashburn will start getting calls the way Allan Houston seems to
get them. In a bit of referee-baiting, the always calculating Riley
said, ``I don't think he gets the benefit of the doubt at all. I
don't think the officials look at Mash yet the way they look at
Houston. He gets manhandled and he's got to earn his. Everything
Allan gets is off a touch. You touch him, he's on the line. It's
probably going to take Mash a couple more playoffs before he gets
that kind of respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
