<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING THOUGHTS AND DISTRIBUTING THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emptying Out The Desk Drawer Of The Sports Mind:
</P>
<P>
   I'm not exactly the type who sleeps with the Daily Racing Form
under his pillow, but even I know that anything over 15 horses on
the track is stupid and dangerous. Are the people at Churchill
Downs waiting until they have a fatality or what?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody pulls up 15 feet ahead of the pack in a sneakaway
situation and launches a 3-pointer. Throw that scene out, and the
basketball segments of ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' ring pretty true.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason odds on Steve Trachsel throwing 17 consecutive
scoreless innings against Pedro and El Duque were about the same as
those of Drew Bledsoe leading the NFL in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that Conseco Fieldhouse in downtown
Indianapolis is the greatest place ever constructed in which to
play the sport of basketball. End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, let the record further show that despite the
presence of Camden Yards, Jacobs Field, and all the other new
cash-cow ballparks, Joe Average Fan has never been served better by
any park than Dodger Stadium these past 38 years. What? No luxury
boxes? Tough. The corporate bleeps, who cares about them?
</P>
<P>
   What was true in December is still true today. No team in the
NBA has more good players than the Portland Trail Blazers. Their
series with the Lakers could be an epic.
</P>
<P>
   Most underpublicized baseball shockeroo: Mike Mussina (career
.618 winning percentage) is 1-4 with a 4.78 ERA. He's only 31, and
nobody is saying he's hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   We here would argue Pedro over Randy, but who can deny that the
sight of an unshaven 6-10 guy, with his hair flying and a snarl on
his face, is the best show in all of baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Earth to Fred Hickman: Even if we follow your ``Where would the
Sixers be without Iverson?'' reasoning, please enlighten us as to
how far the Lakers would have gotten this year with John Salley and
Travis Knight at center. Face it, Freddy. You've made a fool out of
yourself for all sports eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Since everybody is now piling on in L'Affaire Bob Knight, it's
time for me to confess that I once saw him kick over a bench at
Madison Square Garden while he was coaching at West Point some 35
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I hereby propose a constitutional amendment to prevent Steve
Young from playing any more professional football.
</P>
<P>
   The following truths we hold to be self-evident: That expansion
_ not free agency, not arbitration, not anything else _ is the
single biggest reason for the aesthetic decline of our four major
professional sports, and that making freshmen eligible to play
college basketball and football was the single biggest mistake the
NCAA made during the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Shaq. I gotta admit that when a man quotes Aristotle when he
accepts his MVP award, it may be time to stop ragging him about
once having said, ``I've been a winner at every level _ except
college and pro,'' especially when he'll soon be rectifying Part B.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks vs. Heat: Iran-Iraq, with a dose of Hitler vs. Stalin on
the side.
</P>
<P>
   Leader in the clubhouse for Most Disgraceful Stat of the New
Millennium would have to be Toronto's six shots on goal in Game 6
against the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   If both Jason Varitek and Derek Lowe make the All-Star team
(it's certainly conceivable), does that make trading them for a
registered arsonist the greatest transaction since Seward bought
Alaska?
</P>
<P>
   Don't kid yourself. Bobby Orr knows that, absent Ray Lussier's
stunning photograph, his game-winning goal to complete a sweep of
an expansion team would be lucky to rate in his personal top 10
career highlights.
</P>
<P>
   What's even more aggravating about not having a Martin-and-Woods
duo to grace our summer afternoons and evenings is that neither one
of them would have a chance to succeed in today's homogenized
broadcast world.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone out there has a video of the young Arvydas Sabonis in
action, would you please make me a copy? He's still pretty good,
but what we're looking at now is 40 pounds, two Achilles' tendon
operations, and a rumored vat of vodka beyond the point at which he
was said to be a Bill Walton with 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Got no problem with Elton Brand and Steve Francis sharing Rookie
of the Year, but be advised that in five years the best player in
the Class of '99 may very well turn out to be Andre Miller.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me, you wallow deeper and deeper in self-pity
with each playoff-less NBA season. I'd give anything to be inside a
hot, sweaty, sizzling Garden for another May game with the Sixers
and June game with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilt 100-point basketball fiasco gives me a rush. There are
few more despicable areas of modern American life than the world of
sports memorabilia, and people who participate in it deserve to be
taken for a long, long ride.
</P>
<P>
   Attention, Bud Selig: I'd estimate that 30 percent of would-be
base stealers called out by umpires because the throw was in the
vicinity of second base are, in actuality, safe. Do something about
this.
</P>
<P>
   Is it just me, or is it possible they should get someone other
than sister Cheryl to interview Reggie Miller after one of his
boffo playoff performances?
</P>
<P>
   The single most inexplicable and aberrational baseball act in my
lifetime remains Tim Wakefield's 14-1 run five years ago. No
knuckleball pitcher ever has, or ever will, do anything like that
again, and I don't care if they play baseball for 5,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Mother's Day to Mary Ryan. I haven't forgotten how you
made sure I got to ballgames even after Dad died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
