<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-TROMBLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROMBLEY TROUBLED BY EIGHTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ His arm felt fine. He had his usual stuff, and even
on his best days, Mike Trombley freely admits, he's not going to
throw the ball past anyone. He lives by location, not power. When
he's on, he can mix up his pitches, hit spots, keep the hitters
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, it works.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday wasn't one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my loss out there today,'' said Trombley, after serving
up no fewer than three eighth-inning homers in the Orioles'
dispiriting 5-1 loss to the Red Sox. ``I mean, it was all my loss _
it wasn't anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Trombley, the pride of Wilbraham, Mass., entered with two outs
in the eighth, the fast-fading Orioles clinging precariously to a
1-0 lead. Mike Stanley stepped to the plate with a runner on first
and cranked Trombley's 1-and-0 breaking pitch over the left-field
wall. Red Sox, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung a curveball there,'' said Trombley. ``I was trying to
bring it inside, but it got over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme was established. Three pitches later, Scott Hatteberg
sent Trombley's 2-and-0 delivery screaming over the wall in left.
Red Sox, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a (splitter) that I wanted down and away,'' said
Trombley. ``Again, right over the middle of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   After then hitting Wilton Veras with a breaking pitch, Trombley
watched the weak-hitting Donnie Sadler knock a first pitch out of
the park, again over the wall in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fastball that I wanted to keep away from him,'' said
Trombley. ``Every one of them was over the middle of the plate.
It's tough to do that. If I went out there to throw batting
practice, I don't think you could give guys that many. But, hey, it
was me who was throwing 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   These are lowly times, once again, for the beleaguered
Baltimoreans. They have lost six straight, 10 of their last 11,
five straight in their beautiful ballpark. More people came to
Camden Yards Saturday (48,579) than for any regular-season game in
the park's eight-year history. Well into the top half of the
eighth, the Orioles were doing fine by the hometown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But in a hail of fat, soft-serve, silver-platter offerings (``I
all but put Stanley's on a tee,'' said Trombley), Baltimore saw its
record fall to 16-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the effort wasn't there, physically and mentally,'' said
Baltimore manager Mike Hargrove, Cleveland's skipper last year when
the Red Sox drummed the Indians out of the playoffs, ``I'd have
lost all my hair, and I'd be down four quarts of blood by now. It
just seems like every time we make a mistake right now, it gets
capitalized on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Trombley's case, it was a series of mistakes _ curve, sinker,
fastball _ that turned into rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one out away from heading into the ninth with a one-run
lead,'' said Hargrove. ``Then, before we take a deep breath . . .
five runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Trombley, 32, has almost seven years of big league service. He
signed here as a free agent after spending all his career with
Minnesota, with a lifetime mark of 30-33. Following his days in
Wilbraham, he went to Duke and then toiled four seasons in the
minors before making the Twins. He's known bad days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sent to the minors a few times in my career,'' he
said. ``So my confidence level has been low before, and, yeah, this
bothers me. I'm not going to lie and say I'm not disappointed by
what happened. That's as disappointing a game as I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day is still a couple of weeks away, but the Orioles
again are showing signs of sliding off the American League East
landscape. They've been outscored, 25-5, the last three days by the
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by the media after the loss, Hargrove was asked if
the latest defeat was the low point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know,'' he said. ``We haven't played tomorrow yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
