<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-NORMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN IS RIGHT ON THE NUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Here's a guy who's No. 1 on the planet, and protests that
he's not No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The name is Magnus Norman, a name that doesn't mean much even in
his homeland, Sweden. Nevertheless, he took over the tennis
penthouse Saturday _ denying even while ascending _ by crashing the
final of the Italian Open with a 6-3, 6-0, victory over Australia's
Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   That won Norman a championship date Sunday at Il Foro Italico.
He'll battle in the amber dirt against the titleholder from Brazil,
Gustavo Kuerten. Kuerten beat the 1997 champ, Spaniard Alex
Corretja, with weighty serves and massive forehands, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved,'' said Norman, perhaps the most outgoing Swede
ever to grace the courts. ``I thought about it a lot. I knew I'd
move into No. 1 if I won the match. But I'm not really No. 1. Not
with guys like Andre Agassi, Pete Sampras, and Yevgeny Kafelnikov
around. But I'm excited, thrilled to be in front.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like double-talk, it's because Norman and his
colleagues on the ATP Tour have begun leading double lives. Theirs
is now the brave, and maybe confusing, new world of the Champions
Race that began in January.
</P>
<P>
   For 27 years, the tennis standings/rankings were measured by
``Blinky,'' the ATP computer, based on results over a rolling
12-month period. That pecking order continues only as the entry
rankings list, telling a player where he stands in the matter of
getting into a tournament and where, if anywhere, he'll be seeded.
Everybody wears two numbers, and for Kuerten they're a little
different also: No. 6 in the race, No. 4 in the computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter respect, Norman is No. 3, behind Agassi and
Kafelnikov. But the Champions Race was instituted in the hope that
fans can follow the game on a daily basis, from beginning to end of
the season. Each win has a point value and counts in the day-to-day
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the hard-working Swede, toiling in his 11th tournament
(winning one, New Zealand), surged ahead of Agassi, a third-round
loser here to Slovak Dominik Hrbaty. Agassi had headed the mob for
11 weeks. Norman is the fifth to hold first place.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrice Santoro of France had a brief tenancy at the pinnacle,
one week, the first. Hewitt supplanted him for two weeks, then
Kafelnikov took over for four, followed by Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten can't bump Norman from the top by winning Sunday. But
his victory elevated him from eighth to sixth place.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a lanky 6 feet 2 inches, once fancied himself a pretty
fair hockey player. He was even better at the Scandivanian game of
bandy (hockey with a tennis ball substituted for a puck). But best
at substituting a racket for a hooked stick to slap huge forehands.
He will be 24 in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot but pleasant afternoon, he was a 62-minute disaster for
the 19-year-old Hewitt. Running the last seven games, winning 23 of
29 points in the second set (four of them aces), Norman reached
match point. There, a weary Hewitt squelched four match points. But
he was done in by a roaring forhand.
</P>
<P>
   Norman shook his head and said, ``They don't seem to care much
about me at home (even though he helped Sweden win the 1998 Davis
Cup). I haven't seen a Swedish reporter at any tournaments. Maybe
they were spoiled by so much success of Bjorn Borg and Mats
Wilander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was negative about the race when it was announced, but I
like it now. The lead will change hands but I'm going to try my
best to stay in first.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd help his cause by becoming the third Swede to win the
Italian, following Borg (1974, '78) and Wilander (1988).
</P>
<P>
   Corretja, dropping one position to seventh, said, ``The race
seemed strange at the beginning, but now I like it. The way Magnus
is playing, he is the true leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
