<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE TIED WITH HUSTON IN BYRON NELSON CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The harder Davis Love III tries to win, the more
difficult it seems to become.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting his worst round of the GTE Byron Nelson Classic, and
seeing a four-stroke lead disappear, Love was tied with John Huston
heading into Sunday's final round. Huston shot a three-under par 67
and moved to 10 under par for the tournament (200), even with Love,
who struggled to a 71.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Love's one-over-par round left the door ajar for a
host of pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik, who shot 68, moved to seven under par, just
three strokes off the lead. Phil Mickelson, who shot 68, was in
fourth at six under par, while three players were tied for fifth at
five under par _ Mark Brooks, Bob Estes and Paul Stankowski.
</P>
<P>
   All of them will begin Sunday in the hunt, while Love, who has
not won since April 1998, found himself in danger of squandering
another opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Since his last victory at the MCI Classic, Love has 25 top-10
finishes and six second-place finishes, but no victories. That is
enough to make any player lose confidence, but Love said he was
looking forward to Sunday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to shoot one over par, but this wasn't the kind
of day where I have to go back and wonder what's going on,'' said
Love, who started Saturday at 11 under par, four strokes ahead of
Huston. ``I drove the ball really well, and I made some putts. I
just didn't hit the ball close that often, and I misjudged a few
shots because of the wind. It was unbelievable how far the ball
went on some shots, and that made it difficult just to step up and
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another difficult scoring day on the TPC at the Four
Seasons, as the wind blew in the opposite direction from Thursday
and Friday and forced players to adjust. The front nine was
particularly tough, and club selection was an inexact science.
</P>
<P>
   How much did things change? On Friday, Parnevik reached the
green of the 390-yard No. 4 using a driver and a sand wedge.
Saturday at the same hole, Parnevik used a driver and a 5-wood.
</P>
<P>
   But Huston, a five-time PGA Tour winner, made just one bogey and
remained calm in the blustery conditions. He birdied the par-5 No.
7, made a 10-foot putt for birdie at No. 10, then hit a great sand
wedge to 5 feet at No. 11 to set up another birdie. That moved
Huston to nine under par, one stroke behind Love. And when Love
bogeyed the 14th hole, while Huston made a 15-foot putt for birdie,
Huston took a one-stroke lead for the first time in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   However, Love responded with a birdie at the par-5 16th hole,
hitting a splendid bunker shot to 2 feet on his third shot.
</P>
<P>
   Both players made par over the final three holes, and they will
be paired again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play well, I feel I have as good a chance to win as
anyone,'' said Huston, whose last victory came in October 1998 at
the National Car Rental Golf Classic at Walt Disney World in
Florida. ``When you haven't won in a while, it gets a little
harder. But you still have to play your game. With five or six
holes to go, you can't get caught up in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, Sunday will be a key moment for Love, with
players like Parnevik, Huston and Mickelson in pursuit, on a course
where the wind can be a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   Love has been waiting for a final round that ends with people
congratulating him, rather than consoling him. And he hoped that
his wait was almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil and Jesper got right back where they wanted to be, and
John did what he wanted to do _ catch up,'' Love said. ``It think
it will be a good race tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
