<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-NINERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS ZERO IN ON SACKING THEIR QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How is Bill Walsh going to fix the 49ers and decide what to do
with Steve Young and Jerry Rice if he can't even figure out who's
calling him on the phone?
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the San Francisco general manager said he had been
contacted by the NFL and been told the league was looking into
tampering charges against the Denver Broncos for allegedly having
illicit conversations with Young.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he said, ``Only fooling.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Walsh said, ``We feel it was
unfortunate that we brought the National Football League into this
matter. They have indicated no reason to explore this situation,
and we certainly accept their dictates. We acknowledge their
position that the Denver Broncos have not been in contact, directly
or indirectly, with Steve Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact of the matter is, Walsh doesn't want the aging quarterback
in San Francisco anymore, so why don't the 49ers cut the baloney
(which doesn't go well with wine and brie, anyway) and release
Young on June 1 to ease the salary cap problems his contract is
causing?
</P>
<P>
   Young, soon to be 39 years old, met last week with Walsh and
head coach Steve Mariucci to discuss his future.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has already said that Young will have to take a hefty pay
cut and pass two neurological exams because of his repeated
concussions, and still might not be brought back.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who recently married, says he's unclear on whether he'll
play next season but knows that if he wants to, there's a job for
him in Denver working for old friend Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci says, ``Gee whiz, I'll do whatever Steve wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Young would be safer in Denver than in San Francisco,
where the offensive line is full of holes. Young has lost some of
his legendary elusiveness and no longer can take a hit the way he
used to.
</P>
<P>
   So why is this dragging on?
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting last week, Walsh said, ``We're going to do
everything we can to have it work in Steve's best interest and
within the framework of the planning for next season.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded more than a little conciliatory, until he added
that keeping Young and Rice another year could be done but ``at a
terrible cost to the ball club. We might even be short players.''
</P>
<P>
   What Walsh is saying should be clear to someone as bright as
Steve Young. He's saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   What Young needs to do is stop trying to decide whether to
return to the 49ers and start trying to decide whether he wants to
play in Denver, because in the end that will be his only option.
</P>
<P>
   That or retiring to a rather good life as an attorney, unless he
just wants to retire to a golf course and live off the millions
he's made.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy with a lot of headaches, the last option seems the
intelligent way to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In suspense
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots remain interested in free agent defensive lineman
Mike Frederick, but their chances of landing him hinge neither on
the player nor on his former team, the Tennessee Titans. Frederick,
an unrestricted free agent, was offered a contract by the Patriots
for the veteran's minimum salary, $440,000, and given no deadline
to accept it. He continues to work out with the Titans voluntarily
after signing an injury protection form. Tennessee would still like
to keep Frederick. He accepts that he will be earning the minimum
wherever he plays, but wants to sign with the team that gives him
the best chance of making the final roster. In that regard, the key
to his future is neither the Patriots nor the Titans but rather
Tennessee's Josh Evans. Evans recently was suspended for a year by
the league for violating its drug policy. He has appealed, and he
and the Titans believe he has a strong chance of winning or at
least having the ban reduced. At the moment, Evans counts $2.4
million against the Titans' salary cap because of the appeal. If he
loses, that would be reduced by half, leaving Tennessee enough
money to sign Frederick and likely provide him a roster spot. If
Evans wins, however, he returns to the team and Frederick might
well decide to head for New England. The fact that Tennessee
drafted two defensive linemen is also a consideration for Frederick
. . . No one with the Patriots is saying much publicly, but running
back Robert Edwards reportedly is running again. Not like he used
to, but under 5.0 seconds for the 40-yard dash, according to a
source in the organization who should know. No one yet believes
Edwards will play next season, but that remains his secret goal.
The terrible knee injury he suffered more than a year ago probably
has ended his career, but you have to give him credit for trying.
And trying and trying. Maybe he'll pull it off in 2001 . . . Pity
poor Fred Miller. The ex-Rams offensive tackle, who signed a big
free agent deal with Tennessee this winter, is still haunted by the
five false starts called against him on national television last
October when he faced Titans rookie defensive end Jevon Kearse. At
last week's Titans mini-camp, he twice was called for the same
infraction and was forced to run extra laps. Looking on the bright
side, the only time he has to see Kearse now is in practice . . .
The Titans have yet to offer head coach Jeff Fisher a new contract,
although they insist they're working on it. Fisher has a year to go
on his present deal and has told friends if he doesn't have a new
contract by mid-June he's likely to coach out his final season and
take his chances on the open market. That would be wise, because
the new Houston entry wants to hire a veteran NFL coach, and what
could be better than bringing Fisher back to Houston, where he ran
the Oilers before Bud Adams moved them to Tennessee?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's caught on
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to become a star quarterback, but
indifference isn't usually one of them. But that was the case with
Super Bowl MVP Kurt Warner. In 1985, when Warner was a freshman at
Regis High in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, football coach Jim Padlock had a
problem: No one was trying out for quarterback. Lacking volunteers,
Padlock asked some guys to throw, and a tight end threw the
farthest. His name was Kurt Warner. To this day, Warner says he
never wanted to be a quarterback. He considered himself a receiver
until Padlock unlocked his future for him . . . NFL mania seems to
know no bounds, and the Dallas Cowboys are trying to cash in on it.
You now can go to the team's Web site and buy game-used shoes,
socks, and cleats, and a practice jersey of Emmitt Smith or Troy
Aikman. More than $100,000 in sales already has been rung up, with
the cheapest item being a $19.99 pair of Smith's socks. A pair of
his cleats is a far healthier $999.99, while Aikman's game shoes go
for $1,999.99 . . . Not every team would be happy to see its
running back report to mini-camp nearly 30 pounds heavier, but the
Bears reportedly are happy that Curtis Enis came in at 258 pounds,
up 28 from last season. The Bears believe the added bulk will help
him avoid the injuries that have plagued him since being drafted in
the first round in 1998 . . . Barry Sanders won another small
victory over the Lions last week when arbitrator Sam Kagel ruled
that Sanders does not have to pay Detroit interest on the portion
of his signing bonus he must repay because of his early retirement.
Under the ruling, Sanders owes the Lions $1.833 million by July 29.
In March, Sanders paid the Lions $83,000 for the 1999 season
because Detroit had withheld a $1.75 million payment to him. But
now he's into the Lions for big money, and some of his former
teammates believe that will drive him back to training camp this
summer . . . The Arizona Cardinals have decided to spare no expense
in trying to win. Finally. The team recently hired a nutritionist,
a physical therapist, two massage therapists, a chiropractor, and a
neuropsychologist. How about hiring some protection for quarterback
Jake Plummer instead? . . . The chances of Deion Sanders ending up
with the Washington Redskins increased last week when he walked
away from the Cincinnati Reds' Triple A affiliate in Louisville
after being asked to extend his stay there another 10 days. Sanders
insisted he had already done that once and wanted to return to the
big leagues. When the Reds refused to promote him, Sanders returned
to Dallas to continue rehabilitating his knee on his own. It is
expected that the Cowboys will release him after the June 1
deadline for salary cap reasons, and if he is free to play the
entire 2000 season without conflicts with his baseball job,
Washington is eager to hire him. The Reds are not going to release
Sanders, though, so unless he retires he could still return to
baseball next season if his surgically repaired knee is healthy.
What's oddest about this story is that Reds general manager Jim
Bowden, a big Sanders booster, doesn't believe he's healthy enough
to play every day for the Reds. If he can't play baseball, how is
he going to play football? . . . How's this for strange genes?
Cleveland Browns cornerback Anthony Malbrough weighs 178 pounds.
His half-brother, nose tackle Jerry Ball, oftens weighs twice that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grieving in Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   While the Bengals have made clear their intention to release
reluctant wide receiver Carl Pickens, as per his demands, they have
yet to do so because they're insisting that he repay a portion of
his $3.5 million signing bonus of a year ago and that the players'
union drop its grievance against the team. The NFLPA is insisting
the Bengals should lose their right to designate a franchise player
because of the way they handled Pickens's holdout. Thus far the
NFLPA is refusing to back off its grievance, saying Pickens was the
team's franchise player and you can't get that designation back for
four years just because you release him. Meanwhile, agent Marvin
Demoff has asked for a face-to-face meeting with Bengals owner Mike
Brown and his brother Paul to discuss the future of running back
Corey Dillon, also a reluctant Bengal. Cincinnati has offered
Dillon a five-year, $18.3 million deal, but he wants $5 million per
season . . . Pity old friend Michael George. After he wined and
dined Florida State's Peter Warrick for months and spent an
estimated $500,000 on preparing him for his draft workouts, Warrick
jumped to another agent, ex-Laker Norm Nixon, because Nixon's wife,
choreographer and actress Debbie Allen, convinced him they could
get him a future in entertainment. How about in football first? Now
George is on the hot seat at SFX, the huge management company that
bought him out several years ago and now employs him, even though
he did nothing but work his tail off to sign Warrick and then care
for him. A rival agent said last week, ``I feel for the guy. I've
been through it. The players can get away with this because the
contracts they sign with agents are all one way. The NFLPA doesn't
care if they sign with five different guys. They go after the
agents and couldn't care less what the player does.'' In Warrick's
case, he waited until after he was drafted and then dumped SFX for
Nixon, after which the ex-Laker guard decided to bring in somebody
who actually might know what he's doing in a contract negotiation.
Hence the entry of Jimmy Gould, who is also the agent for Patriots
wide receiver Terry Glenn. Nixon and Gould are meeting in Los
Angeles next week, while the Bengals are hoping a deal can be
worked out that allows Warrick to begin informal workouts with the
team on Tuesday. Quarterback Akili Smith has volunteered to stay in
Cincinnati next week to work out with Warrick if he's on hand . . .
New Tennessee offensive coordinator Mike Heimerdinger has decided
that he will call his plays from the sideline rather than from the
press box, as many offensive coordinators do. This is
Heimerdinger's first job as a play caller after working in Denver
for Shanahan, who handles those duties himself. Unlike most
coordinators, Heimerdinger is not bringing in his own offense. He's
using the one quarterback Steve McNair used to lead the Titans to
the Super Bowl last season. To make it easier on his players, he's
learning their terminology instead of making them learn his.
``Sometimes I'll tell a player something and he'll look at me like
I'm crazy,'' Heimerdinger said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deja vu
</P>
<P>
   How's this for eerie? In 1995, Lew Bush replaced David Griggs in
the San Diego Chargers' starting lineup after Griggs died in a
one-car auto accident in Florida. Now Bush is replacing Derrick
Thomas in the Chiefs' lineup after the Kansas City linebacker died
following complications from a crippling car accident during the
offseason. ``I try not to think about it,'' Bush says . . .
Speaking of oddities, what on earth is the University of Alabama
thinking in awarding a posthumous bachelor's degree to Thomas? Of
course, awarding a degree to a dead man isn't too far off from what
happens in big-time college football programs every year . . . The
only NFL player to die in Vietnam will be honored by the Bills this
fall when Bob Kalsu's name is added to the team's Wall of Fame at
Ralph Wilson Stadium. He played only one year in the NFL (1968) and
was killed in action in 1970 while serving as an Army first
lieutenant . . . It's amazing what ends up in court. The Cleveland
Browns and NFL Properties sued a Los Angeles apparel company last
week over the right to the term ``Dawg Pound.'' Honest. The suit
claims that Hawaii-Pacific has attempted to extort millions from
the Browns and NFL Properties by trying to trademark the name used
to describe the denizens of the end zone seats in the old Cleveland
Stadium when the real Browns were playing there. The Browns claim
the company has demanded they stop using the name on licensed
merchandise. The Browns claim the name is a part of their history
dating back to the 1980s. Then again, those Browns moved to
Baltimore under cover of darkness a few years back, didn't they?
And no one from the NFL sued to try and stop them. That seems to be
the essence of Hawaii-Pacific's argument. They claim they were
using the name before the Browns were. Shouldn't these people have
something better to do with their lawyers?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
