<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BOBBYORR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    HALL HAS A DIFFERENT FRAME OF REFERENCE ON ORR'S POSE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Glenn Hall was the St. Louis goalie minding the cage that hot
Mother's Day afternoon, May 10, 1970, when Bobby Orr knocked in the
return pass from Derek Sanderson and clinched the Bruins' first
Stanley Cup in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   The famous shot of Orr flying through the air, frozen in time,
remains one of the most famous sports pictures in history. It
received prominent play around the Hub and throughout Canada last
week, the 30th anniversary of Orr's flight through time.
</P>
<P>
   But the 68-year-old Hall, who lives in Stony Plain, Alberta,
prefers something less sensational for his walls. Hall's favorite
picture is one of Lionel Conacher, who played for four NHL clubs in
the '20s and '30s, long before Hall broke in with the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the dressing room, and his skates are loaded with snow
and his nose is pushed off to one side,'' said Hall, describing his
framed shot of Conacher. ``It's a beautiful picture. It's what
hockey is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hall can't distance himself from the picture of Orr,
snapped that day by Record-American photographer Ray Lussier. Over
the years, he figures, he's signed thousands of copies. He likes to
kid Orr, suggesting it was the only goal the Bruins' legend ever
scored.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, local memorabilia dealer Phil Castinetti was at Hall's
door, toting 510 (remember, May 10) copies of the famous
black-and-white photo. For a fee, Hall signed every one of them, as
did Noel Picard, the Blues' brushcut defenseman who in the picture
appears to have sent Orr flying with a pitchfork lift of his stick.
Castinetti is selling the 510 framed copies, each of them also
signed by Orr, at his Sportsworld collectors shop in Everett for
$510 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   According to Castinetti, ex-Bruins defenseman Ray Bourque bought
the first one, and received limited edition copy No. 77. Another
ex-Bruin, Dave Reid, one of Bourque's Colorado teammates, also
bought one, along with seven other Avalanche, including Joe Sakic,
Peter Forsberg, and Patrick Roy. Bourque, who will turn 40 in
December, is old enough to remember Orr's Cup-winner, but most of
the 1999-2000 Avalanche, including ex-BU Terrier Chris Drury,
weren't even born yet.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of thousand miles away, the good-natured Hall wonders
about all the fuss over an old black-and-white photo. He was in
Boston for the 1996 NHL All-Star Game at the FleetCenter, named an
honorary captain, and he spent days signing the Orr photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, like I've told Bobby a few times,'' recalled Hall, ``I
showered before he even landed on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janney gets his due
</P>
<P>
   Rich Scimone, agent for Craig Janney, reports that the ex-Bruin
recently picked up the $3.6 million he had coming in disability
insurance, relating to the blood clot in his leg that forced his
retirement following the 1998-99 season. Janney, 32, will spend the
summer on Cape Cod and explore postcareer opportunities . . .
Ex-Canadiens coach Jean Perron could be back working behind a bench
next season, this time for the Moncton Wildcats in the Quebec
(Junior A) League . . . Plans aren't finalized, but the Bruins' '70
Cup-winning team is hoping to hold a 30-year reunion this September
at the FleetCenter. It would be similar to the recent Bill Russell
soiree, but this time the Vault no doubt would be burstin' at the
seams. Word around town is that Sept. 8-9 are the tentative dates .
. . The free agent pool, which opens July 1, is rather shallow this
year. The Bruins could have some interest in Gary Roberts ($2.5
million last year with Carolina), Lyle Odelein ($1.7 million,
Phoenix), and maybe Mathieu Schneider ($2.75 million, Rangers), but
none of them is much more than a limited contributor at this point
in his career. Far more intriguing is next year's potential class,
which includes Sakic, John LeClair, Jeremy Roenick, Peter Bondra,
and Rob Blake . . . Just wondering: If Wayne Gretzky is serious
about buying the Coyotes, does that mean bodyguard Dave Semenko
also would be part of the deal? ``I support whatever he does,''
said Glen Sather, the Great One's former boss in Edmonton. Asked by
a reporter if Gretzky has his phone number, Sather said, ``Yes, he
does.'' Speculation began immediately that Gretzky would want to
hire Sather as his GM. But Sather refuses to comment on that
speculation, which has run rampant for weeks, in connection with
the GM vacancy with the Rangers. Sather has two more years
remaining on his Edmonton deal, worth $1.9 million (US funds) per
year . . . Bruins short-timer Joey Mullen likely will hook on as an
assistant coach in Pittsburgh for next season, aiding new head man
Ivan Hlinka. Former Bruins goalie Eddie Johnston, who had been
behind the Penguins bench to aid Herb Brooks, will go back to
helping GM Craig Patrick in the front office . . . Anders Hedberg,
ex- of the Toronto front office, interviewed last week to become
the Flames' new GM. Meanwhile, the Flames find out Monday what
percentage of their season ticket-holders have committed to the
2000-01 season. Ownership has seen 1,500 new applicants pledge for
season tickets but wants 5,000 prior to June 30 or the club will be
put up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pricey club
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings next season must pay Chris Chelios, Brendan
Shanahan, Steve Yzerman, and Nicklas Lidstrom $28 million _ equal
to or more than what a handful of clubs paid this season for their
entire rosters. Ouch. Headed toward a payroll of around $55
million, the Wings must begin to let some of the old guard go, and
that likely will include Igor Larionov and Larry Murphy. Larionov
is an unrestricted free agent July 1. Ditto for Murphy, unless he
agrees to sign on for substantially less than the $3 million he
played for last season . . . Tampa Bay boss Rick Dudley has until
June 1 to sign Brad Richards, who led the Quebec League in scoring
this season with a gaudy 186 points. Richards was the 64th pick in
the '98 draft _ the year the Lightning took Vincent Lecavalier No.
1 _ and he has blossomed into a scoring phenom. Keep in mind,
however: Richards was a fourth-liner for Team Canada at the World
Junior Championships at midseason. He is quick but lacks grit . . .
Swapped to New Jersey late in the season for Odelein, ex-Tabor
Academy star Deron Quint, picked 30th overall in the '94 draft,
should be having the time of his life right now with the
Cup-contending Devils. However, only days after arriving at Exit
16W, Quint was booted from the roster, for what GM Lou Lamoriello
described as conduct unbecoming a member of the club (i.e. he
missed a practice and was late for a team bus). Lamoriello said
Quint would never wear the uniform again. Once targeted as a top 10
pick in the draft, Quint is only 24 and has the skills to be a
regular NHL contributor. His agent, ex-Bruin Brian Lawton, wouldn't
get into specifics about his client's future, other than to say
Quint was back living in Arizona and remained eager to resume his
career. If the Bruins are going to lose Don Sweeney as an
unrestricted free agent, Quint could be someone to consider. He has
some real upside. The impression around the league is that he has
to grow up and be more selective about the company he keeps . . .
Keith Tkachuk was released from the hospital Friday after
undergoing surgery on an ankle and a knee. The ankle repair was
expected, but the knee procedure was somewhat of a surprise.
According to Tkachuk's Boston-based agent, Bob Murray, doctors
drilled holes in the knee, hoping to promote healing via increased
blood flow. Tkachuk is expected to be on crutches for about a week
and then begin a rehab process that could take another 8-9 weeks .
. . Czech star Jiri Dopita, a Bruins draft pick in '92 (No. 133
overall), could sign with the Panthers this offseason. His Czech
club has folded, and while he could play again in Prague, the
high-scoring forward finally may decide to come to North America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sergei searching
</P>
<P>
   Word around Causeway Street is that Bruins winger Sergei
Samsonov is looking for a new agent. The three-year deal he signed
as a rookie, now expired, was negotiated by Jay Grossman . . .
Don't be surprised if the Sabres make Doug Gilmour, 37 years old
next month, available in the June expansion draft. But the price
tag would be high for either Columbus or Minnesota. Gilmour's
2000-01 salary is $6 million, and half of that will be paid by
Chicago, but only if Gilmour remains in Buffalo. Any club that
acquired him would have pay the full $6 million . . . Strange but
true: Former Needham High star Robbie Ftorek, canned as Devils head
coach late in the season, has been in the Meadowlands stands for
all but a couple of the Devils' home games. ``Because I love hockey
and I love the Devils,'' explained Ftorek. ``I've been pulling for
some of these guys for the better part of nine years. I think it's
important to support them.'' Ftorek missed games only if his son,
Sam, was playing for the Augusta (Georgia) Lynx in the ECHL on the
same day . . . Hard not to root for Flyer defenseman Andy Delmore,
the first rookie blue liner to pick up a hat trick in the playoffs.
Delmore sat in Northlands Coliseum for more than six hours in June
'94, his draft year, and never heard his name called. ``You know
what they say, hindsight is 20-20,'' said Al Murray, the Kings'
chief scout. ``But at the time, Delmore didn't hit anybody and was
really an erratic player.'' Philly signed Delmore as a free agent
in '97. After nearly three years in the minors, and at age 23, he
is blossoming. It underscores once more, said Murray, how very
difficult it is to forecast how teenagers will develop . . . Wonder
if the last holdup in the agreement to send NHL players to the Salt
Lake Olympics was a clause that specified that all furniture in
rooms occupied by Team USA players must be bolted to the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
