<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-1980BOYCOTT-ATHLE     05-13 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-1980BOYCOTT-ATHLETES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1980 WAS THEIR SUMMER OF DISCONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lee Kemp still hears it, 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell someone you were on the 1980 Olympic team,'' he says.
``And they say, `Yeah? How did you do?' And you say, `Well, you
know, we didn't go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The United States team didn't go to Moscow that summer because
President Jimmy Carter wanted to protest the Soviet Union's
invasion of Afghanistan. Kemp and 500 fellow athletes were named to
the team. They're on the US Olympic Committee's alumni list.
They're considered Olympians. But they didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always an explanation, a footnote that goes along with
it,'' says swimmer Craig Beardsley, who was favored to win a gold
medal in Moscow. ``I feel like I have to defend myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades after the boycott, millions of Americans can't quite
remember what did and didn't happen in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole team doesn't remember,'' says basketball player Carol
Blazejowski, now general manager of the WNBA's New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But for the athletes who were kept home, the sense of shock, of
loss, of betrayal, of anger, endures.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have it taken away, it was like the death of a loved one,''
says Kemp, who was odds-on to win a gold medal in freestyle
wrestling. ``There's nothing you can do about it. You deal with it,
but you're never quite right.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 1980 US athletes, such as hurdler Edwin Moses,
already had won gold at Olympus. Some of them, such as diver Greg
Louganis, would win it at Los Angeles four years later. But for
more than 200 of them, such as Kemp and Beardsley and Blazejowski
and hurdler Renaldo Nehemiah and cyclist Greg LeMond and coxswain
Holly Hatton, Moscow was their only chance.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Lost Generation, Olympians who never got to Olympus
and aren't quite sure that they deserve the label. Charlie
Altekruse, a rower on the 1980 team, once said he felt as if he had
a doctoral degree from a bogus university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody considers me an Olympian,'' says LeMond, who had a
strong chance at a gold in the road race that year. ``If you didn't
compete in the Olympics it was, `Well, you were on the 1980 team,
but so what?' ''
</P>
<P>
   What gnaws most at the Lost Generation, though, is that their
sacrifice went for naught. The boycott fizzled, as most of
America's staunchest allies _ Great Britain, France, Italy,
Australia, and others _ competed anyway. The Soviets easily topped
the medal table, gobbling up gold that would have gone to
Americans. Carter, who critics said was using the boycott as a
cheap election ploy, was turned out of office by Ronald Reagan. And
the Soviets led a counter-boycott that decimated the 1984 Games in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing,'' says Beardsley. ``No results on this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Politics intervenes
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing but loss, especially the loss of innocence.
The athletes had believed that the Olympics were sacred, that they
were beyond politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so young, so naive,'' says Nehemiah, who is now director
of worldwide track and field for Octagon, a Washington-area sports
marketing and management firm. ``The red-white-and-blue felt so
much a part of me. I never thought seriously that we would boycott.
I took it as propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the USOC voted formally to keep the athletes home in
April, the sports bodies still held trials, the athletes still kept
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was real,'' says Kemp, who now owns a Ford
auto dealership in Minnesota. ``I thought at the last minute we
would go. Dan Gable was coaching us. He said, `Don't look at the
newspapers. Just keep training.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The athletes couldn't imagine that the Olympics would be
disrupted because of international politics. Hadn't the 1972 Games
continued even after the Israelis were slaughtered by terrorists at
Munich? Weren't wars supposed to stop when the flame was kindled?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was superpowers playing with athletes like they were
playing chess,'' says LeMond. ``But in the scheme of the Cold War,
it was such a minor move.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carter first mentioned the boycott, two weeks after the Red
Army went into Afghanistan in December 1979, it was near the end of
a long list of proposed sanctions, such as deferred SALT talks,
restricted trade, curtailed fishing privileges.
</P>
<P>
   But once the Kremlim defied Carter's Feb. 20 deadline for a
pullout, the boycott moved to the top of the list. The Soviets
could buy American computers and wheat from somebody else, but they
couldn't get the US Olympic team on the spot market.
</P>
<P>
   So when the International Olympic Committee flatly refused to
move the Games out of Moscow, the White House told the USOC that
the boycott was on. The decision, Carter declared, was ``final and
irrevocable.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's say we do the bare minimum, the USOC athletes' council
suggested. We'll arrive at the Games at the last minute. We'll just
have a token flagbearer march in the opening ceremonies. We'll
bypass the medal ceremonies. We'll skip the closing ceremonies. In,
compete, out.
</P>
<P>
   No means no, the White House replied. We'll pull your passports
if we have to. It's a national security issue. If the Olympians
stayed home, Carter promised he would give them Congressional
medals and see that they had an alternate Games to compete in. If
they insisted on going to Moscow, it was all but unAmerican.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so hypocritical,'' volleyball player Debbie Green said
then. ``Our winter athletes were described as heroes. We were the
most unpatriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   After the USOC voted not to go, the White House hosted an
Olympic Honors Day for the athletes. ``For being reluctant Great
Americans,'' rower Tiff Wood mused. Some of them posed with Carter;
others, notably the female rowers, refused to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were passionate that this was wrong and we were being
robbed,'' says Hatton, who coxed the eight and now coaches the BU
women's crew. ``I had stickers made up that said, `I'm here to make
sure this never happens again,' and I handed them out to anyone who
would wear them. Someone said that it wasn't the appropriate place
to do that. And I said, we shouldn't even be here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watching and waiting
</P>
<P>
   How could their star-spangled dream have become a nightmare?
Right up until the eve of the opening ceremonies in July, some
athletes thought a miracle might happen. The Red Army might
withdraw. The IOC might move the Games. Carter might back down.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they could compete as independents. Maybe they could
compete for somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were training in Ratzeburg near the East German border
where we could see the guard towers and we had this crazy idea,''
Hatton recalls. ``Let's row over and get ourselves arrested and ask
the East Germans to force us to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unthinkable that the Games could begin without the
Americans. When they did, some Olympians couldn't bear to watch.
Others couldn't bear not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reluctantly watched because I felt it was my turn,'' says
Nehemiah, who saw East Germany's Thomas Munkelt win the 110-meter
hurdles in the slowest time since 1964. ``I needed to see what I
was missing, as painful as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Nehemiah made his point a couple of weeks later when he blew
away the Olympic medalists in a London meet. Beardsley set a world
record in the 200-meter butterfly at the US nationals that would
have won by a body length in Moscow. But Lord Killanin wasn't there
to give them a gold medal and nobody raised their flag. The
five-ringed parade had passed without them.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of the US athletes vowed to chase that parade all the way
to Los Angeles and claim their places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot boycott our own Games,'' figured volleyball player
Rita Crockett. ``I don't care what anybody says.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, like sprinter Evelyn Ashford and swimmer Rowdy Gaines,
the golden ring came around again in 1984. For others, the moment
had fled forever. Kemp lost to Dave Schultz in the wrestling
trials. Beardsley missed the swimming team by one place.
</P>
<P>
   Others couldn't hang on for another quadrennium. Peter Schnugg
had tried for three Olympic water polo teams. In 1972, when the US
won the bronze medal, he was the 13th man on an 11-man squad. In
1976, he'd made the team and the team hadn't qualified. In 1980,
he'd made the team and the team hadn't competed. He was 29 now.
``Gotta go to work sometime,'' Schnugg concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Nehemiah eventually went off to play for the NFL's San Francisco
49ers and won a Super Bowl ring. Blazejowski signed with the
Women's Professional Basketball League. LeMond turned pro and won
the Tour de France three times. Hatton took a coaching job at BU.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but ifs
</P>
<P>
   They are the Olympians with explanations, with footnotes, caught
up in an unfortunate convergence of time and circumstance. Some are
still bitter about the boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll never forgive Jimmy Carter for doing that,'' says
Nehemiah.
</P>
<P>
   Others have chalked it up to chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the way the dice came up,'' shrugs Beardsley.
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Army had stayed home . . . If Carter hadn't been
president . . . If the Lords of the Rings had moved the Games to
the UN parking lot . . . If the East Germans had arrested the whole
team . . .
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years and the ifs still haunt the Lost Generation _ and
always will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that stays with you,'' says Beardsley. ``You
can't shake it. Everyone carries some emotional baggage from 1980 _
and some questions they'll always have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
