<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-MARATHON     05-13 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-MARATHON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY HURDLES FOR MARATHONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the ``wrong'' people (Christine Clark and Rod DeHaven)
have won the Olympic marathon trials, limiting the Americans to one
man and one woman in Sydney, maybe the USA Track and Field people
will use their heads next time and hold the races on a pancake-flat
course (like Chicago) on a weekend in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   That way, it's much more likely that one or more runners will
meet the ``A'' qualifying standard for the Games. And if they
don't, they'll still have at least six months to do it elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sorry state of American marathoning, it was silly to
hold this year's trials on hilly courses in Charleston, S.C., and
Pittsburgh. When both days turned out hot, slow times were
inevitable. Clark ran 30 seconds slower than the women's ``A''
standard of 2:33; DeHaven was 90 seconds slower than the men's
2:14.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greece makes a change
</P>
<P>
   All it took was three years, two inept presidents, and a wakeup
call with a two-by-four from the Lords of the Rings for the Athens
organizers to do the obvious: put Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki,
who directed the bid committee for the 2004 Summer Games, in
charge. ``Now she is the president _ finally,'' exulted
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch,
after the 44-year-old Angelopoulos-Daskalaki replaced the
beleaguered Panagiotis Thomopoulos. At the top of
Angelopoulos-Daskalaki's priority list: venue construction, hotel
rooms, and a host TV broadcaster. The IOC has given Athens 100 days
to get back on track . . . You'd think that IOC vice president
Kevan Gosper of Australia would be lying low while the Olympic
ethics commission investigates whether he took a family ski junket
to Salt Lake City on the bidders' tab. Now, he's embroiled in
``Sophie's Choice,'' the controversial selection of his 11-year-old
daughter, Sophie, to be the first Australian to carry the Olympic
torch after the flame was kindled in Greece last week. He
subsequently apologized for what he called ``fatherly pride'' and a
``lapse in judgment'' . . . Next challenge for the Lords of the
Rings, who are still grappling with doping: what to do about
Internet broadcast rights. Should the IOC sell them separately? Or
bundle them with television packages? If so, will it have to
rewrite NBC's $3.5 billion deal, which runs through 2008? All of
that will be discussed at a New Media summit in November at Olympic
headquarters in Switzerland. ``At the moment,'' says Samaranch, an
Old Media guy, ``we are lost.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So-so showing
</P>
<P>
   The US men's ice hockey team took a three-minute snooze against
the Slovaks in Thursday's world quarterfinals, gave up three goals,
and ended up being bounced from the tournament after going 4-0-2 in
its first six games. Still, it wasn't a bad showing by the
Americans, who had only 13 NHLers on the roster. And it was
dramatically better than the disgraceful walk-through turned in by
the host Russians, who lost four of their six games and were hooted
off the ice in St. Petersburg. Not that they expected to make the
award stand, which hasn't happened in six years. But losing to the
Swiss? The Latvians? The Belarussians? Now that they're cashing NHL
paychecks, many Russians consider playing for the motherland to be
beneath them. Meanwhile, the Czechs and Slovaks joust for the gold
medal Sunday . . . Managing the US Olympic baseball team (all minor
leaguers for the first time) will be ex-Dodger manager Tommy
Lasorda, who'll wear his old No. 2. Lasorda, now a senior vice
president with the ball club, vows he'll bleed red-white-and-blue .
. . Clutch effort by the US women's water polo team, which edged
Hungary by a goal at the last-chance Olympic qualifier in Sicily to
earn a ticket to Sydney. And a crowning moment for 39-year-old
Maureen O'Toole, the squad's grande dame, who unretired for the
second time when the women's event was added to the Olympic program
and made the team. Missing from the six-nation field will be Italy
and Hungary, the last two world champions . . . Turns out that the
US Olympic track cycling events were just for practice. None of the
victors met the tough new time standards, which are pegged to world
medal levels. (Erin Hartwell, who won medals in the kilo at the
last two Games, has switched to pursuit this time after knee
surgery.) So the coaches will choose the entire team in July . . .
Bittersweet victory for Bill May, who won the solo, duet (with
Kristina Lum), and team titles (with the Santa Clara Aquamaids) at
the recent US synchronized swimming championships but is banned
from the Olympics because he's a he. ``This is one small step for
me, one giant step for mankind,'' declared the 21-year-old May,
only the fourth swimmer in 55 years to post a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New job for Schultz
</P>
<P>
   Dick Schultz, who stepped down as USOC executive director this
year after the job was changed to CEO, has turned up as chair of
MAI Sports, a Kansas-based marketing and consulting firm. ``After
50 years in the business, I knew I couldn't quit cold turkey,''
says the 70-year-old Schultz. ``But I'm not going to do this 60
hours a week.'' . . . The 12 gymnasts named to the US Olympic team
at the August trials at the FleetCenter may not all compete in
Sydney. If the international federation approves the use of
alternates for ``tactical'' substitutions, USA Gymnastics probably
will ask the USOC for the right to replace anyone who's not on form
at the Games . . . With nandrolone positives off the charts _ 343
last year _ sports federations such as track and field and swimming
are looking into whether athletes may be unwittingly ingesting the
banned steroid with food or herbal supplements. Meanwhile, the best
way to beat a positive nandrolone test may be to say you ate meat
from uncastrated pigs. That was the alibi used by long-distance
swimmers from Spain and Slovenia after they were nailed at a meet
in Brazil . . . Looks like a sellout for the US Olympic track and
field trials, which will be held in Sacramento in July. By last
month, the organizers had already sold 13,000 all-event packages
for Cal State-Sacramento's 23,000-seat stadium. Single seats go on
sale Monday. Call 1-877-873-9690, toll-free, for details . . . That
Colombian shooter who killed two armed assailants on the road home
from practice recently wasn't a garden-variety 49-year-old
marksman. Bernardo Tobar will be competing in his fifth Olympics at
Sydney. His specialty: rapid-fire pistol . . . Hanging up the sled
after 16 years, three Olympics (a historic silver at Nagano), an
overall World Cup title, and 26 international medals is US luger
Gordy Sheer, who teamed with doubles partner Chris Thorpe for the
last dozen seasons. Sheer, who is 28 and recently married, says he
can't give it 100 percent anymore. Thorpe says he'll keep sliding .
. . Why can't newly independent East Timor compete in Sydney?
Because the former Indonesian province doesn't have the required
five sports federations to qualify. That's why the IOC turned
thumbs-down last month . . . Most inventive anti-Olympic display so
far: The ``Bondi Warriors,'' who don't want a temporary 10,000-seat
volleyball stadium built on their famed beach, buried themselves up
to their necks in the sand . . . How does skater Michelle Kwan feel
about being named one of People magazine's ``50 Most Beautiful
People''? ``Flabbergasted,'' says the world champ. ``Obviously
they've never seen me going to an 8 a.m. class wearing a baseball
cap with no makeup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
