<SLUG> BC-BKN-PATRILEY-HEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RILEY UPSET WITH HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pat Riley was not a happy man Saturday. He talked a
lot more like a coach staring at a 2-1 deficit rather than one
holding a 2-1 advantage in the best-of-seven Eastern Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   His concerns? The attitude of his team. Beneficiaries of a
controversial call at the end of Game 3 on Friday night, the Miami
Heat reported for practice Saturday at Madison Square Garden with
what Riley said was a ``b.s.-loose attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be classic Riley playing the role of master manipulator
or it could be that he saw something that legitimately concerned
him. The Heat won Game 3, 77-76, in overtime, and can take a
commanding 3-1 lead over the Knicks with a victory Sunday in Game
4.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that would make Riley happy. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat watched film for about an hour, then went through a
brief practice. Riley was snippy from the start, whether the topic
was Anthony Carter's disputed game-winner, the status of Tim
Hardaway, or the frame of mind of his battle-hardened team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of it. We're all tired of it,'' he said. ``We're
tired of a lot of things. We're tired of having an advantage and
giving it back. We're tired of winning and relaxing and thinking
we've got something. I'm tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of players' attitudes about, `OK, we got a leg up on
them and (Sunday) we're going to come back and not play with the
same type of ferocity.' Somewhere, we gotta be men and step up and
put some big-time pressure on this team. That's what our
opportunity is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew! And he won Game 3. The Knicks, meanwhile, were in somber
mode at their workout, which was more talking and watching than
playing. Coach Jeff Van Gundy stressed that his team has to start
rebounding _ Miami is killing the Knicks at both ends _ while also
admitting they are still reeling from Carter's behind-the-backboard
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down,'' Van Gundy said. ``But we can't stay down.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Latrell Sprewell, ``We're disappointed. You work that hard
to get that close and it slips away from you at the end. It's
tiring mentally. It drains you. That's why we didn't do too much
(at practice). Guys are a little down. They're tired, low on
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's game-winner came with 2.2 seconds left in overtime. He
was behind the basket when he lofted a floater that hit the rim
like dead weight and settled in. Some replays appeared to show the
ball going over the backboard, which would make it an illegal shot.
Van Gundy said after the game that it was ``clear as day'' the shot
should not have counted. He hadn't changed his mind Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by what I said. But I want the team to start looking
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, too, was trying to do the same thing. Riley said the
referees' decision was a ``good no-call'' and added, ``I'm not
going to get into it. Whether or not it crossed, barely, or
whatever, the game is over with. And to hell with them. That's it.
We're 2-1. The home-court advantage doesn't mean anything., We're
moving on to Game 4 and they can lament all they want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway shot some Saturday and said his sore left foot was
improved. It's hard to see how it couldn't be. ``I'm going to ice
it,'' he said. ``It's sore. But I'm playing.'' He sat out the final
22 minutes of Game 3 while Carter led the attack . . . Riley's
correct about home-court advantage not meaning much. In the 20
playoff games between the Heat and the Knicks, the teams are 6-6 in
Miami and 4-4 in New York . . . Bruce Bowen was not credited with a
steal on the final possession of Game 3, even though he deflected
the inbounds pass intended for Sprewell. ``I just reacted to his
cut,'' Bowen said. ``It happened too quick to even think I'm going
to get a hand on it.'' And the steal? ``That's OK. I'll take the
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000513.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     05-13 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARD FROM WITH THE LONG BALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Red Sox sat quietly in their dugout at Camden
Yards. At times they watched in silence as a skyscraper of a man _
a 6-foot-6-inch pitcher nicknamed JJ _ tried to no-hit them. It
didn't take long for them to realize that they were missing their
favorite, 24-hour, heard-in-two-languages, walking soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Pedro Martinez. On Friday the Sox needed his
right arm to secure a win. Saturday against the Orioles, they
didn't need a complete-game, 15-strikeout two-hitter. They needed
his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting there and, I think it was Andy Sheets who
said, `Get Pedro out here; it's too quiet,' '' Donnie Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   So the call was made to the clubhouse, where Martinez was
watching the early parts of what became a 5-1 Sox win. His
teammates heard him coming through the tunnel before they saw him,
just as you can hear a subway train seconds before it screechingly
arrives at its station.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox could hear that Martinez already was chatting in English
and Spanish as he walked toward the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it was Spanglish,'' Scott Hatteberg said. ``When we're
struggling, we always like to have him around to loosen things up.
I think he's got the Energizer bunny beat with all his energy. It's
unbelievable. He uses all of his own material, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez not only talked to his teammates, he talked to JJ
(Jason Johnson) as well. He reminded the 26-year-old pitcher that
he was throwing a no-hitter. As baseball fans know, there's one
subject that a man with a no-hitter in progress doesn't want
mentioned: a no-hitter in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Before a breeze blew into the park, more than 48,000 fans were
exposed to what felt like desert heat. The Sox must have looked to
the mound and saw a mirage of a young Nolan Ryan. In his first 5
2/3 innings, Johnson had given up no hits and five walks. He was
backed by a single run, Brady Anderson's third-inning homer, which
looked as if it would be enough. After walking Troy O'Leary in the
sixth, he gave up a Mike Stanley single.
</P>
<P>
   The game was never the same. Soon, Martinez was not the only one
talking to and about the Orioles. And, in the eighth, everyone
would have understood if Baltimore reliever Mike Trombley had begun
talking to himself.
</P>
<P>
   By the top of the eighth, Johnson had thrown 115 pitches and was
out of the game. The Orioles turned the ball over to Buddy Groom
and then summoned Trombley. Pinch runner Manny Alexander was on
first when Trombley took the mound for his warmup pitches. Stanley,
who was at the plate, chatted with Hatteberg during the short
break.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Stanley: What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg: He usually throws me splitters. That's what I'm going
to look for.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley: I think I'm going to sit on a first-pitch curveball.
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch was not a curve, but as Hatteberg said, ``I
don't think Stan-o had a plan for the second pitch, so he stayed
with his plan for the first.'' As Stanley predicted, the curveball
came. It was not a good one. Stanley caught it and sent it 367 feet
over the left-field fence. When Orioles fans saw that, they had
conversations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They went something like this: (Expletive)!
</P>
<P>
   It was 2-1 and, unfortunately for starter Jeff Fassero, he
couldn't win the game. The 37-year-old lefthander has pitched well
in his last three starts. Saturday, he walked one Oriole and gave
up the homer to Anderson. Even that was not a bad pitch. It came on
a 3-and-2 count. Fassero and his catcher, Hatteberg, had two
options on the pitch. Hatteberg believes they chose the best one,
but Anderson was able to connect anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (Brief tangent: You should hope that the new Fenway Park is
nothing like this place. Aesthetically, it is beautiful.
Competitively, it is a disgrace. Power alleys of 364 and 373? Scant
foul territory? Every inning is batting practice here.)
</P>
<P>
   As Hatteberg walked to the plate, following Stanley, he kept
thinking of Trombley's splitters. He got it on a 2-and-0 pitch. It
was another home run. Trombley, from Wilbraham, Mass., was being
called lots of creative names at that point. It was 3-1. You could
tell he was frustrated. He couldn't control his breaking pitch. So
when he hit Wilton Veras with a curve, there wasn't a lot of
movement in the Sox dugout. Just a few words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one guy moved to the top step of the dugout,'' Stanley
said. Anyway, why charge the mound? It's better to hit a guy's
pitch rather than his face. Sadler and Veras understood that.
Sadler understood it so well that he started to have a conversation
with himself.
</P>
<P>
   It went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Sadler: This guy is struggling. The fans are on him. I know he
wants to throw a strike. I'm going to look for a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler to Sadler: Good point, Donnie.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Sadler got a first-pitch fastball and pulled it to
left. ``I'm a small guy,'' the 5-foot-6-inch Sadler said, ``I'm
usually not looking for off-speed stuff to pull.'' He got
underneath the fastball and helped it travel 375 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Trombley is also the pitcher who gave up ninth-inning homers to
Darren Lewis and Jeff Frye last June 14. Neither man has homered
since then. He has now allowed five memorable late-inning Sox
homers in less than a year. He doesn't feel good about that. But at
least he's done it against the perfect group of guys. They
obviously love to talk among themselves and the reliever has given
them plenty to discuss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
