<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-APPIER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPIER'S EXPERIENCE A PLUS TO A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While his teammates watched TV, played cards and
joked in the locker room, Kevin Appier was working out in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   When his teammates moved on to the dugout they initiated
sunflower seed-spitting contests and swung from the edge of the
dugout roof like children on monkey bars. Appier simply shook his
head as he walked past on his way to the outfield, where he would
do some running.
</P>
<P>
   Since being traded to the youthful Oakland Athletics late last
season, Appier has found a team in which his maturity is
appreciated almost as much as his pitching.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, this is the same Kevin Appier who once had a
reputation as being temperamental, who wasn't always receptive to
older players trying to guide him in his early years with the
Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a decade makes.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Lancaster native is in his 11th major-league
season. He enjoys the enthusiasm and relaxed atmosphere of the A's
- traits he believes will help him reach the playoffs for the first
time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But he also realizes it is his time to do what players like Mark
Gubicza, Floyd Bannister and Charlie Leibrandt did for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am,'' Appier said. ``They come to me, the pitchers
do. The younger guys come to me and I'll offer advice - even if
they don't ask for it sometimes. So yeah, I'm to that age where I'm
the mentor type.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old, I admit it. I was the youngest guy for so many years.
It feels weird, but there are some older guys here, some veterans.
I think it's a real good blend between youth and veteran guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relaxed, but in a good way. Not relaxed, like lazy, but
relaxed where your actions are good and very focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Appier began the season 3-2 with a 4.06 ERA before a strained
right forearm put him on the disabled list. He returned Saturday to
start against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander's career got off to a rocky start when he went
1-4 with a 9.14 ERA in six games in 1989, but he emerged as the
Royals' ace in 1990 after injuries to Bret Saberhagen and Gubicza.
He won at least 13 games in five of the next six seasons and was
named to the American League All-Star team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his success came from realizing he didn't have to strike
out everyone. Experience and building confidence has also helped.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing that experience and getting young players to keep
believing in themselves when they struggle is one of the biggest
impacts Appier tries to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things have gone bad for a while, to still know that
you're a good pitcher is really humongous,'' Appier said. ``When
you're young and you first came into this game, say you have a
rough month. Well, a lot of guys instantly start doubting whether
they even belong here at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came up, I was getting beat up, my arm was tired
and I didn't know if I was good enough to stay here. Then, '90 I
had a real good year and that's when I felt like I belonged here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when it seems like the advice he gives isn't sinking in,
Appier persists in giving it. He remembers how much he picked up as
a young player despite perceptions of resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to them more than they thought,'' Appier said. ``I
wasn't very good at communicating back then. I definitely paid
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm more mature, I'm realizing how important that
was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-13-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
