<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     05-13 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX DO YARD WORK, RAKE IN 4TH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Don't swing at a single pitch. Understand?
</P>
<P>
   The No. 4 batter in the Red Sox lineup couldn't believe what he
was hearing Saturday. Then again, Derek Lowe has had far more
experience as the Sox closer than he has had as the team's cleanup
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``First I was shocked when they told me, `You're up third,' ''
Lowe said. ``And when (pitching coach) Joe Kerrigan came over and
said, `Don't swing,' I thought he was kidding. Then he said,
`Really, don't swing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was little cause for Lowe to take his bat off his shoulder
in the ninth inning, not after Mike Stanley, Scott Hatteberg, and
Donnie Sadler hit home runs in the span of six pitches from
Baltimore reliever Mike Trombley the inning before, lifting the Sox
to a 5-1 win. It was Boston's fourth straight win and sent the
Orioles to their sixth straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon that began with the Sox begging for a hit _ they
went 5 2/3 innings before Stanley singled for their first hit off
starter Jason Johnson _ they ended the day with Lowe obeying orders
not to swing.
</P>
<P>
   And while it may have been risky business for Jimy Williams to
manage himself out of a DH, it was a disaster for Orioles manager
Mike Hargrove to summon Trombley.
</P>
<P>
   Trombley, brought in to face Stanley with two out and Brian
Daubach aboard on a single off lefty Buddy Groom, hung a 1-and-0
curveball to Stanley, who smacked it into the left-field seats to
give the Sox a 2-1 lead. The next batter was Hatteberg, making just
his seventh start in 33 games, and he hit a 2-and-0 splitter to the
same destination.
</P>
<P>
   Trombley hit Wilton Veras with his next pitch (a breaking ball;
no need to call Frank Robinson), and after a visit from pitching
coach Sammy Ellis, Sadler went deep on the first pitch he saw for
his first hit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's homer gave the Sox a trifecta on the same day the
Dedham (Mass.) High marching band strolled down Pratt Street here
in the Preakness parade. The Dedham kids made sweeter music than
the chorus of boos that cascaded down on Trombley, the Western
Massachusetts native (Wilbraham) who was buried by the biggest
regular-season crowd in Camden Yards history, 48,579.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough when it happens at home,'' Lowe said of Trombley,
who was with the Twins last June when he gave up back-to-back shots
in the ninth to Darren Lewis and Jeff Frye, Frye's being Boston's
only walkoff homer of the '99 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for the guy,'' Lowe said. ``What happened was good for
us, but you don't wish that on anybody. But fans are going to do
what they're going to do. Boston fans do some crazy things, too.
But as players, we've all been there, and it's not a good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who gave up four hits in two innings but escaped jams in
the eighth and ninth, was offered little sympathy in the Boston
clubhouse after his four-pitches-and-out at-bat against Orioles
reliever Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best thing he could have done there,'' said
Daubach, who improved his average against lefties to .300 (6 for
20) with his eighth-inning single off Groom. ``His helmet looked
nice and shiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg, who had been robbed of hits by Orioles first baseman
Jeff Conine before he connected off Trombley, has seen Lowe taking
batting practice in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great golfer,'' Hatteberg said, ``but he can't swing a
baseball bat. As bad as it was, he did go up to the plate with a
game plan. The plan was don't swing the bat. But he didn't fool
anybody. He was flopping around out there, no (batting) glove, no
nothing. Pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe did show big-league potential as a hitter after his whiff,
however, tipping his cap to the fans applauding him behind the
visitors' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were giving me a mock cheer,'' said Lowe, whose two
innings of scoreless work made a first-time winner out of Rich
Garces, who entered in the seventh after Jeff Fassero walked
leadoff hitter B.J. Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to have fun with the game. That's why I tipped my cap.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Lowe could recall getting a hit was in spring
training two years ago. Naturally, he remembered the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearwater, against the Phillies, Tyler Green was pitching,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a clubhouse where Pedro Martinez chirps that he'd like to
come back as Nomar Garciaparra if given the chance, Lowe admitted
he would have liked to take a hack. And that was even without some
needling from Frye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff came over to me and said, `Hey, that's not going on the
back of Kerrigan's baseball card, it's going on yours,' '' Lowe
said. ``0 for 1 with a strikeout.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real takeaway, Hatteberg said, is that the Sox won again
without Garciaparra and Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's huge,'' Hatteberg said. ``It happened last
year, too. When your stars are out, other guys step up when they
need to. Fassero gave us a chance. We've got to win these games,
and today was a good indication we have the guys who can do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
