<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS FACED ADVERSITY ALL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Phoenix Suns, or what's left of them, did not ask
for blindfold, last cigarette or final request - say, Michael
Jordan coming out of retirement?
</P>
<P>
   They know the numbers as well as anyone. They enter today's Game
4 against the Lakers down 0-3 in their best-of-seven series. And
not one team in the NBA history has ever come back from 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   That's zero in 53 years.
</P>
<P>
   So they skipped practice Saturday, had a nice lunch together at
a local restaurant and then met the media, stoically acknowledging
their ambitions have been scaled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us it's real simple - we just need to win one ballgame,''
Suns veteran Kevin Johnson said. ``And that's what we're trying to
do at this point. We're not trying to look at winning the series,
because that obviously seems insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can win just one ballgame and force a Game 5, I think
we'll be very content with that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   For Phoenix, overcoming adversity this season has become a
practiced art. This time, though, even the grittiest of Suns feel
slightly lost in the Lakers' shadow. They've been reduced to
wondering what might have been, talk of their character, and their
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can stay healthy, maybe we can have the best record in
the league,'' Suns guard Jason Kidd said. ``We won 53 games and did
that with one of our players (Tom Gugliotta) almost dying, a
coaching change, injuries to Penny (Hardaway), Shawn Marion,
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the whole team has been hurt at some point besides
Rodney (Rogers). That just shows the character of this team, that
no matter what the circumstances are, we're going to try and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Suns have seemed a marvelous collection of
pieces, never quite taking form. But this year, the pieces kept
coming and going.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, the Suns lost Hardaway, the
high-profile new addition at the center of their offseason buzz,
with a sore right foot. He missed the first 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he came back, the Suns had a new coach. Danny Ainge
decided after 20 games he wanted out to be with his family, and
assistant Scott Skiles was promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Marion, their No. 1 draft pick, hurt his knee Dec. 5 and missed
the next 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   Starting forward Tom Gugliotta survived a life-threatening
seizure, came back and then tore his left knee up and was lost for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days later, Kidd - their best overall player - broke his
right ankle. Kidd returned in the playoffs against San Antonio but
is almost trying to rehab the knee in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And now Cliff Robinson, who became their leading scorer (18.5
points per game) amid all the injuries, twisted his ankle Friday
and is questionable for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive the Suns, if they feel just a tad snake-bitten.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't let ourselves get caught up in that all year, and I
don't think we will now,'' Robinson said. ``If I can go, I'll go.
But if I had to go out there and play right now, I wouldn't be able
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson, who has been in a few of these games
against teams down 0-3, hardly expects Phoenix to suddenly play
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll come out with guns blazing, playing nothing to
lose and everything to gain, upset-minded, show their dander or
their courage,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then as the game gets more and more difficult, doubts
start to form. Close-out games are very difficult. You have to be
able to hang around, and usually find a way to win in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway said the Suns have figured out how to beat the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If possible, you have to play a perfect game,'' he said.
``Less than 10 turnovers, make 50 percent of your shots, go to the
foul line more than them and outrebound them. Because nothing is
going to be given to us. That's how you have to beat the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality, it can be ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand it's a tough situation to be in and just have to
take it one game at a time,'' Robinson said. ``It's a cliche, but
at this point, that's all we can fall back on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
