<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Love, Huston tied for Byron Nelson lead 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Prevailing winds shifted directions yesterday at
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic. So did front-runner Davis Love III,
whose inability to control his approach shots at the Four Seasons
Resort caused him to backtrack to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the player who held the largest 36-hole lead in
tournament history has frittered away a four-stroke advantage and
finds himself tied with John Huston heading into today's final
round. A group of nine players remain within six strokes of the
co-leaders, who stand at 10-under par after exhibiting different
tolerance levels for withstanding northerly wind gusts to 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Huston held firm, scrambling his way to a 67 despite missing
seven greens in regulation. Love struggled. He pumped four approach
shots into greenside bunkers, airmailed two greens in the final
five holes and collected just two birdies after making nine in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let a lot of people back into this thing,'' Love said after
a third-round 71. ``I haven't played here enough to see the wind
blow from that direction. I lost that confidence of just hopping up
there and knowing it was going to go the right distance every time.
I got surprised on some shots and I started second-guessing
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, who blistered the TPC course for an opening 66 while
playing in 38 mph southerly winds, found himself playing yo-yo with
his approach shots after yesterday's 180-degree shift in wind
direction. He was long at No. 12, short at No. 13, long at Nos. 14
and 15 and short at Nos. 16 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   Love shot even par over his final 13 holes by leaning on his
short game but surrendered four strokes to Huston. The last of
Huston's four birdie putts, a 15-footer at No. 14, briefly bumped
Love out of first place for the first time since Thursday. Love,
however, answered with a birdie from a greenside bunker at No. 16
to knot matters heading into the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Huston said he could sympathize with Love's struggles to control
his approach shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to pick the right club,'' Huston said. ``At
times, it would be almost calm, and then it would start blowing
pretty hard. That made it a tougher wind than what we saw earlier
in the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts call for similar conditions today, with one
significant twist. The anticipated 18 mph gusts will come from the
south, after a one-day taste of northern exposure. If it happens,
final-round charges from back in the pack are not out of the
question, said Mark Brooks, a Fort Worth resident who stands in a
five-way tie for fifth, at 5 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind keeps blowing like this, anyone at 4 under or
better has a chance,'' Brooks said. ``If it blows 30 mph, the guys
at 3 under may have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That group includes Tiger Woods and David Duval, the top two
players in the world golf rankings. They will be paired at 11:56
a.m., marking the first time Woods and Duval have played together
in the final round of a PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   Before they could make a serious run at Love and Huston, golf's
dynamic duo must first pass the likes of Jesper Parnevik (7 under),
Phil Mickelson (6 under) and a three-player knot at 5 under that
includes Brooks, Bob Estes and Flower Mound resident Paul
Stankowski.
</P>
<P>
   Can it happen?
</P>
<P>
   If the leaders start quickly, said Woods, they'll be tough to
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come back a little bit, then it will be a different
story,'' said Woods, who is tied for 12th after a second
consecutive 67.
</P>
<P>
   Despite flying several greens down the stretch, Love said he is
confident he can regain the form he showed in the first two rounds
while seizing control of the leader board with rounds of 66-63.
Even after his third-round backslide, Love still is positioned to
be first wire-to-wire winner at the Nelson since Tom Watson in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, obviously, with the way that I scored,''
Love said. ``But I haven't lost any confidence with the way I'm
playing. I scrambled pretty good. I don't feel like I've got to go
figure out what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   What Love would really like is to shift directions on the leader
board, once again, with today's anticipated shift in winds. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
