<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED OF HENDERSON, METS RELEASE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rickey Henderson jogged himself right out of a Mets
uniform Friday night when he unabashedly slipped into his home run
trot without the ball leaving the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the first inning when his shot hit the left-field
wall at Shea Stadium, but the Mets would lose to the Florida
Marlins, and Henderson's effort, compounded by his unrepentant
attitude, would be the lasting memory for the team's management.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Henderson's half-hearted run to first base Friday, he
had to settle for a single. Saturday, after the Mets lost another
game to the Florida Marlins, 7-6, the Mets would settle no more.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, the 21-year veteran left fielder who is baseball's
career stolen base leader, had performed his last act. After the
Mets lost another lead and another game _ the 12th of their last 17
_ General Manager Steve Phillips announced that the team had given
Henderson, 41, a likely Hall of Famer, his unconditional release.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, when you continue to do the wrong thing and say
the wrong thing, you continue to wear out your welcome,'' Phillips
said. ``We were at the point where we were having to compromise our
ideals too many times. When taking everything into account, the
offense, defense and the alternatives we had, and what it does to
the fabric of the team, we thought it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had already put Henderson on outright waivers Monday,
but no team claimed him. He was not in the starting lineup Saturday
and was a defensive replacement in the ninth inning, but he did not
bat in the Mets' fruitless comeback that had Manager Bobby
Valentine out of bench players, forced to even use pitcher Mike
Hampton at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets (19-19) slipped to .500 Saturday, potential already
going unfulfilled, Henderson seemed a prime example of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have our best chance of winning now with other people
playing,'' Valentine said. ``I thought some guys felt he was
keeping us from winning a couple of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's first-inning jog, Valentine said, would have been the
final straw, but Henderson topped that. According to Valentine,
even after he told Henderson the premature trot was unacceptable,
Henderson would not apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to build a responsibility within a group,'' Valentine
said. ``I thought I could have gotten a `I screwed up' comment. Not
in as much as an apology, but in an acknowledgment of
responsibility. I was having a hard time compromising my
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips told Henderson after Saturday's game that the team had
cut him. Henderson did not speak to Valentine but spoke briefly
with reporters. ``I'm a little surprised, but that's fine,'' he
said. ``I didn't cause them to lose; you'd better look someplace
else. I've got to boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. If he clears waivers by Wednesday, the Mets will
have paid him about $500,000 of his $2 million salary for playing a
quarter of the season. If a team claims Henderson within 48 hours,
it would have to pay him the remaining $1.5 million of his salary.
If no team claims him, the likely scenario, and he signs with a
team after 48 hours, the team would have to pay him only $150,000,
a prorated amount of the $200,000 minimum. The Mets would then be
responsible for the rest of Henderson's contract, $1.35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's addition by subtraction,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, his first with the club, Henderson was an integral
part of the Mets' reaching the playoffs with a .423 on-base
percentage, best in the National League. But there were signs of
disruptive disinterest. He did not run out a ball off the wall in
San Diego, settling for a double instead of reaching third with
what would have been the potential tying run.
</P>
<P>
   But his most memorable act came when Mets players walked into
the clubhouse after losing Game 6 of the NL Championship Series to
the Atlanta Braves and saw him playing cards with Bobby Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Then he reported a day late to spring training this year and was
less than enthused about the team's season-opening series in Tokyo.
``I think I knew in Japan,'' Valentine said of Henderson's
dwindling time with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was all but final Saturday morning. Phillips hinted
that the clock was ticking on Henderson. Henderson himself was like
a time bomb, later in the morning cursing at a reporter and
launching into a tirade about a story that quoted Henderson
accurately.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Valentine was somber, having just spent his 50th
birthday releasing a player and losing another game in which the
Mets blew a lead. For the second straight game, the Marlins'
Preston Wilson _ traded by the Mets with two minor leaguers for
Mike Piazza in 1998 _ crushed a three-run home run, off Dennis
Cook, to give the Marlins a 7-5 lead in the seventh inning. Wilson
also hit a three-run homer on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, the Mets had the tying runs at the plate,
but Piazza, pinch-hitting, and Jon Nunnally struck out against
Braden Looper to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost a tough game,'' Valentine said, prefacing his
feelings about Henderson's release. ``You keep hearing guys make
comments. You keep having to take the high road. But there were too
many comments on the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the players who would discuss Henderson's departure were
positive about their teammate. They were a little surprised by the
move, citing Henderson as a team player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved playing with him, he's a Hall of Famer, he was always
exciting,'' Piazza said. ``Personally, no, I did not feel he was a
distraction. He was great with the guys. I know last night was
tough,'' Piazza added, referring to the Friday night incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he gets a bad rap,'' Nunnally said. During Saturday's
game, Henderson worked with Nunnally in the batting cages. ``I
really like Rickey; he's been nothing but kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the utility infielder Melvin Mora was put on the
disabled list with stitches in his right index finger, the Mets
recalled Joe McEwing from Class AAA Norfolk. He was in Henderson's
place batting leadoff, and went 1 for 4, doubling and scoring in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After the game the Mets called up first baseman Mark Johnson,
who was hitting .303 with 25 runs batted in, 7 home runs and 6
stolen bases at Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did not know if he would bat McEwing leadoff again
today. He did concede that nobody would get on base more than
Henderson had. He left the Mets with a .387 on-base percentage and
five stolen bases but a .219 batting average this season. ``If he
had doubles and was able to drive in runs and was hitting .300, I
don't think we would have done this,'' Valentine said. ``I think
Rickey's a good guy, I know he's a great player, and maybe he is
misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson would not do anything to change that conception.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets losing their second straight game to Florida,
Valentine and Phillips thought the timing was right. Once again,
the team squandered chances and blew leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel it was a lack of effort, it was a lack of
execution,'' Piazza said. But for lack of effort, his teammate was
gone Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
