<HEADLINE>
LOVE REMEMBERS ADAM PETTY AT NELSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH, CHARLES CLINES AND JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
\Nsubheds:Remembering Petty
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Davis Love III wore the digit ``45'' on the back
of his cap yesterday in honor of Adam Petty, a 19-year-old driver
who died Friday in a crash during practice for a Busch Grand
National race in Loudon, N.H. Petty, a fourth-generation driver and
grandson of NASCAR legend Richard Petty, drove car No. 45 when he
competed.
</P>
<P>
   Love, a NASCAR fan from Sea Island, Ga., said he developed a
relationship with Adam's father, Kyle Petty, during races he
attended in Charlotte, N.C. Love said he also knows Richard Petty
and called him ``one of the nicest people in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never met Adam, but I got to know Kyle a little bit,''
Love said. ``I watched the start of the race \Ryesterday\S in the
locker room, and you could just see that they had lost part of
their family. It's like out here, when we lost Payne \RStewart\S
last year. It brought back a lot of memories of Payne ... and
that's something that hits you kind of hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know \Rthe Petty family\S has a Web site for condolences.
But I figured if I ever wanted to get in touch, this would be a
good way to do it. So that \RNo. 45\S was for Adam.''
\Nsubheds:Colonial power group Hal Sewell, an amateur golfer from
Fort Worth, drew the pro-am equivalent of a winning lottery ticket
for this week's MasterCard Colonial. In a blind draw to set the
field for Wednesday's pro-am, Sewell was mixed into a group that
includes PGA Tour participant Justin Leonard and MasterCard
executive Jeff Price.
</P>
<P>
   His fellow amateurs? Baseball legend Hank Aaron and hockey
legend Bobby Orr. The fivesome will tee off at 7:57 a.m. Wednesday.
\Nsubheds:No intimidation Tiger Woods said he saw Hank Kuehne's
name jump up on the leader board early yesterday morning at 3 under
par en route to his 7-under 64, and was hoping he could get his
name beside Kuehne's before the leaders teed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping I could get my name up there early at 3 under ...
you never know what might happen,'' Woods said after a birdie on
the 18th to finish with a 67 and move into a tie with Kuehne, David
Duval, Jay Williamson and Glen Day at 207.
</P>
<P>
   Although Woods finally got to 3 under, he said he ``scrambled''
to post his 67.
</P>
<P>
   He said the course played differently because of gusty north
winds rather than the south winds that have been prevalent since
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind would gust, then die,'' he said. ``It was sort of hit
and hope.'' \Nsubheds:Longer than Tiger Paul Stankowski said he had
fun blasting his drive 350 yards on the downwind par-5 16th to clip
Tiger Woods' drive by five yards. Winds gusted as high as 25 mph
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat Tiger, and that's all I cared about,'' Stankowski said.
``Day-in, day-out, he kicks my butt. It means nothing. ... It was
just fun for me to go, `Oh cool, I hit it by Tiger.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hole is being used in the GTE Long Distance Competition, and
Woods won Thursday when he hit a 287-yard drive into the wind that
gusted to 38 mph. Woods was second yesterday with a 345-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Stankowski, who wasn't playing with Woods, cared more
that he eagled the hole after hitting a 9-iron for his second shot
on the 554-yard hole. It helped him shoot a 66 and move into
contention, five shots off the lead. \Nsubheds:Ruling delay TV
coverage of the final two groups wasn't shown because of a delay
caused by two rulings that Neal Lancaster had on the 14th hole and
one on the 17th. Lancaster and Glen Day were one group in front of
the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster's drive on the par-4 14th drifted near a culvert to
the right and finished in an area designated as a hazard. He asked
for a ruling to get relief from the culvert, but because he was in
a hazard, couldn't get it. His next shot hit the culvert and
bounded backward. But his third cleared water in front of the
green, but came to rest near TV cables. After another ruling, he
got relief, chipped up and salvaged a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   On the 17th, his tee shot on the par-3 hole hit in the lap of a
seated spectator. When the spectator stood, the ball remained in
his canvas chair. After another ruling, the seat was closed and the
ball fell out, and that's where Lancaster played from. He finished
with a 75 and is at par for the tournament. \Nsubheds:Mickelson
rebounds Phil Mickelson's short game ranks among the best on the
PGA Tour, and it kept him in contention entering today's final
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly in a lot better position than I thought I was
going to be starting the day after I had a couple of bogeys early
on,'' said Mickelson, who carded a 2-under-par 68 despite bogeys on
Nos. 2 and 3. ``I was just trying to regroup and get my round back
under control. To be within four or five shots of the lead is a
good spot to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson hit 29 of 36 greens in regulation through the second
round but hit only seven in regulation yesterday. He offset that
shortcoming by needing only 22 putts. \Nsubheds:Brooks hangs in
Fort Worth's Mark Brooks completed the third round tied for fifth
among a group of three at 5 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played pretty well, especially on the back nine,'' said
Brooks, who shot an even-par 70. ``I hung in there on the front
nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks hit 14 of 18 greens in regulation, but he found himself
with few realistic opportunities for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every putt I had was downhill, and I really
didn't make many of them,'' he said. \Nsubheds:Briefly Paul
Stankowski, a Flower Mound resident who became eligible for next
week's MasterCard Colonial by moving into the 80th spot on the
money-earning's list after winning $57,800 last week in New
Orleans, said he declined to play in Fort Worth because his new
home is scheduled to be finished during Colonial week. The world's
top two players _ Tiger Woods and David Duval _ are paired today
with a tee time of 11:56 a.m. It's the first time they have been
paired in the final round of a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's estimated gallery count of 85,000 was the largest at
the Nelson since 1997, when Tiger Woods won.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Allem's left contact lens blew out while he has waiting
to hit his second shot on the par-4 third hole. After picking it
off the ground and reinserting it, he had to let Nick Faldo, whose
ball was in front of his, play first. Apparently, Allem lost his
concentration because he pulled his second shot short into the
rough and plopped his third shot into a trap he was trying to go
over.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the names on the leader board are familiar to golf
fans, one probably isn't. Jerry Smith has hung near the top this
week after rounds of 68-68-70. Smith, a 36-year-old from
Scottsdale, Ariz., played on the Buy.com Tour last year and his
biggest victory was the Guam Open in 1998 on the Omega Tour. He was
seventh in the PGA Tour qualifying school, and has missed only
three cuts in 14 starts this year, earning $193,616. \Ntagtop:Staff
writers Jimmy Burch, Charles Clines and Johnny Paul compiled this
report.
nn
</P>
