<SLUG> BC-BOX-TONY-AYALA-JR.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING A MEANS TO AN END FOR TONY AYALA JR.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sweat pours from his body as freely as time's sand
spills through the hourglass of a career nearer its end than
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Ayala Jr. refers to boxing as ``a young man's game.'' His
37-year-old body reminds him of this after sparring six rounds in a
musty gym whose only defense from the Texas heat rests with the
whirl of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Time would not appear to be an ally for someone a year removed
from serving a 16-year sentence in New Jersey's Rahway State Prison
for a sexual-assault conviction. Yet, Ayala exchanged prison garb
for trunks and gloves upon his release in April 1999. He will walk
into Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum Friday night as part of his ``To
Hell &AMP; Back'' tour to fight middleweight Anthony Stephens on the
card's 10-round main event.
</P>
<P>
   Winning in the ring, however, isn't the fuel driving Ayala's
comeback bid. Nor is recapturing his youth, or earning that pot of
gold a world title would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't care about winning. I just don't think
winning is life,'' Ayala said. ``I hope people understand where I'm
coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the visions \Rof winning\S, but they're not as
important anymore, as important as being happy and at peace with
one's self and the world. I've come to realize and understand that
there are much more important things in life than winning a fight
or winning a world title.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ayala views boxing as a means to an end, a tool to
support his wife, Lisa, earn financial security and perhaps start a
business once his boxing career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to God I could say that this was for what we consider
the honorable reasons, that I want the world title wrapped around
me for the fulfillment of a dream,'' said Ayala, who has earned
approximately $500,000 for his first four fights since his release,
according to Boxing Management Inc. president Lester Bedford. ``I
wish I could say that, but that's not the reality, and I'm not
going to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody doubting his commitment in the ring, however, is missing
the point, said Tony's father and trainer, Tony Ayala Sr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell any of these other fighters in his weight class who
think he's too old and slow, `Pick a number and get in line.' It's
coming. Believe me. It's coming.''
</P>
<P>
   On that his son agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing for me is a job. Is it more than that? Yeah. When I'm
in the ring, it is a thousand more times than that,'' Ayala said.
``When I'm in the ring, it's about winning and winning at any cost.
At that point, the gladiator in me comes out. It's win at all costs
because of the sacrifices I have to make.'' \Nsubheds:Turning his
life around No doubt many who know Ayala's story want to see him
fail or believe a convicted rapist should still be in jail. High on
heroin, he raped a 19-year-old neighbor in West Paterson, N.J.
during the early morning hours of New Year's Day 1983. Already on
probation for assaulting a woman four years earlier in San Antonio,
he was convicted of sexual assault and sentenced to 35 years in
prison, with a minimum of 15 years before he became eligible for
parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who refuse to believe that people have the
capability and character to turn their life around,'' Ayala said.
``Am I a saint? I've never said I'm a saint. I have my flaws. Am I
who I was? The answer to that question is definitely not.
Ultimately, people are going to have to search their own souls and
come to a conclusion as to how they feel about me _ if I'm that
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``El Torito'' could be that big in the boxing world.
</P>
<P>
   A victory Friday could catapult him into an August fight on Home
Box Office with ``Yory Boy'' Campas, the former International
Boxing Federation junior middleweight champion. A victory in that
fight could steer him into the direction of Felix Trinidad, David
Reid or Fernando Vargas and a huge financial bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stop and argue with destiny,'' said Ayala, 26-0. ``For
whatever reason, fate has dealt me this hand. Now that I've come
out, I've been able to accomplish a lot, first and foremost through
the grace of God and, secondly, through my hard work and the people
who surround me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala stays close to his extended family. He rarely goes
anywhere in public alone to avoid the chance of a confrontation or
the fear of being falsely accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very hard for something to go wrong,'' said his
wife, Lisa, who stuck with him through his imprisonment. ``His head
is in the right place, and I think that's all that matters. When
he's not with any of us, it's not like we have to worry _ `Well,
where is he? What is he doing?' _ because his head is in the right
place. He does have a great support system, but even outside that,
he has grown tremendously. There's just no way he would ever repeat
the mistakes that he's made.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala could not have made it this far without a blemish unless
he had come to grips with his past, said his manager, Brian Raditz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he would have survived,'' said Raditz, a
psychologist who also served as Ayala's therapist during his
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   His support system includes his wife, his mother and father, his
brothers, Raditz and friends Richard Kenefick of New York and
Junior Suarez of New Jersey. Ayala forged a friendship with former
convicts Kenefick and Suarez during their time in prison together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was released from prison, they were outside the gate
waiting for me,'' Ayala said. ``I cannot express to you how much
help it was to have someone who could relate to what it's like
being in prison.'' \Nsubheds:Getting another chance Ayala never
ducked an opponent before imprisonment and will not bob and weave
from questions regarding his past or time spent as Inmate No.
69765. He uses candor and openness as he would gloves, and the fact
that BMI signed him to a four-fight contract to promote his fights
does not surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the answer I should say is, `Yes,' '' Ayala said.
``The reason I have a hard time saying it is because my change
didn't occur when I walked out of prison. My change occurred
probably after my fifth year in prison, and I've lived this life
for the last 11 years. Is it hard for some people to believe that
I've changed? Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight Friday will be Ayala's fifth since his release from
prison and the second promoted by BMI.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford did not perceive Ayala being the gamble many did and
promoted the boxer's first three fights before becoming BMI's
president in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went and visited him twice in prison,'' Bedford said. ``The
first thing I had to do was get comfortable with him personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedford admitted being concerned that Ayala would be bitter and
angry upon his release and would lay blame for his self-destructive
ways upon others instead of accepting responsibility. Ayala erased
those fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered a guy who was very much remorseful and thankful
for his opportunity in life after 16 years of trying to make
himself better,'' Bedford said. ``I walked away feeling very
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   After joining the company earlier this year, Bedford also
convinced BMI's bosses, Scott Sherman and Billy Rosenthal, but that
took work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an easy sell. I can tell you that,'' Bedford said.
``There was some concern about him having been in prison, and the
other question was could you make money if you took a shot on him.
The answer to both questions for me was definitely yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also felt very comfortable in the fact that he's got a lot
left as a fighter. This guy is a legitimate contender. I think it
will take one of the top two or three guys in the world to beat
him, and I don't know if they can beat him ... He has a desire to
go out there and do something historic and be a real challenger and
not just a freak show or fight for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunger for greatness remains, but Ayala insists it's not his
priority in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could interview me for a thousand hours and I could never
relate to you the gratitude and appreciation that I have for what's
happened in my life,'' Ayala said. ``If I go out and \RStephens\S
knocks me out, I'll feel bad. But who cares? I don't want to sound
callous or like a guy who doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RBut\S when I die, the regrets that I'll take with me are
things no world title or no amount of money can erase the fact that
I victimized a couple of women in my life. That is something I'll
never forget, and I never want to forget. What I did was horrible
and should never be forgotten no matter the level of success I
reach.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds: Tony Ayala Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 37
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   Height: 5-foot-8
</P>
<P>
   Weight: Middleweight
</P>
<P>
   Amateur career: Two-time national junior olympic champion. ...
1979 national Golden Gloves champion. ... member 1980 U.S. Olympic
team (U.S. boycott)
</P>
<P>
   Professional career: 26-0, 24 knockouts, former world No. 1
contender. ... Turned pro on June 17, 1980 at age 17, knocking out
Zip Castillo in San Antonio. ... Two biggest victories were
knockouts of top-10 contenders Carlos Herrera (November, 1982) and
Robbie Epps (August, 1982). ... Was scheduled to fight world
champion Davey Moore for the World Boxing Association junior
middleweight title when arrested on Jan. 1, 1983 and subsequently
sent to prison for 16 years for sexual assault. ... Is 4-0 since
being released from New Jersey's Rahway state prison last year. ...
Last fight was April 14 in San Antonio when he knocked out Jorge
Vado in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Married, wife Lisa, no children. ... Owns the gym,
along with his father, that he trains in.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
