<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Rangers' Wetteland makes 300th memorable 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ John Wetteland kept insisting his 300th save
should not be a particularly memorable moment. Turns out he was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was memorable, for all the wrong reasons,'' Wetteland said
after the Rangers' 13-11 victory over the Anaheim Angels on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   It was memorable because Wetteland almost blew a five-run lead
in the ninth inning. He gave up a leadoff home run to Mo Vaughn, a
double to Tim Salmon and a two-run homer to Garret Anderson before
he got anybody out. Troy Glaus then grounded out, but Orlando
Palmeiro's single allowed the Angels to get the tying run to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, instead of his 300th save, Wetteland was on the verge
of a collapse that would have been huge even by the Rangers' latest
lofty standards. But he got Ben Molina to pop out, then struck out
pinch hitter Scott Spiezio to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, an obviously relieved Wetteland smiled, accepted the
congratulations of his teammates and said, ``I'm encouraged and
discouraged. Discouraged result-wise. ... Anyone would be. But go
figure. I put some stuff together, as good as I've had.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fastball was crisp, my curveball was good, the location
wasn't great, and there were a lot of sharp sliders. The home runs
were belt high, middle of the plate. Go higher or lower, and you're
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, the 12th pitcher in major-league history to get 300
saves, threw 28 pitches in the ninth, giving him ample opportunity
to analyze his stuff. But perhaps most important to him, the quest
for the 300th save is over. He admitted it had become a burden to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually not fun when you've got something like that
staring you in the face day after day,'' Wetteland said.
``Everybody wants you to do it, everybody wants it to happen for
totally different reasons than you want it. You feel that
expectation on top of it. Now it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates, ``Personally, I'm glad he got it
done. You know it's going to happen, but being patient is sometimes
tough. I thought he threw the ball great. I thought it was the best
stuff he's had in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's desire to get it done Friday night probably
contributed to his bad inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I was doing things that would support that,'' said
Wetteland, who settled down after a visit to the mound by pitching
coach Dick Bosman. ``I was doing things I tend to do when I get
emotionally rushing things. After he came out, I settled down and
had better location.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Rangers presented him with a cake
congratulating him on the moment. Rookie pitcher Doug Davis, who
earned his first major-league victory Saturday night, gave
Wetteland the game ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the lineup card,'' Davis said. ``I'm honored to be on
the same team as John. He's great. He's a guy I've looked up to
since I was a kid. ... But don't tell him that. He'll feel old.''
</P>
<P>
   With the moment past, Wetteland is eager to get back to the
normal business of winning a division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said for as long as I've been reminded of this, when that
day happens, tonight or two months from now _ well I wouldn't have
this job if it was two months from now _ you've still got a whole
season left,'' Wetteland said. ``That's why I don't set goals. You
reach the goal, so what's next. You end up setting goal after goal
after goal. That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   One milestone was enough.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
