<SLUG> BC-BBN-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRIGLEY FIELD THE BIG WINNER IN CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a battle for the basement in the National League Central, the
Brewers and Cubs averaged 25,418 spectators for a three-game,
series at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Across town a week earlier, the American League Central-leading
White Sox and the Blue Jays averaged 12,290 paying customers for
their three-game, midweek series at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are a major disappointment, a club that was given an
outside chance to contend but instead is a bottom feeder.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox are a pleasant surprise, a club expected to be an
also-ran that instead continues to hold off the heavily favored
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   So why do the Cubs outdraw the White Sox by about a 2-1 margin?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is Chicagoans' lingering bitterness toward White Sox
owner Jerry Reinsdorf, both for his role as a hawk in the labor
wars followed by the hypocrisy of briefly making Albert Belle the
best-paid player in the game, and for the ``white flag'' trade in
'97.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is the Cubs have star power that the White Sox
lack. Sammy Sosa plies his trade on the North Side, as does Kerry
Wood. The Cubs drew 38,121 for Wood's comeback start against the
Astros on the same evening that a mere 10,397 bothered to watch the
White Sox play the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest reason, though, is that the Cubs play in Wrigley,
and the White Sox play in Comiskey.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox's South Side ballpark suffers from a bad location,
from a vertigo-inducing upper deck, and from an unfortunate lack of
vision and foresight.
</P>
<P>
   It opened in 1991 as an upgrade on old Comiskey, but devoid of
personality. It's got a lower deck, a ring of luxury suites, the
upper deck, and lots of outfield bleacher seats. The seats are
light blue. Nice, but nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the gorgeous Camden Yards opened in
Baltimore, touching off the building boom of aesthetically
pleasing, retro ballparks with all the modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   Comiskey Park pales by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field, which opened in 1914 as the home to the Chicago
Whales of the Federal League two years before the Cubs moved in,
lacks the modern conveniences. But it more than makes up for it
with a charm all its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrigley Field is a special place,'' said Diamondbacks pitcher
Mike Morgan, a one-time Cub.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field is ``the friendly confines,'' a neighborhood
ballpark, ivy-covered walls, a brick wall behind the plate, a view
of Lake Michigan beyond the right-field wall, home runs that carry
out of the ballpark and onto Waveland Avenue, fans watching from
adjacent rooftops, and day games.
</P>
<P>
   It's a park unsullied by senses-assaulting, garish billboards.
The only advertising seen at Wrigley is on buildings outside the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm really glad they haven't done here is put those
stupid signs behind home plate where they're constantly rolling
over every minute and advertising for this and that,'' Cubs
infielder Jeff Huson said. ``It's nice to just have a brick
background. In the big leagues I don't think there should be any
advertising on the outfield walls, or behind home plate when that
thing's rotating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field is bleacher bums who interact with the
outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field is fans showing up to root, root, root for the
home team, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're for you when you're losing; they're for you when
you're winning,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field is an old ballpark that ranks among the best in
the game. Comiskey is a relatively new one that's average at best.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Wrigley is the place to watch a ballgame in
Chicago.
Helton, Guerrero stars on the slugging horizon
Fusaichi Pegasus is not the only Triple Crown threat in the world
of sports these days.
</P>
<P>
   There's two in the National League in Rockies first baseman Todd
Helton and Expos outfielder Vladimir Guerrero. Both are in the top
10 in batting average, home runs and runs batted in, baseball's
Triple Crown categories.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the weekend, Helton was second with a .392 average,
third with 12 home runs and first with 38 RBI. Guerrero was fourth
with a .387 average, ninth with 10 home runs (four out of first)
and third with 33 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Helton's numbers are padded a bit by the advantage of playing
his home games in the thin air of Colorado. He's hitting .500
(24-for-48) with seven home runs and 21 RBI in 13 home games,
compared to a .319 average (23-72) with five home runs and 17 RBI
in 20 road games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that shouldn't obscure the fact that the 26-year-old,
left-handed hitting Helton has become one of the best young hitters
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .320 with 35 home runs and 113 RBI last year. He's on
pace to top that this season because he avoided an early-season
slump and he has improved his hitting against left-handed pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In his two previous Aprils, Helton batted .240 with just three
home runs in 44 games. This April, Helton batted .337 and led the
team with six home runs and 25 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I consciously thought about in the
off-season, something I wanted to correct,'' Helton said of his
previous slow starts.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .245 against lefties in '99. So far this year he's hit
them at a .349 clip.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, 24, is continuing his ascent to becoming perhaps the
best all-around player in the game. He batted .324 with 38 home
runs and 109 RBI in his first full season in '98, and .316 with 42
home runs and 131 RBI last year.
</P>
<P>
   Giants outfielder Barry Bonds said Guerrero ``hits, throws,
runs, everything. He's an MVP-caliber player. Will he win it?
There's a good chance. He's in that league; he's in that class.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he or Helton win the Triple Crown? Probably not. It'll be
tough to win the home run crown in a league that includes Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't alter the fact that they are special young talents
having special seasons.
\Nsubheds:Dandy of a duel Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown, the two
highest-paid pitchers in history, lived up to the contracts with a
good old-fashioned pitcher's duel Wednesday. They were so good that
the game wasn't decided until they left after eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's Diamondbacks beat Brown's Dodgers, 2-1, with a run in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two warriors going after it,'' D'backs manager Buck Showalter
said. ``Neither one was willing to blink, either. I found myself at
times during the game a fan of it, watching it. Usually games don't
live up to the hype, but this one did.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley's second-inning home run was the only run off
Johnson, who struck out 13 and lowered his earned-run average to
0.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a grind out there,'' he said. ``I knew once
I gave up that run, I couldn't afford to give up any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed six hits in eight innings, striking out six, and
lowered his ERA to 2.20. He was relieved for a pinch hitter in the
top of the ninth, opening the door for Arizona to win in the bottom
of the inning. \Nsubheds:Galarraga struggling Andres Galarraga's
feel-good comeback has hit a snag now that NL pitchers have changed
their pattern against him. In the first three weeks of the season,
pitchers tested the Braves first baseman with fastballs. Despite a
16-month absence from the game, he had no problems and hit a flurry
of home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, he's seeing an abundance of breaking pitches, and
he hasn't been able to adjust. He leads the club with 26
strikeouts, and hasn't hit a home run since April 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been pitching me differently,'' Galarraga said. ``They
haven't been throwing me too much stuff to hit. As soon as I get
patient and start taking pitches, I'll be all right.''
\Nsubheds:Lowe impressive Forget Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciaparra
and Carl Everett. The Red Sox's most valuable player might be
closer Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of last season, the Red Sox are 68-19 in games
Lowe has pitched, including 12-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 13 appearances and 202/3 innings this season, Lowe
was 2-0 with a 0.87 ERA. He had allowed just nine hits and five
walks and struck out 12. He was 8-for-8 in save opportunities. With
runners on base, opposing batters were just 2-for-25 against him.
He allowed two runs, on solo home runs by Scott Spiezio and Richie
Sexson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been tremendous, to say the least,'' Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams said. ``He has an outstanding sinker and breaking ball and
he can throw them both for strikes.''
Around the NL Dodgers ace Kevin Brown pitched in 10 games last
season against an opponent's Opening Day starter or a pitcher of
that caliber. He went 4-3 with three no-decisions, and a 4.10 ERA.
This year, he has made five of his six starts against Opening Day
starters or a pitcher with similar talent _ Randy Johnson, Dustin
Hermanson, Alex Fernandez, Shane Reynolds and Tom Glavine. In those
five games he is 2-1 with two no-decisions and an ERA of 1.75.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had scored in 108 consecutive games through
Thursday, the longest current streak in the majors. The Astros are
second, scoring at least one run in 67 consecutive games. No NL
team has scored in every game in an entire season. The modern NL
record is 174, set by the Philadelphia Phillies from Sept. 20, 1992
to Sept. 29, 1993. Barring rainouts, Arizona would have to score in
every game through July 25 at St. Louis to break that record. The
major-league record is 308 consecutive games, by the Yankees from
Aug. 3, 1931 to Aug. 2, 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves closer Mark Wohlers continues to make progress in
his rehabilitation from both elbow surgery and the ``anxiety
disorder'' that caused him to lose his control. Wohlers, now with
the Reds, has exhibited a fastball in the mid-90s and is throwing
strikes in his batting practice sessions. He started throwing
breaking pitches Wednesday, throwing about 12 sliders among his 40
pitches. He's expected to begin throwing split-fingers in a week to
10 days, and could begin a rehab assignment in 2-4 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies closer Jose Jimenez doesn't have a save since April 22
in St. Louis, the Rockies' 19th game. He hasn't even had a save
opportunity since then. The Rockies are 5-9, winning four of those
games by at least six runs and getting a complete game from Pedro
Astacio in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams was cleared to begin jogging, and could return to
the Diamondbacks' lineup in less than three weeks. The club's third
baseman and cleanup hitter, who's been out since the final week of
spring training after a foul ball broke a bone in his foot,
Williams has been taking batting practice and fielding ground balls
since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs relievers allowed 18 ninth-inning runs in four games of a
recent five-game stretch. The Pirates scored six in the ninth on
May 6, rallying to win, 11-9, and four in the final inning of an
11-3 victory last Sunday. The Brewers scored four in the ninth on
Monday to cap a comeback from a 9-1 deficit to an 11-11 tie before
the Cubs rallied to win, 12-11, in the 10th inning. The Brewers
then scored three in the eighth and four in the ninth to turn a 3-1
deficit into an 8-3 lead before the Cubs escaped for a wild 9-8
victory on Wednesday. Desperate for help, the Cubs signed veteran
pitchers Tim Worrell and Eric Plunk to minor-league deals.
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing new when the Marlins handed Tom Glavine his first
loss of the season in a 5-3 victory against the Braves on
Wednesday. Glavine is 6-11 against the Marlins _ the only team he
has a losing record against in his career.
Around the AL Tampa Bay right-hander Steve Trachsel was a
thoroughly mediocre (actually, lousy) 1-2 with a 6.15 ERA and a
.317 opponents' batting average going into his start against the
Red Sox on May 6, making what came next perhaps the most improbable
feat of the season. Trachsel pitched a complete-game shutout to
beat Pedro Martinez, 1-0. Then, on Thursday, he pitched seven
shutout innings to outduel Orlando Hernandez in a 1-0 victory
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   His line in the two games: 16 innings, six hits, five walks and
16 strikeouts. ``Just my normal game out there,'' Trachsel said.
``Nothing special, just locating my fastball real well and working
my other pitches off of that. It just worked especially well. I'm
not throwing any harder. I'm not throwing a new pitch. My location
is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero improved to 4-1 when he beat Tampa Bay last Sunday,
one victory shy of all of last season, when he went 5-14 for the
Mariners and Rangers. His victory over the Rays marked the first
time he has won three consecutive starts since pitching for Seattle
in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alomar Jr. reclaimed his job as the Indians' starting
catcher when he came off the DL on Monday, but Einar Diaz will
continue to play two or three times a week. Diaz hit .356 while
Alomar was out, and is better at throwing out runners.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox sent Baylor ex Kip Wells to Triple-A Charlotte
after he went 2-3 with a 7.28 ERA in seven starts. Wells was 4-1
with 4.04 ERA in seven starts at the end of last year, his first
season as a pro, but struggled with his control this season. He was
leading the AL with 28 walks when he was shipped out. ``Hopefully
it will be just a bump in the road,'' Wells said. ``I didn't expect
to waltz in here and take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Since adjusting his delivery to include a rocking motion and
moving to the first-base side of the pitching rubber, Yankees
starter David Cone is 1-0 with a 3.48 ERA, a huge improvement from
his 0-2, 10.70 record after his first four starts. ``I like where I
am right now,'' Cone said. ``I feel good about what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the fanfare that accompanied Kerry Wood, A's
right-hander Ariel Prieto returned from surgery last week to make
his first major-league start since April 19, 1998. Prieto also
returned without Wood's success. He allowed five runs on 11 hits in
four innings of a 9-8 loss to the Angels on Tuesday, and was sent
back to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are considering trying to acquire Rickey Henderson,
who was put on waivers by the Mets. ``I had Rickey once before \Rin
Toronto\S, and there were times then when I thought he might be
finished,'' GM Pat Gillick said. ``Obviously he wasn't. But you
don't know how much you are going to get from him. There's always a
chance that you could get a real good burst of 30 or 60 days,
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The longball note of the week: the Blue Jays have homered in all
21 of their home games, the only team to do so this season. In all
but five of those games the Jays have hit more than one home run.
The league record for consecutive home games with at least one home
run is 23, held by the 1963 Yankees. The big-league mark is 32, by
the '99 Colorado Rockies. The Jays return home tomorrow for a
seven-game homestand.
The week ahead The Giants, who climbed into contention in the NL
West with a hot streak, should be tested with a three-game visit to
East-leading Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In the AL, there could be an early preview of the wild-card
battle when the Red Sox travel to Toronto for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've got to break out the mushballs. I don't know
what's causing it, but it's not very enjoyable, whether the fans
love it or not.'' _ A's manager Art Howe, on the increased offense
this season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
