<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4623 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-13 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE NIGHT INSPECTOR &LR;  By Frederick Busch. Ballantine, $14. A
former Union sniper, wearing a mask to conceal a wound sustained in
the Civil War, wanders the streets of New York, where he becomes a
friend of a forgotten writer who resembles Melville. This novel
``is a marvelously dark-hued story by a master craftsman,'' John
Crowley wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999. ``His
prose and his conversations are precisely, surprisingly and
thoroughly of their time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRYPTONOMICON &LR;  By Neal Stephenson. HarperPerennial, $16. This
overstuffed picaresque novel is an audaciously conceived tale of
code making and code breaking. It takes place both during World War
II, when the Allies were scrambling to break the Nazis' Enigma
code, and in the present day, when a couple of entrepreneurial
computer hackers are trying to create a ``data haven'' for
encrypted information in the Philippines. With its profusion of
plot lines, characters and gonzo riffs, the book is ``as
fascinating, and as frustrating, as a string of partly decrypted
code,'' Dwight Garner wrote last year. ``It wants to blow your mind
while keeping you well fed and happy. ... It's brain candy for
bitheads.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOOD MAN OF NANKING: The Diaries of John Rabe &LR;  Edited by
Erwin Wickert. Vintage, $14. The author, a German businessman and
Nazi supporter, not only witnessed the Japanese massacre in Nanking
in 1937 but also saved the lives of many poor Chinese. His
unpolemical account ``is at once riveting, inspiring, terrifying
and tragically sad,'' Sheryl WuDunn wrote in 1998. It is
``compassionate and, at times, humorous.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SEXTANTS OF BEIJING: Global Currents in Chinese History &LR; ,
by Joanna Waley-Cohen (Norton, $14.95), surveys the history of
China's ambivalent relations with the outside world and seeks to
shatter the myth that the nation traditionally has been deeply
isolationist. Last year the reviewer Nicholas D. Kristof disagreed
with much of the thesis but found this to be a ``thoughtful and
highly readable'' book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BROADWAY BABIES SAY GOODNIGHT: Musicals Then and Now &LR;  By Mark
Steyn. Routledge, $17. A columnist and critic offers an irreverent
history of the Broadway musical, a diverse and lively art form
that, judging from the flood of revivals these days, may be in its
death throes. Last year in The New York Times Book Review, Robert
Gottlieb called this an ``eccentric, funny, shrewd and somewhat
dismaying book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PALACE &LR;  By Lisa St. Aubin de Teran. Ecco/HarperCollins,
$13. The narrator of this exotic fairy tale is a former political
prisoner who assumes a gentleman's guise, makes a fortune as a
gambler in 19th-century Venice and builds a dream house for the
woman he loves. Last year the reviewer David Willis McCullough
admired the novel's ``lovingly rendered descriptive prose'' and its
``sensuous and sinuous portrait of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHADOW: Five Presidents and the Legacy of Watergate &LR;  By Bob
Woodward. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16. The celebrated
investigative journalist examines how the rules of presidential
politics have changed since the Nixon administration, dwelling in
depth on the Clinton White House and its efforts to manage the
Whitewater, Lewinsky and other scandals. ``Some of Woodward's
judgments are shrewd and plausible,'' Michael Lind wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIMBUKTU &LR;  By Paul Auster. Picador USA, $11. Mr. Bones, this
novel's canine protagonist, roams urban, suburban and rural America
looking for a home (and spiritual enlightenment) after the death of
his beloved longtime companion, a homeless man from Brooklyn. Last
year the reviewer Jim Shepard praised the tale's ``periodic flashes
of gorgeous prose.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DISOWNED BY MEMORY: Wordsworth's Poetry of the 1790s &LR;  By David
Bromwich. University of Chicago, $15. The author explores the
crucial years of the poet's moral development, when his republican
ardor was transformed by the Terror that followed the French
Revolution. ``Bromwich is a rigorous critic, but he is a general
one whose insights are broadly applicable,'' Vijay Seshadri wrote
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE PLEASURES OF THE
IMAGINATION: English Culture in the Eighteenth Century &LR; , by John
Brewer ($20), a grand tour of the world of fine arts and literature
during a time when culture moved from the court into the public
domain, to be possessed as well as consumed. ``Brewer gives us a
brilliantly illustrated social history of the many people who
produced plays and paintings, music and books,'' T.H. Breen wrote
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I LEFT MY BACK DOOR OPEN &LR;  By April Sinclair. HarperPerennial,
$13. Daphne Dupree is a Chicago radio host with lots to say about
race, weight, self-esteem and popular music. ``It's a `Bridget
Jones' Diary' for black women,'' Sarah Vowell wrote last year.
``Many readers will respond to this novel's honesty'' and
``colloquial humor.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GARDENS IN THE DUNES &LR;  By Leslie Marmon Silko. Scribner, $14.
Set in the 19th century, this novel follows the fate of two
American Indian girls who are sent from their desert home to
government-run schools to become ``civilized.'' The result is ``a
rich, intriguing, irritating mix of myth, allegory, Victorian
children's tale and adventure yarn,'' Suzanne Ruta wrote in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
