<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-DCUNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DC UNITED FALLS TO REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ After four years finding ways to lose soccer
games, the Revolution appear to be finding ways to win. And,
fortunately for the Revolution, D.C. United has adopted just the
opposite formula.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution also appears able to retain its composure,
another break from the past, and among the keys to success. The
Revolution took a 3-1 win over D.C. United Saturday night, their
second 3-point win over the three-time Major League Soccer Cup
champions this season and only their fourth in 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde Harris (15th minute), Mauricio Ramos (66th), and Imad Baba
(82d) converted free kicks from virtually the same spot, and
goalkeeper Jeff Causey stopped a second-half Jaime Moreno penalty
as the Revolution remained in a first-place tie with Miami in the
Eastern Division. D.C. United is in last place.
</P>
<P>
   But United, which played without Marco Etcheverry, controlled
possession for most of the game and dominated play well into the
second half. Some individual heroics and effective substitutions by
coach Fernando Clavijo made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have created a lot of chances in the past and we were not
able to finish them,'' Clavijo said. ``Sometimes it goes your way
and sometimes it doesn't. Sometimes a good team needs to win even
playing bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played against a very good team that was eager to get 3
points at home and we managed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, replacing Etcheverry as midfield director, carved
through the Revolution in the first half. Moreno, among the MLS's
all-time leading scorers, displayed his versatility by ranging from
side to side to find space, accelerating through the heart of the
defense, deftly chesting down long passes, and laying off
perfectly-timed balls into space for teammates to run onto. But
United squandered excellent chances after Moreno had provided a 1-0
lead with a 14th-minute header off a corner kick.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, though, Revolution substitute Mike Burns
made things difficult for Moreno. And, the longer United went
without scoring, the more the Revolution seemed to gain confidence.
</P>
<P>
   William Sunsing, who replaced Johnny Torres in the 60th minute,
added energy and unpredictability as the Revolution launched
effective counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   Harris scored the tying goal by drilling a low shot under a
United wall. As the United players jumped, Harris's shot skipped
through into the left side of the goal, less than a minute after
Moreno's goal.
</P>
<P>
   But United seemed destined to take the lead until Sunsing helped
break their momentum. Ted Chronopoulos intercepted a Richie
Williams pass in the 66th minute and carried to the penalty arc,
where he was fouled by Williams. Ramos then curled a shot just
inside the left post for a 2-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Chronopoulos was cautioned by Korean referee Kim Tae Young for
holding Chris Albright on a corner, surrendering a penalty. But
Causey aggressively cut the angle as Moreno shot directly at him in
the 78th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes later, the Revolution put the match out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution continued to counter, and Sunsing sped from his
own penalty area to the edge of the penalty arc, where he was
caught from behind. Baba then curled a free kick inside the left
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were patient and disciplined and believed in what we wanted
to do,'' Revolution captain John Harkes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
